// english-content-4.js  Comprehension: 40 passages with embedded questions
// Flat array; no sub-islands. Used by comprehension.html

var COMPREHENSION_PASSAGES = [
  {id:'F01',title:'The Jungle at Night',type:'fiction',source:'Adapted from Rudyard Kipling, The Jungle Book (1894)',
   text:'The moon rose above the trees and cast long silver shadows across the clearing where the wolf pack had gathered. Mowgli sat cross-legged on the Council Rock, watching the wolves circle below him. He had lived among them since he was a small child — carried into the cave by Father Wolf on a warm night when the tiger Shere Khan had come hunting in the wrong territory. That felt like a lifetime ago now. Mowgli could barely remember a world before the jungle.\n\nThe boy knew every scent in the jungle: the sweet heaviness of the mahua flower, the sharp tang of damp earth after rain, and the musty warmth of the wolf den where he slept each night. He understood the language of the wolves better than the language of men. When Akela, the great grey Lone Wolf, raised his head to howl, Mowgli felt the sound deep in his own chest, as though his bones were humming. He had once tried to howl back, and the younger cubs had fallen over each other in delight. Even Bagheera, the black panther who rarely showed affection, had purred.\n\nBut tonight something was different. The wolves were restless. Their ears twitched towards the bamboo thickets to the east, and even Baloo the bear had stopped his lazy scratching to sniff the wind. Mowgli had learned long ago to trust the instincts of the pack. If they were uneasy, there was reason. He rose to his feet and placed a hand on Akela\'s shoulder, feeling the old wolf\'s muscles tense beneath the coarse grey fur.\n\nThen the scent reached him — faint at first, carried on the warm breeze like a whisper. Smoke. Not the comforting smoke of a village cooking fire, but something sharper and more dangerous. Somewhere beyond the river, the jungle was burning. Mowgli\'s stomach tightened. Fire was the one thing every creature in the jungle feared, from the smallest mouse deer to Shere Khan himself. The wolves called it the Red Flower, and they would not even speak its true name. Mowgli had seen it only once before, when a lightning strike had set the grasslands ablaze and the animals had fled together — predator and prey side by side, enemies made equal by terror.\n\nAkela rose slowly to his feet, and one by one the pack turned to face the east. Nobody moved. The silence was heavier than the heat, broken only by the distant crack of splitting bamboo as the fire ate its way forward. Mowgli stood too, his bare feet gripping the warm stone of the Council Rock, and stared into the darkness where an orange glow was beginning to stain the sky. He was not afraid — not yet. But he could feel fear gathering around him, rising from the pack like heat from sun-baked earth.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['The passage explores how Mowgli must choose between his loyalty to the wolf pack and his growing curiosity about the world of men.','Kipling uses the approaching fire to reveal how Mowgli\'s leadership has gradually replaced Akela\'s authority within the pack.','Mowgli\'s deep bond with the jungle and wolf pack is disrupted when a fire threatens their world.','The story presents the strict hierarchy of jungle law, showing how every creature must follow the rules set down at the Council Rock.'],c:2,e:'The passage spends its first half establishing Mowgli\'s profound connection to the jungle — his knowledge of its scents, his bond with the wolves, his shared language with the pack. The second half disrupts this calm when smoke signals an approaching fire. The main idea is this contrast between belonging and threat.'},
      {q:'"Mowgli felt the sound deep in his own chest, as though his bones were humming." Which literary device is used here, and what effect does it create?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['Metaphor — it suggests Mowgli has become one with the pack on an emotional level, his body literally absorbing the wolves\' collective voice as his own.','Simile — it emphasises how deeply Mowgli is connected to the wolves, feeling their call inside his own body.','Personification — it gives the howl a physical presence that enters Mowgli\'s body, making the sound feel like a living force with its own intent.','Onomatopoeia — the word \'humming\' recreates the vibrating quality of the howl, immersing the reader in the sensory experience of the scene.'],c:1,e:'The phrase uses \'as though\' to compare the feeling of Akela\'s howl to Mowgli\'s bones vibrating, making it a simile. The effect goes beyond sound — it suggests Mowgli doesn\'t just hear the call but physically resonates with it, reinforcing his total immersion in the jungle world.'},
      {q:'How does the tone change across the passage, and where is the turning point?',skill:'Author\'s purpose & tone',opts:['It shifts from peaceful and warm to tense and threatening, turning at the start of paragraph three (\'But tonight something was different\').','It shifts from curious and exploratory to sorrowful and nostalgic, turning when Mowgli recalls his earliest days in the wolf den.','It shifts from reverent and spiritual to frantic and chaotic, turning when Akela begins to howl and the pack responds with panic.','It maintains a consistently ominous and foreboding atmosphere throughout, with subtle hints of danger woven into even the opening descriptions.'],c:0,e:'Paragraphs one and two build warmth and belonging through sensory details (\'sweet heaviness\', \'musty warmth\', cubs falling over in delight). The word \'But\' at the start of paragraph three signals the shift — from here, words like \'restless\', \'twitched\', \'tightened\', and \'terror\' create mounting tension.'},
      {q:'In paragraph four, we learn that during a previous fire, \'predator and prey\' fled \'side by side, enemies made equal by terror\'. Why does the author include this detail?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['To foreshadow that Mowgli will eventually unite the jungle animals against Shere Khan by reminding them of their shared vulnerability to outside threats.','To demonstrate the overwhelming power of fire — it is so terrifying that it overrides even the deepest instincts of hunter and hunted.','To establish that Mowgli has survived dangerous situations before, building his credibility as someone the pack can rely on in a crisis.','To contrast the jungle\'s usual rigid hierarchy with Mowgli\'s unique ability to understand and empathise with all species equally.'],c:1,e:'This detail elevates the threat of fire beyond ordinary danger. If animals that would normally kill each other abandon all instinct to run side by side, the reader understands that fire is in a category of its own. It also foreshadows what may be about to happen.'},
      {q:'In the final paragraph, Mowgli can feel fear \'rising from the pack like heat from sun-baked earth\'. What does this simile suggest?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['The pack\'s fear has been building gradually throughout the evening, and this moment captures the tipping point where individual worry becomes a shared group emotion.','The fear connects to the approaching fire through the shared image of heat, suggesting that the pack\'s emotional state is already being shaped by the physical threat.','The pack\'s fear is something almost physical — invisible but powerfully felt, radiating outwards from the group the way heat radiates from hot ground.','The wolves are projecting their fear outward, deliberately using their collective anxiety to warn Mowgli that he must take action and lead them to safety.'],c:2,e:'Heat rising from sun-baked earth is invisible but unmistakable — you feel it in the air around you even if you can\'t see it. By comparing the pack\'s fear to this, Kipling makes fear tangible and environmental. It also connects fear to the fire itself (heat), creating a layered image where the danger and the emotional response merge.'},
      {q:'The passage is told from a third-person perspective that stays close to Mowgli\'s experience. How does this point of view help the reader understand the jungle?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['It allows the narrator to move freely between Mowgli\'s thoughts and the wolves\' collective consciousness, giving the reader a complete picture of jungle life.','It creates emotional distance between the reader and Mowgli, allowing us to judge his responses objectively rather than being swept up in his feelings.','It enables the narrator to describe events beyond Mowgli\'s awareness, such as the fire\'s origin and the reactions of animals elsewhere in the jungle.','It lets the reader experience the jungle through Mowgli\'s senses and instincts, making the animal world feel natural and familiar rather than strange.'],c:3,e:'The third-person limited perspective filters everything through Mowgli\'s perceptions. Because Mowgli knows the jungle intimately, the reader absorbs details like scent, sound, and instinct as normal rather than exotic. This makes the jungle feel like home, which is essential for the passage\'s emotional impact when that home is threatened.'},
      {q:'What theme is developed through the detail that fire makes "predator and prey" flee "side by side, enemies made equal by terror"?',skill:'Theme',opts:['The boundary between human and animal identity is artificial, and Mowgli\'s presence in the pack proves that courage matters more than species.','True leadership means protecting the vulnerable, and the detail positions Mowgli as the figure who will restore order when the jungle\'s rules collapse.','Nature contains forces so powerful that they override all other instincts and hierarchies, reducing every creature to the same level of vulnerability.','Survival in the jungle depends on forming strong alliances, because no single animal — not even the fiercest predator — can face a crisis alone.'],c:2,e:'This detail develops the theme that nature\'s most destructive forces transcend the usual order. The jungle operates on a predator-prey hierarchy, but fire dissolves it entirely. This theme elevates fire from a simple danger to something almost existential, a force that undoes the jungle\'s fundamental rules.'},
      {q:'How does the text structure of the passage contribute to the building of tension?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['Each paragraph introduces a different character\'s perspective on the approaching threat, building a layered picture of the jungle community\'s diverse responses to danger.','The first two paragraphs establish calm and belonging, while the final three gradually introduce and intensify the threat, creating a structure that mirrors the approaching fire.','The passage alternates between Mowgli\'s internal thoughts and external sensory detail, creating a rhythm that mirrors the tension between instinct and reason.','The opening and closing paragraphs mirror each other structurally, with the Council Rock serving as a frame that bookends and contains the narrative.'],c:1,e:'The passage is structured as a slow build. Paragraphs one and two immerse us in Mowgli\'s peaceful world. Paragraph three introduces unease. Paragraph four names the threat. Paragraph five shows the pack frozen in dread. This escalating structure mirrors the fire itself, creeping closer paragraph by paragraph.'},
      {q:'What does the detail that wolves call fire "the Red Flower" and "would not even speak its true name" suggest about their relationship with fire?',skill:'Inference',opts:['The wolves have developed their own symbolic language for dangerous forces, demonstrating the sophistication of animal communication and culture within the jungle.','The nickname reflects the wolves\' respect for fire as a powerful natural force, suggesting they view it with awe and reverence rather than fear.','The phrase shows that the wolves\' understanding of fire is limited to its visual appearance, and they lack the intelligence to comprehend what it truly is.','The wolves fear fire so deeply that even naming it feels dangerous, suggesting an almost superstitious dread that goes beyond ordinary caution.'],c:3,e:'Refusing to speak a thing\'s true name is a behaviour associated with deep, almost sacred fear. It suggests the wolves treat fire not as an ordinary hazard but as something fundamentally different from other dangers. This taboo-like avoidance heightens the reader\'s sense of how serious the approaching fire is.'},
      {q:'What does the description of Mowgli\'s knowledge of jungle scents in paragraph two reveal about his character?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['It demonstrates Mowgli\'s exceptional survival intelligence, showing that he has systematically catalogued every scent in order to navigate the jungle\'s dangers effectively.','It reveals that Mowgli has deliberately trained his senses over many years so that he can outperform the wolves in tracking prey and detecting approaching threats.','It shows that Mowgli has fully absorbed the jungle into his identity, experiencing the world through animal-like senses rather than human reasoning.','It suggests that Mowgli\'s awareness of every familiar scent has left him restless and bored, hinting at a growing desire for something new beyond the pack\'s territory.'],c:2,e:'The catalogue of scents — mahua flower, damp earth, wolf den — shows Mowgli perceives the jungle the way a wolf would, through smell rather than sight. This sensory knowledge is instinctive, not learned from books, revealing how deeply his identity is rooted in the animal world rather than the human one.'},
      {q:'Mowgli once tried to howl back at Akela, and "the younger cubs had fallen over each other in delight". What can we infer from this moment?',skill:'Inference',opts:['The cubs are testing Mowgli\'s ability to communicate as a wolf, and their playful reaction is a form of encouragement that signals he is slowly improving his skills.','The wolves accept Mowgli with genuine affection and amusement, treating his attempt to be wolf-like as endearing rather than threatening or strange.','The moment reveals the pack\'s hierarchy, with the younger cubs given freedom to play and express emotion while the older wolves maintain their composure and discipline.','Mowgli\'s howl accidentally mimics a specific wolf sound, and the cubs\' excitement comes from their surprise at hearing a recognisable pack signal from a human voice.'],c:1,e:'The cubs\' reaction — delight, not fear or rejection — shows Mowgli is genuinely loved within the pack. Their amusement at his attempt to howl suggests they see him as a charming oddity, a family member who is different but fully accepted. Even Bagheera purring reinforces this warmth.'},
      {q:'Why does the author end the passage with Mowgli stating he is "not afraid — not yet" while fear gathers around him from the pack?',skill:'Author\'s purpose & tone',opts:['To demonstrate that Mowgli\'s human nature gives him a fundamental advantage over the wolves, because humans can rationalise fear while animals are entirely governed by instinct.','To establish Mowgli as the emotional anchor of the pack, showing that the wolves instinctively look to him for reassurance and leadership during moments of collective crisis.','To create a contrast between Mowgli\'s personal composure and the collective dread of the pack, building suspense by suggesting that his courage will soon be tested.','To signal that the approaching fire will ultimately prove less dangerous than expected, since Mowgli\'s calm reaction foreshadows that the threat will pass without real harm.'],c:2,e:'The ending creates dramatic tension through contrast. Mowgli stands calm while fear rises around him like a tide. The phrase "not yet" is crucial — it promises that his composure is temporary, that something will push even Mowgli to fear. This leaves the reader on the edge, anticipating the moment when the fire becomes inescapable.'}
  ]},
  {id:'F02',title:'The Door in the Garden Wall',type:'fiction',source:'Adapted from Frances Hodgson Burnett, The Secret Garden (1911)',
   text:'Mary stood in front of the long stretch of wall, covered in dark ivy that rustled and swayed in the wind. She had been told there was a garden behind it — a garden that had been locked up for ten years, ever since the mistress of the house had died. Nobody was allowed to enter. Nobody even spoke of it. The servants changed the subject when she asked, and her uncle — the master of the house — had given strict instructions that the garden was never to be mentioned in his presence.\n\nBut Mary was not the sort of girl who accepted being told \'no\'. She had spent her childhood in India, largely ignored by her parents and left in the care of servants who gave her whatever she wanted. This had made her sour and contrary, but it had also made her fearless. Rules, in Mary\'s experience, were things that applied to other people. She had never been punished for disobedience, and so she had never learned to fear it.\n\nShe ran her fingers along the ivy, feeling the rough stone underneath. Somewhere behind this wall, there were trees that had not been pruned, flower beds that had not been weeded, and paths that no feet had walked on for a decade. The thought made her heart beat faster. She imagined roots pushing through cracked earth, branches tangled together in wild arches, and roses — if there had ever been roses — grown so tall they had swallowed their own trellises. It would not look like a garden any more. It would look like a small, secret wilderness, a place that belonged to nobody and nothing except the rain and the wind.\n\nThen her fingers found something cold and metallic, hidden beneath the leaves. A keyhole. Mary crouched down and pressed her eye against it, but she could see nothing except darkness. She tugged at the ivy around it, pulling away handful after handful until a small wooden door emerged from the greenery. It was no taller than Mary herself, weathered grey by years of rain, with a rusted iron handle that looked as though it had not been turned in a very long time. A beetle scuttled out from under the frame and disappeared into the grass.\n\nMary tried the handle. It did not move. She pulled harder, bracing her feet against the base of the wall, but the door held firm. Locked, as she had known it would be.\n\nShe stood back and stared at it. She did not have a key — not yet. But something had shifted inside her, something that felt like the first green shoot of a plant pushing through frozen ground. For the first time since arriving at this grey, draughty house on the edge of the Yorkshire moors, Mary Lennox wanted something badly enough to wait for it. She would find the key. She was certain of it. She would get inside that garden if it took her all winter.',
   questions:[
      {q:'Which theme is most strongly developed across the whole passage?',skill:'Theme',opts:['The passage develops the theme of grief and loss, showing how the locked garden represents the household\'s inability to move beyond the death of its mistress and find healing.','Curiosity and determination — the longing to discover hidden things and the willingness to pursue them.','The central theme is the contrast between the wildness of nature and the order of civilisation, with the garden symbolising what happens when human control is removed from the natural world.','The passage explores how childhood neglect shapes personality, using the garden as a backdrop to examine the lasting effects of Mary\'s isolated upbringing in India.'],c:1,e:'Every paragraph builds this theme. Mary refuses to accept \'no\' (paragraph 2), imagines the wild garden in vivid detail (paragraph 3), physically searches the wall (paragraph 4), tests the handle (paragraph 5), and commits to finding the key (paragraph 6). The passage traces a journey from idle curiosity to fierce determination.'},
      {q:'In the final paragraph, we learn that \'for the first time, Mary Lennox wanted something badly enough to wait for it\'. What does this reveal about how Mary is changing?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['Mary is learning to channel her natural stubbornness into practical problem-solving, replacing her impulsive nature with a more calculated and strategic approach to obstacles.','Mary is recognising that the garden represents something her uncle has forbidden, and her willingness to wait reflects a growing respect for the grief behind his rules.','Mary is developing patience and genuine desire for the first time — the garden is teaching her to care about something beyond her own immediate wishes.','Mary is beginning to understand that some things require physical strength she does not yet possess, and her patience is really a reluctant acceptance of her own limitations.'],c:2,e:'This is significant character development. Earlier, Mary always got what she wanted immediately. The fact that she is now willing to wait — and that wanting something this much is new for her — shows the garden is already changing her before she has even entered it.'},
      {q:'From whose point of view is this passage told, and what evidence supports your answer?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['Third person omniscient — the narrator moves freely between the perspectives of Mary, her uncle, and the servants, revealing each character\'s private thoughts and motivations.','First person — Mary narrates the passage herself using \'I\' and \'my\', filtering every observation through her own voice and emotional responses.','Third person limited — the narrator uses \'she\' and reveals only Mary\'s thoughts, feelings, and imaginings.','Second person — the narrator addresses Mary directly as \'you\', placing the reader inside her experience and creating an intimate, immersive tone throughout.'],c:2,e:'The passage uses \'she\' and \'her\' (third person) and gives us access only to Mary\'s inner world: \'The thought made her heart beat faster\', \'She imagined roots pushing through cracked earth\'. We learn about the uncle\'s instructions and servants\' behaviour, but only through Mary\'s observations — we never enter their minds directly.'},
      {q:'In the final paragraph, Mary\'s inner feeling is described as \'the first green shoot of a plant pushing through frozen ground\'. What does this metaphor suggest, and why is it particularly fitting?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['The metaphor suggests that Mary\'s stubborn nature is finally breaking down, with the frozen ground representing her old defiance crumbling under the influence of the Yorkshire countryside.','The plant imagery implies that Mary\'s loneliness has reached a breaking point, and the green shoot represents her desperate need for human companionship rather than interest in the garden itself.','A new sense of hope and purpose is beginning to grow inside Mary — and the plant imagery mirrors the garden she is trying to reach, connecting her inner growth to the garden\'s potential rebirth.','The frozen ground represents the uncle\'s grief and the green shoot suggests that Mary\'s presence will heal his emotional wounds before she ever finds the garden door.'],c:2,e:'The metaphor works on two levels. Literally, it describes something small and new emerging from harsh conditions — matching Mary\'s first experience of genuine desire. But it also mirrors the garden itself, which has been locked in a kind of frozen state for ten years. Mary\'s emotional growth and the garden\'s physical revival are symbolically linked.'},
      {q:'In paragraph three, Mary imagines roses that have \'swallowed their own trellises\'. What does this word choice suggest?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['The word suggests gentle, gradual growth over time, with the roses slowly and carefully winding around the trellises in a way that emphasises the garden\'s quiet beauty.','The roses have grown so wildly and powerfully that they have completely engulfed their supports — nature has reclaimed the garden with an almost aggressive force.','The word implies decay and destruction, suggesting the roses have rotted along with the trellises, and the garden is now a dead and lifeless space rather than a wild one.','The language suggests the trellises were poorly built and could not withstand even normal growth, emphasising the neglect of the garden\'s original design rather than nature\'s power.'],c:1,e:'\'Swallowed\' personifies the roses, giving them an active, almost predatory quality. It suggests that ten years of neglect have allowed nature to take over completely. This wild, untamed imagery makes the garden feel both beautiful and slightly intimidating, deepening Mary\'s fascination.'},
      {q:'What is the main idea of the passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['The passage centres on the servants gradually revealing the full tragic history of the garden, giving Mary the knowledge she needs to understand her uncle\'s grief and isolation.','The passage traces Mary\'s growing respect for her uncle\'s authority, showing how she learns to accept the boundaries adults set and finds peace in obedience.','A lonely, stubborn girl discovers a hidden garden door and becomes consumed by the desire to find a way inside, marking the beginning of her emotional transformation.','The passage focuses on the contrast between Mary\'s privileged life in India and her new life in Yorkshire, exploring how a change of environment reshapes a child\'s personality.'],c:2,e:'The passage traces Mary\'s journey from hearing about the forbidden garden to physically discovering its door and resolving to find the key. The main idea centres on this discovery sparking something new inside Mary — a desire strong enough to teach her patience, which represents the start of her inner change.'},
      {q:'How would you describe the tone of paragraph three, where Mary imagines the garden\'s interior?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Melancholy and mournful — the descriptions of unpruned trees and unweeded flower beds emphasise decay and loss, creating sadness for the garden\'s former beauty.','Suspenseful and foreboding — the imagery of tangled branches and swallowed trellises suggests the garden has become a threatening, dangerous space that Mary should fear.','Defiant and rebellious — the paragraph reflects Mary\'s determination to break rules, with the wild garden symbolising her own refusal to be controlled by adults.','Dreamy and enchanted — the vivid, almost magical descriptions of wild growth create a sense of wonder and longing.'],c:3,e:'Paragraph three is rich with imaginative imagery: "roots pushing through cracked earth, branches tangled together in wild arches." The language is lush and slightly fantastical, creating a tone of enchantment. Mary is not just curious — she is captivated, and the dreamy tone reflects her emotional state.'},
      {q:'What can we infer about Mary\'s upbringing from the detail that "rules, in Mary\'s experience, were things that applied to other people"?',skill:'Inference',opts:['Mary was so neglected and indulged that she never learned boundaries, making her both spoiled and independent in a way that serves her well in this situation.','Mary grew up with strict but loving parents who enforced clear boundaries, and her defiance of rules reflects a teenage rebellion against their expectations.','Mary learned to break rules strategically in India as a deliberate way of gaining the attention her emotionally distant parents withheld from her.','Mary\'s view of rules as meaningless comes from watching Indian servants ignore household instructions, teaching her that authority figures rarely enforce their commands.'],c:0,e:'The passage tells us Mary was "largely ignored" and servants "gave her whatever she wanted." This neglect paradoxically created both negative traits (she is "sour and contrary") and useful ones (she is fearless and persistent). Her disregard for rules, born from neglect, is exactly what drives her to pursue the forbidden garden.'},
      {q:'The passage describes the garden door as "no taller than Mary herself, weathered grey by years of rain, with a rusted iron handle." How does this description contribute to the atmosphere?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['The physical details build sympathy for the uncle — the rusted handle and weathered wood remind the reader of his decade of grief, shifting attention from Mary\'s excitement to his suffering.','The small, worn, hidden door creates an atmosphere of secrecy and timelessness, suggesting something forgotten and precious waiting to be rediscovered.','The worn, hidden door mirrors Mary\'s own emotional state — she too has been neglected and overlooked, and the parallel between girl and door strengthens their symbolic connection.','The child-sized door and natural decay suggest the garden has been slowly preparing for Mary\'s arrival, creating an almost fairy-tale sense that the garden has chosen her specifically.'],c:1,e:'Every detail reinforces the atmosphere of long abandonment: the door is child-sized (intimate, secret), weathered grey (aged, neglected), and has a rusted handle (unused for years). Even the beetle scuttling away suggests undisturbed solitude. Together, these details make the garden feel like a buried treasure waiting for someone brave enough to uncover it.'},
      {q:'The passage mentions that Mary\'s uncle "had given strict instructions that the garden was never to be mentioned in his presence." What can we infer about the uncle\'s emotional state?',skill:'Inference',opts:['The garden is so closely tied to his dead wife\'s memory that even hearing it mentioned causes him pain, suggesting deep unresolved grief.','The uncle is a controlling man who enjoys exercising power over his household, and the ban on mentioning the garden is one of many strict rules designed to maintain his authority.','The uncle is angry at the servants for failing to maintain the garden properly, and his prohibition reflects frustration with their negligence rather than any emotional attachment to the space.','The uncle considers the garden dangerous because it has become overgrown and structurally unsafe, and his instruction is a practical safety measure to protect the household from injury.'],c:0,e:'The uncle\'s prohibition is extreme — not just that nobody should enter the garden, but that nobody should even speak of it near him. This level of avoidance strongly implies that the garden is bound up with his grief for his dead wife. He cannot bear even the reminder, which tells us his grief is still raw after ten years.'},
      {q:'How does the author use the structure of paragraph four to create a sense of discovery?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['The paragraph moves from touch to sight to physical action, mirroring Mary\'s step-by-step discovery as her fingers find the keyhole, her eyes search, and her hands tear away the ivy.','The paragraph builds tension by alternating between hope and disappointment — Mary finds the keyhole but cannot see through it, finds the door but cannot open it, creating a pattern of raised and dashed expectations.','The paragraph uses increasingly long sentences to mirror the growing size of Mary\'s discovery, with short phrases for the keyhole expanding into detailed description as the full door is revealed.','The paragraph contrasts the natural world (ivy, beetle, grass) with the man-made world (door, handle, keyhole), structuring the discovery around the tension between nature\'s concealment and human construction.'],c:0,e:'The paragraph is structured as a sequence of sensory discoveries: first Mary feels something cold and metallic (touch), then she presses her eye to the keyhole (sight), then she pulls away ivy to reveal the door (action). This step-by-step structure makes the reader experience the discovery in real time alongside Mary, building excitement with each new detail.'},
      {q:'How does the author use Mary\'s character flaws to drive the plot forward in this passage?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['Mary\'s loneliness is the main driver — she searches for the garden not out of defiance but because she desperately wants a private space where she can escape the cold, unwelcoming house.','Mary\'s stubbornness and refusal to accept "no" — traits born from neglect — are precisely what motivate her to search the wall and commit to finding the key.','Mary\'s curiosity about nature is the key trait — her childhood in India gave her a love of gardens and plants, and she is drawn to the wall by botanical interest rather than rebelliousness.','Mary\'s anger at her uncle\'s strict rules is what drives her — she searches for the garden specifically because it has been forbidden, and her motivation is revenge against his authority rather than genuine desire.'],c:1,e:'Burnett deliberately frames Mary\'s negative traits as plot engines. Her contrariness, fearlessness, and disregard for rules — all consequences of a neglectful upbringing — are exactly the qualities needed to pursue a forbidden garden. The passage shows how flaws can become strengths when channelled in the right direction.'}
  ]},
  {id:'F03',title:'The Map in the Captain\'s Chest',type:'fiction',source:'Adapted from Robert Louis Stevenson, Treasure Island (1883)',
   text:'The old sea captain had been dead for less than an hour when my mother and I broke open his chest. We had every right to do so — he owed us weeks of rent, and his room at the Admiral Benbow inn smelled of rum and tobacco and something else I could not name. Something old and slightly rotten, like seaweed left too long in the sun.\n\nThe chest itself was battered and salt-stained, with brass corners that had turned green with age. My mother\'s hands trembled as she lifted the lid, though whether from cold or fear I could not tell. Inside, on top of a folded suit of good cloth and a pair of pistols, was a canvas bundle tied with string. I cut the string with my father\'s old knife and unrolled the canvas carefully.\n\nWhat fell out made my heart stop. A map. Not a printed map from a shop, but a hand-drawn chart on thick, yellowed paper, with compass lines radiating from the corners and tiny inked numbers marking depths along a coastline I did not recognise. In the centre of the island — for it was clearly an island, roughly the shape of a fat dragon standing upright — three crosses had been drawn in red ink. Beside the largest cross, in a cramped and careful hand, someone had written: \'Bulk of treasure here.\'\n\nI stared at the words until they blurred. Treasure. Real treasure, hidden on a real island, and the map to find it was sitting in my hands in a cold, dark room above a village inn. The idea was so enormous that for a moment I could not think at all. It was as if someone had opened a door in the wall of my ordinary life and shown me a vast, terrifying ocean on the other side.\n\nMy mother said something about taking what we were owed and leaving the rest. She was a practical woman — she counted the coins in the chest with steady hands and took exactly what the captain owed us, not a penny more. But I barely heard her. My mind was already out at sea, already following those compass lines towards an island I had never seen.\n\nI folded the map and put it inside my shirt, next to my skin, where I could feel the stiff paper crinkle with every breath. I did not know then what that map would cost me — the danger, the treachery, the friends I would lose along the way. All I knew was that my life in the village was over. The map had seen to that. Some things, once seen, cannot be unseen, and some doors, once opened, cannot be closed again.',
   questions:[
      {q:'From whose point of view is this passage narrated, and how does the narration style affect the story?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['Second person — the narrator addresses the reader directly as \'you\', creating the sensation that the reader is opening the chest and discovering the map themselves.','Third person omniscient — the narrator reveals both Jim\'s and his mother\'s private thoughts, allowing the reader to understand why she remains practical while he becomes consumed by the map.','First person — the narrator is Jim Hawkins, telling the story from his own perspective, which means we experience events through his emotions and limited knowledge.','Third person limited — an outside narrator describes Jim\'s actions and surroundings but does not reveal his inner thoughts, leaving the reader to infer his emotions from his behaviour alone.'],c:2,e:'The passage uses \'I\', \'my\', and \'we\' — Jim is telling his own story. This first-person narration means we experience his shock (\'my heart stop\'), his distraction (\'I barely heard her\'), and his foreshadowing (\'I did not know then what that map would cost me\') directly. We only know what Jim knows, which creates suspense.'},
      {q:'Jim describes finding the map as if \'someone had opened a door in the wall of my ordinary life and shown me a vast, terrifying ocean on the other side\'. What does this metaphor suggest?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['The discovery has shattered Jim\'s normal, predictable existence and revealed a world of adventure that is both thrilling and frightening.','The metaphor suggests Jim feels trapped and suffocated by village life, and the ocean represents his longing to escape the responsibilities of running the inn.','Jim is realising the door image implies he has been deliberately shut out from knowledge by the adults around him, and the map finally reveals their secrets.','The metaphor warns the reader that the map will lead Jim into physical danger at sea, with the "terrifying ocean" foreshadowing the specific shipwreck that awaits him on the voyage.'],c:0,e:'The metaphor contrasts Jim\'s \'ordinary life\' (the village, the inn) with the \'vast, terrifying ocean\' (adventure, danger, the unknown). The door represents a point of no return — once opened, Jim\'s old world is no longer enough. The word \'terrifying\' is important: this isn\'t pure excitement but a mixture of wonder and fear.'},
      {q:'The final paragraph states that \'some things, once seen, cannot be unseen, and some doors, once opened, cannot be closed again\'. Which theme does this support?',skill:'Theme',opts:['The bond between parent and child is tested by ambition — Jim\'s willingness to hide the map from his mother shows that greed can erode even the closest family relationships.','Discovery changes you permanently — once you glimpse a larger world, you cannot return to your old life unchanged.','Innocence must be sacrificed for growth — Jim\'s loss of his childhood is presented as a necessary and positive step towards becoming an adult who can face the world\'s dangers.','Wealth and treasure corrupt those who pursue them — the passage presents the map as a temptation that will ultimately destroy Jim\'s moral character and the values his mother represents.'],c:1,e:'This theme runs through the whole passage. Jim goes from an ordinary village boy to someone whose \'mind was already out at sea\'. The map doesn\'t just show him an island — it transforms his sense of what\'s possible. The final sentence frames this as irreversible: knowledge and discovery change who you are.'},
      {q:'How does the contrast between Jim and his mother help develop Jim\'s character?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['It reveals that Jim\'s mother is the more courageous of the two — while Jim is frozen with shock, she calmly takes charge, showing the practical bravery that Jim has yet to develop.','It highlights Jim\'s impractical, dreaming nature against his mother\'s steadiness — she counts coins while he imagines oceans, showing that the map has already pulled him away from his ordinary world.','It presents Jim\'s mother as a moral compass — by taking only what she is owed, she models the honesty and integrity that Jim will need to survive the treachery the final paragraph foreshadows.','It suggests a generational divide — the mother belongs to a world of honest wages and careful accounts, while Jim belongs to a new era of risk and adventure, and neither can fully understand the other.'],c:1,e:'The mother is practical: she takes \'exactly what the captain owed us, not a penny more\'. Jim barely hears her — his mind is \'already out at sea\'. This contrast shows that the map has immediately begun to separate Jim from his everyday life and the people in it. His mother represents the world he is about to leave.'},
      {q:'How would you describe the tone of the final paragraph, and what creates it?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Ominous and foreboding — the older narrator deliberately withholds details to frighten the reader, using dark hints about \'treachery\' and loss to create a mood of pure dread and warning.','Reflective and bittersweet — Jim looks back with the knowledge of what the adventure would cost him, creating a sense of lost innocence.','Triumphant and resolute — despite mentioning danger, Jim\'s certainty that his village life was over celebrates his escape from a dull existence, making the tone primarily one of liberation.','Regretful and guilt-ridden — the phrase \'what that map would cost me\' reveals that the older Jim blames himself for everything that followed, and the paragraph is an admission of his mistake.'],c:1,e:'The final paragraph is told from a future perspective: \'I did not know then what that map would cost me — the danger, the treachery, the friends I would lose\'. This creates a bittersweet, reflective tone — older Jim looking back at the moment his childhood ended. He doesn\'t regret it, but he understands the price.'},
      {q:'How does the author use sensory details in the opening paragraph to establish the setting and mood?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['The sensory details characterise the dead captain as a lonely, self-destructive man — the smells of rum and tobacco paint a picture of his unhealthy habits, building sympathy for a wasted life.','The smells establish the coastal setting by connecting the inn to the sea — the seaweed reference and salt-air associations remind the reader of the maritime world the treasure map will soon reveal.','The sensory details convey Jim\'s nervousness about searching a dead man\'s room — the way he notices every smell shows his heightened alertness, revealing fear rather than establishing mood.','Details of rum, tobacco, and "something old and slightly rotten, like seaweed left too long in the sun" create a mood of decay and unease that foreshadows the dark discovery within the chest.'],c:3,e:'The opening engages smell — rum, tobacco, and rot — to create discomfort before anything dangerous has happened. The simile about seaweed adds a nautical flavour that connects the captain to the sea even in death. These details establish a mood of decay and foreboding that prepares the reader for the sinister discovery of the map.'},
      {q:'What does Jim\'s decision to put the map "inside my shirt, next to my skin" reveal about his character?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['It shows that Jim has already claimed the map as personally his, holding it close to his body as though it is part of him, revealing how deeply the discovery has affected him.','It reveals Jim\'s fear that others will try to take the map — placing it against his skin is a practical security measure, showing he already suspects the danger the map will bring.','It suggests Jim feels guilty about keeping the map and is hiding it from his mother, whose honest character makes her unlikely to approve of chasing pirate treasure.','It demonstrates Jim\'s respect for the dead captain — by keeping the map close, Jim is honouring the captain\'s legacy and treating the map as a sacred trust rather than stolen property.'],c:0,e:'Placing the map against his skin is an intimate act — Jim is not just carrying the map but absorbing it into himself. He can feel it "crinkle with every breath," connecting the map to his very life force. This physical closeness mirrors the emotional grip the map already has on him; it has become inseparable from his identity.'},
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['The passage explores the close bond between Jim and his mother, showing how they work together to handle the captain\'s possessions and make responsible decisions about what to do with his belongings.','A boy\'s discovery of a treasure map in a dead man\'s chest transforms his understanding of the world and sets him on an irreversible path towards adventure.','The passage is primarily a character study of the dead sea captain, using the objects in his chest to reconstruct his life story and explain how a man of the sea ended up dying alone in a village inn.','The passage examines how Jim copes with his father\'s absence — the detail of cutting string with \'my father\'s old knife\' suggests that loss and inheritance, not treasure, are the central concerns.'],c:1,e:'The passage traces Jim\'s transformation from an ordinary village boy to someone whose life has been permanently altered by a single discovery. The map does not just promise treasure — it shatters his old world. The main idea is that some discoveries fundamentally change who you are and make returning to your previous life impossible.'},
      {q:'The map shows an island "roughly the shape of a fat dragon standing upright." Why might the author have chosen this particular comparison?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['The dragon comparison makes the island seem alive and monstrous, suggesting that the land itself is a hostile enemy Jim will have to defeat — the island is not just a location but an adversary.','A dragon suggests danger, mystery, and treasure-guarding — all associations that make the island feel both thrilling and threatening before Jim has even set foot on it.','The comparison highlights Jim\'s childish imagination — seeing a dragon in a map\'s outline reveals his immaturity and suggests he is romanticising a journey that will prove far grimmer than he expects.','The \'fat dragon standing upright\' creates a humorous, slightly absurd image that lightens the passage\'s dark tone, reminding the reader that Jim is still a child playing with adult possibilities.'],c:1,e:'Dragons in literature are associated with guarding treasure, danger, and the unknown. By making the island dragon-shaped, Stevenson layers these associations onto the map itself. Before Jim knows anything about the island, its very shape promises both the treasure he desires and the danger he will face getting it.'},
      {q:'How does the author build suspense in paragraph three when Jim unrolls the canvas?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['The paragraph builds suspense through Jim\'s emotional reactions rather than physical description — his racing heart and trembling hands tell the reader something important is happening before the map is fully revealed.','The paragraph delays revealing the map by describing the canvas, compass lines, inked numbers, and coastline before finally revealing the red crosses and the words "Bulk of treasure here," creating a slow reveal that mirrors Jim\'s own growing excitement.','Suspense comes from the contrast between the ordinary chest contents (a suit, pistols) and the extraordinary map — the mundane items set low expectations, making the map\'s appearance more shocking.','The paragraph creates suspense by switching between Jim\'s perspective and his mother\'s — her trembling hands and his racing thoughts alternate, building tension from two viewpoints simultaneously.'],c:1,e:'Stevenson structures the discovery as a layered unveiling. First Jim sees it is a map, then that it is hand-drawn, then that it shows an island, then the red crosses, and finally the words. Each layer adds more significance, and the reader\'s anticipation builds with Jim\'s. The climactic phrase "Bulk of treasure here" lands with full impact because of this careful pacing.'},
      {q:'What can we infer about the dead sea captain from the contents of his chest?',skill:'Inference',opts:['The contents reveal a man preparing to flee — the suit for disguise, the pistols for protection, and the map as his escape plan, suggesting the captain was running from someone when he arrived at the inn.','The careful preservation of the map alongside personal items suggests the captain valued it sentimentally rather than financially — it was a memento of his seafaring days, not a guide he intended to follow.','The mix of a good suit, pistols, and a treasure map suggests a man who lived a double life — outwardly respectable but secretly connected to piracy and hidden wealth.','The good suit and carefully drawn map suggest a man of education and discipline — likely a former naval officer whose knowledge of navigation and cartography came from legitimate military service.'],c:2,e:'A "folded suit of good cloth" suggests the captain could appear respectable. Pistols suggest danger and violence. A hand-drawn treasure map suggests piracy. Together, these items paint a picture of a man who straddled two worlds — the respectable surface of society and the violent underworld of pirate treasure. His death at a village inn adds to the sense of a man hiding from his past.'},
      {q:'Why does Jim describe the idea of the treasure as "so enormous that for a moment I could not think at all"?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['To highlight the physical danger of the situation — Jim is so frightened by the implications of the map that his body freezes, revealing that his first response to the discovery is terror rather than excitement.','To show that Jim already suspects the map will cause harm — his inability to think clearly is an instinctive warning that he is about to make a decision he will regret, foreshadowing the final paragraph\'s darker tone.','To convey that the discovery has overwhelmed Jim\'s ordinary mind — the sheer scale of possibility has temporarily short-circuited his ability to process reality, marking the moment his old life begins to dissolve.','To emphasise Jim\'s youth and inexperience — an adult would have immediately assessed the map\'s practical value, but Jim is too young to process what he has found, revealing his childish inability to handle serious situations.'],c:2,e:'This moment of mental paralysis is significant because it captures the instant of transformation. Jim\'s old frame of reference — village, inn, ordinary life — cannot contain the concept of real treasure on a real island. The momentary inability to think marks the gap between who Jim was and who he is about to become.'}
  ]},
  {id:'F04',title:'The Trial of the Knave',type:'fiction',source:'Adapted from Lewis Carroll, Alice\'s Adventures in Wonderland (1865)',
   text:'The courtroom was unlike any Alice had ever imagined. The jury box was filled with twelve creatures — lizards, mice, a duck, and several animals Alice could not name — all scribbling furiously on tiny slates. The King of Hearts sat on his throne with his crown balanced crookedly on his head, looking important but slightly confused, as though he had wandered into the wrong room and decided to stay. Beside him, the Queen of Hearts glared at everything and everyone, her face as red as the hearts embroidered on her enormous collar.\n\nThe accused was the Knave of Hearts, a thin, nervous-looking card who stood in chains between two soldiers. He was charged with stealing the Queen\'s tarts — an offence which, in this kingdom, appeared to be considered as serious as treason.\n\n\'Call the first witness!\' the King announced, and a trumpet blew so loudly that the duck in the jury box fell off its chair.\n\nThe Mad Hatter shuffled forward, clutching a teacup in one hand and a slice of bread-and-butter in the other. He bowed to the King, then to the jury, then to a potted plant that was not involved in the proceedings.\n\n\'Give your evidence,\' said the King, \'and don\'t be nervous, or I\'ll have you executed on the spot.\'\n\nAlice thought this was a remarkably unhelpful thing to say to a nervous witness. The Hatter\'s hands shook so badly that tea slopped over the rim of his cup and splashed onto the jury\'s notes. The duck quacked in outrage.\n\n\'I\'m a poor man, Your Majesty,\' the Hatter began. \'And I hadn\'t but just begun my tea — not above a week ago — when —\'\n\n\'What day did you begin?\' interrupted the King.\n\n\'The fourteenth of March, I think,\' said the Hatter.\n\n\'Fifteenth,\' said the March Hare.\n\n\'Sixteenth,\' said the Dormouse.\n\n\'Write all three dates down,\' the King told the jury importantly, as though this settled something. The jury obediently wrote all three dates on their slates, then added them up and converted the answer into shillings and pence.\n\nAlice watched all of this with growing astonishment. She had believed — because she had been taught to believe — that courts existed to find the truth. Evidence was supposed to be examined carefully. Witnesses were supposed to be treated with respect. Judgements were supposed to be fair. But nothing in this courtroom worked the way it should. The jury was adding up dates as if they were sums. The King was threatening witnesses. The Queen was calling for executions before the trial had even properly begun.\n\nIt struck Alice, quite suddenly, that the most dangerous thing about this courtroom was not the Queen\'s temper. It was the fact that everyone was pretending that something ridiculous was perfectly normal.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the deeper theme of this passage, beyond the surface comedy?',skill:'Theme',opts:['The passage explores the importance of speaking up against injustice — Alice learns that staying silent makes her complicit in the court\'s cruelty, and her growing astonishment represents her moral awakening.','Carroll uses the trial to satirise the class system, with the animal jury representing the uneducated masses who blindly follow the orders of a ruling class that does not serve their interests.','The passage is a commentary on the unreliability of memory and testimony — the conflicting dates from the Hatter, March Hare, and Dormouse show that no witness can be fully trusted.','Authority and justice can be absurd and dangerous when people in power act irrationally and nobody challenges them.'],c:3,e:'Beneath the humour, the passage makes a serious point. The King threatens execution, the Queen demands it, the jury converts dates into money, and nobody questions any of it. Alice\'s final realisation — that the most dangerous thing is everyone pretending \'something ridiculous was perfectly normal\' — is a commentary on how unjust systems survive when people go along with them.'},
      {q:'How does the tone shift between the main body of the passage and Alice\'s reflection in the final two paragraphs?',skill:'Tone',opts:['It shifts from confused and disoriented to amused and entertained — Alice starts bewildered by the courtroom but gradually comes to enjoy its absurdity as harmless entertainment.','The tone remains comedic throughout — even Alice\'s final thoughts are delivered with light irony, and the passage never genuinely suggests the court\'s behaviour is dangerous or threatening.','It shifts from objective observation to personal anger — Alice becomes increasingly furious at the court\'s treatment of the Hatter, and her final paragraphs express outrage rather than insight.','It shifts from chaotic and comedic to thoughtful and disturbing — Alice realises the absurdity has a darker meaning.'],c:3,e:'Most of the passage is slapstick comedy: the duck falling off its chair, the Hatter bowing to a plant, the jury converting dates to money. But the final two paragraphs shift to Alice\'s serious internal reflection. She compares what courts should be with what this one is, and her final thought — about the danger of normalising the absurd — is genuinely unsettling.'},
      {q:'The King says \'don\'t be nervous, or I\'ll have you executed on the spot\'. What technique is Carroll using, and what is its effect?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['Hyperbole — the King is exaggerating for effect, using an extreme threat he does not actually intend to carry out in order to emphasise the seriousness of the proceedings.','Dramatic irony — the reader knows the King has no real power over the Hatter, but the Hatter himself genuinely believes the threat, creating tension between the audience\'s knowledge and the character\'s fear.','Irony — telling someone not to be nervous while threatening to kill them is contradictory, highlighting the absurd cruelty of the court.','Characterisation through dialogue — the line reveals the King as a stern but well-intentioned authority figure who is trying to calm the Hatter down, even if his choice of words is clumsy.'],c:2,e:'The statement is ironic because the instruction (\'don\'t be nervous\') directly contradicts the threat (\'I\'ll have you executed\'). Carroll uses this to expose the court\'s irrational cruelty while making the reader laugh. The humour makes the criticism more effective — we see how absurd the authority is.'},
      {q:'Why does the author include the detail about the jury adding up the three dates and converting them into shillings and pence?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['To show that Wonderland operates on its own internal logic — the jury converts dates to money because in this world, time and currency are genuinely equivalent, following rules that are consistent within the story even if strange to Alice.','To satirise the obsession with record-keeping in real courts — the jury writes everything down with exaggerated thoroughness, mocking how real legal systems can prioritise documentation over actual understanding.','To demonstrate how completely meaningless the court\'s procedures are — they treat nonsensical information as though it is serious evidence, highlighting the breakdown of logic.','To reveal that the jury members are more competent than they appear — their ability to perform quick calculations suggests hidden intelligence beneath their chaotic exterior, complicating Alice\'s assumption that the court is entirely foolish.'],c:2,e:'Three different witnesses give three different dates, and the King treats all three as equally valid. The jury then does maths with them as if the result means something. This escalation of nonsense — from contradictory evidence to meaningless calculation — satirises how institutions can process information that has no real value and present it as legitimate.'},
      {q:'Alice\'s final thought is that \'the most dangerous thing about this courtroom was not the Queen\'s temper\' but \'the fact that everyone was pretending that something ridiculous was perfectly normal\'. What does the word \'pretending\' suggest here?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['\'Pretending\' suggests the court\'s behaviour is a deliberate performance staged for Alice\'s benefit — the creatures are testing her to see whether she will challenge the absurdity or accept it passively.','The court\'s participants are not genuinely fooled — on some level they know the proceedings are absurd, but they choose to go along with it, which makes the injustice a collective choice rather than an accident.','\'Pretending\' reveals that the court\'s absurdity is actually a clever disguise — the animals are deliberately acting foolish to distract from the real judicial process happening behind the scenes.','\'Pretending\' implies that the characters are innocent and unaware — they genuinely believe they are conducting a fair trial, and the word highlights the gap between their good intentions and the ridiculous reality.'],c:1,e:'\'Pretending\' implies awareness. If Carroll had written \'believing\', it would suggest the characters genuinely think the court is fair. \'Pretending\' suggests complicity — they participate in absurdity because challenging it (especially with the Queen threatening execution) is too dangerous. This makes Alice\'s insight more powerful: injustice survives not through ignorance but through silent cooperation.'},
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['The passage examines how fear controls behaviour in Wonderland — the Queen\'s threat of execution silences opposition, and the main idea is that tyranny survives because people are too frightened to resist.','The passage is primarily a character study of Alice, tracing her journey from a polite, rule-following child to someone beginning to question the adult world\'s authority and logic.','The passage satirises the British legal system\'s reliance on ceremony and tradition, arguing that real courts — like Wonderland\'s — often prioritise procedure and formality over genuine justice.','A courtroom that is supposed to deliver justice instead operates through absurdity and intimidation, and the greatest danger lies in everyone accepting this as normal.'],c:3,e:'The passage builds through increasingly absurd courtroom behaviour — threats, irrelevant testimony, mathematical nonsense — towards Alice\'s final insight that the real danger is not the Queen\'s anger but the collective pretence that absurdity is normality. The main idea is about the failure of justice when authority goes unchallenged.'},
      {q:'From whose point of view do we experience the trial, and why is this perspective important?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['Third person limited through Alice — her outsider perspective allows the reader to see the absurdity that the Wonderland characters treat as normal, making the satire work.','Third person omniscient — the narrator reveals the inner thoughts of Alice, the King, and the Hatter equally, showing how each character interprets the same events from their own logic.','Second person — the narrator addresses the reader directly as \'you\', creating the effect that you are sitting in the courtroom alongside the jury, witnessing the trial yourself.','First person through the King of Hearts — the King narrates the proceedings from the bench, revealing his private reasoning behind each decision and showing that he believes his judgements are fair.'],c:0,e:'We see everything through Alice\'s eyes. Because she comes from the real world and knows how courts should work, she can recognise what the Wonderland characters cannot — that the proceedings are absurd. Without Alice\'s outsider perspective, the satire would not function because there would be no standard of normality against which to measure the madness.'},
      {q:'What does Alice\'s observation that courts should examine evidence "carefully" and treat witnesses "with respect" reveal about her character?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['Alice is naively applying idealistic rules she learned at school without understanding that the real world — even outside Wonderland — rarely lives up to such standards, revealing her sheltered upbringing.','Alice is using her knowledge of court procedure to plan her own intervention — her observations are strategic rather than moral, as she prepares to challenge the King\'s authority directly.','Alice\'s internal monologue about how courts should work reveals her as a conformist — she is uncomfortable not because the trial is unjust but because it does not follow the proper rules she has been taught.','Alice has a strong moral compass and a rational mind — she holds firm ideas about fairness and justice that allow her to see through the court\'s absurdity.'],c:3,e:'Alice\'s internal comparison between how courts should work and how this one does work reveals her to be thoughtful, principled, and clear-headed. Despite being a child in a bewildering world, she maintains her own standards of fairness. This moral clarity is what enables the passage\'s final, powerful insight about the danger of collective pretence.'},
      {q:'Why does Carroll describe the King\'s crown as "balanced crookedly on his head" and his expression as "slightly confused, as though he had wandered into the wrong room and decided to stay"?',skill:'Inference',opts:['To create sympathy for the King — the crooked crown and confused expression suggest he is overwhelmed by responsibilities he never wanted, making him a victim of his position rather than an incompetent ruler.','To contrast the King with the Queen — his confusion and informality are presented as gentleness compared to her fury, suggesting he is a moderating force who tries to soften her harsh judgements.','To suggest that the King has no real authority or competence — his power is accidental and superficial, symbolised by a crown that does not even sit straight.','To signal that the King\'s authority is theatrical and performative — like an actor in costume, he wears the trappings of power without truly inhabiting the role, which makes the trial feel like a staged play.'],c:2,e:'The crooked crown and confused expression undermine the King\'s authority from his very first appearance. A judge should command respect and understanding, but this King seems bewildered by his own courtroom. Carroll uses these physical details to signal that the person running the trial is fundamentally unqualified, which makes every subsequent decision suspect.'},
      {q:'How does the author use the Hatter\'s testimony about when he began his tea to create humour and make a deeper point?',skill:'Author\'s purpose & tone',opts:['The three different dates create a sense of mystery, encouraging the reader to work out which date is correct and whether the truth of the testimony matters to the outcome of the trial.','The contradictory dates from three witnesses, all treated as valid, satirise how institutions can treat meaningless information as significant, creating humour that carries serious social criticism.','The contradictory dates expose the unreliability of all eyewitness testimony — Carroll is making the serious point that memory is always flawed, even when witnesses are trying to be honest.','The scene develops the Hatter\'s character by showing his anxiety and vulnerability — his inability to remember a simple date reveals the psychological toll of living under the Queen\'s constant threat of execution.'],c:1,e:'Three witnesses give three different dates for the same event. Instead of recognising this as contradictory, the King orders all three recorded. The jury then converts them to money. This escalating absurdity is funny, but it also mirrors how real institutions can process worthless information with great ceremony, creating an illusion of legitimate procedure.'},
      {q:'The passage describes the Knave of Hearts as "a thin, nervous-looking card who stood in chains between two soldiers." What does the word "thin" suggest in this context?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['It draws a visual parallel between the Knave and the Hatter, who is also described as anxious — the shared physical frailty links the two characters and suggests that anyone in Wonderland could end up accused.','It suggests vulnerability and powerlessness — the Knave is physically diminished, making the full force of the court\'s authority against him seem disproportionate and unjust.','It works as a double meaning — \'thin\' describes both his physical appearance and the thinness of the case against him, subtly signalling to the reader that the charges are weak before the trial even begins.','It contrasts the Knave with the well-fed Queen, whose \'enormous collar\' suggests excess — the thin accused and the extravagant monarch represent the imbalance of power that the passage critiques.'],c:1,e:'Describing the accused as "thin" and "nervous-looking" before we even know the charge creates sympathy. When we then learn he is charged with stealing tarts — and that this is treated like treason — the contrast between his frail appearance and the severity of his treatment sharpens the satire. The word "thin" makes the court\'s aggression feel like bullying.'},
      {q:'What is the effect of the final sentence standing as its own short paragraph?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['The short final paragraph creates a cliffhanger, encouraging the reader to continue to the next chapter to find out whether Alice will speak up and challenge the court\'s proceedings.','The separated final sentence mirrors Alice\'s isolation — she is the only one who sees the truth, and the structural separation reflects her intellectual separation from the Wonderland characters around her.','Isolating Alice\'s key realisation in its own paragraph gives it emphasis and weight, forcing the reader to pause and absorb the passage\'s most important insight.','The final paragraph works as a punchline — after the long, detailed build-up of courtroom chaos, the sudden brevity creates a comedic snap that makes the reader laugh at the absurdity of the whole scene.'],c:2,e:'After paragraphs of chaotic, detailed courtroom action, the final sentence lands in its own space: the most dangerous thing is everyone pretending absurdity is normal. The structural isolation mirrors the insight\'s importance — it is the passage\'s thesis statement, and giving it its own paragraph forces the reader to sit with it rather than rushing past.'}
  ]},
  {id:'F05',title:'The Red Weed',type:'fiction',source:'Adapted from H.G. Wells, The War of the Worlds (1898)',
   text:'By the third day after the Martians landed, the landscape around Woking had changed in ways that seemed impossible. Where there had been neat English fields and hedgerows, a strange red weed was spreading — a plant unlike anything that had ever grown on Earth. It crept along the ground in thick, ropy tendrils, climbing walls and smothering fences, turning the familiar green countryside into something alien and unsettling.\n\nI first noticed it when I ventured out from the coal cellar where I had been hiding. The road that had once led to the railway station was barely recognisable. The red weed had crawled across the pavement and wrapped itself around the iron railings of the footbridge. It grew with terrifying speed — I could almost see it moving, reaching outward like fingers searching for something to grip. A pillar box that had stood on the corner for as long as I could remember was now entirely enclosed in a cage of dark crimson stems.\n\nThe weed seemed to thrive wherever there was water. The stream that ran behind the church had become a sluggish red river, choked with the stuff, and the air above it carried a strange, faintly metallic smell that caught in the back of my throat. I covered my mouth with my sleeve and kept walking, though every instinct told me to turn back.\n\nWhat disturbed me most was not the weed itself but what it meant. The Martians were not merely invaders — they were colonisers. They had not come to destroy our world. They had come to replace it. The red weed was their plant, brought from their dying planet, and it was displacing ours with ruthless efficiency. Our grass, our wildflowers, our ancient oaks — all of it was being buried beneath this creeping, alien carpet. England was being terraformed, reshaped to suit creatures that breathed a different air and fed on different soil.\n\nI stood at the crest of the hill and looked out across what had been, just a week ago, the most ordinary landscape in Surrey. Now it looked like the surface of Mars — or what I imagined Mars to look like. Red as far as the eye could see, broken only by the grey spire of the church and the dark line of the railway cutting.\n\nA thought came to me then that was worse than any I had had since the invasion began. It was not the thought that I might die. I had accepted that possibility days ago. It was the thought that even if every human being survived, we might have no world left to live in. The Martians did not need to kill us. They only needed to change the ground beneath our feet.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['The passage focuses on the narrator\'s personal survival journey as he escapes from hiding and searches for other survivors across the devastated English countryside.','The passage examines how the narrator copes with isolation and loneliness during the invasion, using the red weed as a symbol of his deteriorating mental health and growing despair.','The Martian invasion threatens not just human lives but the Earth\'s entire natural environment — the red weed represents colonisation and replacement rather than simple destruction.','The narrator documents the speed and aggression of the Martian military campaign, arguing that humanity\'s weapons are useless against their superior technology and firepower.'],c:2,e:'While the passage describes the red weed physically, its deeper point emerges in paragraphs four and six: the Martians are not just attacking humans, they are replacing Earth\'s ecosystem with their own. The narrator\'s final realisation — that survival means nothing without a world to live in — captures this main idea.'},
      {q:'The narrator says the Martians \'had not come to destroy our world. They had come to replace it.\' Which theme does this passage explore?',skill:'Theme',opts:['Survival and resilience — the passage explores how human beings adapt and endure when confronted with an overwhelming threat that they cannot fight or control.','Colonisation — the systematic replacement of one world with another, mirroring how human empires have historically displaced indigenous environments and peoples.','The destructive power of advanced technology — the passage argues that scientific progress inevitably leads to the domination and suffering of less developed civilisations.','Environmental destruction — the passage warns that industrial expansion and unchecked human activity will eventually devastate the natural world beyond repair.'],c:1,e:'Wells wrote this novel during the height of the British Empire, and the parallel is deliberate. The Martians do to England exactly what European colonisers did to other lands: they don\'t just conquer — they reshape the environment to suit themselves. The word \'colonisers\' is used explicitly, and \'terraformed\' reinforces the idea of remaking a world.'},
      {q:'The red weed is described as \'reaching outward like fingers searching for something to grip\'. What device is this, and what effect does it create?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['Metaphor — the red weed stands for the Martian invasion as a whole, with the searching fingers representing the aliens\' systematic, deliberate strategy of conquest and territorial expansion.','Extended metaphor — the weed represents the Martian invasion as a whole, with each tendril standing for a different aspect of their military strategy and technological dominance.','Pathetic fallacy — the weed\'s aggressive movement reflects the narrator\'s own inner turmoil and growing anxiety about the invasion, projecting his emotions onto the landscape.','Simile and personification — comparing the weed\'s tendrils to searching fingers makes it seem deliberate and predatory, as though the plant has intent.'],c:3,e:'The comparison uses \'like\' (simile) and gives the weed human qualities — \'searching\' and \'grip\' (personification). Together, these make the plant feel purposeful and menacing rather than passive. It\'s not just growing — it\'s reaching, hunting, claiming. This transforms an ordinary plant description into something threatening.'},
      {q:'How would you describe the overall tone of this passage?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Detached and scientific — the narrator describes the weed with careful precision, cataloguing its growth patterns and behaviour as though writing a field report rather than expressing personal emotion.','Quietly horrified and reflective — the narrator observes the devastation with growing dread and arrives at a deeply disturbing conclusion.','Nostalgic and mournful — the narrator dwells on memories of how the landscape used to look, and the passage is primarily an elegy for the lost English countryside rather than a response to an ongoing invasion.','Defiant and determined — despite the devastation, the narrator\'s decision to keep walking shows growing resolve, and the passage ends on a note of quiet resistance rather than dread.'],c:1,e:'The tone is not panicked but measured and deeply unsettling. The narrator observes carefully (\'I could almost see it moving\'), reflects thoughtfully (\'What disturbed me most was not the weed itself but what it meant\'), and reaches a conclusion that is worse than the fear of death. The quiet, intellectual horror is more disturbing than screaming would be.'},
      {q:'The narrator says the Martians \'only needed to change the ground beneath our feet\'. Why is \'ground beneath our feet\' a powerful choice of words?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['It emphasises the physical reality of the invasion — the red weed is literally growing in the soil, and the phrase draws attention to the ground-level destruction that the narrator witnesses on his walk.','It connects the Martian threat to the narrator\'s personal survival — by focusing on the ground he walks on, the phrase shifts from the abstract idea of invasion to the immediate, physical danger of having nowhere safe to stand.','It reveals the narrator\'s practical concerns — even in a crisis, he is thinking about whether the soil can still grow food, showing that his fears are rooted in survival rather than philosophy.','It works both literally (the soil and plants are being replaced) and figuratively (the foundation of human existence and security is being destroyed), making the threat feel both physical and existential.'],c:3,e:'\'The ground beneath our feet\' is a phrase we use to mean the basic foundation of our lives — stability, home, certainty. Wells uses it literally (the red weed is replacing English soil) and figuratively (everything humans took for granted is being removed). This double meaning makes the final sentence resonate beyond the story\'s plot.'},
      {q:'The passage is narrated in the first person by someone hiding in a coal cellar. How does this point of view affect the reader\'s experience?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['It limits the passage to one survivor\'s observations, which means the reader cannot learn the full scope of the invasion — we see only the local damage in Surrey, not the global picture.','The first-person perspective makes the narrator\'s conclusions feel subjective and emotionally driven — his claim that the Martians are \'colonisers\' may reflect his personal fears rather than objective truth.','The first-person perspective makes the invasion feel personal and immediate — we experience the narrator\'s fear, confusion, and dawning horror directly rather than observing from a distance.','The first-person perspective shifts attention from the Martians\' actions to the narrator\'s philosophical reflections, making the passage feel more like an essay about colonisation than a survival story.'],c:2,e:'First-person narration puts us inside the narrator\'s body — covering our mouth with a sleeve, feeling the metallic smell catch in our throat. We share his limited knowledge (he can only see what he encounters) and his evolving understanding. This makes the horror visceral and personal rather than abstract.'},
      {q:'What can we infer about the narrator\'s state of mind from the sentence "I covered my mouth with my sleeve and kept walking, though every instinct told me to turn back"?',skill:'Inference',opts:['The narrator has become desensitised to danger after days of hiding — covering his mouth is an automatic reflex rather than a sign of fear, and his continued walking shows emotional numbness rather than courage.','The narrator is driven by a sense of duty to document the invasion for future generations — he overrides his fear because he feels responsible for recording what he witnesses as a warning to others.','The narrator is searching for specific survivors he hopes to find ahead — his refusal to turn back suggests he has a destination in mind, and his determination comes from hope rather than intellectual curiosity.','The narrator is forcing himself to continue despite overwhelming fear, suggesting a determination to understand the threat even when survival instincts urge retreat.'],c:3,e:'The contrast between action ("kept walking") and instinct ("every instinct told me to turn back") reveals a man at war with himself. He is terrified but driven by a need to see, to understand, to witness. This internal conflict makes him a compelling narrator — he pushes through fear not from bravery but from a compulsion to comprehend what is happening to his world.'},
      {q:'Why does the author describe a specific familiar object — the pillar box — being swallowed by the red weed?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['The author uses the pillar box because its red colour blends with the red weed, creating a visual metaphor for how English identity is being absorbed into the alien landscape until the two become indistinguishable.','The pillar box represents the breakdown of communication during the invasion — without postal services, the narrator and other survivors are cut off from news and unable to coordinate a response.','The pillar box is an icon of ordinary English life, so its engulfment by alien weed dramatises the theme of familiar civilisation being erased and replaced.','The pillar box detail suggests the weed targets human infrastructure specifically, supporting the narrator\'s theory that the Martians are strategically dismantling civilisation rather than allowing their plant to spread randomly.'],c:2,e:'A pillar box is quintessentially English — a symbol of order, communication, and daily normality. By showing it "entirely enclosed in a cage of dark crimson stems," Wells transforms a reassuring everyday object into evidence of alien conquest. The specific, familiar detail makes the invasion tangible in a way that abstract description could not.'},
      {q:'The narrator describes the stream as having become "a sluggish red river, choked with the stuff." What does the word "choked" suggest?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['It suggests violent suffocation — the weed is not merely growing in the water but strangling it, implying that Earth\'s natural systems are being killed rather than simply changed.','It connects the stream\'s condition to the narrator\'s own physical discomfort — just as the water is choked by the weed, the narrator is choking on the metallic smell, creating a parallel between landscape and person.','It suggests the weed is using the stream to spread — the water carries seeds or fragments downstream, making the stream an accomplice in the invasion rather than a victim of it.','It conveys the overwhelming abundance of the weed — the stream is so full of plant matter that it can barely flow, emphasising the speed and scale of the weed\'s growth rather than implying violence.'],c:0,e:'"Choked" implies forced obstruction and suffocation. A stream that is "choked" is being killed — its natural flow stopped, its water made sluggish and alien. The word choice turns a description of plant growth into an image of violence, reinforcing the passage\'s theme that the Martians are not just adding to Earth\'s ecosystem but destroying it.'},
      {q:'How does the structure of the passage mirror the narrator\'s emotional journey?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['The passage is structured geographically, moving from the road to the stream to the hilltop — this journey through space mirrors the narrator\'s physical walk and gives the reader a guided tour of the devastation.','It moves from physical observation (describing the weed) to intellectual understanding (recognising colonisation) to existential dread (realising survival itself may be meaningless), reflecting the narrator\'s deepening comprehension of the threat.','The passage is structured as a scientific argument, with the narrator presenting evidence (the weed\'s behaviour) before stating his hypothesis (the Martians are colonisers), following the format of a research paper.','The passage builds chronologically from the narrator leaving the cellar to reaching the hilltop, and the structure simply follows the order of events without any deliberate emotional design or progression.'],c:1,e:'The passage\'s structure tracks the narrator\'s mind. He begins by observing physical changes (paragraphs 1-3), then interprets what they mean (paragraph 4: colonisation), then reaches an existential conclusion (paragraph 6: even survival is pointless without a world). Each stage goes deeper, from eyes to brain to soul, creating a structure of escalating dread.'},
      {q:'What does the narrator\'s comparison of the changed Surrey landscape to "the surface of Mars" reveal about his psychological state?',skill:'Inference',opts:['It shows that the narrator has been expecting this transformation — his immediate comparison to Mars suggests he had already theorised about what the Martians would do to Earth, revealing a scientific mind prepared for this outcome.','It reveals that the narrator can no longer recognise his own homeland — the familiar has become so alien that he can only compare it to another planet, indicating a profound sense of displacement and loss.','The comparison reveals that the narrator finds the new landscape strangely fascinating — his ability to step back and make an aesthetic observation suggests he is coping with trauma by intellectualising what he sees.','It emphasises the narrator\'s isolation — comparing his own county to an alien planet suggests he feels as though he is the last human alive, marooned on a world that no longer belongs to his species.'],c:1,e:'When your own countryside looks like another planet, the alienation is complete. The narrator qualifies the comparison with "or what I imagined Mars to look like," acknowledging he has never seen Mars — yet his own Surrey is now more alien than his imagination of another world. This reveals a man whose sense of home has been entirely destroyed.'},
      {q:'How does the character of the narrator develop across the passage?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['He becomes increasingly practical and resourceful — starting as a frightened man hiding in a cellar and ending as a capable survivor who has mapped the weed\'s behaviour and identified its weaknesses.','He moves from denial to acceptance — initially refusing to believe the weed is alien, he gradually admits the truth, and his final thought marks the moment he stops hoping the invasion can be reversed.','He grows from a passive observer into an active analyst of the Martians\' strategy — his use of words like \'colonisers\' and \'terraformed\' shows him adopting military terminology, preparing himself to resist.','He evolves from a frightened survivor focused on physical safety to a thinker grappling with the philosophical implications of invasion, showing that intellectual horror can be more devastating than physical fear.'],c:3,e:'In the opening, the narrator is a man in a coal cellar, focused on survival. By the end, he has arrived at a thought "worse than any I had had since the invasion began" — not about dying but about the meaninglessness of survival without a world. His journey from physical fear to existential dread shows a character whose understanding deepens even as his hope diminishes.'}
  ]},
  {id:'F06',title:'The Ghost of Christmas Past',type:'fiction',source:'Adapted from Charles Dickens, A Christmas Carol (1843)',
   text:'The ghost took Scrooge\'s hand, and suddenly the dark bedroom was gone. They were standing in an open countryside on a clear winter\'s morning, with snow on the ground and a pale sun hanging low in a sky the colour of wet slate. Scrooge knew this place. He knew it the way you know the face of someone you once loved — instantly, painfully, with a rush of feeling he had spent decades trying to forget.\n\nIt was the village where he had grown up. There was the church with its square tower. There was the bridge over the frozen stream where he had once played with the other boys. And there — set back from the road behind a tall iron gate — was the school.\n\nScrooge\'s throat tightened. The school. He had spent more Christmases there than he cared to remember, alone in the empty dormitory while the other boys went home to their families. His father had not wanted him — not at Christmas, not at Easter, not at all. The other boys would leave in a clatter of trunks and excited voices, and young Ebenezer would stand at the window and watch the last carriage disappear down the lane, and then there would be nothing but silence and the smell of cold stone.\n\n\'You recognise this place,\' the ghost said. It was not a question.\n\nScrooge could not speak. He nodded, and felt something hot run down his cheek. He wiped it away quickly, ashamed. He was Ebenezer Scrooge — the hardest, coldest, most tight-fisted man in London. He did not cry. He had not cried in forty years.\n\nBut the ghost was already leading him forward, through the school gates and down the stone corridor to the dormitory at the end. The door was open. Inside, sitting beside a dying fire with a book on his lap, was a small boy. He was thin, with sharp cheekbones and large, serious eyes, and he was completely alone.\n\nScrooge stared at the child. He knew those eyes. He had seen them every day of his life in the mirror, though they had long since lost the softness they carried now.\n\n\'I wish...\' Scrooge began, then stopped. His voice was barely a whisper. \'There was a boy who sang a carol at my door yesterday. I sent him away. I wish I had given him something.\'\n\nThe ghost said nothing, but Scrooge felt the silence press against him like a judgement. He understood now — or was beginning to understand — that the cold, hard shell he had built around himself had not been constructed all at once. It had been built slowly, brick by brick, starting with a small boy left alone in an empty school on Christmas Day. And if the wall had been built slowly, perhaps it could be taken down the same way.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['Scrooge is confronted with the childhood loneliness that shaped him into a cold, hard man — and begins to understand that his character was not inevitable but built gradually by pain.','The passage primarily explores the Ghost of Christmas Past\'s supernatural abilities, showing how the spirit uses magic to transport Scrooge through time and test whether he can endure revisiting painful memories.','The Ghost of Christmas Past deliberately forces Scrooge to relive his school years as a form of punishment, intending to make him suffer for the cruelty he has shown to others throughout his adult life.','Scrooge returns to his childhood village and is overwhelmed by nostalgia for the happy times he spent at school, wishing he could recapture the innocence and joy of his younger years.'],c:0,e:'The passage traces a cause-and-effect chain: childhood abandonment led to emotional armour, which led to the cold adult Scrooge. The key insight comes in the final paragraph — his hardness was \'built slowly, brick by brick\', which implies it can also be dismantled. The main idea is about understanding the origins of cruelty.'},
      {q:'Scrooge recognises the village \'the way you know the face of someone you once loved — instantly, painfully, with a rush of feeling he had spent decades trying to forget\'. What device is being used, and what does it reveal?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['Onomatopoeia — the phrase \'rush of feeling\' mimics the sound of emotion surging through Scrooge, using the auditory quality of the words themselves to convey the intensity of his recognition.','Simile — comparing recognition of the village to recognising a loved one\'s face reveals that Scrooge has deep emotions buried beneath his cold exterior that he has spent years suppressing.','Hyperbole — Dickens deliberately exaggerates the strength of Scrooge\'s memory to emphasise that he has been away from the village for a very long time, making the moment of return feel more dramatic.','Metaphor — the village is described as being identical to a person\'s face, suggesting that Scrooge has projected his own identity onto the landscape and can no longer distinguish between place and person.'],c:1,e:'The simile (using \'the way\') compares place-recognition to person-recognition, immediately telling us this is emotional, not geographical. The words \'painfully\' and \'decades trying to forget\' reveal that Scrooge has been actively burying his feelings — his coldness is not natural but effortful.'},
      {q:'Why does Scrooge suddenly wish he had given something to the carol singer at his door?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['Because the Ghost of Christmas Past directly instructs Scrooge to reflect on his recent behaviour, and the supernatural authority of the spirit compels him to feel remorse he would not naturally experience.','Because Scrooge wants to demonstrate to the ghost that he is capable of kindness, hoping that a show of regret will end the vision early and allow him to return to his comfortable bedroom.','Because seeing his younger self alone at Christmas makes him recognise the loneliness in others — the carol boy at his door was also seeking warmth and connection, and Scrooge turned him away just as his father turned him away.','Because the vision of the dormitory has made Scrooge realise that children are inherently vulnerable, and his regret about the carol singer reflects a general sadness about childhood rather than a specific connection to his own past.'],c:2,e:'This is the passage\'s emotional turning point. Scrooge sees the lonely child he was, and for the first time connects that to his own behaviour as an adult. By rejecting the carol singer, he did to a child what was done to him. The recognition is not intellectual but deeply felt — it comes mid-sentence, as a wish, not a logical argument.'},
      {q:'The final paragraph describes Scrooge\'s cold personality as a wall \'built slowly, brick by brick\'. What theme does this metaphor develop?',skill:'Theme',opts:['People are not born cruel — emotional hardness is constructed gradually through painful experiences, and understanding this process is the first step towards change.','The passage argues that emotional suffering in childhood is permanent and irreversible — the wall metaphor suggests that once cruelty has been built, it cannot be dismantled regardless of what happens later.','The wall represents the barrier between the living and the dead — Scrooge\'s cold personality is a defence against the grief of losing people he loved, and the ghost is trying to help him mourn properly.','The metaphor develops the theme that self-protection is necessary and wise — the wall kept Scrooge safe from further emotional pain, and the passage suggests his coldness was a rational survival strategy.'],c:0,e:'The wall metaphor is central to the passage\'s theme. By framing Scrooge\'s personality as something constructed rather than innate, Dickens suggests it can also be deconstructed. The phrase \'perhaps it could be taken down the same way\' introduces hope — if cruelty was built by experiences, kindness can be rebuilt through different ones.'},
      {q:'How would you describe the tone of paragraph five, where Scrooge wipes away a tear?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Nostalgic and warm — Scrooge\'s tears are tears of happiness at being reunited with his childhood memories, and the paragraph captures the gentle pleasure of revisiting the past.','Defiant and stubborn — Scrooge wipes the tear away because he refuses to let the ghost manipulate his emotions, and the paragraph shows his resistance to the spirit\'s power rather than genuine vulnerability.','Vulnerable and conflicted — Scrooge is experiencing genuine emotion but is ashamed of it, creating tension between his feelings and his self-image as a hard, unfeeling man.','Melodramatic and performative — Scrooge exaggerates his emotional reaction because he believes the ghost wants to see him cry, and his tears are calculated rather than genuine.'],c:2,e:'The paragraph creates tension between feeling and identity. Scrooge cries — but immediately wipes the tear away and reminds himself that he is \'the hardest, coldest, most tight-fisted man in London\'. The shame he feels about crying is itself revealing: it shows how much energy he puts into maintaining his emotional armour.'},
      {q:'From whose point of view is the passage told, and how does this affect the emotional impact?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['Second person — the narrator addresses the reader as \'you\', making us feel as though we are standing beside Scrooge in the snowy village and experiencing his memories firsthand.','First person through the ghost — the spirit narrates the journey, describing what it observes about Scrooge\'s reactions, which creates an outside perspective on his emotional breakdown.','Third person omniscient — the narrator reveals the thoughts of both Scrooge and the young boy, showing the child\'s loneliness as well as the adult\'s guilt, and connecting them through shared awareness.','Third person limited through Scrooge — this allows the reader to experience his suppressed emotions and dawning self-awareness directly, making his pain feel intimate and immediate.'],c:3,e:'We are locked inside Scrooge\'s perspective: we feel his throat tighten, share his shame at crying, and hear his whispered wish. Because the narration stays close to his consciousness, every emotion hits the reader directly. If the passage were told from the ghost\'s perspective, Scrooge\'s pain would be observed rather than felt.'},
      {q:'What can we infer about Scrooge\'s relationship with his father from the detail that "his father had not wanted him — not at Christmas, not at Easter, not at all"?',skill:'Inference',opts:['Scrooge deliberately chose to stay at school because he found comfort in books and solitude — the repetition of \'not at Christmas, not at Easter\' emphasises how often he made this choice rather than how often he was rejected.','Scrooge\'s father loved him but could not afford the journey to collect him — the repetition expresses the father\'s frustration at his poverty rather than emotional rejection, making the situation tragic for both of them.','Scrooge was completely rejected by his father, left at school year-round, suggesting that his adult coldness is rooted in childhood abandonment and a lack of parental love.','The phrase reveals that Scrooge\'s father sent him away as a form of tough love — believing that independence and discipline would make the boy stronger, even if it meant short-term loneliness.'],c:2,e:'The repetition — "not at Christmas, not at Easter, not at all" — emphasises the totality of the rejection. This was not a practical arrangement but an emotional one: Scrooge\'s father simply did not want him. This detail is crucial because it explains the origin of Scrooge\'s emotional armour. A child who is unwanted learns to stop wanting.'},
      {q:'How does the detail about the "dying fire" in the dormitory contribute to the scene\'s atmosphere?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['The dying fire represents the passage of time — it tells the reader that the boy has been alone for hours, sitting by the fire since morning as it slowly burns down, emphasising the length of his isolation.','The dying fire mirrors the boy\'s determination to survive — he has kept it going as long as he can on his own, showing resilience and self-reliance even in the face of abandonment.','The dying fire symbolises the warmth and comfort that is fading from young Scrooge\'s life, reinforcing the loneliness and neglect of a boy left alone at Christmas.','The fire is a symbol of hope — the fact that it is dying but not yet dead suggests that young Scrooge still has a chance of being saved from loneliness, creating suspense about whether someone will arrive in time.'],c:2,e:'A "dying fire" is not dead — it still has some warmth left, but it is fading. This mirrors young Scrooge perfectly: he still has softness in his eyes, still reads books by the remaining light, but the warmth in his life is disappearing. The fire\'s slow death parallels the slow construction of Scrooge\'s emotional wall, brick by brick.'},
      {q:'Why does Dickens describe Scrooge looking at the boy and recognising "those eyes" that "had long since lost the softness they carried now"?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['The detail emphasises Scrooge\'s vanity — even in this emotional moment, he is focused on his own reflection, unable to look beyond himself to truly empathise with the child he once was.','The detail highlights the passage of time rather than emotional change — Scrooge\'s eyes have physically aged and hardened, but the \'softness\' in the child\'s eyes is simply a feature of youth that everyone loses naturally.','It forces both Scrooge and the reader to see the direct connection between the innocent, vulnerable child and the hard, cold adult — showing exactly what was lost over the years of emotional self-protection.','The recognition creates a moment of pride — Scrooge sees his own strength in the boy\'s serious expression, and the \'softness\' he notices is not something he regrets losing but something he outgrew.'],c:2,e:'This moment is devastating because it makes the loss visible. The same eyes exist in two versions: soft and serious in the child, hard and cold in the adult. By having Scrooge recognise his own eyes, Dickens collapses the distance between past and present, forcing Scrooge to see himself as both victim and perpetrator — the abandoned child who became the man who abandons others.'},
      {q:'How does the text structure of the passage build towards Scrooge\'s emotional breakthrough?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['The passage moves from external landscape to specific location to individual child to Scrooge\'s emotional response, narrowing focus like a camera zooming in until it reaches the most painful point.','The passage builds tension by withholding key information — the reader does not learn that the boy is young Scrooge until the final paragraphs, creating a reveal that reframes everything that came before.','The passage is structured as a dialogue between Scrooge and the ghost, with each exchange peeling back another layer of Scrooge\'s emotional defences until he finally breaks down and speaks honestly.','The passage alternates between the past (the dormitory scene) and the present (Scrooge\'s reactions), creating a back-and-forth structure that emphasises the contrast between who Scrooge was and who he has become.'],c:0,e:'The structure works like a funnel. We begin with the wide countryside, move to the village, then the school, then the corridor, then the dormitory, and finally the single child by the fire. Each paragraph narrows the focus, drawing Scrooge — and the reader — closer to the emotional core. By the time Scrooge speaks, the intimacy is inescapable.'},
      {q:'The ghost says "You recognise this place" as a statement, not a question. What effect does this have?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['It establishes the ghost as an emotionally supportive figure — by stating recognition rather than asking, the ghost saves Scrooge the difficulty of having to speak when he is clearly overwhelmed by emotion.','It reveals the ghost\'s supernatural omniscience — the spirit already knows everything about Scrooge\'s past and uses statements instead of questions because it has no need to ask, demonstrating its power.','It creates intimacy between the ghost and Scrooge — the statement feels like something a close friend would say, suggesting the ghost understands Scrooge deeply and is approaching him with compassion rather than confrontation.','It removes any possibility of denial — the ghost is not asking Scrooge to acknowledge his past but stating that he already does, stripping away his defences before he can raise them.'],c:3,e:'By phrasing recognition as a fact rather than a question, the ghost takes away Scrooge\'s option to deflect or deny. A question ("Do you recognise this place?") would allow Scrooge to say no. A statement forces confrontation. This small grammatical choice has a large emotional effect — it makes Scrooge\'s past inescapable.'},
      {q:'The silence after Scrooge\'s wish is described as pressing "against him like a judgement." What literary device is this, and what does it reveal?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['Personification — the silence is given the physical force to press against Scrooge, acting as a living presence in the dormitory that holds him accountable for the wish he has just spoken.','Hyperbole — the author deliberately exaggerates the weight of an ordinary pause in conversation to make the quiet dormitory feel more threatening than the scene truly warrants.','Simile — comparing silence to a judgement suggests that the ghost does not need to speak; Scrooge\'s own conscience is already condemning him, and the silence forces him to sit with his guilt.','Metaphor — the silence is not compared to a judgement but has become one, transforming the dormitory into a moral courtroom where Scrooge stands trial for abandoning his younger self.'],c:2,e:'The simile "like a judgement" transforms silence from an absence of sound into an active moral force. The ghost says nothing, but the silence itself condemns. This is more powerful than any words the ghost could speak — it forces Scrooge to be his own judge. The ghost\'s silence becomes the loudest thing in the scene.'}
  ]},
  {id:'F07',title:'The Speckled Band',type:'fiction',source:'Adapted from Arthur Conan Doyle, The Adventure of the Speckled Band (1892)',
   text:'I had been sharing rooms with Sherlock Holmes for only a few months when the case of the Stoner sisters arrived at our door on Baker Street. It came in the form of a young woman — pale, exhausted, and trembling — who appeared on our doorstep before seven o\'clock on a bitter March morning. Her name was Helen Stoner, and she believed that her life was in danger.\n\nHolmes listened to her story without interruption, his sharp grey eyes fixed on her face the way a hawk watches a field mouse — not with cruelty, but with an intensity that missed nothing. He sat perfectly still, his fingertips pressed together beneath his chin, and only the slight narrowing of his eyes betrayed that he was thinking faster than most men could speak.\n\nHelen explained that she lived with her stepfather, Dr Grimesby Roylott, in a crumbling manor house in Surrey. Two years ago, her twin sister Julia had died under mysterious circumstances — found in her nightgown in the corridor outside her locked bedroom, screaming about a \'speckled band\' before collapsing. The doctors had found no cause of death. The coroner had been baffled. And Dr Roylott, who had a violent temper and kept exotic animals from India in the grounds, had shown remarkably little grief.\n\nNow Helen herself had been moved into Julia\'s old room — the room where her sister had died — because Dr Roylott claimed the wall in her own room needed repair. At night, she had begun to hear a low whistling sound, exactly as Julia had described hearing in the weeks before her death.\n\n\'You have done wisely in coming to me,\' Holmes said when she had finished. There was no warmth in his voice — Holmes did not deal in comfort — but there was something better: certainty. He already knew, or suspected, something. I could see it in the way his fingers had stopped their drumming.\n\n\'The case presents several features of interest,\' he continued, turning to me with the faintest suggestion of excitement. \'A locked room. A mysterious death with no apparent cause. An identical room assignment. A whistling sound. And a stepfather with a temper, a medical background, and a collection of exotic animals.\' He paused. \'Watson, clear your schedule. We shall visit Stoke Moran today.\'\n\nI confess that at that moment I felt a familiar mixture of excitement and unease. Holmes\'s cases had a habit of beginning in our comfortable sitting room and ending in circumstances considerably less comfortable. But there was never any question of refusing. When Holmes said \'we\', he meant it, and there was something in his voice — that quiet, precise urgency — that told me this case would be more dangerous than most.',
   questions:[
      {q:'The story is narrated by Dr Watson, not Sherlock Holmes. Why might Doyle have chosen Watson as the narrator rather than Holmes himself?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['Because Holmes\'s cold, analytical personality would alienate readers, and Watson\'s warmer, more emotional voice makes the detective stories feel accessible and human rather than purely intellectual.','Because Watson\'s limited understanding creates suspense — he notices details without understanding their significance, keeping the reader in the same position and making Holmes\'s eventual deductions more impressive.','Because Doyle wanted a narrator who could describe Holmes objectively from the outside, building his mystique as an almost legendary figure whose inner thoughts remain deliberately hidden from the reader.','Because using Watson allows Doyle to present unreliable narration, subtly hinting that Watson\'s deep admiration for Holmes may cause him to exaggerate or romanticise the details of their cases.'],c:1,e:'Watson is an ideal narrator because he is intelligent enough to observe accurately but not brilliant enough to deduce like Holmes. This means the reader experiences the mystery as Watson does — seeing clues without understanding them. When Holmes later explains, the revelation feels earned.'},
      {q:'Holmes watches Helen \'the way a hawk watches a field mouse — not with cruelty, but with an intensity that missed nothing\'. What does this simile reveal about Holmes?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['The simile suggests that Holmes views Helen as a potential suspect rather than a victim, scrutinising her story for inconsistencies with the same detachment a hawk uses when selecting vulnerable prey.','The comparison reveals Watson\'s unease with Holmes\'s methods, implying that Watson finds his friend\'s intense observation of a frightened woman uncomfortable and bordering on inappropriate.','The hawk imagery highlights Holmes\'s isolation from normal human connection, suggesting that his extraordinary analytical ability comes at the cost of genuine empathy for the people he is trying to help.','Holmes observes people with predatory focus — he is not hostile but intensely analytical, watching for details others would miss, the way a hawk\'s vision is sharper than any other bird\'s.'],c:3,e:'The hawk simile captures Holmes\'s defining quality: extraordinary perceptual focus. The clarification \'not with cruelty\' is important — it distinguishes analytical intensity from malice. Hawks don\'t watch mice out of hatred; they watch because every detail matters. Similarly, Holmes reads Helen\'s face for information, not from hostility.'},
      {q:'In paragraph five, Watson notes that Holmes\'s voice has \'no warmth\' but \'something better: certainty\'. What does this reveal about how Watson views Holmes?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['Watson is frustrated that Holmes cannot offer human warmth and sees this as a flaw — he views Holmes\'s certainty as a cold substitute for the empathy that a terrified woman actually needs.','Watson understands that Holmes shows care through competence rather than emotion — his certainty that he can help is more reassuring than any sympathetic words would be.','Watson admires Holmes\'s certainty but privately resents that he himself can never offer the same kind of reassurance, revealing an insecurity about his own usefulness in their partnership.','Watson is being sarcastic — the phrase "something better" is ironic, subtly criticising Holmes for lacking basic emotional intelligence when dealing with a vulnerable client.'],c:1,e:'This observation is affectionate and perceptive. Watson recognises that Holmes\'s way of helping is not through comfort but through capability. For a frightened woman, knowing that the greatest detective in London is already on the case is more useful than kind words. Watson sees this as \'something better\' — a genuine form of care.'},
      {q:'In paragraph six, Holmes lists the key features of the case: \'A locked room. A mysterious death with no apparent cause. An identical room assignment. A whistling sound. And a stepfather with a temper, a medical background, and a collection of exotic animals.\' Why does the author structure this as a list?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['To overwhelm the reader with an excessive number of details at once, reflecting Holmes\'s tendency to show off his intellect by listing everything he has noticed rather than explaining what it means.','To mirror Holmes\'s logical, methodical mind — he organises scattered information into a clear sequence of clues, showing the reader how a detective processes a case and building suspense about what the clues mean together.','To demonstrate that Holmes has simply memorised Helen\'s story and is repeating it back to Watson without adding any analytical insight of his own, since the items are listed in the same order Helen mentioned them.','To give Watson a checklist he can refer back to during the investigation, turning Holmes\'s verbal summary into a practical tool for the less observant narrator to follow.'],c:1,e:'The list structure does several things simultaneously. It characterises Holmes (logical, organised), it summarises the case for readers who might have lost track, and it builds suspense by placing the most suggestive detail (\'exotic animals\') last. Each item alone is curious; together, they form a pattern that Holmes already sees but hasn\'t yet revealed.'},
      {q:'In the final paragraph, Watson describes a \'familiar mixture of excitement and unease\'. How does this set the tone for what is to come?',skill:'Tone',opts:['It suggests Watson secretly dreads accompanying Holmes and participates only out of obligation, creating a reluctant, resentful undertone to the closing paragraph.','It foreshadows a tragic outcome, implying Watson already senses that this case will end in failure and that Holmes will be unable to save Helen from her stepfather.','It establishes a lighthearted, self-deprecating tone — Watson is exaggerating the danger for comic effect, poking fun at his own tendency to dramatise their adventures.','It creates anticipation tinged with danger — the reader understands that the investigation will be thrilling but potentially deadly, which generates suspense.'],c:3,e:'Watson\'s mixed feelings mirror what the reader should feel: eager to see Holmes solve the mystery, but aware that a man with exotic animals, a violent temper, and a dead stepdaughter makes this case physically dangerous. The phrase \'more dangerous than most\' raises the stakes explicitly.'},
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['Helen Stoner has come to accuse her stepfather of medical malpractice, believing that his incompetent treatment caused Julia\'s death rather than any deliberate criminal act.','Watson reflects on the challenges and rewards of living with an eccentric genius, using Helen\'s visit as one example among many of the disruptions Holmes brings to their shared domestic routine.','A terrified young woman brings a dangerous mystery to Holmes, and the careful presentation of clues suggests that her stepfather is behind the threat to her life.','Holmes is testing Watson\'s observational skills by recounting the case details aloud, and the passage is primarily about the mentor-student dynamic between the two men.'],c:2,e:'The passage introduces a mystery with life-or-death stakes. Helen\'s story — her sister\'s unexplained death, the room reassignment, the whistling sound, and her stepfather\'s suspicious behaviour — forms a pattern that Holmes immediately recognises as significant. The main idea is the presentation of a threatening puzzle that Holmes is uniquely equipped to solve.'},
      {q:'What does the detail about Dr Roylott keeping "exotic animals from India in the grounds" suggest when combined with the other clues?',skill:'Inference',opts:['It suggests that one of Dr Roylott\'s exotic animals escaped its enclosure and killed Julia by accident, making her death a tragic case of negligence rather than deliberate murder.','It characterises Dr Roylott as an eccentric but harmless collector, implying that his passion for Indian wildlife reflects cultural interests from his time abroad rather than any sinister purpose.','It hints that the murder weapon may be an exotic animal rather than a conventional weapon, explaining both the locked room mystery and the absence of a visible cause of death.','It primarily establishes the setting as a rural estate where exotic animals are kept for prestige, reflecting Dr Roylott\'s wealth and social status rather than connecting to the method of murder.'],c:2,e:'Holmes lists the exotic animals alongside a locked room, a death with no apparent cause, a medical background, and a whistling sound. Individually, each detail is curious. Together, they point towards a method of murder involving a creature that could enter a locked room, leave no visible wound, and be summoned by a whistle. The inference is dark and deliberate.'},
      {q:'How does Doyle use the character of Helen Stoner to create sympathy and urgency in the opening?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['Helen is portrayed as composed and businesslike despite her fear, presenting her case to Holmes with the controlled precision of someone who has rehearsed exactly what to say.','Helen is described as "pale, exhausted, and trembling," arriving before seven on a bitter morning, which immediately establishes her as desperate and vulnerable, making the reader care about her safety.','Helen arrives relaxed and unhurried in the afternoon, suggesting she has been considering whether to visit Holmes for some time and has finally decided to seek his opinion at her convenience.','Helen is presented as suspicious and evasive, withholding key details from Holmes and forcing him to ask probing questions before she reveals the full truth about her stepfather.'],c:1,e:'Every detail about Helen\'s appearance signals distress: pale (fear or illness), exhausted (sleepless nights), trembling (terror), arriving before seven in March cold (so desperate she could not wait). Doyle front-loads these details to establish that this is not a trivial case — a woman\'s life hangs in the balance, and the reader immediately wants Holmes to help her.'},
      {q:'What theme is suggested by the contrast between the "comfortable sitting room" on Baker Street and the danger Holmes\'s cases lead to?',skill:'Theme',opts:['The pursuit of truth and justice often requires leaving safety behind — intellectual curiosity and moral duty pull Holmes and Watson from comfort into danger.','The passage suggests that true safety comes from familiar domestic routines, and Watson\'s reluctance to leave Baker Street represents a theme about the importance of protecting one\'s home and stability.','Baker Street is presented as a place of intellectual danger where Holmes\'s deductions and experiments are just as threatening as the criminals he investigates, blurring the line between safety and risk.','The contrast highlights Watson\'s growing resentment of Holmes, developing a theme about how one-sided friendships eventually become unsustainable when one person consistently puts the other in harm\'s way.'],c:0,e:'Watson notes that Holmes\'s cases begin in comfort and end in danger, yet he never refuses. This recurring pattern suggests a theme about the cost of pursuing justice: it demands that you leave safety behind. The "comfortable sitting room" represents the easy life Watson could choose; following Holmes represents a harder, more meaningful path.'},
      {q:'Why does Watson describe Holmes\'s excitement as only "the faintest suggestion" rather than an obvious display?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['It implies that Holmes is deliberately hiding his excitement to manipulate Watson into thinking the case is routine, using emotional restraint as a strategic tool to control those around him.','It indicates that Holmes is only mildly interested in Helen\'s case and considers it unremarkable compared to previous investigations, which is why his reaction barely registers.','It characterises Holmes as someone who controls his emotions so tightly that even genuine excitement barely surfaces, reinforcing his image as a disciplined, analytical mind.','It suggests that Holmes is performing excitement for Helen\'s benefit — the "faintest suggestion" is a calculated display designed to reassure her that he is taking her case seriously.'],c:2,e:'The phrase "faintest suggestion" tells us that Holmes\'s excitement exists but is almost invisible. This restraint is central to his character — a man so disciplined that even when confronted with an intriguing mystery, his reaction is a micro-expression rather than an outburst. Watson\'s ability to detect this faint signal also shows how well he knows Holmes.'},
      {q:'How does the parallel between Julia\'s experience and Helen\'s current situation create suspense?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['The parallel is purely coincidental within the story — Doyle mentions the matching details to add realistic domestic flavour about old houses needing repairs, not to create narrative tension.','The repetition of the same pattern — same room, same whistling sound — strongly implies Helen will meet the same fate as her sister unless Holmes intervenes, creating urgent, life-or-death suspense.','The similarities suggest that the events are supernatural in nature — Julia\'s ghost is producing the whistling sound to warn Helen, and the room itself carries a haunted presence that causes identical experiences.','The parallel demonstrates that Dr Roylott treats both sisters equally, assigning them the same room because he views them as interchangeable, which reveals his emotional indifference rather than any murderous intent.'],c:1,e:'Doyle constructs the suspense through deliberate parallelism: Julia heard a whistling, then died in that room. Now Helen has been moved to the same room and hears the same whistling. The pattern creates a terrifying equation — if the same conditions are repeating, the same outcome may follow. The reader understands that Helen is living inside a countdown.'},
      {q:'What does Watson\'s admission that "there was never any question of refusing" reveal about his relationship with Holmes?',skill:'Inference',opts:['Watson has no genuine interest in Holmes\'s investigations and simply accompanies him because he has no medical patients of his own and nothing better to do with his time.','Watson follows Holmes out of fear rather than loyalty — he knows that Holmes would publicly humiliate him or end their living arrangement if Watson ever refused to participate in a case.','Watson agrees to accompany Holmes because he is being paid a salary as a medical consultant, making their relationship a professional arrangement rather than a personal bond.','Watson is deeply loyal to Holmes and feels a sense of duty and shared purpose that overrides his personal fear, suggesting a bond built on mutual trust and admiration.'],c:3,e:'Watson\'s statement reveals that his loyalty to Holmes is automatic and absolute. Despite knowing the danger ("circumstances considerably less comfortable"), he never considers staying behind. This tells us their partnership is not transactional but deeply personal — Watson follows Holmes because of who Holmes is, not because of what he gains from it.'}
  ]},
  {id:'F08',title:'Rikki-Tikki-Tavi',type:'fiction',source:'Adapted from Rudyard Kipling, The Jungle Book (1894)',
   text:'Rikki-tikki-tavi was a mongoose — small, quick, and curious about everything. He had been washed out of his burrow by a great summer flood and carried, half-drowned and bedraggled, into the garden of a bungalow where a British family lived. The boy, Teddy, had found him lying limp on the garden path and had carried him inside, wrapped in cotton wool, and warmed him by the fire until the small creature sneezed, shook himself, and began to explore the room with the restless energy that is the birthright of every mongoose.\n\nWithin a day, Rikki had made the bungalow his home. He slept on Teddy\'s pillow, explored every cupboard and bookshelf, and stuck his nose into everything from the bathtub to the inkpot. Teddy\'s mother was not entirely comfortable having a wild animal in the house, but Teddy\'s father — who knew something about mongooses — said, \'If a cobra comes into the nursery now, Rikki will deal with it.\' He said this so calmly that it took a moment for the weight of the words to land.\n\nBecause there were cobras in the garden. Nag and Nagaina, a pair of black king cobras, had lived among the roots of the thorn bushes for years. They were enormous — Nag was five feet long, with a hood that spread like a dark, veined hand when he raised himself to strike. They killed mice, frogs, and the small birds that nested in the hedges, and they considered the garden their kingdom. The arrival of a mongoose threatened everything.\n\n\'Who is Nag?\' said Nag himself, rearing up from behind the dustbin one evening, his hood spread wide. \'I am Nag. The great God Brahma put his mark upon all our people. Look, and be afraid!\'\n\nRikki-tikki stared at the cobra. He was afraid — every creature with sense is afraid of a cobra\'s strike, which comes faster than the eye can follow. But a mongoose\'s blood runs hot, and the motto of the mongoose family, as Rikki\'s mother had once told him, was \'Run and find out.\' Fear was something you carried with you, not something that stopped you.\n\nSo Rikki held his ground. He puffed up his fur to make himself look twice his size, and he danced sideways on the tips of his toes, keeping his eyes fixed on the slight movement of Nag\'s head that would signal a strike. His tail bristled like a bottle brush. His heart hammered. But he did not run.\n\nIt was the bravest thing he had ever done — and it was only the beginning. The real battle, the one that would decide whether the family lived or died, had not yet started.',
   questions:[
      {q:'The passage states that for Rikki, \'Fear was something you carried with you, not something that stopped you.\' Which theme does this develop?',skill:'Theme',opts:['The passage develops the idea that survival in the wild depends on physical strength rather than emotional resilience, since Rikki\'s size and speed matter more than his mindset.','Animals can only overcome dangerous predators by relying on their natural instincts rather than making conscious decisions about how to respond to threats.','True courage is not the absence of fear but the decision to act despite it.','The family motto suggests that mongooses are genetically incapable of feeling fear, which gives them a biological advantage over cobras in any confrontation.'],c:2,e:'The passage is careful to note that Rikki is afraid — \'every creature with sense is afraid of a cobra\'s strike\'. His bravery is not fearlessness but a choice to act despite fear. His family motto (\'Run and find out\') reframes fear as something you acknowledge and carry forward, not something that paralyses you.'},
      {q:'Nag\'s hood is compared to \'a dark, veined hand when he raised himself to strike\'. What effect does this simile create?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['The simile emphasises the sheer physical size of Nag\'s hood, comparing it to a hand primarily to help the reader visualise the scale and width of the cobra\'s spread.','It makes the cobra\'s hood feel human-like and threatening — a hand that can reach out and grab, combining the natural danger of the snake with an unsettling human quality.','The comparison to a hand suggests that Nag is a protective figure who shelters smaller creatures in the garden, giving the cobra a nurturing rather than predatory quality.','The word \'veined\' in the simile draws attention to Nag\'s age and physical weakness, implying that the cobra is old and frail rather than genuinely dangerous to Rikki.'],c:1,e:'Comparing the hood to a \'dark, veined hand\' is deliberately unsettling because hands are human — they reach, grab, and control. This personification gives Nag an almost purposeful menace, as though the cobra is not just a predator but a calculating enemy. The word \'veined\' adds visceral, physical detail.'},
      {q:'Why does the author include Teddy\'s father\'s calm remark: \'If a cobra comes into the nursery now, Rikki will deal with it\'?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['To characterise Teddy\'s father as overprotective and anxious, since his calm delivery disguises the worry he feels about raising a child in a house surrounded by wildlife.','To reassure the reader that Rikki is a fully domesticated pet who poses no risk to the household, helping the family accept the mongoose\'s presence as harmless fun.','To foreshadow that Teddy\'s father will personally confront the cobras later in the story, showing that the adults — not Rikki — will ultimately resolve the danger.','To establish the real stakes beneath the domestic setting — the bungalow is not safe, cobras are a genuine threat, and Rikki\'s presence is not just charming but necessary for the family\'s survival.'],c:3,e:'The remark shifts the passage\'s tone from cute domesticity (mongoose exploring the inkpot) to genuine danger. The father says it \'so calmly that it took a moment for the weight of the words to land\' — this delayed impact mirrors the reader\'s experience of realising that the story is not just about a pet but about life and death.'},
      {q:'How does the tone change between the first two paragraphs and the confrontation with Nag?',skill:'Tone',opts:['It shifts from a detached, factual description of Rikki\'s habits to an emotionally charged first-person perspective once the confrontation with Nag begins.','The tone remains consistently serious throughout, as even the early domestic scenes carry an undercurrent of danger established by the mention of Rikki being washed out by a flood.','It shifts from warm and domestic (Rikki exploring, sleeping on pillows) to tense and dangerous (the cobra confrontation), mirroring the shift from safety to threat.','It moves from a tone of mystery and suspense in the opening paragraphs to a lighter, more humorous tone once Nag appears, since the cobra\'s dramatic self-introduction is played for comedy.'],c:2,e:'Paragraphs one and two are cosy: cotton wool, fire, sleeping on pillows, exploring the inkpot. The introduction of Nag and Nagaina transforms the tone entirely — the garden becomes a battleground, and words like \'strike\', \'kill\', and \'afraid\' replace the earlier warmth. Kipling uses this contrast deliberately.'},
      {q:'The final paragraph says this confrontation \'was only the beginning\' and that \'the real battle had not yet started\'. What narrative technique is this, and what effect does it create?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['Dramatic irony — the narrator reveals information that Rikki himself does not yet know, creating tension between the character\'s ignorance and the reader\'s awareness of coming danger.','Metaphor — the phrase \'real battle\' is a figurative comparison suggesting that Rikki\'s internal struggle with fear is more significant than any physical confrontation with the cobras.','Foreshadowing — it signals to the reader that greater danger lies ahead, building suspense and making them want to continue reading.','Pathetic fallacy — the passage uses the approaching \'battle\' to reflect the darkening mood of the natural environment as the story moves from daylight to evening.'],c:2,e:'By telling us that the confrontation with Nag is \'only the beginning\', the author promises escalation — the stakes will get higher. This foreshadowing creates suspense because the reader has just seen how dangerous Nag is. If that was the easy part, the \'real battle\' must be terrifying.'},
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['The passage focuses primarily on Rikki\'s relationship with the human family, exploring how a wild animal gradually learns to trust people and adapt to domestic life inside a household.','A small mongoose, rescued by a human family, discovers that their garden is home to deadly cobras, and despite his fear he stands his ground in a confrontation that marks the beginning of a larger battle.','The central idea is that Teddy\'s father understands the natural world and uses his knowledge of mongooses to deliberately engineer a confrontation between Rikki and the cobras.','The passage is mainly about the rivalry between Nag and Nagaina as they defend their established territory from both the human family and the mongoose who has arrived uninvited.'],c:1,e:'The passage traces Rikki\'s journey from rescued animal to brave defender. It establishes the domestic setting, introduces the cobra threat, and culminates in Rikki\'s first confrontation with Nag. The main idea combines the themes of courage and protection — a small creature choosing to face a deadly enemy to defend those who saved him.'},
      {q:'From whose point of view is this passage told, and how does it shape the reader\'s experience?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['First person through Rikki, using "I" and "my" to narrate events, which would create strong intimacy but limit the reader to only what Rikki personally observes and feels.','Third person omniscient, giving equal access to the thoughts of every character, which allows the reader to understand both Rikki\'s fear and Nag\'s motivations simultaneously.','Second person, addressing the reader directly as "you" to create a sense of immersion and make the confrontation with Nag feel like a shared experience.','Third person limited, closely following Rikki\'s perspective — this lets us feel his fear and courage from inside, making the confrontation with Nag more personal and tense.'],c:3,e:'The narration uses "he" and "his" (third person) but stays close to Rikki\'s consciousness — we know his fear, his instincts, his mother\'s motto. This limited perspective means we face Nag as Rikki does: looking up at a five-foot cobra from the height of a small mongoose. The intimacy of the viewpoint makes the courage feel earned rather than automatic.'},
      {q:'What does the mongoose family motto "Run and find out" reveal about Rikki\'s nature?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['The motto implies that Rikki\'s mother specifically trained him in combat techniques for fighting cobras, passing down practical survival strategies through family tradition.','The motto suggests that mongooses are impulsive and reckless by nature, acting without caution or forethought, which explains why Rikki confronts Nag without any real strategy.','It shows that curiosity is central to mongoose identity — they instinctively investigate rather than flee, and this inherited boldness is what enables Rikki to stand his ground against Nag.','The motto reveals that mongooses prioritise speed above all else, relying on their ability to outrun predators rather than standing their ground in any confrontation with a larger animal.'],c:2,e:'The motto "Run and find out" perfectly captures the mongoose temperament: not reckless (they do run) but investigative (they run towards, not away). This inherited curiosity-as-courage is what defines Rikki. When he faces Nag, he does not freeze or flee — he stays and investigates, following his deepest instinct. The motto frames bravery as a family trait, not an anomaly.'},
      {q:'Why does Nag introduce himself by referencing "the great God Brahma" and commanding Rikki to "Look, and be afraid"?',skill:'Inference',opts:['Nag is following a traditional greeting ritual common among cobras, introducing himself formally to establish peaceful coexistence with a new arrival in the garden.','Nag references Brahma to explain the physical markings on his hood, providing Rikki with a factual account of cobra biology wrapped in the language of cultural storytelling.','Nag is proud of his species and wants to educate Rikki about cobra heritage, sharing the cultural significance of the hood markings as a way of building mutual respect.','Nag uses religious authority and intimidation to establish dominance, revealing that he relies on fear and self-mythology as much as physical power to control the garden.'],c:3,e:'Nag\'s self-introduction is a power display. By invoking divine authority ("the great God Brahma put his mark upon all our people") and issuing a command ("be afraid"), Nag tries to overwhelm Rikki psychologically before any physical confrontation. This reveals Nag as a creature who weaponises fear — he wants to win the encounter before it begins. Rikki\'s refusal to submit is therefore doubly brave.'},
      {q:'How does the author use physical description in paragraph six to convey Rikki\'s emotional state during the confrontation?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['The physical details primarily demonstrate Rikki\'s confidence and aggression, showing that he is eager to fight and views Nag as a lesser opponent he can easily defeat.','The author includes these details to provide scientific accuracy about mongoose behaviour during territorial encounters, prioritising factual description over emotional storytelling.','Details like puffed-up fur, dancing on tiptoes, a bristling tail, and a hammering heart externalise Rikki\'s fear and readiness, showing emotion through action rather than telling the reader how he feels.','The physical descriptions serve mainly to slow the pace of the narrative, giving the reader a pause between the dialogue with Nag and the action that follows in later paragraphs.'],c:2,e:'Kipling uses the "show, don\'t tell" principle masterfully here. Instead of writing "Rikki was scared but brave," he gives us puffed fur (making himself look bigger), tiptoe dancing (ready to dodge), bristling tail (instinctive alarm), and a hammering heart (fear). Every physical detail carries emotional information, letting the reader feel Rikki\'s state rather than being told about it.'},
      {q:'What is the effect of the passage\'s final sentence: "The real battle, the one that would decide whether the family lived or died, had not yet started"?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['It reassures the reader that Rikki has already proven himself capable of defeating the cobras, building confidence that the family will ultimately be protected from harm.','It shifts the focus from Rikki\'s personal bravery to the wider theme of nature\'s indifference, suggesting that the outcome is determined by instinct rather than individual choice.','It provides a satisfying conclusion to the passage by resolving the tension between Rikki and Nag, letting the reader know the family is now safe from the cobra threat.','It reframes everything that came before as merely a prelude, dramatically raising the stakes and compelling the reader to continue by promising even greater danger ahead.'],c:3,e:'Structurally, this final sentence transforms the passage from a self-contained scene into the opening act of a larger drama. By calling the confrontation with Nag "only the beginning" and introducing life-or-death stakes for the family, it retroactively heightens everything we have read and creates powerful forward momentum. The reader realises that if this was the easy part, what comes next must be extraordinary.'},
      {q:'The passage tells us that Nag and Nagaina "considered the garden their kingdom." What does this word choice suggest about the coming conflict?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['The word "kingdom" is used humorously to exaggerate the cobras\' self-importance, suggesting that Kipling views their territorial claims as amusing rather than genuinely threatening.','The word "kingdom" frames the garden as territory to be ruled, making the conflict between Rikki and the cobras a war over sovereignty rather than a simple animal encounter.','The word "kingdom" emphasises how long Nag and Nagaina have lived in the garden, suggesting their deep familiarity with the space gives them a natural advantage over any newcomer.','The word "kingdom" reveals that the cobras see themselves as benevolent guardians of the garden ecosystem, maintaining balance among the smaller creatures who live there.'],c:1,e:'"Kingdom" elevates the cobras from animals to rulers and the garden from a space to a domain. This word choice reframes the entire conflict: Rikki is not just a mongoose facing snakes — he is a challenger to an established regime. The arrival of a mongoose "threatened everything" because it threatens the cobras\' power, not just their safety. This political language gives the animal story a deeper, almost epic dimension.'}
  ]},
  {id:'F09',title:'The Workhouse Boy',type:'fiction',source:'Adapted from Charles Dickens, Oliver Twist (1838)',
   text:'The room where the boys ate their meals was a large stone hall, cold in every season, with a copper boiler at one end from which the master ladled out gruel at mealtimes. The gruel was thin — mostly water with a memory of oats — and each boy received one small bowlful and no more. On Sundays, they were given an additional quarter of bread. This was considered generous.\n\nOliver Twist and his companions had suffered the tortures of slow starvation for three months. They ate their gruel in silence, staring at the copper boiler with desperate eyes, and licked their fingers clean as though even the ghost of nourishment could be recovered from their own skin. The younger boys, especially, had grown hollow-cheeked and listless. One boy, who was tall for his age but so thin that his elbows looked like door knobs, whispered to his neighbours that unless he had another basin of gruel, he was afraid he might eat the boy who slept next to him. The others believed him.\n\nThey drew lots to decide who would ask for more, and the lot fell upon Oliver Twist.\n\nThe evening arrived. The boys took their places. The master stood behind the copper boiler in his apron, with his assistants lined up beside him. The gruel was served, and it vanished in seconds. The boys whispered to each other and nudged Oliver. He rose from the bench.\n\nChild as he was, Oliver was desperate. Hunger had worn away his shyness the way water wears away stone — slowly, invisibly, until one day the stone is no longer the shape it was. He walked to the master, bowl in hand, and said — quietly, but clearly enough to be heard across the silent hall:\n\n\'Please, sir, I want some more.\'\n\nThe master was a fat, healthy man, well-fed on the same food budget that left fifty boys starving. He stared at Oliver with a mixture of disbelief and outrage, as though the child had asked for permission to set the building on fire. His face turned white, then red. He gripped the ladle so tightly that his knuckles cracked.\n\n\'What?\' he said, in a voice that could have curdled milk.\n\nOliver, trembling, repeated his request.\n\nThe hall erupted. The assistants grabbed Oliver. The master struck him with the ladle. Within the hour, Oliver had been dragged before the board of governors, who declared, with absolute sincerity, that the boy was destined for the gallows. Asking for more food — in a building funded specifically to feed hungry children — was treated as an act of rebellion so dangerous that it could only end in hanging.\n\nAnd that, Dickens tells us, was considered perfectly reasonable by everyone in the room except Oliver.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['Oliver\'s individual courage sets him apart from the other boys, and the passage focuses on his personal bravery in standing up to authority despite knowing the severe consequences he would face.','The passage highlights the collective solidarity of the workhouse boys, who band together through a democratic process to challenge the adults and ultimately succeed in improving their conditions.','A starving child\'s simple request for more food is treated as a criminal act, exposing the cruelty and hypocrisy of the institutions supposed to care for the poor.','The passage explores how Victorian workhouses provided basic but adequate care for orphans, focusing on Oliver\'s difficulty adjusting to the strict rules and limited routines of institutional life.'],c:2,e:'The passage builds towards the absurdity of Oliver\'s punishment. A child in a building \'funded specifically to feed hungry children\' is treated as a criminal for asking for food. The gap between what the institution should do and what it actually does is the passage\'s central point.'},
      {q:'Hunger is described as wearing away Oliver\'s shyness \'the way water wears away stone — slowly, invisibly, until one day the stone is no longer the shape it was\'. What does this simile suggest?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['Hunger is a gradual, relentless force that reshapes a person\'s character over time — Oliver did not suddenly become brave, but was slowly worn down until desperation overcame fear.','The simile compares Oliver to water, suggesting he is adaptable and resourceful, able to find ways around obstacles just as water flows around stone.','Oliver is compared to a stone because he is emotionally hardened and unfeeling, suggesting that the workhouse has already turned him cold and indifferent before he even asks for more.','Oliver\'s shyness vanished suddenly when the other boys chose him by drawing lots, and his anger at being selected is what drove him to confront the master rather than any gradual change.'],c:0,e:'The simile compares hunger to water erosion — both are invisible processes that transform something solid over time. This reframes Oliver\'s famous request not as a single brave moment but as the inevitable result of months of suffering. He doesn\'t choose courage; starvation removes his ability to stay silent.'},
      {q:'What is Dickens\'s tone in the final paragraph, and how can you tell?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Cheerful and admiring — Dickens presents the workhouse as a well-run institution and the governors as sensible men making difficult decisions about limited resources.','Neutral and documentary — Dickens reports the events exactly as they happened without inserting his own judgement, allowing the reader to form their own conclusions about the workhouse system.','Bitterly ironic — Dickens states that the governors\' reaction was \'considered perfectly reasonable\' by everyone except Oliver, using irony to expose how outrageous the situation truly is.','Sympathetic towards the master — Dickens understands the difficulty of managing fifty hungry boys on a limited budget and portrays the staff as doing their best under impossible circumstances.'],c:2,e:'The final sentence is devastating irony. Dickens says the reaction was \'considered perfectly reasonable\' — but the passage has just shown us it is anything but reasonable. By stating the characters\' insane perspective as fact, he forces the reader to see the gap between what these people believe and what is actually true.'},
      {q:'Why does Dickens describe the master as \'a fat, healthy man, well-fed on the same food budget that left fifty boys starving\'?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['To suggest that the master\'s good health proves the food is nutritious enough — the boys\' hunger comes from their growing bodies needing more than an adult portion, not from the institution being cruel.','To explain that Victorian adults were expected to eat more than children, reflecting the social norms of the period rather than any personal failing on the master\'s part.','To show that the master has earned his comfortable position through years of service, implying that the workhouse system rewards loyalty and hard work even among its staff.','To create a damning contrast — the master thrives on resources meant for the children, exposing the system\'s corruption where those in charge benefit while those they serve go hungry.'],c:3,e:'The detail is surgical. Dickens does not need to call the master cruel — the physical contrast does it for him. The master is \'fat, healthy\' while the boys are \'hollow-cheeked and listless\', and they share the same budget. The reader draws the obvious conclusion: the master is eating the children\'s food.'},
      {q:'The board of governors declares that Oliver is \'destined for the gallows\' for asking for more food. What theme does this extreme reaction develop?',skill:'Theme',opts:['Oliver\'s request proves he is ungrateful for the care the workhouse provides, and the governors\' reaction reflects a reasonable concern that one boy\'s defiance could inspire wider disobedience.','The governors genuinely believe they are protecting the other children by making an example of Oliver, and the passage explores the theme of well-intentioned authority figures making harsh but necessary decisions.','Systems of power can become so corrupt that they treat the most basic human needs as threats — when the powerful benefit from injustice, any challenge to the system, however small, is treated as dangerous.','The passage explores the theme of childhood innocence, suggesting that Oliver\'s simple request reveals how children see the world more clearly than adults and are unafraid to speak obvious truths.'],c:2,e:'Oliver\'s request threatens the system not because it is violent but because it exposes the truth: the children are starving, and the people in charge know it. Declaring him destined for hanging is not about justice — it is about silencing a challenge to the comfortable arrangement that keeps the governors well-fed and the children quiet.'},
      {q:'From whose point of view is the story told, and how does this affect the reader\'s understanding?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['The master\'s point of view, which helps the reader understand the pressures of managing a workhouse and explains why a seemingly cruel reaction might feel justified from inside the system.','A neutral journalist reporting facts without opinion or bias, presenting both the boys\' suffering and the governors\' reasoning with equal weight so the reader must decide who is right.','A third-person omniscient narrator who uses irony to expose the workhouse system — this allows the reader to see both the characters\' absurd beliefs and the reality they ignore.','Oliver\'s first-person perspective, which limits the reader to his childish understanding of events and prevents them from seeing the full picture of why the adults respond the way they do.'],c:2,e:'The third-person omniscient narrator can describe Oliver\'s desperation and the master\'s cruelty simultaneously. Crucially, this viewpoint allows Dickens to use dramatic irony — stating that the governors\' reaction was \'perfectly reasonable\' while the reader knows it is monstrous. A first-person narrator could not achieve this double vision.'},
      {q:'What does the phrase \'gruel was thin — mostly water with a memory of oats\' suggest about the quality of the food?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['The word "memory" suggests the gruel is made from an old family recipe that has been passed down through generations of workhouse cooks, connecting the food to tradition rather than deprivation.','The oats are so scarce that their presence is barely detectable — calling it a \'memory\' implies the gruel is almost entirely water, with only a ghost of real nourishment.','The word "memory" implies that the oats were once present in larger quantities but the recipe has been deliberately watered down over time, suggesting a gradual decline in standards rather than intentional cruelty.','The phrase "memory of oats" is a factual description of how porridge becomes thinner when cooked in large batches, reflecting practical kitchen limitations rather than deliberate starvation.'],c:1,e:'The word \'memory\' is used metaphorically to suggest something that was once present but has almost disappeared. Just as a memory is a faint trace of something real, the oats are a faint trace of actual food. This clever word choice reinforces the theme of starvation without Dickens needing to state it directly.'},
      {q:'Why does the author describe how the boys \'licked their fingers clean as though even the ghost of nourishment could be recovered from their own skin\'?',skill:'Author\'s purpose & tone',opts:['To make the reader viscerally feel the boys\' desperation — the image of children trying to extract nutrition from their own skin is designed to provoke outrage at the system that allows this.','To show that the boys have developed their own rituals around mealtimes, turning the act of eating into a shared bonding experience that helps them cope with workhouse life.','To demonstrate the boys\' good manners and discipline — even in poverty they eat neatly and clean up after themselves, which reflects the workhouse\'s success in teaching them proper behaviour.','To illustrate that the boys are still children who find amusement even in difficult circumstances, using the finger-licking as a playful habit rather than a sign of genuine hunger.'],c:0,e:'Dickens uses this detail to create physical revulsion in the reader. The image of children licking their own fingers for traces of food is deliberately shocking. His purpose is social criticism — he wants the reader to feel angry at institutions that starve children while claiming to care for them.'},
      {q:'How does the passage use contrast to develop its meaning?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['It contrasts Oliver\'s life before and after entering the workhouse, showing that his earlier life with a loving family was happy and secure, which makes his current suffering feel like a fall from grace.','It repeatedly contrasts the powerful and the powerless — the fat master versus the starving boys, the institution\'s stated purpose versus its actual cruelty, and the small request versus the extreme punishment.','It contrasts the boys\' behaviour with the adults\' behaviour, showing that the children are orderly and obedient while the staff are disorganised and incompetent at managing their responsibilities.','It contrasts the cold stone hall with the warmth of the copper boiler, using the physical setting to symbolise a workhouse that provides just enough heat and food to keep the boys alive but not comfortable.'],c:1,e:'Contrast is the passage\'s main structural tool. The master is \'fat, healthy\' while the boys are \'hollow-cheeked\'. The building is \'funded specifically to feed hungry children\' yet starves them. Oliver makes a modest request and receives a violent, disproportionate response. Each contrast exposes the same hypocrisy from a different angle.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about the board of governors from their reaction to Oliver\'s request?',skill:'Inference',opts:['They are genuinely frightened that Oliver might inspire a dangerous uprising among the other boys, and their harsh response is a reasonable security measure to prevent fifty starving children from rioting.','They want to help Oliver but are constrained by strict government regulations that dictate exact portion sizes, making them victims of the same system that harms the children.','They are shocked because Oliver\'s request violates a clear rule that every boy understands, and their punishment reflects a consistent enforcement of boundaries rather than personal cruelty.','They are more concerned with maintaining their authority and the system that benefits them than with the welfare of the children they are supposed to protect.'],c:3,e:'The governors declare Oliver \'destined for the gallows\' for asking for food. This extreme overreaction reveals that they view any challenge to their authority as a threat. Their \'absolute sincerity\' suggests they genuinely believe their own warped logic, which makes their corruption even more disturbing — they don\'t see themselves as villains.'},
      {q:'The tall boy whispers that \'unless he had another basin of gruel, he was afraid he might eat the boy who slept next to him\'. What is the effect of this darkly comic detail?',skill:'Inference',opts:['It reveals the tall boy as a genuine threat to the younger children, foreshadowing violence among the boys themselves and suggesting that the real danger in the workhouse comes from within their own group.','It shows that the boys still have enough energy and spirit to joke around, suggesting that their situation, while uncomfortable, is not as dire as the narrator claims.','It uses grim humour to convey the severity of the boys\' hunger — the exaggeration makes the reader both laugh and feel horrified, reinforcing how desperate conditions have become.','It is meant to be taken literally — the boy is genuinely considering cannibalism, and Dickens includes this detail to show that the workhouse has reduced the children to an animalistic state beyond recovery.'],c:2,e:'The detail works on two levels. On the surface, it is darkly funny — a boy threatening cannibalism over porridge. But the fact that \'the others believed him\' undercuts the humour and reveals genuine desperation. Dickens often uses this technique: making the reader laugh before making them feel guilty for laughing.'},
      {q:'What role does the character of Oliver play within the group of boys, and why is this significant?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['Oliver is chosen by drawing lots, making him an unwilling representative of the group\'s collective desperation — his request speaks for all the boys, not just himself.','Oliver is the group\'s natural leader, chosen because the other boys respect his confidence and look up to him as the bravest and most articulate speaker among them.','Oliver acts entirely alone, driven by his own hunger rather than the group\'s need, and the other boys watch in surprise because they had no idea he would make such a bold request.','Oliver volunteers eagerly because he wants to prove himself to the older boys, using the situation as an opportunity to gain social status and respect within the workhouse hierarchy.'],c:0,e:'The drawing of lots is significant because it means Oliver does not choose to be brave — he is chosen. This makes his request a collective act of desperation rather than individual courage. The other boys \'whispered to each other and nudged Oliver\', showing he carries their hopes. His punishment is therefore an act against all of them.'}
  ]},
  {id:'F10',title:'The River Bank',type:'fiction',source:'Adapted from Kenneth Grahame, The Wind in the Willows (1908)',
   text:'The Mole had been working very hard all morning, spring-cleaning his little underground home. He had swept and dusted and whitewashed until his arms ached, and his back was sore, and his fur was full of chalk. Spring was stirring above him — he could feel it, even underground, the way you feel music through a wall without hearing the tune. The air tasted different. Something was calling to him.\n\nSuddenly, without quite knowing how, he had flung down his brush, said \'Bother!\' and \'Hang spring-cleaning!\' and bolted out of the house. He scrambled up the steep little tunnel that led to the surface, and the next moment he was standing in the warm sunshine of a meadow, blinking like a man who has stepped out of a dark cinema into a bright afternoon.\n\nEverything was new. The warm sun on his fur. The breeze that carried the scent of flowers and fresh-cut grass. Birds were singing in every tree, and the sky was the sort of blue that makes you want to lie on your back and stare at it forever. The Mole ran across the meadow with the pure, unthinking joy of an animal released, not caring where he was going, only knowing that he was above ground and that the world was magnificent.\n\nHe ran until he reached the river. He had never seen a river before — his whole life had been spent in underground tunnels and cramped, dark rooms — and the sight of it stopped him completely. It was wide and slow-moving, glinting in the sunlight, with willows trailing their branches in the water and water-voles popping in and out of holes in the bank. The river seemed alive — not just carrying water, but carrying stories, adventures, entire worlds flowing past.\n\n\'Are you coming in, or just going to stand there with your mouth open?\' said a voice.\n\nThe Mole looked down and saw a Water Rat sitting in a small blue boat, polishing a pair of oars with a cloth. The Rat had bright eyes, a cheerful face, and the air of someone who had never spent a single anxious minute in his entire life.\n\n\'I\'ve never been in a boat,\' the Mole said, rather shyly.\n\n\'Never been in a —!\' The Rat\'s mouth fell open. \'Well, what have you been doing all your life?\'\n\n\'Living underground,\' said the Mole.\n\nThe Rat stared at him for a moment, then laughed — not unkindly, but with the genuine amazement of someone who had just heard the saddest thing imaginable. He held out a paw.\n\n\'Come along then,\' he said. \'There\'s nothing — absolutely nothing — half so much worth doing as simply messing about in boats.\'',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the central theme of this passage?',skill:'Theme',opts:['The dangers of leaving your home without a plan — the Mole\'s impulsive decision to abandon his chores leads him into an unfamiliar environment where he is vulnerable and dependent on a stranger.','The joy of discovering a wider world and the freedom that comes from stepping outside your comfort zone.','The importance of friendship between different species — the passage focuses on how the Mole and the Rat form an unlikely partnership based on their complementary personalities and shared love of nature.','The importance of finishing what you start — the Mole\'s abandonment of his spring-cleaning represents a failure of discipline that the passage gently criticises through the chaos that follows.'],c:1,e:'Every moment in the passage reinforces this theme. The Mole moves from a dark, cramped underground home to sunshine, meadows, and a river he has never seen. His journey is both physical (underground to above ground) and emotional (routine to wonder). Meeting the Rat opens up yet another new world — the river.'},
      {q:'Spring is described as something the Mole can feel underground \'the way you feel music through a wall without hearing the tune\'. What does this simile suggest?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['The simile suggests that the Mole\'s senses are dulled by years underground, implying he can barely perceive the outside world and only notices spring because it is unusually strong this year.','The comparison to music suggests the Mole experiences spring as entertainment — a pleasant background distraction from his housework rather than a powerful force that disrupts his routine.','Spring\'s arrival is a powerful, instinctive feeling that reaches the Mole even through barriers — he cannot see or hear it directly, but something in him responds to it, pulling him towards the surface.','The simile emphasises the physical barrier between the Mole and the surface world, suggesting he is trapped underground against his will and can only dream of escaping.'],c:2,e:'The simile captures something felt but not fully understood. When you feel bass through a wall, you can\'t identify the song, but you know music is playing. Similarly, the Mole can\'t see spring from underground, but he senses its energy. This instinctive pull is what drives him to abandon his cleaning and bolt for the surface.'},
      {q:'How would you describe the overall tone of this passage?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Warm, joyful, and gently humorous — the passage celebrates simple pleasures and the delight of new experiences, with affectionate comedy in the dialogue.','Cold and formal — the passage reads like a naturalist\'s field report, describing the Mole\'s behaviour with scientific detachment rather than emotional warmth or affection.','Dark and threatening — the Mole is vulnerable above ground among predators, and the bright descriptions of sunshine and flowers disguise an underlying sense of danger that builds towards a confrontation.','Sad and nostalgic — the Mole immediately regrets leaving his underground home and spends the passage longing to return to the safety and familiarity of his tunnel.'],c:0,e:'The tone combines sensory joy (sunshine, birdsong, \'the sort of blue that makes you want to lie on your back\') with gentle humour (the Rat\'s disbelief that anyone could have never been in a boat). There is no danger, no villain, no tension — just the pleasure of discovery. The warmth extends to the dialogue, where even teasing is kind.'},
      {q:'Why does the Rat laugh \'not unkindly, but with the genuine amazement of someone who had just heard the saddest thing imaginable\' when the Mole says he has lived underground?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['The Rat is laughing at the Mole\'s ignorance, finding it comical that anyone could be so sheltered — his amusement is condescending rather than sympathetic, establishing a power dynamic between them.','The Rat laughs because he is relieved to find a companion who knows nothing about the river — he can position himself as an expert and teacher, satisfying his own need for importance.','The Rat is nervous because he prefers solitude and laughs awkwardly to cover his discomfort at having to make conversation with an uninvited stranger who interrupted his morning routine.','The Rat genuinely cannot comprehend a life without the river and boats — his amazement reveals both his love for his own world and his immediate sympathy for what the Mole has been missing, which motivates his invitation.'],c:3,e:'The phrase \'not unkindly\' is crucial — the Rat isn\'t mocking the Mole. His laughter comes from genuine disbelief that anyone could live without the river. Calling it \'the saddest thing imaginable\' shows his values — to him, life without water and boats is barely life at all. His immediate response is to invite the Mole in.'},
      {q:'The Mole sees the river and thinks it is \'not just carrying water, but carrying stories, adventures, entire worlds flowing past\'. What does this personification suggest about what the river represents?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['The Mole is hallucinating from sudden exposure to bright light after a lifetime underground, and his exaggerated perception of the river reflects confusion rather than genuine wonder.','The river reminds the Mole of bedtime stories he was told as a child underground, triggering childhood memories rather than inspiring new feelings about the world above.','The river represents possibility and adventure — the Mole sees it not just as a body of water but as a gateway to a wider, richer life full of experiences he has never had.','The river is described this way to foreshadow danger — the "stories" and "adventures" it carries include threats and hardships the Mole does not yet understand, giving the description an ominous undertone.'],c:2,e:'By giving the river the ability to \'carry stories\' and \'adventures\', Grahame transforms it from a landscape feature into a symbol. For the Mole, who has only known tunnels, the river represents everything he has been missing — movement, variety, connection, and the unknown. This is the moment he falls in love with the world above ground.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about the Mole\'s life before this passage from the details given?',skill:'Inference',opts:['He has a large social circle underground and regularly hosts visitors, but has simply never ventured to the surface himself because his community provides everything he needs.','He has visited the surface before but always returned quickly, and his reaction to the river is exaggerated because he wants to impress the Rat with his enthusiasm.','He recently moved underground after previously living near the river, and his emotional reaction is one of nostalgic recognition rather than genuine first-time discovery.','His life has been narrow, routine, and isolated — he has never seen a river or been in a boat, suggesting he has spent his entire existence underground doing domestic tasks without experiencing the wider world.'],c:3,e:'The passage provides several clues: the Mole\'s \'whole life had been spent in underground tunnels and cramped, dark rooms\', he has \'never seen a river\' and \'never been in a boat\'. These details build a picture of extreme isolation. His explosive joy at the surface world only makes sense if we understand how confined his previous life was.'},
      {q:'How does the author structure the passage to build towards the Mole\'s discovery of the river?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['The passage moves from enclosed spaces to open ones — underground home, then meadow, then the wide river — each setting larger and more exciting than the last, creating a crescendo of wonder.','The passage is structured as a debate between the Mole\'s desire for adventure and his guilt about abandoning his chores, weighing the arguments for freedom against the responsibilities of home.','The passage alternates between the Mole\'s inner thoughts and the Rat\'s inner thoughts in equal measure, giving the reader dual perspectives on the same river landscape.','The passage builds towards a sudden anticlimax — after the excitement of discovery, the Mole\'s conversation with the Rat is deliberately deflating, showing that reality rarely matches expectation.'],c:0,e:'Grahame structures the passage as an expanding journey. The Mole starts in a cramped tunnel, emerges into a sunlit meadow, and finally encounters the vast river. Each stage is bigger and more wondrous. This spatial expansion mirrors the Mole\'s emotional journey from routine to freedom to awe.'},
      {q:'What is the author\'s purpose in writing this passage?',skill:'Author\'s purpose & tone',opts:['To celebrate the joy of new experiences and the natural world, encouraging the reader to see everyday wonders — sunshine, rivers, friendship — with the same fresh eyes as the Mole.','To teach readers factual information about the habitats and behaviours of moles and water rats, using the fictional framework as a vehicle for a nature documentary aimed at children.','To warn young readers about the dangers of talking to strangers, using the Mole\'s trusting acceptance of the Rat\'s invitation as an example of naivety that could lead to harm.','To argue that domestic responsibilities should be prioritised over leisure, using the Mole\'s impulsive abandonment of his chores as a cautionary example of what happens when duty is neglected.'],c:0,e:'Grahame uses the Mole\'s first experience of the surface world to make familiar things feel extraordinary. Sunshine, birdsong, and a river become magical because we see them through someone encountering them for the first time. The author\'s purpose is to reawaken the reader\'s sense of wonder at the natural world.'},
      {q:'What does the Mole\'s action of flinging down his brush and saying \'Bother!\' and \'Hang spring-cleaning!\' reveal about his character?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['He is an irresponsible character who cannot commit to anything — his abandonment of the spring-cleaning foreshadows a pattern of starting projects and leaving them unfinished.','He is frightened by the physical demands of spring-cleaning and uses the call of spring as a convenient excuse to escape hard work, revealing laziness rather than adventurous spirit.','Beneath his routine domestic life, the Mole has an impulsive, adventurous spirit — he acts on instinct without planning, suggesting he has been suppressing a need for freedom.','He is angry at himself for wasting the morning on chores and storms out in frustration, suggesting the outburst comes from irritation rather than from any positive impulse towards adventure.'],c:2,e:'The Mole\'s sudden abandonment of his chores reveals a character who can be swept away by feeling. He doesn\'t plan his escape — he acts on an instinct he cannot even name. This impulsiveness is presented positively, as a sign of his deeper need for something more than routine. It sets the tone for his whole adventure.'},
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['A sheltered creature discovers the wider world for the first time and finds it magnificent — his journey from underground confinement to riverside wonder represents the transformative power of new experience.','The passage is mainly about the Mole\'s spring-cleaning routine and the satisfaction he takes in domestic work, with the river trip serving as a brief interruption before he returns home.','The main idea is that the natural world contains hidden dangers beneath its beauty, and the Mole\'s naivety about the surface world leaves him vulnerable to exploitation by more experienced animals.','The passage explores the Rat\'s loneliness, suggesting he invites the Mole into his boat because he desperately needs companionship after years of living alone on the river bank.'],c:0,e:'Everything in the passage serves the Mole\'s journey from confinement to discovery. He moves from sweeping his dark tunnel to standing in sunshine, running across meadows, and seeing a river for the first time. The main idea is that stepping outside what you know can transform your understanding of the world.'},
      {q:'The Mole runs across the meadow \'with the pure, unthinking joy of an animal released\'. What does the phrase \'unthinking\' suggest here?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['The word suggests the Mole is unintelligent and acts without any rational thought, implying his joy is shallow and animal-like rather than a meaningful emotional experience.','His joy is instinctive and physical rather than intellectual — he is not reflecting on his happiness but simply experiencing it, like an animal freed from a cage.','The word implies the Mole is in a state of confusion caused by sensory overload — he cannot process his new surroundings and is running blindly rather than joyfully.','The word "unthinking" is a gentle criticism from the narrator, who views the Mole\'s reckless dash across unfamiliar terrain as foolish and irresponsible rather than joyful.'],c:1,e:'The word \'unthinking\' is not negative here — it describes joy that is so pure it bypasses thought entirely. The Mole doesn\'t analyse or question his happiness; he simply feels it. The comparison to \'an animal released\' reinforces this: his joy is primal, physical, and completely in the moment.'},
      {q:'How does the dialogue between the Mole and the Rat help develop the passage\'s themes?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['Their conversation reveals that the Rat and the Mole have met before in a different context, and their dialogue is a renewal of an old acquaintance rather than a first meeting.','The dialogue focuses mainly on practical boating details — the Rat explains how to row, where to sit, and what safety precautions to take before getting into the water.','The dialogue reveals that the Rat is territorial and reluctant to share his space, only inviting the Mole aboard out of social obligation rather than genuine enthusiasm.','Their exchange highlights the contrast between the Mole\'s sheltered inexperience and the Rat\'s confident familiarity with the river world — their meeting promises that the Mole\'s journey of discovery is just beginning.'],c:3,e:'The Rat\'s astonishment at the Mole never having been in a boat mirrors the reader\'s delight at the Mole\'s innocence. Their dialogue establishes a dynamic — the Rat as experienced guide, the Mole as eager newcomer — that promises further adventures. The Rat\'s invitation represents the next stage of the Mole\'s expanding world.'}
  ]},
  {id:'F11',title:'The Last Lap',type:'fiction',source:'Original passage — school sports / contemporary fiction',
   text:'Priya\'s lungs were screaming. The 800 metres had never felt this long, and the packed stands on either side of the track had turned into a single roaring blur. She could hear Coach Adeyemi\'s voice cutting through the noise — \'Arms! Arms!\' — reminding her to pump harder, to stop wasting energy with her shoulders hunched up around her ears. She had been working on that for weeks in training, but in the heat of a race, her body always reverted to its old habits.\n\nShe was in third place. The girl from Ashfield Academy was five metres ahead, her ponytail swinging like a metronome — steady, mechanical, unreachable. Second place. Priya had already accepted she couldn\'t catch her. But the runner right in front — the tall one from Greenhill in the green vest — was fading. Her stride was shortening, her head was tilting back, and Priya recognised the signs because she had been there herself a hundred times: the body begging to stop, the legs filling with concrete, the strange temptation to simply step off the track and walk away.\n\nTwo hundred metres to go. The bell rang, sharp and bright, and the crowd noise surged like a wave breaking. Priya forced her arms to swing faster and felt her legs respond — not willingly, but obediently, the way a tired dog follows its owner home. The gap shrank: four metres, three, two. She pulled level with the Greenhill runner and heard the girl\'s ragged breathing beside her, each exhale a small, desperate sound. Their elbows almost touched.\n\nFor a moment they ran together, stride for stride, and Priya felt something unexpected: sympathy. She knew exactly what the other girl was feeling — the burning thighs, the lungs that couldn\'t fill, the voice in your head screaming that you should just stop and let the pain end. Last month, at the county trials, Priya had been the one fading in the final straight, watching helplessly as another runner pulled away from her. She had crossed the line in fifth place, bent double, tasting metal on her tongue, and Coach Adeyemi had said nothing — which was worse than shouting.\n\nBut today was different. Today, something shifted. Priya dropped her shoulders, lengthened her stride, and found a gear she didn\'t know she had. It wasn\'t that the pain disappeared — it didn\'t. It roared louder than ever. But it stopped mattering. The Greenhill runner fell behind — one metre, two, three — and then Priya was through, arms pumping, eyes fixed on the white line, running not away from pain but straight into it. She crossed the line in second place, collapsed onto the track, and lay staring at the sky while the crowd noise faded to a distant hum. Her lungs burned. Her legs shook. And she was smiling.',
   questions:[
      {q:'The passage moves through several emotional stages. Which sequence best describes the tone shifts?',skill:'Author\'s purpose & tone',opts:['Calm and reflective → tense and competitive → nostalgic and regretful → quietly resigned, as Priya accepts she cannot catch the leader and focuses on finishing.','Hopeful and energetic → anxious and self-doubting → angry and frustrated → numb and emotionless, as Priya shuts down her feelings to survive the final lap.','Detached and analytical → panicked and desperate → peaceful and accepting → bittersweet and melancholy, as Priya realises racing demands more than she can give.','Urgent and physical → tense and tactical → reflective and sympathetic → explosive and triumphant.'],c:3,e:'Paragraph one is physical urgency (screaming lungs, Coach shouting). Paragraph two shifts to tactical awareness (reading the Greenhill runner\'s body language). Paragraph four becomes reflective (sympathy, the county trials memory). The final paragraph is explosive — Priya finds her extra gear and finishes with a triumphant, exhausted smile.'},
      {q:'"Her ponytail swinging like a metronome — steady, mechanical, unreachable." What does this simile reveal about how Priya sees the Ashfield runner?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['The simile suggests Priya finds the Ashfield runner\'s style boring and uninspired — mechanical rather than athletic — implying Priya views her own more expressive running form as ultimately superior.','The simile suggests Priya feels intimidated by the runner\'s lack of visible effort, but believes such mechanical running lacks the heart and passion needed to win a close race.','The comparison reveals that Priya thinks the Ashfield runner is pacing herself conservatively, holding back energy for a final sprint rather than running flat out.','She sees the runner as having a machine-like, effortless consistency that is beyond Priya\'s ability to match — someone operating on a different level.'],c:3,e:'A metronome keeps perfect, unvarying time. By comparing the Ashfield runner to one, Priya reveals that she sees this competitor as impossibly consistent. The three adjectives (\'steady, mechanical, unreachable\') escalate from description to judgement, showing Priya has already mentally surrendered this battle to focus on the one she can win.'},
      {q:'Why does the author include the detail about Coach Adeyemi saying nothing after the county trials — and why is that described as \'worse than shouting\'?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['To suggest that Coach Adeyemi was angry with Priya and held her poor performance against her, creating unresolved tension between them that adds pressure to today\'s race.','To show that Coach Adeyemi uses deliberate silence as a coaching technique, withholding feedback to force Priya to evaluate her own performance independently.','To establish that the county trials were insignificant to Coach Adeyemi and not worth discussing, suggesting Priya cares more about competitive results than her coach does.','To reveal that Priya values the coach\'s opinion so much that his silence felt like deeper disappointment than anger would have — she carries the weight of that failure into today\'s race.'],c:3,e:'Silence from someone whose opinion matters is often more painful than criticism. This detail reveals that Priya\'s motivation today is partly fuelled by wanting to prove herself after that failure — she\'s running against her own past as much as against the other girls.'},
      {q:'Priya\'s legs respond \'not willingly, but obediently, the way a tired dog follows its owner home\'. What does this comparison reveal?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['She is thinking about her pet dog waiting at home, which distracts her from the race and causes her to lose focus on the Greenhill runner ahead of her.','The comparison suggests Priya\'s legs are unreliable and might give way at any moment, foreshadowing an injury that will prevent her from finishing the race.','The simile reveals that Priya resents her own body for not being naturally talented, viewing her legs as stubborn obstacles rather than allies in the race.','Her body has no energy left but is still following her willpower — she is forcing herself forward through mental strength alone.'],c:3,e:'The simile separates willingness from obedience. A tired dog doesn\'t want to keep walking, but it follows anyway. Similarly, Priya\'s body has no desire to continue, but her mind is overriding her exhaustion. This reinforces the theme of mental toughness.'},
      {q:'\'It wasn\'t that the pain disappeared — it didn\'t. It roared louder than ever. But it stopped mattering.\' Which theme does this best support?',skill:'Theme',opts:['True determination is not about avoiding pain but about choosing to keep going despite it — courage means accepting difficulty, not escaping it.','The importance of following your coach\'s technical instructions precisely, since Priya\'s breakthrough only happens after she corrects her arm movement as Coach Adeyemi taught her.','The shared suffering of competition creates a bond between rivals that is stronger than winning — Priya\'s moment of sympathy for the Greenhill runner is the passage\'s emotional climax.','Competitive sport is fundamentally unfair because natural talent determines outcomes — Priya can only beat the fading Greenhill runner, never the dominant Ashfield girl ahead of them both.'],c:0,e:'This is the passage\'s thematic core. Priya\'s breakthrough doesn\'t come from the pain going away — it comes from her relationship with pain changing. Combined with the final line (\'running not away from pain but straight into it\'), the passage redefines determination as a choice to embrace difficulty.'},
      {q:'From whose point of view is the passage told, and what effect does this create?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['Third-person limited, closely following Priya\'s thoughts and physical sensations — this immerses the reader inside her experience of pain, doubt, and determination during the race.','The coach\'s point of view, watching the race from the sidelines and assessing Priya\'s technique, which explains why the passage focuses heavily on arm movement and body position.','First-person narration by Priya, who is telling the story years later as a successful adult athlete reflecting on the race that changed her approach to competition.','Omniscient narration that reveals the Greenhill runner\'s thoughts alongside Priya\'s, allowing the reader to understand how both athletes experience the same moment of passing differently.'],c:0,e:'The passage stays tightly inside Priya\'s consciousness. We feel her burning lungs, hear Coach Adeyemi\'s voice as she hears it, and share her tactical thinking. This close third-person perspective creates intensity — the reader experiences the race from inside Priya\'s body and mind, making the final breakthrough feel personal.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about Priya\'s relationship with running from the details about the county trials?',skill:'Inference',opts:['She has decided to quit running after the county trials and is only competing today because she promised the school she would represent them in this final event.','Running is deeply important to her — the memory of finishing fifth and Coach Adeyemi\'s silence still haunts her, suggesting she measures her self-worth partly through her performance.','She found the county trials easy and finished in a comfortable position, suggesting she is overconfident about today\'s race and has not trained seriously enough.','She only started running recently and is competing in her first-ever 800 metres, which explains her lack of experience with managing pain in the final lap.'],c:1,e:'The county trials memory surfaces mid-race, showing it still affects Priya. She remembers \'tasting metal on her tongue\' and her coach\'s painful silence. These vivid, lingering details suggest running is central to her identity — she doesn\'t just want to run well, she needs to, and past failure weighs on her.'},
      {q:'How is the passage structured to build tension towards the climax?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['The passage begins with the finish and works backwards to explain how Priya reached that point, using reverse chronology to build mystery about the outcome before revealing the journey.','It uses a series of flashbacks that interrupt the race timeline, cutting between the current event and detailed memories of every previous race Priya has run this season.','It narrows focus progressively — from the whole race to Priya\'s position, to the gap with one runner, to stride-by-stride competition, to the final internal shift — creating increasing intensity.','It alternates between Priya\'s perspective and the Greenhill runner\'s perspective in equal measure, giving both athletes full interior monologues during the final 200 metres.'],c:2,e:'The structure mirrors the narrowing of a race. It starts wide (the packed stands, the 800m), focuses on Priya\'s tactical position, then zooms in on the gap closing metre by metre. The county trials memory provides a brief pause before the explosive final paragraph. This progressive narrowing builds tension naturally.'},
      {q:'What does the passage suggest about Priya\'s character through her moment of sympathy for the Greenhill runner?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['She considers deliberately slowing down to let the Greenhill runner stay ahead, valuing sportsmanship over competitive success and prioritising the other girl\'s feelings.','She studies the Greenhill runner\'s body language to learn how to fake exhaustion herself in future races, showing she is a calculating and manipulative competitor.','She is empathetic and self-aware — even while competing, she recognises shared suffering, which shows maturity and depth beyond simple competitiveness.','She is distracted by the Greenhill runner\'s suffering and nearly loses her rhythm, suggesting her sympathy is a weakness that undermines her competitive edge.'],c:2,e:'The sympathy moment reveals Priya\'s emotional complexity. Most sports narratives focus purely on winning, but Priya pauses to acknowledge that her competitor is experiencing the same pain she knows intimately. This doesn\'t weaken her — she still overtakes — but it adds depth to her character and connects to the passage\'s understanding of shared human struggle.'},
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['Running is too physically demanding for young people and the passage argues that schools should limit competitive events to protect students from the damaging effects of extreme exertion.','The passage focuses on the importance of Coach Adeyemi\'s technical instructions, showing that Priya\'s improvement in arm technique is the sole reason she overtakes the Greenhill runner.','Priya wins the 800 metres and sets a new school record, proving she is the most talented runner in her year group and validating Coach Adeyemi\'s training programme.','A young athlete overcomes past failure and present pain by finding a new relationship with difficulty — learning that breakthroughs come not from the absence of suffering but from pushing through it.'],c:3,e:'The passage builds towards a specific insight: pain \'stopped mattering\'. Priya doesn\'t find a way to avoid suffering — she finds a way to run through it. Combined with the county trials backstory, the main idea is about growth through difficulty and the difference between being defeated by pain and accepting it.'},
      {q:'Why does the author end the passage with Priya lying on the track, looking at the sky, and smiling?',skill:'Author\'s purpose & tone',opts:['To show that her achievement is personal rather than competitive — the smile comes from having overcome herself, not from the second-place finish, creating a quiet, satisfying resolution.','To create a dramatic cliffhanger, leaving the reader uncertain about whether Priya has collapsed from exhaustion or finished the race successfully.','To suggest that Priya has been seriously injured and needs medical attention, ending the passage on a note of concern rather than triumph.','To show that Priya is disappointed with second place and the smile is forced — she is masking her frustration at failing to catch the Ashfield runner who beat her.'],c:0,e:'The ending is deliberately peaceful after the intensity of the race. Priya doesn\'t celebrate with a crowd or check her time — she lies still and smiles. This inward focus tells us the victory that matters is internal. The author\'s purpose is to redefine success: it is not about the position but about the breakthrough.'},
      {q:'Priya reads the Greenhill runner\'s body language: \'her stride was shortening, her head was tilting back\'. What does this reveal about Priya\'s skill as a competitor?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['She is an experienced and intelligent racer who can read physical signs of fatigue in opponents — she uses observation and tactical awareness, not just physical ability.','She is watching the Greenhill runner to copy her technique and improve her own stride pattern, using observation as a training strategy during the race itself.','She studies other runners because she is interested in sports science and plans to become a running coach after she finishes school.','She is staring at the Greenhill runner because she has given up trying to overtake and is mentally preparing herself for a third-place finish.'],c:0,e:'This detail shows Priya as a thinking athlete. She doesn\'t just run — she analyses. She recognises the signs of fading because she has \'been there herself a hundred times\'. This combination of experience, observation, and tactical awareness makes her eventual overtaking feel earned rather than lucky.'}
  ]},
  {id:'F12',title:'The New School',type:'fiction',source:'Original passage — school life / belonging / contemporary fiction',
   text:'Amara stood at the gates of Westfield Academy and felt her stomach drop. The building was enormous — three storeys of red brick with tall windows that reflected the grey September sky like blank, watching eyes. Hundreds of students streamed past her in blazers and ties, laughing in groups, calling out to friends they hadn\'t seen since July. Nobody looked at Amara. She was invisible, which was both a relief and a wound.\n\nHer old school had been small — two classrooms, a concrete yard, and a teacher who knew everyone\'s name and their mother\'s name and their grandmother\'s name. Here, the corridors were wide enough to drive a car through, and the noise was like being inside a drum. Amara clutched her timetable and tried to look as though she knew where she was going.\n\nShe found her form room on the second floor after two wrong turns and a panicked moment in a stairwell that seemed to lead nowhere. The room was half full. She chose a seat near the back — close enough to see the board, far enough to avoid being noticed. The girl next to her had her phone out under the desk and didn\'t look up.\n\nThe form tutor, Mr Okafor, was a tall man with a deep voice and a habit of clapping his hands together to get attention. He called the register, and when he reached Amara\'s name, he paused.\n\n\'Amara Diallo. Welcome to Westfield. Where have you joined us from?\'\n\nEvery head turned. Amara felt heat rise up her neck. \'St Catherine\'s,\' she said, though her voice came out so quietly that Mr Okafor asked her to repeat it.\n\n\'St Catherine\'s — lovely school. Well, I hope you\'ll feel at home here soon.\' He smiled and moved on to the next name, but the damage was done. She had been singled out. The new girl. The one who didn\'t belong yet.\n\nAt break time, Amara sat on a bench near the science block and ate her sandwich alone. She watched the other students move in their established orbits — friendship groups that had been forming since Year Three or Four, inside jokes she would never understand, shared histories she could not enter. It was like watching a dance where everyone knew the steps except her.\n\nThen a voice said, \'You\'re in my seat.\'\n\nAmara looked up. A girl with short braids and paint-stained fingers was standing over her, grinning.\n\n\'I\'m joking. Move up.\' The girl sat down beside her and pulled out a sketchbook. \'I\'m Fatou. You looked like you needed rescuing. I know the look — I was the new girl last year.\' She opened the sketchbook to a page covered in tiny, detailed drawings of faces. \'I draw everyone. Want to be next?\'\n\nAmara smiled for the first time that day. \'Okay,\' she said. And just like that, the first brick of something new was laid.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['Mr Okafor is an unkind teacher who deliberately embarrasses new students.','Amara hates her new school and wants to return to St Catherine\'s immediately.','Starting at a new school is isolating and overwhelming, but a single act of kindness can begin to change everything.','Amara and Fatou have been best friends since childhood.'],c:2,e:'The passage traces Amara\'s experience from anxiety (the gates) through isolation (eating alone at break) to the first moment of connection (Fatou sitting beside her). The main idea is about the journey from outsider to the tentative beginning of belonging, triggered by one person reaching out.'},
      {q:'Amara watches other students in \'established orbits\' with \'inside jokes she would never understand\'. The word \'orbits\' compares friendship groups to what, and what does this suggest?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['Classroom seating plans arranged in circles, suggesting that friendship groups are assigned by teachers rather than forming naturally among the students.','Sports teams running laps around a track, suggesting that friendship at Westfield is based on physical activity and shared hobbies rather than deeper emotional connections.','Planets following fixed paths — suggesting these friendships are stable, self-contained systems that Amara cannot enter because she is not part of their gravitational pull.','Satellites broadcasting signals, suggesting friendship groups actively exclude outsiders by sending coded social signals that only members can understand.'],c:2,e:'The orbital metaphor suggests friendship groups move in fixed, self-contained patterns — like planets around a star. Amara is outside these systems, observing but unable to join. The metaphor also implies these bonds have been forming for years, making them feel permanent and impenetrable.'},
      {q:'How does the tone shift between the scene on the bench and Fatou\'s arrival?',skill:'Tone',opts:['It shifts from exciting to boring as Amara gets used to the school.','It shifts from angry to frightened when a stranger approaches.','It stays sad throughout — Fatou\'s arrival doesn\'t change anything for Amara.','It shifts from lonely and observational to warm and hopeful — Fatou\'s humour and directness break the isolation.'],c:3,e:'The bench scene is quiet and melancholy: Amara eats alone, watches others, feels excluded. Fatou\'s arrival changes everything — her joke (\'You\'re in my seat\'), her grin, and her directness inject warmth and humour. The final line (\'the first brick of something new was laid\') confirms the shift towards hope.'},
      {q:'Why does the author have Fatou say \'I was the new girl last year\'?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['To prove that Fatou is a better student than Amara, having already mastered the school\'s social dynamics and earned her place among the established friendship groups.','To explain why Fatou recognises Amara\'s isolation — she has lived through the same experience, making her empathy genuine and her friendship credible rather than random.','To show that the school has a formal buddy system where last year\'s new students are assigned to welcome this year\'s arrivals, making Fatou\'s approach a required duty rather than a personal choice.','To suggest that new students at Westfield always form a separate social group, gravitating towards each other and remaining permanent outsiders to the established friendship circles.'],c:1,e:'This detail transforms Fatou from a random friendly stranger into someone who understands exactly what Amara is going through. Her empathy is rooted in shared experience (\'I know the look\'), which makes the connection feel authentic rather than convenient.'},
      {q:'The final sentence says \'the first brick of something new was laid\'. What does this metaphor suggest?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['A new friendship is beginning to be constructed — like a building, it will be built gradually, one brick at a time, and this first conversation is the foundation.','The metaphor suggests the friendship is fragile and could crumble easily — bricks break under pressure, implying this connection may not survive the challenges of a new school environment.','The "brick" represents a defensive wall Amara is building around herself, suggesting she is using the friendship with Fatou as emotional protection rather than genuine connection.','The building metaphor suggests that Amara sees friendships as transactional structures requiring careful planning and effort, reflecting her analytical rather than emotional approach to relationships.'],c:0,e:'The building metaphor suggests that belonging is not instant but constructed gradually. One conversation is one brick — not a complete friendship, but a necessary start. It also echoes the passage\'s theme: Amara felt she couldn\'t enter others\' \'established orbits\', but now she is beginning to build her own.'},
      {q:'From whose point of view is the passage told, and how does this shape the reader\'s experience?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['Mr Okafor\'s perspective, observing his new student with professional concern, which would allow the reader to understand the teacher\'s good intentions behind singling Amara out in front of the class.','First-person narration by Fatou, looking back on the day she met Amara, which would give the reader insight into why Fatou decided to approach the new girl and what she noticed about her.','Third-person limited, closely following Amara\'s thoughts and feelings — this makes the reader share her anxiety, isolation, and eventual relief, experiencing the new school through an outsider\'s eyes.','Omniscient narration that reveals every student\'s thoughts equally, which would show the reader that other students noticed Amara too and were considering reaching out before Fatou did.'],c:2,e:'The passage stays inside Amara\'s consciousness throughout. We feel her stomach drop, experience her two wrong turns, and share her isolation on the bench. This tight perspective means the reader is as much an outsider as Amara, making Fatou\'s arrival feel like a rescue for the reader too.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about Amara\'s previous school from the details given?',skill:'Inference',opts:['It was a school Amara disliked and was eager to leave, since the fond description of its smallness is tinged with relief at having escaped a place that felt suffocating and limiting.','It was a large, well-resourced school similar to Westfield, and Amara\'s difficulty adjusting comes from personal shyness rather than from any real difference between the two schools.','It was a boarding school where Amara lived during term time, which explains why she is accustomed to institutional routines but struggles with the social dynamics of a day school.','It was a small, close-knit community where everyone knew each other personally — the contrast with Westfield\'s size and anonymity helps explain why Amara feels so overwhelmed and lost.'],c:3,e:'The description of St Catherine\'s — \'two classrooms, a concrete yard, and a teacher who knew everyone\'s name and their mother\'s name and their grandmother\'s name\' — paints a picture of intimate community. This extreme contrast with Westfield\'s vast corridors and anonymity explains Amara\'s culture shock and makes her isolation feel inevitable rather than exaggerated.'},
      {q:'The school windows are described as reflecting the sky \'like blank, watching eyes\'. What technique is this and what effect does it create?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['It is hyperbole that exaggerates the number of windows to make the building seem impossibly large, emphasising Amara\'s sense of being overwhelmed by scale rather than creating any specific emotional atmosphere.','It is personification that makes the school building feel judgemental and intimidating — the \'watching eyes\' suggest Amara feels observed and scrutinised before she has even entered.','It is alliteration in "blank" and "building" that creates a pleasing rhythm, drawing attention to the sound of the language rather than projecting any emotional meaning onto the school.','It is a factual description of how glass reflects light on overcast days, included to establish the weather and time of year rather than to convey anything about Amara\'s emotional state.'],c:1,e:'Personifying the windows as \'blank, watching eyes\' projects Amara\'s anxiety onto the building itself. The school becomes a face staring at her, making it feel actively hostile rather than merely large. This technique reveals Amara\'s emotional state — she feels exposed and judged — through the way she perceives her surroundings.'},
      {q:'What theme does the passage explore through Amara\'s experience?',skill:'Theme',opts:['New schools are inherently hostile environments, and the passage argues that institutions like Westfield are designed to exclude newcomers rather than welcome them.','Belonging is not automatic — it must be built, and a single moment of connection can begin the process of transforming an outsider into someone who belongs.','Making friends is largely a matter of luck — Amara happens to sit on Fatou\'s favourite bench, and without this coincidence the friendship would never have formed.','Teachers are the most important factor in helping new students adjust, and Mr Okafor\'s warm welcome is presented as more significant than Fatou\'s friendship in helping Amara feel she belongs.'],c:1,e:'The passage traces the full arc of not-belonging: anxiety at the gates, invisibility in the corridors, isolation at break. But Fatou\'s arrival shows that belonging can begin with one person reaching out. The final metaphor — \'the first brick of something new\' — confirms that belonging is built gradually, not given instantly.'},
      {q:'Why does the author describe Amara as feeling that being invisible was \'both a relief and a wound\'?',skill:'Author\'s purpose & tone',opts:['To show that Amara prefers solitude and genuinely enjoys being unnoticed, suggesting she is an introvert who finds social interaction draining rather than desirable.','To capture the contradictory emotions of being new — Amara wants to avoid attention but also craves acknowledgement, showing the painful complexity of feeling like an outsider.','To suggest that Amara feels physically unsafe at the new school, with "wound" implying she has been bullied before and associates invisibility with protection from harm.','To suggest the other students are deliberately excluding Amara as a form of collective bullying, choosing to ignore her as a coordinated social punishment for being new.'],c:1,e:'This phrase captures a contradiction that many readers will recognise. Being unnoticed protects Amara from embarrassment (relief) but also confirms that she does not matter to anyone here (wound). The author includes this to show emotional complexity — Amara\'s feelings are not simply negative but layered and conflicting.'},
      {q:'What does Fatou\'s sketchbook reveal about her character?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['She is a shy, withdrawn person who uses her sketchbook as a barrier to avoid direct conversation, hiding behind her art rather than engaging with people face to face.','She is showing off her artwork to establish social dominance over the new girl, using her talent to demonstrate that she has skills and status that Amara lacks.','She draws people without their permission, suggesting she is intrusive and lacks social boundaries despite her outwardly friendly manner.','She is observant, creative, and socially confident — drawing everyone suggests she pays close attention to people, and offering to draw Amara is a warm, creative way of welcoming a stranger.'],c:3,e:'The sketchbook filled with \'tiny, detailed drawings of faces\' reveals someone who watches and studies people closely. Offering to draw Amara is both an act of inclusion (you are worth drawing) and a conversation starter. It shows Fatou is socially skilled — she uses her talent not just for art but for connection.'}
  ]},
  {id:'F13',title:'The Storm Chasers',type:'fiction',source:'Original passage — adventure / sibling rivalry / weather',
   text:'The sky had turned the colour of a bruise — purple-black at the centre, with sickly yellow edges where the last of the afternoon light was being squeezed out. Kai pressed his face against the car window and watched the clouds boil and tumble overhead. They looked alive, rolling over each other like enormous grey animals fighting.\n\n\'We should turn back,\' said his older sister, Nia, from the driver\'s seat. She was seventeen and had only passed her test three months ago, and her knuckles were white on the steering wheel. \'This is stupid, Kai. Dad\'s going to kill us.\'\n\n\'Dad said to check on the weather station,\' Kai replied, not taking his eyes off the sky. \'The data logger hasn\'t transmitted in two days. If we lose this storm\'s readings, we lose the whole project.\'\n\nTheir father was a meteorologist who ran a small network of weather stations across the North Pennines. The most remote station — the one that had gone silent — sat on a moorland hilltop forty minutes from the nearest road, accessible only by a track that turned to mud in anything heavier than drizzle. And what was coming now was considerably heavier than drizzle.\n\nNia slowed the car to a crawl as the first raindrops hit — fat and heavy, bursting against the windscreen like water balloons. Within seconds the rain was so dense that the wipers couldn\'t keep up. The track ahead dissolved into a river of brown water.\n\n\'There,\' Kai said, pointing through the blur. The weather station was visible on the ridge — a white metal box on a pole, with an anemometer spinning wildly on top. One of the solar panels had come loose and was hanging by a cable, swinging in the wind like a broken wing.\n\n\'That\'s what\'s wrong,\' Kai said. \'The power\'s out. If I can reattach the panel—\'\n\n\'In this?\' Nia gestured at the storm. A gust of wind rocked the car sideways, and something — a branch, maybe — flew past the bonnet.\n\nKai was already pulling on his waterproof. He knew Nia was right — it was dangerous, probably reckless. But he also knew that this storm was exactly the kind their father\'s research needed: a once-in-a-decade event passing directly over a data station that wasn\'t recording. If Kai could get it running again, even for twenty minutes, the readings would be invaluable.\n\n\'Ten minutes,\' he said. \'I fix the panel, restart the logger, and I\'m back.\'\n\nNia stared at him. Then she reached behind her seat and pulled out a second waterproof. \'Five minutes,\' she said. \'And I\'m coming with you. If you get struck by lightning, someone needs to drive you to hospital.\'\n\nKai grinned. \'That\'s the most loving thing you\'ve ever said to me.\'',
   questions:[
      {q:'The sky is described as \'the colour of a bruise — purple-black at the centre, with sickly yellow edges\'. What effect does this metaphor create?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['It makes the sky feel damaged and threatening — a bruise implies violence, and \'sickly\' adds unease, as though the weather itself is unwell.','It indicates the storm has already peaked and is now dissipating, with the "sickly yellow" representing clearing skies rather than building danger.','It reveals that Kai perceives colours differently from Nia, and his unusual description of the sky as bruise-like reflects his artistic imagination rather than the actual weather conditions.','It implies the sky has been literally damaged by the storm, treating the weather as something physically wounded rather than using the bruise as a metaphorical comparison to create atmosphere.'],c:0,e:'The bruise metaphor transforms the sky from a neutral backdrop into something that feels hurt and dangerous. Bruises are caused by impact — suggesting the storm is violent. \'Sickly yellow\' adds a sense of wrongness. Together, these create powerful atmosphere before the storm even hits.'},
      {q:'How does the relationship between Kai and Nia develop across the passage?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['Nia starts as the cautious, reluctant older sibling but ultimately chooses to support Kai — her decision to come with him shows protectiveness outweighing fear.','Nia is the adventurous sibling who pushes Kai to take risks, while Kai is the cautious one who must be persuaded to leave the safety of the car.','Kai persuades Nia the storm poses no real danger by showing her the weather data, and she relaxes once she understands the science behind it.','They argue throughout without resolution, and Nia\'s final decision to grab a waterproof represents surrender to Kai\'s stubbornness rather than any genuine change of heart.'],c:0,e:'Nia\'s journey mirrors the reader\'s: she starts wanting to turn back, objects to Kai\'s plan, then grabs a waterproof and comes anyway. Her final line — about driving him to hospital — is affection disguised as sarcasm. She doesn\'t stop being cautious; she just decides letting her brother go alone is worse.'},
      {q:'How would you describe the tone of the final exchange between Kai and Nia?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Warm and humorous — the siblings show love through teasing and sarcasm, breaking the tension of the storm scene.','Angry and hostile — the siblings are having a genuine argument that reveals deep resentment, with Nia resenting Kai\'s recklessness and Kai dismissing her concerns entirely.','Sad and emotional — both siblings are frightened and on the verge of tears, with the storm triggering deeper anxieties about their father\'s dangerous profession.','Formal and polite — the siblings speak with careful restraint, avoiding humour because the situation is too dangerous for anything other than serious, measured communication.'],c:0,e:'Nia\'s line about driving Kai to hospital if he\'s struck by lightning is simultaneously practical, protective, and funny. Kai\'s response (\'the most loving thing you\'ve ever said\') acknowledges the affection beneath the sarcasm. This warm, teasing exchange releases the building tension and reveals genuine sibling love.'},
      {q:'What theme does this passage explore through Kai\'s decision to go out into the storm?',skill:'Theme',opts:['Children should always defer to their older siblings in dangerous situations, since Nia\'s caution proves she has better judgement and the storm is genuinely too dangerous to enter.','Passion for something meaningful — science, knowledge, understanding — can motivate people to take risks that seem reckless but are driven by genuine purpose.','Storms are never as dangerous as they appear, and Kai\'s confidence proves correct because the passage implies the weather improves as soon as they step outside the car.','Technology always fails at the worst possible moment, and the passage argues that relying on electronic equipment in remote locations is fundamentally irresponsible.'],c:1,e:'Kai\'s decision isn\'t random bravery — it comes from understanding that this storm is \'exactly the kind their father\'s research needed\'. His willingness to face danger is rooted in purpose, not recklessness. The passage asks whether risk is justified when the goal matters enough.'},
      {q:'The loose solar panel is described as \'swinging in the wind like a broken wing\'. What does this simile suggest?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['Solar panels are physically shaped like bird wings, and the simile draws attention to this visual resemblance rather than creating any emotional response about the station\'s condition.','The "broken wing" suggests the weather station is about to detach from its pole and blow away entirely, implying the situation is already beyond repair.','The wind is actually quite gentle, and the swinging panel is moving slowly and gracefully rather than being battered by the storm, suggesting the danger is exaggerated.','The station is damaged and vulnerable — like a bird with a broken wing, it cannot function properly, creating sympathy and urgency about repairing it.'],c:3,e:'Comparing the panel to a broken wing personifies the weather station, making it feel like something injured that needs help. This creates emotional motivation for Kai\'s risky decision — he\'s not just fixing equipment, he\'s rescuing something. The image also visually captures the panel\'s helpless swinging motion.'},
      {q:'From whose perspective is the story primarily told, and what effect does this have?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['Their father\'s perspective, watching through a remote camera connected to the weather station, creating dramatic irony as he sees dangers his children cannot.','Kai\'s perspective through third-person limited narration — this puts the reader inside his excitement and determination, making us understand why he wants to brave the storm even when Nia thinks it is reckless.','Nia\'s first-person narration, explaining her thought process as she weighs the risks of the storm against her brother\'s determination to save the scientific data.','An omniscient narrator who reveals both siblings\' thoughts equally, showing that Nia secretly wants to go out into the storm as much as Kai does but feels obligated to be the responsible one.'],c:1,e:'The passage follows Kai\'s thoughts and motivations closely. We learn why the data matters, why this storm is special, and why he is willing to take risks. Because we see through his eyes, his decision feels purposeful rather than foolish. Nia\'s caution provides balance, but Kai\'s perspective drives the narrative.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about the siblings\' father from the details in the passage?',skill:'Inference',opts:['He is a wealthy hobbyist who funds weather stations as a tax write-off rather than out of genuine scientific interest, which explains the neglected equipment.','He is irresponsible for asking his teenage children to check on a remote station during dangerous conditions, prioritising data collection over their safety.','He is a dedicated scientist whose passion for meteorology has clearly influenced Kai — the remote weather station network and the importance of storm data suggest years of committed research.','He has lost interest in the project and stopped maintaining the equipment, which is why the solar panel came loose and the data logger failed in the first place.'],c:2,e:'Though the father never appears, his presence shapes the story. He runs a network of weather stations on remote moorland, and his research is important enough that Kai risks a storm to preserve it. Kai\'s knowledge of meteorology and his dedication to the data clearly come from his father\'s influence.'},
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['The passage argues that children should never handle scientific equipment in remote locations, since Kai\'s decision to repair the station puts both siblings in unnecessary danger.','Nia is a nervous new driver whose lack of confidence behind the wheel creates the real danger in the passage — the storm is secondary to her inexperience on the road.','The passage is mainly an explanation of how remote weather stations work and why solar panels are essential for transmitting meteorological data from hilltop locations.','Two siblings venture into a dangerous storm to save scientific data, and their shared purpose reveals both the power of passion and the strength of their bond despite their different temperaments.'],c:3,e:'The passage weaves together two threads: the scientific mission (saving irreplaceable storm data) and the sibling relationship (cautious Nia choosing to support impulsive Kai). The main idea combines both — passion drives people to take meaningful risks, and love makes others follow them.'},
      {q:'How does the author use the storm to create atmosphere and tension?',skill:'Author\'s purpose & tone',opts:['Through escalating sensory details — the sky darkening, rain bursting like water balloons, wipers failing, wind rocking the car, and flying debris — the storm becomes increasingly threatening, raising the stakes of Kai\'s decision.','The storm serves mainly as a backdrop for the siblings\' comedy, with the exaggerated weather descriptions providing humorous contrast to their bickering rather than creating genuine danger.','The storm is described in calm, measured language that reduces rather than increases tension, suggesting the author wants the reader to feel the siblings are overreacting to ordinary weather.','The author uses the storm primarily to provide factual information about weather patterns in the North Pennines, educating the reader about regional climate rather than building narrative tension.'],c:0,e:'The storm builds progressively. It begins visually (bruised sky), becomes physical (fat raindrops), then overwhelming (wipers can\'t keep up, wind rocks the car). Each detail raises the stakes further, so by the time Kai decides to go outside, the reader understands exactly how dangerous and how important his choice is.'},
      {q:'What does Nia\'s decision to grab a second waterproof and come with Kai reveal about her character?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['Despite being the cautious sibling, her protectiveness and loyalty override her fear — she would rather face danger alongside Kai than let him go alone.','She wants to repair the weather station herself because she has more technical knowledge than Kai and is frustrated that he always takes credit for their father\'s research.','She has changed her mind and now believes the storm is harmless, having been reassured by Kai\'s explanation of the weather data and the station\'s importance.','She is following a specific instruction from their father, who told her before they left that she must always accompany Kai if he decides to go outside in bad weather.'],c:0,e:'Nia\'s character arc is compressed into one gesture. She has argued against the plan, called it stupid, and predicted their father\'s anger. But when Kai is determined to go, she does not let him go alone. Her condition (\'five minutes\') shows she is still cautious, but her action shows love winning over fear.'},
      {q:'How does the text structure build towards Nia\'s decision to join Kai?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['Through a pattern of escalating disagreement followed by a surprising reversal — Nia resists at every stage until the moment she grabs the waterproof, making her decision feel both unexpected and inevitable.','It alternates between scenes inside and outside the car in equal measure, devoting as much time to describing the landscape through the windows as to the dialogue between the siblings.','The structure is built around flashbacks to previous storms the family has experienced, comparing this event to earlier incidents that shaped their attitudes towards weather and risk.','The passage follows a straightforward chronological sequence without any shifts in pacing or surprise moments, presenting events in a predictable order that builds no particular tension.'],c:0,e:'The structure sets up a clear opposition: Kai wants to go, Nia wants to turn back. Each exchange raises the tension. Nia\'s objections grow stronger (\'In this?\'), making her final reversal more powerful. The reader expects continued resistance, so her grabbing the waterproof lands as both a surprise and a natural culmination of her protective instincts.'},
      {q:'The rain hits the windscreen \'like water balloons\' and the track \'dissolved into a river of brown water\'. What do these details suggest about the risk Kai is about to take?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['They prove the car will be swept away by flooding within minutes, foreshadowing a dramatic rescue scene that the passage is building towards but does not reach.','They are included to provide accurate meteorological information about rainfall intensity in the Pennines, educating the reader about weather patterns rather than building narrative tension.','They suggest the storm is mild — "water balloons" are playful and harmless, implying Kai is overreacting to ordinary weather conditions that pose no real danger.','They make the storm\'s force tangible and physical — the playful image of water balloons contrasts with the serious reality, while the dissolving track shows the environment itself breaking down, emphasising genuine danger.'],c:3,e:'The water balloon simile gives the raindrops weight and impact — these are not gentle drops but heavy, bursting projectiles. The track dissolving into a \'river of brown water\' shows the landscape becoming impassable. Together, these details make the storm\'s danger concrete and physical, raising the stakes before Kai opens the car door.'}
  ]},
  {id:'F14',title:'The Audition',type:'fiction',source:'Original passage — performing arts / nerves / self-doubt',
   text:'The waiting room smelled of hairspray and fear. Twelve girls sat in a row of plastic chairs, each holding a script they had already memorised, turning the pages without reading them just to give their hands something to do. A boy in a hoodie sat apart from the group, mouthing his lines with his eyes closed. Someone\'s mother was pacing by the water fountain.\n\nZara was number nine. She knew this because a woman with a clipboard had written the number on a sticker and pressed it onto her chest, as though she were a parcel waiting to be delivered. Her mouth was dry. Her palms were wet. These two facts seemed contradictory and unfair.\n\nThe role was Lady Macbeth in the school\'s winter production — the biggest part in the biggest play of the year. Zara had wanted it since September, when Mrs Hargreaves had announced the production in assembly and Zara had felt something ignite in her chest like a match being struck. She had practised the sleepwalking scene in her bedroom every night for three weeks, whispering \'Out, damned spot!\' to her reflection until her little brother had banged on the wall and told her to stop being creepy.\n\nBut wanting something and believing you deserve it are different things. Every girl in this room had practised. Every girl wanted the part. The girl who was number three — Priya, from the year above — had been in every school production since Year Seven and had a voice that could fill a hall without a microphone. Zara had never been in a play before.\n\nThe door opened. \'Number nine?\'\n\nZara stood. Her legs felt disconnected from her body, as though they belonged to someone else and she was borrowing them. She walked into the auditorium. It was dark except for the stage, which was lit by a single spotlight that turned the wooden floor gold.\n\nMrs Hargreaves sat in the third row with a notepad. \'Whenever you\'re ready, Zara.\'\n\nFor a terrible moment, Zara\'s mind went completely blank. The lines she had repeated a thousand times vanished, as if someone had erased a whiteboard. She could feel her heart slamming against her ribs. The silence stretched.\n\nThen she remembered something her grandmother had told her: \'When you\'re frightened, don\'t try to be brave. Just start. The brave part comes after.\'\n\nZara took a breath. She looked down at her hands. She imagined them stained with blood that wouldn\'t wash away.\n\n\'Yet here\'s a spot,\' she said quietly. And then she was Lady Macbeth — not Zara pretending, but something else entirely, something that rose up from a place inside her she hadn\'t known existed. The words came like water from an opened tap, and she did not stop until the hall was silent and Mrs Hargreaves had put down her pen.',
   questions:[
      {q:'How does the tone change across the passage?',skill:'Tone',opts:['It shifts from anxious and self-doubting → crisis (blank mind) → transformation and flow, mirroring Zara\'s emotional journey from fear to performance.','It moves from calm confidence in the waiting room to mild frustration during the audition, reflecting Zara\'s growing irritation with the process and her impatience to claim the role she feels entitled to.','It builds steadily from nervous excitement to sustained comedy, using the brother anecdote and the grandmother\'s advice as humorous beats that lighten the mood throughout the performance scene.','It begins with a detached, observational tone as Zara watches the other candidates, then shifts into cold determination once she enters the auditorium, suggesting she suppresses her emotions entirely to focus.'],c:0,e:'The passage tracks three emotional phases: nervous waiting (dry mouth, wet palms, comparing herself to Priya), crisis (mind going blank, heart slamming), and breakthrough (the words coming \'like water from an opened tap\'). The tone mirrors the universal experience of overcoming stage fright.'},
      {q:'Zara\'s grandmother says \'When you\'re frightened, don\'t try to be brave. Just start. The brave part comes after.\' Which theme does this support?',skill:'Theme',opts:['Family wisdom passed down through generations is more reliable than formal training — the grandmother\'s words succeed where weeks of rehearsal and preparation could not.','Courage is not something you feel before you act — it emerges through beginning, even when you are terrified.','True preparation means practising until fear disappears completely — the grandmother is telling Zara that repetition and familiarity will eventually remove all nervousness before a performance.','Real confidence comes from knowing you are more talented than your competitors — the grandmother encourages Zara to trust that her natural ability will carry her through the audition.'],c:1,e:'The grandmother\'s advice redefines bravery as something that follows action, not precedes it. Zara doesn\'t overcome her fear and then perform — she starts performing while still afraid, and the fear dissolves through the act of beginning. The theme is about action despite uncertainty.'},
      {q:'\'The lines she had repeated a thousand times vanished, as if someone had erased a whiteboard.\' What makes this simile effective?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['The simile emphasises the gradual nature of forgetting — just as a whiteboard fades over time when not cleaned properly, Zara\'s memory slowly deteriorates under the sustained pressure of the audition spotlight.','The comparison highlights the visual nature of Zara\'s memory — she learned her lines by writing them repeatedly, so the simile directly references her specific revision method and study habits at school.','The whiteboard image connects Zara\'s stage fright to her classroom experience, suggesting that her fear of performing in the audition mirrors her deeper anxiety about academic tests and school assessments.','The whiteboard image captures both the completeness of the memory loss (everything wiped clean in one swipe) and its suddenness, using a school-setting object the reader instantly understands.'],c:3,e:'The simile works because whiteboards are familiar to the reader, making the experience instantly relatable. Erasing a whiteboard is total and instant — one swipe and everything is gone. This captures the terrifying completeness of stage fright, where weeks of preparation vanish in a second.'},
      {q:'Why does the author include the detail about Priya, who \'had a voice that could fill a hall without a microphone\'?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['To foreshadow Zara\'s inevitable failure by showing her the standard she cannot possibly reach, suggesting the passage will end with Zara accepting she is not ready for lead roles yet.','To establish a credible rival and raise the stakes — competing against someone experienced and talented makes Zara\'s eventual performance more impressive and the outcome uncertain.','To introduce a supportive mentor figure who will later help Zara prepare backstage, since Priya\'s experience makes her the ideal person to offer practical audition advice and encouragement.','To criticise the school\'s lack of proper equipment and resources, implying that Priya\'s powerful voice is necessary only because the auditorium has no working sound system for performances.'],c:1,e:'Priya\'s presence raises the difficulty. If Zara were the only serious candidate, the audition would lack tension. By showing us a confident, experienced competitor, the author creates genuine uncertainty and makes Zara\'s breakthrough more meaningful — she\'s not just performing, she\'s competing.'},
      {q:'The passage says Zara became \'not Zara pretending, but something else entirely, something that rose up from a place inside her she hadn\'t known existed\'. What does this suggest about great performance?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['Great performance is not imitation but transformation — Zara accesses a deeper part of herself she didn\'t know was there, suggesting acting reveals hidden capabilities rather than creating false ones.','It means the performance depends entirely on thorough memorisation, and because Zara practised so many times the words simply emerged automatically without any emotional engagement or deeper connection.','The description implies that Zara has lost conscious control of her actions on stage, and the \'something else entirely\' represents a dissociative state caused by overwhelming anxiety rather than genuine talent.','It suggests that great performance requires completely abandoning your own personality and replacing it with the character\'s, implying that the best actors are those who suppress their real selves most effectively.'],c:0,e:'The description of transformation — not pretending but becoming — suggests performance draws out something authentic. \'A place inside her she hadn\'t known existed\' implies the audition has not just tested Zara but revealed her to herself, connecting to the theme that beginning despite fear can unlock something real.'},
      {q:'From whose point of view is the passage told, and how does this affect the reader\'s experience of the audition?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['Third-person limited following Zara — this traps the reader inside her anxiety, self-doubt, and eventual transformation, making the moment her mind goes blank feel personally terrifying.','First-person narration by Mrs Hargreaves, who is evaluating each student — this allows the reader to see Zara\'s raw talent objectively and understand why she is ultimately cast as Lady Macbeth.','Omniscient narration that reveals every candidate\'s thoughts and nervousness, showing that Priya is equally terrified and that all twelve girls share the same self-doubt before performing.','Priya\'s perspective, watching Zara\'s audition from the waiting room and realising that this newcomer poses a genuine threat to her usual dominance in school productions.'],c:0,e:'By staying inside Zara\'s consciousness, the passage makes her emotions the reader\'s emotions. We feel her dry mouth, her self-doubt when she thinks about Priya, and the terrifying blankness when her lines vanish. This tight perspective turns the audition into a shared experience rather than an observed one.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about Zara\'s character from the detail that she practised the sleepwalking scene every night for three weeks?',skill:'Inference',opts:['She only practised because she had nothing else to do in the evenings, since the passage implies she has no friends or hobbies and uses the rehearsal to fill empty time at home.','Her drama teacher Mrs Hargreaves required all audition candidates to practise every night as compulsory homework, and Zara was simply following instructions rather than choosing to prepare independently.','She has a poor memory and needs far more repetition than other students to memorise lines, which is why she still forgets everything under pressure despite three full weeks of nightly practice.','She is deeply committed and passionate about the role — her sustained dedication over three weeks shows this is not a casual interest but something she cares about intensely.'],c:3,e:'Three weeks of nightly practice reveals serious dedication. Zara doesn\'t just want the role — she has invested significant time and emotional energy. The detail of her brother banging on the wall adds authenticity and humour, but the core inference is about Zara\'s determination and how much Lady Macbeth means to her.'},
      {q:'How does the passage use the physical setting of the auditorium to reflect Zara\'s emotional state?',skill:'Author\'s purpose & tone',opts:['The setting is described in neutral, factual terms without any emotional significance, focusing only on practical details like the wooden floor and the row Mrs Hargreaves sits in.','The spotlight is broken and flickering, which adds to the chaos of the audition and explains why Zara cannot concentrate enough to remember her opening lines.','The dark auditorium with a single spotlight creates a sense of isolation and exposure — Zara stands alone in the light surrounded by darkness, mirroring her vulnerability and the pressure of being watched.','The auditorium is described as warm and welcoming — the golden floor and quiet atmosphere help Zara feel safe, which is why she is eventually able to relax and perform confidently.'],c:2,e:'The author deliberately uses the setting as emotional landscape. The darkness surrounding the stage isolates Zara, while the spotlight makes her feel exposed. The wooden floor turning \'gold\' adds beauty to the moment, suggesting that the stage is both terrifying and magnificent — much like performing itself.'},
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['A girl overcomes paralysing stage fright to discover a hidden talent — the passage shows that beginning despite fear can unlock abilities you did not know you possessed.','Mrs Hargreaves is a strict and intimidating teacher who deliberately creates a high-pressure audition environment, and the passage focuses on criticising her cold, unsupportive approach to young performers.','Zara fails her audition because she forgets all her lines under pressure, and the passage ends with her standing in defeated silence while Mrs Hargreaves writes critical notes.','The passage is mainly about how competitive school drama productions unfairly favour experienced students like Priya over newcomers like Zara, who never get a real chance regardless of talent.'],c:0,e:'The passage builds from Zara\'s desire for the role through escalating anxiety to a crisis (blank mind) and finally a breakthrough. The main idea is captured in the grandmother\'s advice: \'Just start. The brave part comes after.\' Zara discovers that beginning — even terrified — can release something extraordinary.'},
      {q:'Why does the author include the detail about Zara\'s brother banging on the wall and telling her to \'stop being creepy\'?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['It shows that Zara\'s family does not support her interest in drama — her brother\'s mocking response represents the household\'s dismissive attitude toward performing arts.','It adds warmth, humour, and realism — showing Zara\'s dedication through a relatable family moment that balances the passage\'s tension and makes her feel like a real person.','It proves that Zara is too loud and theatrical at home, foreshadowing that her overly dramatic style will be a weakness during the audition when subtlety is required.','It is included to explain why Zara has not prepared enough for the audition — her brother\'s constant interruptions prevented her from finishing her rehearsals each evening.'],c:1,e:'This detail does several things at once. It shows dedication (she practises every night), adds humour (the brother\'s complaint), and creates a believable home life. By grounding Zara in a realistic family dynamic, the author makes her more relatable and her anxiety more affecting.'},
      {q:'The passage says wanting something and believing you deserve it \'are different things\'. What does this statement reveal about Zara\'s internal conflict?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['She thinks the audition process is unfair and resents having to compete against more experienced students like Priya for a role she has wanted since September.','She does not actually want the role of Lady Macbeth and is only auditioning because her grandmother pressured her into trying out for the school production.','She is battling imposter syndrome — she passionately wants the role but cannot convince herself she is good enough, especially compared to experienced performers like Priya.','She believes she is the best candidate but is being strategically modest so that other girls will underestimate her before she delivers a stunning audition performance.'],c:2,e:'This sentence captures Zara\'s core struggle. Desire is not the problem — she has wanted the role since September. Self-belief is. The gap between wanting and deserving creates her anxiety, and it is this gap that the grandmother\'s advice and the final performance ultimately bridge.'},
      {q:'How does the structure of the passage mirror Zara\'s emotional journey?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['It uses alternating flashbacks and present-day scenes throughout — cutting between the waiting room and earlier memories of rehearsal to show how Zara\'s past experiences directly cause her stage fright.','It moves through preparation, rising anxiety, crisis, and breakthrough — each section increasing in intensity until the blank-mind moment, then releasing into the flow of performance.','The passage begins with Zara\'s triumphant performance and then flashes back to explain the nervous build-up, using reverse chronology to create suspense about how she reached the stage.','The passage is structured as a simple chronological account without emotional shifts, presenting events in a flat, reportorial style that lets the reader decide how to feel about each moment independently.'],c:1,e:'The structure tracks Zara\'s emotions precisely. It begins with nervous waiting (the room, the number), builds through self-doubt (comparing herself to Priya), peaks at crisis (mind going blank), and resolves through action (the grandmother\'s words, the performance). This arc mirrors the universal experience of overcoming fear through beginning.'},
      {q:'How does the passage use the number sticker detail — \'as though she were a parcel waiting to be delivered\' — to develop Zara\'s feelings?',skill:'Inference',opts:['It suggests Zara feels dehumanised and passive — reduced to a number rather than treated as a person, heightening her sense of being processed by an impersonal system before she has even performed.','It suggests the audition staff are deliberately trying to unsettle the candidates, using bureaucratic processes to assert power over nervous performers.','It shows that Zara is overreacting to a normal process — every candidate is given a number, and her comparison to a parcel reveals a tendency to dramatise ordinary situations.','It shows that the numbering system simply keeps the audition fair and organised, and the parcel comparison reflects Zara\'s relief at being given a clear place in the queue.'],c:0,e:'The parcel comparison reveals how Zara perceives the audition process: impersonal and mechanical. She is labelled with a number rather than greeted by name, which makes her feel like an object being sorted rather than a person — sharpening her vulnerability in the moments before she performs.'}
  ]},
  {id:'F15',title:'Night Shift at the Museum',type:'fiction',source:'Original passage — mystery / history / imagination',
   text:'Marcus had always thought museums were boring. Dusty cases full of old things nobody cared about, labelled with cards written in handwriting so small you needed a magnifying glass. But that was before his mum got the job as night security officer at the Ashworth Museum of Local History, and before Marcus started spending Thursday evenings sitting behind the front desk doing his homework while she did her rounds.\n\nThe museum was different at night. During the day it was bright and busy — school trips, pensioners, the occasional tourist who had taken a wrong turn. But after six o\'clock, when the last visitor left and the main lights went off, the building transformed. The emergency lighting cast long amber shadows across the stone floors, and the glass cases glowed faintly, as though the objects inside were generating their own light. The silence was not empty but thick, layered, full of the tiny sounds old buildings make when they think nobody is listening: the tick of cooling radiators, the creak of settling floorboards, the faint hum of the climate control system keeping the air at exactly the right temperature for a two-thousand-year-old Roman coin.\n\nMarcus had started wandering. His mum\'s rounds took forty-five minutes, and homework rarely lasted that long. He would walk the galleries slowly, torch in hand, reading labels he would never have bothered with during the day. There was something about the darkness that made the objects feel closer, more present. A Viking sword that looked like a lump of brown metal in daylight seemed to pulse with intent under torchlight. A Victorian child\'s shoe, cracked and tiny behind its glass, suddenly felt unbearably sad — someone\'s daughter had worn that shoe, walked in it, scuffed it, grown out of it. And now here it was, two hundred years later, behind glass in a room that smelled of floor polish.\n\nOne Thursday, he found something the museum didn\'t know it had. In the basement storage room — which his mum had told him never to enter, a rule he treated with the same respect most twelve-year-olds give to suggestions — he discovered a wooden crate labelled \'Miscellaneous — Victorian — Unsorted\'. Inside, wrapped in brown paper and newspaper from 1987, was a leather-bound journal. The handwriting was small and slanted, the ink faded to the colour of weak tea, and the dates ran from January to November 1842.\n\nMarcus sat on an upturned crate and opened it. The first entry read: \'Arrived in Ashworth today. The mill is larger than I expected and the noise unbearable. There are children working here younger than my own daughter. I have been asked to say nothing. I cannot promise that I will.\'\n\nHe turned the page. And then the next. He did not hear his mum calling his name until she was standing right behind him.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['A boy who thought museums were boring discovers that history becomes alive in the right conditions — and finds a journal that hints at a powerful, hidden story about injustice.','Marcus is searching for valuable artefacts in the museum basement that he can sell, motivated by financial need after his mum took a low-paying security job.','The museum is haunted by Victorian ghosts who communicate through objects that glow at night, and the journal is a supernatural message left specifically for Marcus to find.','Marcus\'s mum is negligent and irresponsible as a security officer, and the passage is mainly a critique of parents who bring children to their workplaces unsupervised.'],c:0,e:'The passage traces Marcus\'s transformation from finding museums \'boring\' to being so absorbed in a historical journal that he doesn\'t hear his own name. The journey is about how context (darkness, silence, solitude) and personal discovery can make history feel real and urgent.'},
      {q:'The museum silence is described as \'not empty but thick, layered, full of tiny sounds old buildings make when they think nobody is listening\'. What techniques are used here?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['Onomatopoeia only — \'tick\' and \'creak\' imitate exact sounds, but the passage does not personify the building or give it human qualities like awareness.','Alliteration — the repeated \'l\' sounds in \'layered\' and \'listening\' create a lulling rhythm that mimics the effect of silence on a drowsy visitor.','Hyperbole — the author exaggerates how quiet the museum is, since a building with radiators, floorboards, and climate control would actually be quite noisy.','Personification and imagery — giving the building the ability to \'think\' and \'listen\' makes it feel alive, while the layered sounds create atmosphere and suggest a hidden life after hours.'],c:3,e:'\'When they think nobody is listening\' personifies the building, giving it awareness and secrecy. The accumulated details (ticking, creaking, humming) create a soundscape that makes the museum feel like a living organism. This transforms the setting from a boring backdrop into a character in its own right.'},
      {q:'Why does the author describe the Victorian child\'s shoe in detail — \'cracked and tiny\', \'someone\'s daughter had worn that shoe, walked in it, scuffed it, grown out of it\'?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['To demonstrate how Marcus\'s perspective has changed — he now sees historical objects not as dead artefacts but as evidence of real lives, creating emotional connection across centuries.','To suggest that Marcus is developing an unhealthy obsession with the museum\'s objects and is beginning to confuse imagination with reality during his night-time wandering.','To show that the museum\'s Victorian collection is particularly well preserved, providing background detail about the quality of the Ashworth Museum\'s holdings.','To prove that Victorian children lived in poverty by contrasting the worn-out shoe with the polished modern museum, making a direct argument about social inequality.'],c:0,e:'The shoe passage marks Marcus\'s transformation. He moves from seeing \'a lump of brown metal\' (the Viking sword by daylight) to imagining the child who wore the shoe — walking, scuffing, growing. This empathetic leap is what makes the later journal discovery so powerful: Marcus can now connect with the past emotionally.'},
      {q:'The journal entry mentions \'children working here younger than my own daughter\' and the writer being \'asked to say nothing\'. What theme does this introduce?',skill:'Theme',opts:['The tension between witnessing injustice and being pressured to stay silent — the journal writer feels a moral obligation to speak up despite being told not to.','The journal writer is a factory owner who is proud of his successful mill and is documenting its growth as a personal record of achievement.','Children in 1842 chose factory work over school because industrial jobs offered independence and practical skills that formal education could not provide.','Victorian children enjoyed working in mills because the labour was light and well supervised, and the writer is simply recording everyday life without complaint.'],c:0,e:'The journal entry introduces a moral conflict: the writer sees child labour and is told to stay silent, but writes \'I cannot promise that I will\'. This suggests the journal may document someone\'s decision to speak out against injustice — giving Marcus\'s discovery both historical weight and ethical urgency.'},
      {q:'How does the tone of the final two paragraphs differ from the earlier gallery-wandering passages?',skill:'Tone',opts:['The earlier passages are frightening and suspenseful, building dread about what Marcus might find in the dark galleries, while the journal discovery brings relief and calm.','The earlier passages are dreamy and atmospheric; the journal discovery is urgent and gripping — the historical voice pulls Marcus and the reader into a real human story with moral stakes.','The tone stays exactly the same throughout because Marcus maintains the same level of curiosity from the moment he begins wandering the galleries to when he reads the journal.','The final paragraphs are dull and anticlimactic because the journal\'s old-fashioned language and faded ink make the discovery feel disappointing after the atmospheric build-up.'],c:1,e:'The gallery passages are contemplative and atmospheric — Marcus drifts, observes, imagines. The journal entry changes everything: suddenly there is a real voice, a real moral dilemma, and real children at stake. Marcus becomes so absorbed he doesn\'t hear his mum — the reader is meant to feel the same pull.'},
      {q:'From whose point of view is the passage told, and how does this affect the reader\'s relationship with the museum?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['Third-person limited following Marcus — this means the reader discovers the museum\'s night-time magic and the journal alongside him, sharing his journey from boredom to fascination.','The journal writer\'s point of view from 1842, describing the mill and Ashworth through Victorian eyes, so the reader experiences history directly rather than through Marcus.','Omniscient narration that moves freely between Marcus, his mum, and the museum\'s daytime visitors, giving the reader a complete picture of everyone\'s thoughts and feelings.','First-person narration by Marcus\'s mum, who describes her worry about her son wandering the museum alone during her security rounds each Thursday evening.'],c:0,e:'The passage follows Marcus\'s perspective closely, from his initial dismissal of museums as boring to his absorption in the journal. Because the reader sees everything through his eyes, we experience his transformation — we are bored when he is bored and fascinated when he is fascinated. This makes the discovery feel personal.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about the journal writer from the first entry?',skill:'Inference',opts:['The writer is a child who works in the mill and is describing their own daily experience of the unbearable noise and long hours alongside other young workers.','The writer is a tourist visiting Ashworth for a holiday who wandered into the mill by accident and was surprised to see children working there.','The writer is a moral person with a conscience — they are disturbed by child labour, have their own daughter, and are already considering defying the instruction to stay silent.','The writer is the mill owner who built the factory in Ashworth and is proudly recording its impressive size and the efficiency of its young workforce.'],c:2,e:'The first entry reveals someone who has arrived from outside (\'Arrived in Ashworth today\'), has a daughter, is shocked by child labour, and has been told to say nothing. The final sentence — \'I cannot promise that I will\' — reveals moral courage. The reader can infer this person may be an inspector, journalist, or official whose conscience will not allow silence.'},
      {q:'What is the author\'s purpose in beginning the passage with Marcus thinking museums are boring?',skill:'Author\'s purpose & tone',opts:['To create a relatable starting point for young readers who may feel the same way — Marcus\'s transformation from boredom to fascination mirrors the journey the author wants the reader to take.','To show that Marcus is unintelligent and unimaginative, establishing him as someone who lacks the curiosity needed to appreciate the historical objects around him.','To argue that museums should modernise their displays and replace old-fashioned glass cases with interactive technology that appeals to younger audiences.','To criticise Marcus\'s generation for being too focused on screens and technology to appreciate the value of physical historical artefacts in traditional museum settings.'],c:0,e:'Starting with \'Marcus had always thought museums were boring\' hooks readers who might agree. The author then gradually shows Marcus changing his mind, which is more persuasive than simply telling the reader museums are interesting. By the time Marcus is lost in the journal, the reader has been led through the same transformation.'},
      {q:'The Viking sword \'seemed to pulse with intent under torchlight\'. What does this choice of vocabulary suggest?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['Marcus is imagining things because the emergency lighting is playing tricks on his eyes, and the flickering amber shadows make ordinary objects appear to move.','The sword is literally glowing because Viking metalwork contained phosphorescent materials that become visible when illuminated by a narrow beam of torchlight.','The word \'intent\' gives the sword a sense of purpose and hidden life — in darkness, it feels like it retains the energy of the warriors who once used it, suggesting history is alive rather than dead.','The word \'pulse\' means the sword is vibrating due to the climate control system\'s hum travelling through the display case and into the metal blade.'],c:2,e:'The word \'intent\' normally describes human purpose or will. Applying it to a sword personifies the object, suggesting it still carries the energy of its past use. Combined with \'pulse\', the vocabulary creates a sense that historical objects are dormant rather than dead — they come alive when the right person pays attention in the right conditions.'},
      {q:'How does the passage use contrast between day and night in the museum to develop its ideas?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['Daytime is bright, busy, and ordinary; night-time is atmospheric and intimate — this contrast shows that the same objects can feel completely different depending on context, developing the idea that how you experience history matters as much as what you see.','The daytime museum is presented as more interesting because school trips and tourists create energy, while the empty night-time museum feels lonely and neglected.','The contrast is used mainly to explain why Marcus is there on Thursday evenings — his mum works the night shift, so the day-night structure simply establishes the practical circumstances.','The day and night descriptions show that the museum looks identical regardless of lighting, reinforcing the idea that historical objects have fixed, unchanging significance.'],c:0,e:'The structural contrast between day (\'bright and busy\', school trips, tourists) and night (amber shadows, glowing cases, thick silence) transforms the same space. Objects that look like \'lumps of brown metal\' by day \'pulse with intent\' at night. This contrast develops the passage\'s central idea: context shapes how we connect with history.'},
      {q:'What does Marcus\'s decision to explore the forbidden basement suggest about his character?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['He is curious and independent-minded — his willingness to break a rule shows that his growing fascination with history has overcome his caution, driven by genuine intellectual curiosity.','He is searching for valuable objects he can take from the unsorted storage crates, since the museum does not even know what it has down there.','He enters the basement by accident while looking for a toilet, not realising he has wandered into a restricted area of the building in the dark.','He is a deliberately disobedient child who enjoys defying his mother\'s authority, and the basement rule is just the latest instruction he has chosen to ignore.'],c:0,e:'The narrator describes Marcus treating his mother\'s rule \'with the same respect most twelve-year-olds give to suggestions\' — humorous but telling. His disobedience is driven not by rebellion but by curiosity. The passage has shown his growing engagement with the museum objects, making his basement exploration a natural extension of his developing passion.'},
      {q:'Why does the author end the passage with Marcus not hearing his mum calling his name?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['To show how completely absorbed he has become — the boy who once found museums boring is now so captivated by a historical voice that he is oblivious to the present, completing his transformation.','To create a cliffhanger suggesting Marcus is in danger, since his mum will punish him severely for entering the forbidden basement storage room.','To show that the basement is physically far from the main building and sound cannot travel through the thick stone walls separating the storage area from the galleries.','To suggest that Marcus has been reading for so many hours that it is now very late at night and he has missed the end of his mum\'s shift entirely.'],c:0,e:'The ending mirrors and reverses the opening. Marcus began thinking museums were boring; he ends so absorbed in a historical document that he cannot hear his own mother. This total absorption is the passage\'s proof that history, encountered personally and in the right conditions, is anything but boring.'}
  ]},
  {id:'F16',title:'The Coding Competition',type:'fiction',source:'Original passage — technology / teamwork / pressure',
   text:'The timer on the screen read 01:47:23 and was counting down. In one hour and forty-seven minutes, Team Pixel — which consisted of Dani, her best friend Leo, and a boy called Sanjay whom they had met approximately ninety minutes ago — would need to present a working app to a panel of judges. At the moment, what they had was not so much a working app as a collection of errors displayed in angry red text.\n\n\'It\'s the API call,\' Sanjay said, his fingers moving across the keyboard at a speed that made Dani feel both impressed and inadequate. \'The data\'s coming back but it\'s nested three levels deep and we\'re only reading two.\'\n\n\'Can you fix it?\' Dani asked.\n\n\'I can fix anything,\' Sanjay said, without looking up. \'The question is whether I can fix it in time.\'\n\nDani turned to Leo, who was supposed to be designing the user interface but had spent the last twenty minutes staring at a colour palette on his screen with the expression of someone choosing which wire to cut on a bomb. Leo was an artist — genuinely talented, endlessly creative — but deadlines made him freeze. The more urgent the task, the more paralysed he became.\n\n\'Leo,\' Dani said quietly. \'Just pick blue. Blue is fine. Everything works in blue.\'\n\nLeo looked at her with wounded eyes. \'Dani, blue is not just blue. There are four hundred shades of—\'\n\n\'Pick one.\'\n\nDani\'s own role was project manager, which sounded important but in practice meant she was the person who panicked on behalf of the whole team so that the others didn\'t have to. She kept the task list, watched the clock, and made decisions when nobody else would. It was not glamorous work. It did not involve code or design or anything that would look impressive on screen during the final presentation. But without it, she had learned, talented people could spend three hours arguing about shades of blue while their app crashed in the background.\n\nThe timer hit 01:00:00. One hour left. Sanjay\'s fix worked — the data flowed correctly for the first time, populating the screen with real information instead of error messages. Leo, having been firmly steered towards a colour scheme, had produced an interface that was simple, clean, and — Dani had to admit — beautiful.\n\n\'It\'s actually working,\' Leo said, as though he didn\'t quite believe it.\n\n\'Of course it\'s working,\' Sanjay said. \'I fixed the back end. You made it pretty. And Dani made sure we didn\'t kill each other in the process.\'\n\nDani laughed, but she also wrote that down. When the judges asked what each team member contributed, she wanted a good answer. \'Prevented murders\' had a nice ring to it.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the central theme of this passage?',skill:'Theme',opts:['The central theme is that leadership under pressure means making personal sacrifices for the group, and Dani\'s willingness to suppress her own ambitions reveals the hidden emotional cost of coordination.','Individual excellence matters more than collaboration, and Sanjay\'s ability to fix the code singlehandedly demonstrates that technical skill is the most essential ingredient in any team\'s success.','Successful teamwork requires different skills — technical ability, creativity, and coordination are all equally valuable, even though some roles are less visible than others.','The passage explores how creative talent is undervalued in technical environments, since people like Leo struggle to have their artistic contributions recognised by teammates focused on coding and functionality.'],c:2,e:'The passage gives each team member a distinct skill: Sanjay codes, Leo designs, Dani manages. The theme emerges through Dani\'s reflection that her role \'did not involve code or design\' but was essential. Sanjay\'s final line confirms all three contributions mattered equally.'},
      {q:'Why does the author describe Leo as someone who freezes under pressure?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['To highlight the competitive pressure of the event by showing that even talented individuals can break down, raising the stakes and making the reader question whether the team will finish in time.','To contrast Leo\'s artistic sensitivity with Sanjay\'s technical confidence, implying that creative people are inherently less suited to high-pressure environments than logical thinkers are.','To create a realistic flaw that adds tension and shows why Dani\'s management role is necessary — without someone to push Leo past his indecision, his talent would be wasted.','To suggest that Leo\'s perfectionism is a fundamental character flaw that will eventually prevent him from succeeding in any collaborative creative project he attempts in the future.'],c:2,e:'Leo\'s paralysis under pressure is recognisable and relatable. It creates a problem Dani solves (steering him to a decision), which justifies her role and demonstrates the passage\'s theme about different kinds of contribution being equally important.'},
      {q:'Leo stares at a colour palette \'with the expression of someone choosing which wire to cut on a bomb\'. What effect does this comparison create?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['It shows that Leo has training in bomb disposal as a hobby, and his serious expression reflects real fear rather than artistic overthinking.','It suggests the colour choice could literally crash the app, since choosing an incompatible shade might cause a software conflict that wipes out Sanjay\'s back-end work.','It humorously exaggerates Leo\'s overthinking — comparing a colour decision to a life-or-death scenario highlights how paralysing perfectionism can be, while making the reader laugh.','It implies that the computer screen is glitching and displaying colours incorrectly, which is why Leo cannot decide which shade to use for the interface.'],c:2,e:'The bomb-disposal comparison is comic hyperbole — inflating a trivial decision to absurd proportions. It makes the reader laugh while efficiently communicating Leo\'s character: he treats every creative choice as monumental, which is both his strength (he cares deeply) and his weakness (he can\'t decide).'},
      {q:'How would you describe the overall tone of this passage?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Warm, witty, and affectionate — the passage finds comedy in the chaos of teamwork while genuinely respecting each character\'s contribution.','Anxious and pressured throughout — the countdown timer dominates the atmosphere, and the humorous moments only serve to mask the characters\' underlying panic about the competition deadline.','Tense but ultimately triumphant — the passage builds a feeling of mounting dread that shifts into proud celebration once the team\'s app finally begins working correctly.','Sarcastic and ironic — the narrator uses dry wit to gently mock each character\'s weaknesses, creating a tone that is more amused by their flaws than genuinely supportive of their efforts.'],c:0,e:'The tone balances genuine tension (the countdown, the error messages) with warmth and humour (Leo\'s colour agonising, Dani\'s self-deprecating description of her role, the \'prevented murders\' joke). The affection between characters comes through even in their teasing.'},
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['Three students with different strengths learn to work together under extreme pressure, discovering that coordination and communication are as important as technical talent.','A talented coder can overcome any technical challenge if given enough time, but artificial deadlines in competitions prevent teams from producing their best possible work and create unnecessary stress.','The passage follows a group of strangers who bond through shared adversity, showing how competitive pressure can forge lasting friendships between people who might otherwise never have connected.','The main focus is on how project managers like Dani carry the invisible burden of keeping teams functional, often at the expense of developing their own technical skills or creative abilities.'],c:0,e:'The passage shows a team where each member brings something different. Success comes not from any one person\'s talent but from how they combine — and Dani\'s less visible coordination role is the glue that holds it together.'},
      {q:'From whose point of view is the passage told, and how does this shape the reader\'s understanding of teamwork?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['First-person narration by Sanjay, who describes the technical problems from his own expert perspective and barely notices what Dani and Leo are doing around him.','Omniscient narration that gives equal time to all three characters\' inner thoughts, showing Sanjay\'s frustration with bugs, Leo\'s anxiety about colours, and Dani\'s private doubts about her role.','Third-person limited following Dani — this lets the reader see through the eyes of the project manager, highlighting the often-invisible work of coordination that holds a team together.','Leo\'s perspective, showing his frustration with Dani\'s bossiness and his feeling that his artistic vision is being rushed and undervalued by the rest of the team.'],c:2,e:'By following Dani\'s perspective, the passage makes visible the work that usually goes unnoticed. The reader sees her watching the clock, managing Leo\'s paralysis, and keeping the team functional. If the passage followed Sanjay, we would see technical problem-solving; through Dani, we see the human management that makes technical success possible.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about Sanjay\'s character from his dialogue and behaviour?',skill:'Inference',opts:['He is nervous and unsure of his coding abilities, as shown by his constant questions to Dani about whether he is doing the right thing and his hesitation before making changes.','He is hostile towards Dani and Leo and resents being paired with strangers, as shown by his refusal to acknowledge their contributions in the final lines of the passage.','He is highly skilled and confident in his abilities, but his confidence could become arrogance — his focus on code means he may undervalue the non-technical contributions of others.','He is a beginner coder who is pretending to know more than he actually does, since the API problem he claims to fix is never fully resolved and the app remains broken at the end.'],c:2,e:'Sanjay says \'I can fix anything\' without looking up — suggesting genuine skill combined with casual confidence. His final line credits all three team members equally, showing he does recognise others\' contributions. The inference is that Sanjay is talented and somewhat cocky but ultimately fair and generous in acknowledging the team.'},
      {q:'Why does the author begin the passage with the countdown timer reading 01:47:23?',skill:'Author\'s purpose & tone',opts:['To show that the team has plenty of time remaining and there is no real reason to worry, since almost two hours is more than enough to build a simple app.','To demonstrate that the competition is sponsored by a technology company, establishing the professional setting where the three students are working.','To suggest that the team started late and are already behind all the other competitors, explaining why their app is full of errors while other teams have likely finished.','To create immediate urgency and tension — the ticking clock establishes pressure from the first sentence and drives the pace of the entire passage.'],c:3,e:'Opening with a specific, counting-down number instantly creates tension. The reader feels the time pressure before knowing anything else about the situation. This structural choice means every subsequent event — the errors, Leo\'s indecision, Sanjay\'s fix — is experienced against the clock, raising stakes throughout.'},
      {q:'Dani describes her role as \'the person who panicked on behalf of the whole team so that the others didn\'t have to\'. What does this reveal about how she sees herself?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['She is describing a role she does not actually perform — in reality she spends most of the competition watching others work rather than contributing anything practical to the team.','She genuinely believes her role is worthless compared to coding and design, and the statement reveals her regret that she never learned the technical skills Sanjay and Leo possess.','She is self-deprecating about her contribution but actually describes a vital role — she absorbs the team\'s anxiety so others can focus, showing emotional intelligence disguised as a joke.','She is proud and arrogant about being the most important team member, and uses humour to remind Sanjay and Leo that neither of them could succeed without her leadership.'],c:2,e:'Dani\'s self-description is humorous but reveals real insight. Describing project management as \'panicking on behalf of the whole team\' is self-deprecating, but the passage proves her role is essential. Without her, Leo would still be choosing colours. Her ability to laugh at herself while doing vital work shows both humility and emotional intelligence.'},
      {q:'How does the passage structure the team\'s progress to create a satisfying narrative arc?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['The passage is structured as three separate stories about three separate characters who never interact, with each section focusing on one person\'s individual experience of the competition.','It moves from success to failure as the team runs out of time — the app works at first but gradually breaks down, ending with the team unable to present anything to the judges.','The structure is circular, ending exactly where it began — the final paragraph returns to the same error messages and countdown timer that opened the passage.','It moves from chaos (errors, panic, indecision) through individual breakthroughs (Sanjay\'s fix, Leo\'s design) to collective success — mirroring the way real teamwork gradually comes together.'],c:3,e:'The passage follows a clear arc: disorder (angry red errors, Leo paralysed, timer counting down) gives way to progress (Sanjay fixes the API, Dani steers Leo) and finally success (the app works, the team acknowledges each other). This mirrors real collaborative work, where early chaos gradually resolves through individual contributions.'},
      {q:'What does the exchange about \'four hundred shades of blue\' reveal about the tension between Leo\'s perfectionism and the team\'s deadline?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['Leo\'s insistence on precision with colour shows his artistic integrity, but in a timed competition it becomes a liability — the \'four hundred shades\' highlights the gap between creative idealism and practical reality.','It shows that Dani is being impatient and controlling, since by forcing Leo to choose quickly she prioritises efficiency over quality and undermines the creative process.','It demonstrates that the competition requires external pressure distorts individual talent, as Leo\'s deep colour knowledge becomes paralysis under time constraints, revealing competition formats are poorly suited to creative work.','It proves that Leo is wasting time deliberately to sabotage the team.'],c:0,e:'The phrase \'four hundred shades\' captures Leo\'s artistic nature in a single detail. To him, colour choices matter deeply — this is a strength that produces a \'beautiful\' interface. But under time pressure, the same quality becomes a weakness. The exchange encapsulates the passage\'s insight that every strength has a corresponding vulnerability.'},
      {q:'What does the final line — Dani noting that \'Prevented murders\' had a nice ring to it — suggest about her character and the passage\'s tone?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['It proves that Dani does not take the competition seriously enough and would rather make jokes than help with the final stages of preparing the presentation.','It shows that Dani is planning to exaggerate her contribution to the judges by taking credit for Sanjay\'s coding fix and Leo\'s design work during the team\'s presentation.','It suggests that the team members were in genuine physical danger from each other, and that Sanjay and Leo nearly came to blows over a disagreement about the app\'s direction.','It shows Dani\'s wit and self-awareness — she can find humour even under pressure, and her joke acknowledges the reality of her role while keeping the tone light and affectionate.'],c:3,e:'The line works as both a joke and a truth. Dani\'s real contribution — preventing conflict, forcing decisions, managing time — is hard to describe impressively. By framing it as murder prevention, she simultaneously makes the reader laugh and acknowledges the unglamorous reality of her role. The tone remains warm and self-deprecating.'}
  ]},
  {id:'F17',title:'The Refugee\'s Suitcase',type:'fiction',source:'Original passage — displacement / memory / hope',
   text:'The suitcase was small and brown, with a broken clasp that had to be held shut with a belt. It had belonged to Yusuf\'s grandfather, and before that to his great-grandfather, and it had crossed more borders than Yusuf could count. Now it sat on the floor of a temporary room in a temporary building in a country where everything — the language, the food, the grey flatness of the sky — was temporary too, or at least felt that way.\n\nYusuf was twelve. He had been twelve for three months, though he had not celebrated his birthday because birthdays require a home, and he had not had one of those since leaving Aleppo. What he had was the suitcase, and inside it, the things he had chosen to carry when his mother told him, on a Tuesday evening that now felt like it belonged to someone else\'s life, that they were leaving and they could each bring one bag.\n\nOne bag. His whole life condensed into a rectangle of cracked leather. He had chosen: a photograph of his father, taken in the garden before the war, laughing at something outside the frame. A notebook filled with drawings of buildings — not the bombed ones he had seen from the car window, but buildings he wanted to design one day, with gardens on the roofs and glass walls that let in light. A small brass compass his grandfather had given him, its needle still swinging faithfully north no matter how many countries they passed through. And a bag of za\'atar spice mix from the kitchen shelf, because his mother always said that home is wherever you can smell za\'atar.\n\nThe room they were staying in now had two beds, a radiator that clanked like a tired horse, and a window that looked out onto a car park. It was warm and dry, which was more than could be said for some of the places they had slept. Yusuf\'s mother was downstairs, filling in forms — she was always filling in forms, in a language she was still learning, with a patience that Yusuf found both impressive and heartbreaking.\n\nHe opened the suitcase and took out the compass. The needle swung and settled. North. It had pointed north in Aleppo, north on the boat, north in the camp with the grey tents, and north here, in this small room above a car park in a city whose name he could now almost pronounce. The world kept changing around him — languages, borders, faces — but the compass was constant. It did not care about wars or visas or forms written in languages you couldn\'t read. It just pointed north.\n\nYusuf held it in his palm and made a decision. He would learn this country\'s language. He would draw its buildings. He would find a way to make this temporary place feel less temporary. The compass couldn\'t tell him how, but it told him which direction to face. That was enough to start.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['A young refugee carries a few precious objects that represent his identity, his memories, and his hope — and finds the determination to build a new life despite having lost almost everything.','Yusuf is unhappy in his new country and wants to return to Aleppo immediately, which is why he keeps holding the compass and refusing to unpack his suitcase or settle in.','Yusuf is a talented architect who has already designed many buildings back in Aleppo, and the passage focuses on his professional skills rather than his emotional journey.','The passage is mainly about the practical challenges of refugee accommodation, focusing on the poor quality of the temporary building and its broken facilities.'],c:0,e:'The passage builds from loss (leaving home, one bag) through the objects that carry Yusuf\'s identity (photo, drawings, compass, za\'atar) to a moment of resolve (he will learn the language, draw buildings, make this place less temporary). The arc is from displacement to tentative hope.'},
      {q:'The word \'temporary\' is repeated several times in the first paragraph: \'temporary room\', \'temporary building\', \'temporary too\'. What effect does this repetition create?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['It suggests Yusuf enjoys living in temporary accommodation because he finds the constant change of scenery exciting and prefers it to staying in one place.','It shows that the author has made a careless error by accidentally repeating the same adjective, rather than choosing different words to describe the room and building.','It means the building is literally scheduled for demolition soon, and the family will be forced to move again within days of arriving.','It creates a sense of instability and rootlessness — everything in Yusuf\'s life feels impermanent, emphasising his lack of a real home and his longing for something lasting.'],c:3,e:'The repetition of \'temporary\' is deliberate. Each use adds another layer of impermanence — the room, the building, the country itself. By the time the narrator adds \'or at least felt that way\', the word has created an atmosphere of instability that defines Yusuf\'s emotional state.'},
      {q:'Yusuf\'s four chosen objects are a photograph, a notebook of building drawings, a compass, and za\'atar spice. What do these objects reveal about him as a character?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['The objects have no deeper meaning — they are simply the most practical items for travelling, such as the compass for navigation and the spice for cooking meals on the journey.','He chose these objects because they were the most valuable things he owned, and he wanted to be able to sell them if the family needed money in their new country.','He packed randomly without thinking, grabbing whatever was closest to him when his mother told him they were leaving on that Tuesday evening.','Each object represents a different part of his identity: the photo is family and the past, the drawings are ambition and the future, the compass is guidance, and the za\'atar is home and culture — together they show a complete person.'],c:3,e:'The four objects are not random — each carries meaning. The photograph connects Yusuf to his father and his pre-war life. The drawings reveal his dreams. The compass symbolises direction and constancy. The za\'atar represents home and cultural identity. Together, they portrait a whole person in four small items.'},
      {q:'The compass \'did not care about wars or visas or forms written in languages you couldn\'t read. It just pointed north.\' What theme does this symbol develop?',skill:'Theme',opts:['Compasses are the most important practical survival tool for refugees, and the passage argues that Yusuf\'s grandfather was wise to give him one for the physical journey ahead.','Technology is always more reliable than human beings, and the compass proves that simple mechanical instruments outperform the adults in Yusuf\'s life who keep making wrong decisions.','Yusuf should use the compass to navigate back to Aleppo, and his decision at the end to stay in the new country goes against what the compass symbolically tells him to do.','Amid chaos and displacement, some things remain constant — the compass represents the idea that direction and purpose can survive even when everything else is lost.'],c:3,e:'The compass symbolises constancy in a world of change. While everything around Yusuf shifts — languages, borders, homes — the compass keeps pointing the same way. This becomes a metaphor for inner purpose: even when external circumstances are beyond your control, you can still choose a direction.'},
      {q:'How would you describe the overall tone of this passage?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Angry and bitter — Yusuf resents his new country and blames the people around him for his family\'s suffering, particularly the officials who make his mother fill in forms.','Cheerful and optimistic — Yusuf is excited about the adventure of living in a new country and sees the temporary accommodation as a fun and interesting experience.','Cold and factual — the passage reads like a news report, presenting statistics about refugee displacement without revealing Yusuf\'s personal feelings or inner thoughts.','Quietly determined and bittersweet — the passage acknowledges enormous loss without self-pity, and ends with hope that is realistic rather than naive.'],c:3,e:'The tone balances sadness and strength. Details like the uncelebrated birthday and the mother filling in forms are poignant but not sentimental. Yusuf\'s final decision — to learn, to draw, to build — is hopeful but measured. He doesn\'t claim everything will be fine; he says it\'s \'enough to start\'. This restraint makes the hope feel genuine.'},
      {q:'From whose perspective is the passage told, and how does this affect the reader\'s understanding of displacement?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['Third-person limited following Yusuf — this lets the reader experience displacement through a child\'s specific, personal observations rather than abstract statistics, making the refugee experience feel intimate and real.','First-person by Yusuf\'s mother, who describes filling in forms downstairs and reflects on her own struggles to learn the new language while caring for her son.','A journalist\'s perspective, reporting objectively on conditions at the refugee centre and interviewing multiple families about their experiences of displacement.','Omniscient narration that moves between Yusuf upstairs with his suitcase and his mother downstairs with her forms, giving equal attention to both characters\' inner thoughts.'],c:0,e:'By following Yusuf closely, the passage makes displacement personal rather than political. We do not learn about refugee statistics — we learn about one boy\'s suitcase, one brass compass, one uncelebrated birthday. This tight perspective transforms a large, abstract issue into a specific, emotional human story.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about Yusuf\'s mother from the details given about her?',skill:'Inference',opts:['She is filling in forms as a way to keep herself busy and avoid thinking about their situation, treating the paperwork as a distraction rather than a necessity.','She is unable to cope with their new situation and has given up trying, which is why Yusuf must take charge and make the decision to learn the language himself.','She is resilient, patient, and determined — learning a new language and endlessly filling in forms shows she is doing the difficult, unglamorous work of rebuilding their lives.','She speaks the new country\'s language fluently and has no difficulty with the forms, since she studied the language before leaving Aleppo in preparation for the move.'],c:2,e:'The mother appears briefly but powerfully. She is \'always filling in forms, in a language she was still learning, with a patience that Yusuf found both impressive and heartbreaking\'. This reveals determination and quiet strength. She is doing the practical, grinding work of displacement — bureaucracy in a foreign language — without complaint.'},
      {q:'Why does the author include the detail that Yusuf \'had not celebrated his birthday because birthdays require a home\'?',skill:'Author\'s purpose & tone',opts:['To suggest that Yusuf does not enjoy birthday parties and prefers to skip them, since he is now twelve and considers himself too old for celebrations.','To show a specific, personal loss that makes the abstract concept of displacement concrete — losing a birthday celebration is something every reader can understand and feel.','To show that Yusuf\'s mother forgot his birthday because she was too busy filling in forms, revealing a growing distance between mother and son.','To explain that birthdays are not traditionally celebrated in Yusuf\'s culture, and the passage uses this cultural difference to contrast his background with Western customs.'],c:1,e:'The uncelebrated birthday is a small but devastating detail. Every reader understands birthdays, making this loss immediately relatable. By connecting birthdays to having a home, the author shows how displacement affects not just safety and shelter but the small rituals that make life feel normal.'},
      {q:'What does the description of the radiator \'clanking like a tired horse\' contribute to the passage?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['It makes the temporary room feel worn-out and imperfect while also adding a note of weary endurance — the tired horse image echoes the exhaustion of Yusuf\'s own journey.','It means there is an actual horse stabled somewhere near the building, and the sounds Yusuf hears are coming from the animal rather than the heating system.','It shows that the building is in excellent condition and recently renovated, since the radiator produces a gentle rhythmic sound that Yusuf finds comforting and familiar.','It is a purely factual description of how all radiators normally sound, included only to give the reader practical information about the heating in the temporary accommodation.'],c:0,e:'The simile gives the radiator personality — tired, working but worn. This mirrors the family\'s own state: functioning but exhausted. The \'tired horse\' echoes the weariness of long travel. However, the narrator also notes the room is \'warm and dry\', showing this imperfect space still provides basic comfort after worse conditions.'},
      {q:'How does the passage structure Yusuf\'s items to build emotional impact?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['Each object is introduced with its emotional meaning — the photograph represents the past, the drawings represent the future, the compass represents guidance, and the za\'atar represents home — building a portrait of a whole identity in four items.','The objects are listed randomly without any particular order, and the passage would work just as well if they were rearranged or if different items had been chosen.','The objects are structured chronologically by when Yusuf acquired them — the photograph came first from his father, then the notebook from school, then the compass from his grandfather, then the za\'atar from the kitchen.','The passage describes the objects from most expensive to least expensive, showing that Yusuf prioritised financial value when deciding what to save from his old life.'],c:0,e:'The four objects are carefully ordered to create cumulative emotional effect. The photograph looks backward (father, garden, laughter). The drawings look forward (buildings he wants to design). The compass provides direction. The za\'atar provides home. Together they build a complete emotional portrait — past, future, guidance, and belonging — in four small items.'},
      {q:'What does Yusuf\'s final decision — to learn the language, draw buildings, and make the temporary place less temporary — reveal about his character?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['He is resilient and forward-looking — despite everything he has lost, he chooses to actively build a new life rather than wait passively, showing determination and agency.','He is unrealistic and naive about how difficult his situation truly is, since learning a language and drawing buildings will not solve the practical problems of finding permanent housing and legal status.','He has completely forgotten about Aleppo and no longer cares about his old life, which is why he is ready to embrace his new country without any sadness or hesitation.','He is making these plans only because his mother told him to while she was filling in forms downstairs, and the decision reflects her wishes rather than his own initiative.'],c:0,e:'Yusuf\'s decision is an act of agency in a situation where he has had very little control. He cannot choose his country, his room, or his circumstances, but he can choose his response. The three actions — learning, drawing, making — are all constructive and outward-facing, showing a character who refuses to be defined solely by loss.'},
      {q:'The passage says Yusuf\'s mother packs with \'a patience that Yusuf found both impressive and heartbreaking\'. What does the word \'heartbreaking\' suggest about how Yusuf sees his mother?',skill:'Inference',opts:['He recognises that her patience comes at great personal cost — she is enduring humiliation and difficulty without complaint, and he is old enough to understand the unfairness of what she must go through.','He is upset because his mother is not paying attention to him, since she spends all her time downstairs doing paperwork instead of being with him in their room.','He thinks his mother is too slow at filling in forms and wishes she would hurry up so they can leave the temporary building and move to a proper home sooner.','The word means Yusuf feels physical chest pain from watching his mother work, and the passage is describing a medical symptom caused by the stress of their refugee experience.'],c:0,e:'The word \'heartbreaking\' reveals Yusuf\'s maturity. A younger child might not notice a parent\'s struggle, but Yusuf sees both the strength (impressive) and the cost (heartbreaking) of his mother\'s patience. This dual perception shows he understands that her calm exterior hides difficulty, and he feels the injustice of her situation.'}
  ]},
  {id:'NF01',title:'The Language of Bees',type:'nonfiction',source:'Original passage — science / animal behaviour',
   text:'When a honeybee finds a rich source of nectar, she faces a problem: how does she tell the rest of the hive where it is? She cannot speak, draw a map, or send a text message. Instead, she dances.\n\nIn the 1940s, Austrian scientist Karl von Frisch discovered that returning forager bees perform a \'waggle dance\' on the surface of the honeycomb. The dance is a figure-of-eight pattern with a straight run through the middle. During this straight run, the bee waggles her abdomen rapidly from side to side. The direction of the straight run tells the other bees which way to fly relative to the sun. The duration of the waggle — how long the bee shakes — tells them how far away the food source is. A longer waggle means a greater distance. Even the enthusiasm of the dance matters: the more vigorously the bee waggles, the richer the nectar source is believed to be.\n\nWhat makes this truly remarkable is the precision. Bees can communicate the location of flowers more than five kilometres away, and their hivemates can find those flowers with surprising accuracy — often arriving within just a few metres of the exact spot. Von Frisch was so astonished by his discovery that he spent the next twenty years studying it. In 1973, he was awarded the Nobel Prize for his work — one of the very few scientists ever to win the prize for research into animal behaviour.\n\nHowever, not all scientists are convinced that the waggle dance tells the full story. In recent years, researchers have found that bees also rely on scent trails, visual landmarks such as distinctive trees or buildings, and their own spatial memory to navigate. Some carefully controlled experiments have shown that bees can still locate food sources even when the waggle dance is deliberately disrupted — for example, by rotating the honeycomb so that the dance gives false directions. If the dance were the only navigation method, these bees should have become lost. The fact that many still found the flowers suggests that other methods of communication are working alongside the dance.\n\nThe truth, as is often the case in science, is probably a combination of all these factors. The waggle dance remains one of the most sophisticated communication systems found anywhere in the animal kingdom, but it appears to be one tool in a larger navigational toolkit — not the sole explanation for the honeybee\'s extraordinary ability to find food across vast distances. What began as a simple question about a dancing bee has opened up an entire field of research that, nearly eighty years after von Frisch\'s first observations, scientists are still working to fully understand.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['The passage traces the history of bee research from von Frisch\'s initial observations through to his Nobel Prize, arguing that his work remains the single most important contribution to animal behaviour science.','The passage presents evidence that bees rely primarily on scent trails and visual landmarks rather than the waggle dance, which carefully controlled experiments have shown to be largely inaccurate.','Honeybees use a sophisticated waggle dance to communicate food locations, but modern research suggests the dance is part of a larger navigational system rather than the complete explanation.','The passage argues that the waggle dance functions effectively only over short distances, and that bees navigating beyond a few hundred metres must rely on entirely different communication methods.'],c:2,e:'The passage explains the waggle dance in detail (paragraphs 2–3), then introduces evidence that complicates this picture (paragraph 4), before concluding that the truth is a combination of factors (paragraph 5). The main idea captures both the wonder of the dance and the nuance of ongoing research.'},
      {q:'How is this passage structured overall?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['Persuasive argument — the author builds the case that the waggle dance should be preserved and protected, using von Frisch\'s Nobel Prize as an appeal to authority and the honeycomb experiment as a warning about human interference.','Compare and contrast — the passage systematically compares bee communication with human language to argue that bees possess a grammar as complex as any spoken language.','Question, explanation, complication, balanced conclusion — a question is posed, answered, challenged by new evidence, then resolved with a balanced view.','Strict chronological order — the passage begins with von Frisch\'s 1940s discovery, moves through his 1973 Nobel Prize, and ends with present-day research, never departing from a timeline structure.'],c:2,e:'Paragraph one poses a question. Paragraphs two and three explain the waggle dance. Paragraph four introduces complicating evidence. Paragraph five offers a balanced conclusion. This mirrors how scientific understanding develops — discovery, challenge, refinement.'},
      {q:'In paragraph four, the author describes an experiment where scientists rotated the honeycomb. Why is this experiment included?',skill:'Analyse informational texts',opts:['To provide concrete evidence that bees navigate using methods beyond the dance — if it were the only method, the bees with false directions should have become lost.','To illustrate how modern researchers use carefully controlled experimental methods to test animal behaviour theories, isolating individual variables to determine their relative importance.','To demonstrate that Karl von Frisch\'s original research was fundamentally flawed and that his Nobel Prize was awarded prematurely based on incomplete evidence.','To prove that scent trails are the primary navigation method and the waggle dance is merely a social bonding ritual with no directional information.'],c:0,e:'The rotated-honeycomb experiment tests the waggle dance in isolation. By corrupting the dance\'s information and showing many bees still found food, it demonstrates other navigation systems must exist — supporting the paragraph\'s argument without dismissing the dance entirely.'},
      {q:'Why does the author mention that von Frisch won the Nobel Prize?',skill:'Author\'s purpose',opts:['To argue that the Nobel Prize committee always makes correct decisions.','To entertain the reader with an interesting but irrelevant piece of trivia.','To persuade the reader that everyone should study science.','To add credibility to the waggle dance discovery by showing it was recognised at the highest level of scientific achievement.'],c:3,e:'The Nobel Prize detail raises the stakes of the passage\'s argument. When paragraph four then challenges this Nobel-winning discovery, the reader understands that serious, well-established science is being refined, not fringe ideas being debunked.'},
      {q:'The waggle dance is described as \'one tool in a larger navigational toolkit\'. What does this metaphor mean?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['Scientists need better laboratory equipment to study bees — the metaphor is criticising the inadequacy of current research tools and calling for more funding to decode the waggle dance.','The dance was effective in the 1940s but has since become obsolete as bees have evolved to rely entirely on scent trails, making von Frisch\'s discovery historically interesting but no longer relevant.','Bees carry tiny physical tools with them when they fly — the metaphor is literal, suggesting that forager bees use pollen baskets and other body parts as navigational instruments alongside the dance.','The dance is valuable but is only one of several methods bees use — the metaphor emphasises that no single explanation is sufficient and multiple systems work together.'],c:3,e:'A toolkit contains multiple tools for different situations. Similarly, bees appear to use the dance alongside scent, memory, and landmarks. The metaphor respects the dance\'s importance while placing it in a broader context, matching the passage\'s balanced tone.'},
      {q:'What tone does the author adopt throughout this passage, and how is it maintained?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Dismissive and sceptical — the author consistently undermines von Frisch\'s findings by describing the honeycomb rotation experiment as proof that the waggle dance is unreliable and overhyped.','Enthusiastic yet balanced — the author clearly finds the waggle dance fascinating (words like \'truly remarkable\') but remains objective when presenting challenges to the theory, maintaining scientific credibility.','Humorous and light-hearted — the passage treats bee communication as a joke, using the image of a dancing insect primarily for comic effect rather than scientific explanation.','Dry and academic — the passage contains no personality or enthusiasm at all, relying solely on technical vocabulary like \'figure-of-eight\' and \'waggle\' without any attempt to engage a general audience.'],c:1,e:'The author\'s enthusiasm is evident in phrases like \'truly remarkable\' and the detailed description of von Frisch\'s astonishment. However, this enthusiasm is balanced by careful, objective language when discussing counter-evidence in paragraph four. This combination makes the passage both engaging and trustworthy — the reader can enjoy the wonder while trusting the science.'},
      {q:'What does the opening scenario — a bee finding nectar and needing to tell her hive — achieve as a structural choice?',skill:'Author\'s purpose & tone',opts:['It is an inaccurate description of how bees actually behave — honeybees do not individually search for nectar, so the scenario misleads the reader about the foraging process before the scientific explanation begins.','It is included to establish that bees lack human language, which is the passage\'s main argument — the author believes the waggle dance is inferior to speech and uses the opening to highlight this limitation.','It frames the scientific content as the answer to a relatable problem, making the reader curious about the solution before the technical explanation begins — this hooks the reader\'s interest through narrative rather than data.','It wastes space before getting to the important scientific information — the paragraph about nectar-finding delays the discussion of von Frisch\'s Nobel Prize, which is the passage\'s real subject.'],c:2,e:'By opening with a problem (how does a bee communicate?), the author creates a question in the reader\'s mind that demands an answer. This is a classic non-fiction technique: posing a relatable scenario before introducing technical content ensures the reader is engaged and motivated to keep reading through the more complex paragraphs about dance direction and duration.'},
      {q:'From the passage, what can you infer about why von Frisch spent twenty years studying the waggle dance after his initial discovery?',skill:'Inference',opts:['He had no other research projects to work on and needed to fill his time — as an Austrian scientist working in the post-war period, bee research was the only funding available to him.','The dance\'s complexity — encoding direction, distance, and quality of food — was so unexpected in an insect that it raised far more questions than it answered, compelling decades of further investigation.','He was trying to prove his original discovery was wrong — the passage suggests von Frisch doubted the waggle dance\'s accuracy and spent two decades attempting to disprove his own theory.','His university forced him to continue studying bees against his will — the word \'astonished\' suggests reluctance rather than enthusiasm, implying the research was an obligation rather than a passion.'],c:1,e:'The passage tells us von Frisch was \'so astonished\' by the discovery that he spent twenty more years on it. We can infer that a communication system this sophisticated in a creature with a brain the size of a sesame seed would raise profound questions about animal cognition, evolution, and the nature of communication — enough to sustain a career of research.'},
      {q:'The passage says bees can locate flowers \'within just a few metres of the exact spot\' over five kilometres away. Why does the author include this specific detail?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['To prove that bees have better eyesight than humans — the ability to locate flowers a few metres from the exact spot over five kilometres suggests their visual acuity far exceeds human capabilities.','To quantify the dance\'s precision and make the reader appreciate just how effective it is — the contrast between the vast distance (5km) and the tiny margin of error (a few metres) creates a sense of wonder.','To suggest that the waggle dance works only at distances greater than five kilometres — the detail implies shorter-range navigation relies entirely on scent trails and visual landmarks instead.','To argue that all insects can communicate with equal precision — the author uses honeybees as a representative example to suggest that ants, wasps, and other social insects share the same navigational accuracy.'],c:1,e:'The juxtaposition of five kilometres (the distance) with a few metres (the accuracy) is deliberately striking. It transforms an abstract claim about precision into something the reader can grasp: imagine telling someone to find a specific flower bed five kilometres away, and they arrive within a few metres. This concrete detail makes the waggle dance\'s effectiveness feel genuinely astonishing.'},
      {q:'What theme about scientific knowledge does the passage develop across its five paragraphs?',skill:'Theme',opts:['That scientists always disagree with each other and can never reach conclusions — the passage presents von Frisch\'s Nobel Prize and the honeycomb experiment as evidence that the scientific community is fundamentally divided on bee communication.','That older scientific theories are always wrong and should be discarded — the honeycomb rotation experiment in paragraph four definitively disproves the waggle dance, rendering von Frisch\'s 1940s discovery obsolete.','That scientific understanding is always evolving — initial discoveries are refined, challenged, and complicated by new evidence, and the \'truth\' is usually more complex than any single explanation.','That animal behaviour is too complex to ever be understood by humans — the passage ends by stating scientists are \'still working to fully understand,\' implying that bee navigation will permanently remain beyond human comprehension.'],c:2,e:'The passage traces a pattern: von Frisch\'s elegant discovery (paragraphs 2-3) is complicated by new evidence (paragraph 4), leading to a more nuanced understanding (paragraph 5). This mirrors how science actually works — not as a series of definitive answers but as an ongoing process of discovery, challenge, and refinement. The final sentence explicitly states research is \'still working to fully understand\'.'},
      {q:'What does the phrase \'she dances\' at the end of the first paragraph achieve as a literary technique?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['It creates a dramatic, surprising one-sentence reveal after a build-up of things the bee cannot do — the short sentence contrasts with the longer preceding ones, giving it impact and drawing the reader into the explanation that follows.','It anthropomorphises the bee in a way that is scientifically inaccurate — real bees do not \'dance\' in any meaningful sense, and the word misleads readers into imagining choreographed human movement.','It is grammatically incorrect and should be a longer sentence — the fragment \'she dances\' lacks the detail needed to explain the waggle dance, leaving readers confused until paragraph two.','It is a metaphor suggesting the bee is performing ballet — the word \'dances\' evokes artistic performance, implying that the waggle dance is an aesthetic display rather than a communication system.'],c:0,e:'The first paragraph lists what the bee cannot do (speak, draw a map, send a text), building expectation. Then the short declarative sentence \'Instead, she dances\' lands with surprising force. The brevity after the longer build-up creates emphasis, and the unexpected verb \'dances\' is intriguing enough to pull the reader into the next paragraph for an explanation.'},
  ]},
  {id:'NF02',title:'The City That Drowned Twice',type:'nonfiction',source:'Original passage — history / geography / Galveston hurricane',
   text:'On 8 September 1900, the city of Galveston, Texas, was the wealthiest city per capita in the United States. It was a booming port city with grand Victorian mansions, electric streetcars, and one of the first telephone systems in the country. Visitors called it \'the New York of the South\'. By the morning of 9 September, it had been almost completely destroyed. A hurricane — the deadliest natural disaster in American history — had struck without adequate warning, killing between 6,000 and 12,000 people in a single night.\n\nGalveston\'s geography made it dangerously vulnerable. The city sat on a narrow barrier island in the Gulf of Mexico, with its highest point just 2.7 metres above sea level. When the storm surge hit, waves swept across the entire island. Whole streets were erased. Wooden houses were torn apart and their wreckage piled into enormous walls of debris that trapped residents inside their homes. There was simply nowhere higher to go, and for many, nowhere to hide.\n\nAfter the disaster, the city\'s leaders faced a stark choice: abandon Galveston or find a way to protect it. They chose an extraordinary — some said impossible — solution. Over seven years, engineers raised the entire city. Every building, every street, every water pipe and sewage line was lifted by up to five metres. They achieved this by pumping millions of tonnes of sand from the seabed underneath the city\'s foundations, jacking up structures one by one while residents continued to live and work around them. Alongside this, they constructed a massive concrete seawall, five metres tall and over five kilometres long, curving along the coast like a shield.\n\nThe engineering worked. When another powerful hurricane struck in 1915, the seawall held firm and casualties were dramatically fewer. The city\'s extraordinary gamble had paid off — at least in terms of survival. Galveston had proven that human ingenuity could stand up to nature\'s most destructive forces.\n\nBut the damage to Galveston\'s reputation could not be repaired by concrete and sand. Businesses had already relocated to safer ground. Investors turned their attention inland. Insurance companies refused to cover coastal properties at affordable rates. Houston, just fifty miles to the north, had suffered no such catastrophe and offered the stability that nervous investors craved. Within a decade, Houston had overtaken Galveston as the region\'s dominant commercial centre. The city that had once been called the jewel of the Texas coast never fully recovered its former status.\n\nGalveston had won the battle against the sea, but it had already lost the war for the future. Its story remains one of the most remarkable examples of engineering triumph and economic tragedy existing side by side — a reminder that surviving a disaster and recovering from one are not the same thing.',
   questions:[
      {q:'Which text structure best describes the overall organisation of this passage?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['Compare and contrast — Galveston and Houston are compared throughout, with equal space devoted to each city\'s response to the hurricane and their respective engineering achievements.','Problem, solution, and evaluation — a disaster is described, an engineering response is explained, and the long-term outcome is assessed with a twist.','Description only — the passage describes what Galveston looked like before the storm and catalogues the physical damage without analysing causes, solutions, or long-term consequences.','Persuasive argument — the author wants readers to donate to Galveston, using the 1900 death toll and the seawall construction costs to appeal to the reader\'s sympathy and sense of civic duty.'],c:1,e:'Paragraphs 1–2 establish the problem (hurricane destruction). Paragraphs 3–4 describe the solution and its success. Paragraphs 5–6 evaluate the outcome with a twist — the engineering worked but the economic damage was irreversible. This evaluation gives the passage its complexity.'},
      {q:'Which statement from the passage is an opinion rather than a verifiable fact?',skill:'Analyse informational texts',opts:['A hurricane killed between 6,000 and 12,000 people in a single night.','The city sat on a narrow barrier island in the Gulf of Mexico.','Houston was just fifty miles to the north.','They chose an extraordinary — some said impossible — solution.'],c:3,e:'\'Extraordinary\' and \'impossible\' are judgements. The author signals this by including \'some said\', acknowledging that the word \'impossible\' is opinion. The other statements are verifiable facts about death toll, geography, and distance.'},
      {q:'The final paragraph says \'surviving a disaster and recovering from one are not the same thing\'. What does this distinction mean?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['Physical survival (preventing deaths) and full recovery (regaining economic importance) are different challenges — Galveston achieved the first but not the second.','The author believes Galveston should have been abandoned instead of rebuilt — the distinction between surviving and recovering implies the seven-year engineering project was ultimately a waste of resources.','Houston also suffered a hurricane but recovered more quickly than Galveston because it invested in a seawall before the storm, giving it the economic resilience that Galveston lacked.','Galveston was never actually hit by a hurricane — the author uses a fictional disaster as an extended metaphor for how cities decline economically even without physical destruction.'],c:0,e:'This is the passage\'s central insight. Galveston \'survived\' by preventing future catastrophic loss of life. But \'recovery\' — returning to its former status — proved impossible because reputational and economic damage outlasted the physical threat. The sentence asks the reader to see success and failure coexisting.'},
      {q:'Why does the author describe Galveston\'s wealth and technology in the opening before the hurricane?',skill:'Author\'s purpose',opts:['To create dramatic contrast — establishing what Galveston had makes its destruction more shocking and the stakes of rebuilding higher.','To fill space with unnecessary historical details — the information about Victorian mansions and electric streetcars is decorative and could be removed without affecting the passage\'s argument about engineering.','To prove Galveston was more technologically advanced than Houston — the opening establishes that Galveston\'s telephone system and streetcars were superior to Houston\'s, explaining why investors initially preferred it.','To argue that wealthy cities are always targeted by hurricanes — the author implies that Galveston\'s prosperity attracted the storm, drawing a causal connection between economic success and natural disaster.'],c:0,e:'By painting Galveston as wealthy and thriving — \'the New York of the South\' — the author makes the hurricane\'s devastation hit harder. This technique (establishing high stakes before the crisis) makes the rebuilding effort feel more heroic and the eventual economic decline more tragic.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about why insurance companies refused to cover Galveston\'s coastal properties at affordable rates after the 1900 hurricane?',skill:'Inference',opts:['The insurance companies had all been destroyed in the hurricane themselves — their offices were located on the barrier island and were swept away along with Galveston\'s wooden houses and Victorian mansions.','The hurricane proved that Galveston\'s low-lying coastal location made it extremely high-risk, and insurers calculated that the probability of future catastrophic losses was too great to offer competitive premiums.','Insurance companies were punishing Galveston for building the seawall — they viewed the five-metre concrete barrier as an admission that the city was permanently unsafe and refused to insure properties behind it.','Insurance was not available in Texas during this time period — the passage implies that the industry had not yet expanded to cover Gulf Coast states, which is why Houston also lacked affordable coverage.'],c:1,e:'Insurance is based on risk assessment. After a hurricane killed up to 12,000 people and destroyed the city, insurers had hard evidence that Galveston was extremely vulnerable. Even with the seawall, the demonstrated risk made affordable coverage impossible. This is a logical inference from the passage\'s description of the devastation and the subsequent economic consequences.'},
      {q:'How does the author use the metaphor of the seawall curving \'like a shield\' to shape the reader\'s understanding?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['It frames the engineering project in heroic, defensive terms — a shield protects against attack, which positions Galveston\'s engineers as defenders fighting back against the sea, making the rebuilding feel brave and purposeful.','It suggests the seawall was made of the same materials as ancient shields — the five-metre concrete structure echoes Roman defensive engineering, implying that Galveston\'s builders drew on classical construction methods.','It means the seawall was shaped exactly like a medieval shield — the five-kilometre curve along the coastline literally replicated the rounded profile of a knight\'s shield for maximum wave deflection.','It implies the seawall was decorative rather than functional — the comparison to a shield suggests it was built to reassure nervous investors rather than to withstand an actual hurricane storm surge.'],c:0,e:'The shield metaphor casts the engineering project as an act of defiance against nature. Shields are associated with protection, battle, and courage. By using this image, the author elevates the seawall from a practical structure to a symbol of human determination, which aligns with the passage\'s theme of engineering triumph alongside economic tragedy.'},
      {q:'What is the overall tone of the final paragraph, and how does it differ from the tone of paragraphs three and four?',skill:'Tone',opts:['The tone remains consistently optimistic throughout all paragraphs — even the final paragraph\'s mention of Houston overtaking Galveston is presented as a positive development for the Texas Gulf Coast region as a whole.','The final paragraph is angry and accusatory, blaming Houston for Galveston\'s decline — phrases like \'nervous investors\' and \'safer ground\' portray Houston as an opportunistic rival that exploited Galveston\'s misfortune.','The final paragraph is reflective and melancholy, contrasting with the triumphant, admiring tone of paragraphs three and four — this tonal shift mirrors Galveston\'s own journey from engineering success to economic decline.','The final paragraph is humorous, making light of Galveston\'s misfortune — the phrase \'won the battle but lost the war\' is used as a witty punchline to entertain the reader rather than to convey genuine loss.'],c:2,e:'Paragraphs three and four celebrate the engineering achievement with words like \'extraordinary\' and \'gamble had paid off.\' The final paragraph shifts to a more sombre, reflective register: \'won the battle\' but \'lost the war.\' This tonal contrast is deliberate — it mirrors the passage\'s central paradox that physical survival and full recovery are different things.'},
      {q:'Why does the author include the specific detail that Galveston\'s highest point was \'just 2.7 metres above sea level\'?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['To argue that all cities below 3 metres should be abandoned immediately — the 2.7-metre figure is presented as a universal threshold, implying that any coastal city near this elevation faces the same inevitable destruction.','To demonstrate the author\'s knowledge of precise geographical measurements — the specific figure establishes the writer\'s credentials as a geography expert, lending authority to the later claims about Houston\'s economic rise.','To show that Galveston was actually quite high above sea level and should have been safe — 2.7 metres is presented as a substantial elevation, making the hurricane\'s destructive power seem even more extraordinary.','The precise measurement makes the vulnerability concrete and measurable — the reader can visualise 2.7 metres (roughly the height of a room) and understand why a storm surge easily overwhelmed the island.'],c:3,e:'The specific figure 2.7 metres is more effective than a vague description like \'very low.\' Readers can relate this to familiar heights — a tall person, or a room ceiling — and immediately grasp how inadequate such elevation would be against a major storm surge. This precision transforms abstract vulnerability into something the reader can physically imagine.'},
      {q:'The passage describes Galveston as having had \'electric streetcars\' and \'one of the first telephone systems in the country\'. What theme do these details develop?',skill:'Theme',opts:['They establish Galveston as a place of progress and innovation, which makes its decline more tragic — the theme is that even the most advanced and prosperous communities can be undone by forces beyond their control.','They suggest that technology caused the hurricane by interfering with natural weather patterns — the electric streetcars and telephone wires created an artificial environment that attracted the 1900 storm to Galveston\'s barrier island.','They are included only to provide historical context with no thematic significance — the details about streetcars and telephones simply help the reader picture 1900s America and have no bearing on the passage\'s argument about engineering or economics.','They prove that Galveston was the most technologically advanced city in the world — the passage presents its telephone system and electric streetcars as globally unprecedented innovations that no other city had achieved by 1900.'],c:0,e:'By emphasising Galveston\'s technological achievements, the author establishes it as a symbol of progress. This amplifies the tragedy: it was not a backward or unprepared city, but a thriving, forward-looking one. The theme is that prosperity and progress offer no protection against natural disaster, and that even the most successful places can fall.'},
      {q:'From what point of view is this passage written, and why is that choice effective for this subject matter?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['Second person, making the reader feel as though they lived through the hurricane — the use of \'you\' places the audience directly on Galveston\'s barrier island as the 1900 storm surge sweeps across the city.','Third-person limited through the perspective of a single Galveston engineer — the passage focuses on one person\'s experience of jacking up buildings and constructing the seawall over the seven-year rebuilding period.','Third-person objective, providing a broad historical overview without personal bias — this allows the author to present facts, engineering details, and economic consequences with authority while letting the reader draw their own emotional conclusions.','First person from a Galveston survivor\'s perspective, creating immediate emotional impact — the narrator describes hiding from the storm surge and watching wooden houses torn apart into walls of debris.'],c:2,e:'The objective third-person perspective is ideal for this passage because it needs to cover a wide scope — the hurricane, the engineering response, the economic aftermath, and the comparison with Houston. A personal perspective would limit the view. The author\'s restraint also makes the facts speak for themselves: the contrast between engineering triumph and economic tragedy is more powerful presented objectively than emotionally.'},
      {q:'What is the effect of the author\'s choice to structure the final sentence as a paradox — \'engineering triumph and economic tragedy existing side by side\'?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['It encapsulates the passage\'s central argument that success and failure can coexist — Galveston\'s story cannot be reduced to either a victory or a defeat, and the paradox forces the reader to hold both truths simultaneously.','It suggests the author cannot decide whether Galveston\'s story is positive or negative — the contradictory phrasing reveals the writer\'s own uncertainty about whether the seawall project was ultimately worthwhile.','It confuses the reader by presenting contradictory information — claiming both triumph and tragedy in the same sentence is logically impossible and weakens the passage\'s credibility as a historical account.','It proves that engineering is ultimately pointless if the economy suffers — the seawall\'s success in 1915 is rendered meaningless by Houston\'s rise, suggesting Galveston should never have attempted to rebuild.'],c:0,e:'The paradox is the passage\'s thesis in miniature. By placing \'triumph\' and \'tragedy\' side by side, the author refuses to simplify Galveston\'s story into a single narrative. This challenges the reader to think in more complex terms — real historical events rarely fit neatly into categories of success or failure, and Galveston embodies both simultaneously.'}
  ]},
  {id:'NF03',title:'The Octopus Problem',type:'nonfiction',source:'Original passage — science / animal intelligence',
   text:'In 2016, an octopus named Inky made headlines around the world by escaping from the National Aquarium of New Zealand. During the night, Inky pushed the lid off his tank, slid across the floor of the aquarium, squeezed his football-sized body through a narrow drain pipe, and dropped into the ocean. When staff arrived the next morning, all they found was a trail of water leading from the tank to the drain. Inky was gone.\n\nThe story delighted the public, but it didn\'t surprise marine biologists. Octopuses are widely considered to be the most intelligent invertebrates on Earth, and their ability to solve problems, use tools, and escape from enclosures is well documented. In laboratories, they have been observed unscrewing jars from the inside to reach food, navigating complex mazes after a single attempt, and even squirting water at lights to short-circuit them — apparently because the brightness annoyed them.\n\nWhat makes octopus intelligence so fascinating to scientists is that it evolved entirely separately from our own. Humans and octopuses share a common ancestor that lived roughly 500 million years ago — a simple, worm-like creature with no brain to speak of. Since then, intelligence has evolved along two completely independent paths. Our brains are centralised: a single mass of neurons inside our skulls controls everything we think and do. An octopus\'s nervous system, by contrast, is radically distributed. Nearly two-thirds of its neurons are located not in its head but in its eight arms, meaning each arm can taste, touch, and make decisions semi-independently.\n\nThis raises a question that philosophers and scientists have debated for decades: what does it feel like to be an octopus? When an arm reaches into a crevice to investigate a shape, is the arm \'deciding\' to do this, or is the central brain issuing instructions? When an octopus changes colour to match its surroundings — a process that takes less than a second — is it making a conscious choice, or is it a reflex? The honest answer is that we do not yet know.\n\nWhat we do know is that octopuses display behaviours that, in any other context, we would call curious, playful, and even mischievous. They have been seen pulling apart Lego structures, rearranging the objects in their tanks, and — in one famous case — repeatedly dismantling a water filtration system until the aquarium gave up and moved the octopus to a different tank.\n\nInky\'s escape was remarkable, but it was not an accident. It required recognising an opportunity, formulating a plan, and executing it with precision — all without any teaching or prior experience. Whether we choose to call that \'intelligence\' or something else, it is clear that the octopus possesses a kind of mind that challenges everything we thought we knew about what it means to think.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['Octopuses are remarkably intelligent creatures whose entirely separate evolutionary path to intelligence challenges our understanding of what it means to think.','Octopuses have developed remarkable camouflage abilities that allow them to change colour instantly, which scientists believe is the primary evidence of their superior intelligence compared to all other marine animals.','The passage argues that octopus intelligence is primarily demonstrated through their escape abilities, and that Inky\'s story was the most significant event in marine biology research.','Octopuses possess a centralised brain similar to humans but with significantly more neurons, which explains why they can perform complex tasks such as unscrewing jars and navigating mazes.'],c:0,e:'The passage uses Inky\'s escape as a hook but its real argument is deeper: octopus intelligence evolved independently from ours, is structured differently (distributed vs centralised), and raises philosophical questions about consciousness. The main idea is about challenging assumptions, not just cataloguing clever behaviour.'},
      {q:'Why does the author begin with Inky\'s escape story before moving to scientific analysis?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['To argue that aquariums are failing in their duty of care, since Inky\'s escape is presented as evidence of institutional negligence rather than animal intelligence.','Because Inky\'s escape is the passage\'s central scientific argument, and the later paragraphs about neurons and consciousness merely provide background context for this single event.','Because the passage is structured chronologically, beginning with the most recent event in 2016 and then moving backwards through the history of octopus research.','The anecdote hooks the reader with a dramatic, entertaining story before introducing the more complex scientific content — it makes abstract ideas about intelligence and evolution feel concrete and accessible.'],c:3,e:'Starting with Inky\'s escape is a classic non-fiction technique: open with a compelling story, then zoom out to the bigger picture. The escape is vivid and memorable, which draws the reader in before the passage introduces more complex ideas about neuron distribution and consciousness.'},
      {q:'The passage states that \'the honest answer is that we do not yet know\' whether octopuses make conscious choices. Why does the author include this admission?',skill:'Analyse informational texts',opts:['To undermine the earlier evidence of octopus intelligence by conceding that none of the observed behaviours can be scientifically verified as genuine cognition.','Because the author is transitioning from a scientific perspective to a philosophical one, signalling that the passage will abandon factual evidence in favour of personal speculation from this point onward.','To demonstrate intellectual honesty — admitting the limits of current knowledge makes the passage more trustworthy and shows that science is an ongoing process, not a set of fixed answers.','To suggest that the distributed nervous system prevents octopuses from having true consciousness, since their neurons are spread across their arms rather than centralised in a brain.'],c:2,e:'Admitting uncertainty is a strength, not a weakness. By saying \'we do not yet know\', the author shows that the question of octopus consciousness is genuinely open — which makes it more interesting, not less. It also models good scientific thinking: acknowledging what you don\'t know is as important as stating what you do.'},
      {q:'What is the author\'s primary purpose in writing this passage?',skill:'Author\'s purpose',opts:['To inform the reader about octopus intelligence and explore how it challenges human assumptions about what it means to think.','To persuade the reader to stop eating octopus — the examples of Inky\'s escape and the Lego experiments are chosen to create emotional attachment so readers will feel guilty about consuming octopus.','To argue that aquariums are cruel and should be banned — Inky\'s escape and the repeated dismantling of the filtration system are presented as evidence that captive octopuses suffer in artificial environments.','To entertain the reader with a funny story about an escaping octopus — the passage is primarily a humorous anecdote, and the paragraphs about neurons and consciousness are secondary padding around Inky\'s adventure.'],c:0,e:'While the passage is entertaining (Inky\'s escape, the Lego story), its primary purpose is to inform and explore. It explains octopus intelligence, describes how it differs from human intelligence, and raises philosophical questions. The entertaining examples serve the informational purpose, not the other way around.'},
      {q:'The final sentence says Inky\'s escape \'required recognising an opportunity, formulating a plan, and executing it with precision\'. Why does the author use these particular words?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['To suggest that Inky had been trained by the aquarium staff — the words \'recognising,\' \'formulating,\' and \'executing\' imply a taught sequence of steps rather than independent problem-solving by the octopus.','These words are scientific terms that only marine biologists would understand — the technical vocabulary signals that the passage is aimed at specialist readers rather than a general Year 7 audience.','To make the escape sound less impressive than it actually was — by breaking the action into three clinical steps, the author reduces Inky\'s dramatic nighttime escape to a routine series of mechanical movements.','These are words we normally associate with human strategic thinking — by applying them to an octopus, the author deliberately blurs the line between human and animal intelligence, reinforcing the passage\'s argument.'],c:3,e:'\'Recognising\', \'formulating\', and \'executing\' are words from human project management and strategy. Applying them to an octopus is a deliberate rhetorical choice — it forces the reader to either accept that the octopus is thinking strategically or explain why these words shouldn\'t apply. Either way, it challenges the human-animal intelligence boundary.'},
      {q:'What is the overall tone of this passage, and how does the author achieve it?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Condescending — the author talks down to the reader as though they know nothing about animals, over-explaining basic concepts like what an invertebrate is and how neurons work in a patronising manner.','Dry and uninterested — the author presents the information without any engagement, listing Inky\'s escape, the jar experiments, and the Lego incidents as flat data points with no sense of amazement.','Wonder mixed with intellectual humility — the author conveys genuine amazement at octopus abilities while honestly acknowledging the limits of scientific understanding, creating a tone that is both enthusiastic and carefully measured.','Frightened and alarmed — the author is worried that octopuses might be dangerous to humans, using examples of short-circuiting lights and dismantling filtration systems to suggest octopuses are destructive and threatening.'],c:2,e:'The tone blends fascination (the author\'s evident amazement at the octopus\'s abilities) with honesty (\'the honest answer is that we do not yet know\'). This combination makes the passage feel both exciting and trustworthy. The author is clearly captivated by the subject but never overclaims, which creates a tone of informed wonder rather than sensationalism.'},
      {q:'Why does the author describe the common ancestor of humans and octopuses as \'a simple, worm-like creature with no brain to speak of\'?',skill:'Inference',opts:['To insult worms and suggest they are unintelligent creatures — the dismissive phrase \'no brain to speak of\' establishes a hierarchy in which worms are inferior to both humans and octopuses.','To prove that brains are not necessary for survival — the fact that the worm-like ancestor thrived without a brain suggests that intelligence is an evolutionary luxury rather than a requirement.','To argue that humans are descended from octopuses — the shared common ancestor 500 million years ago is presented as evidence that the human brain evolved directly from the octopus\'s distributed nervous system.','To emphasise how extraordinary it is that intelligence evolved independently in both lineages — starting from a brainless ancestor makes the parallel development of complex cognition in octopuses seem even more remarkable.'],c:3,e:'By describing the shared ancestor as brainless and worm-like, the author establishes a starting point of zero intelligence. This makes the endpoint — two radically different but sophisticated forms of intelligence — feel astonishing. The vast evolutionary distance (500 million years, two completely separate paths) amplifies the wonder of convergent intelligence.'},
      {q:'The passage mentions octopuses \'squirting water at lights to short-circuit them — apparently because the brightness annoyed them.\' What literary device is at work, and what effect does it create?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['Anthropomorphism and bathos — attributing human-like annoyance to an octopus and describing a dramatic action (destroying equipment) for a mundane reason (being annoyed by light) creates humour that also demonstrates the octopus\'s problem-solving ability.','Hyperbole, because octopuses cannot actually squirt water with enough force to damage electrical equipment — the author exaggerates a minor splashing behaviour to make the anecdote more entertaining.','Alliteration, because the repeated \'s\' sounds in \'squirting,\' \'short-circuit,\' and \'lights\' create a hissing effect that mimics the sound of water hitting electrical equipment.','Foreshadowing, because it hints that Inky will later escape by exploiting a weakness in the aquarium\'s plumbing — the water-squirting behaviour previews the octopus\'s ability to manipulate its environment.'],c:0,e:'The anecdote works on two levels. It is funny because the octopus\'s motivation (annoyance at brightness) is absurdly relatable and human. But it also demonstrates sophisticated behaviour: identifying a cause (the light), devising a solution (squirting water), and executing it effectively. The humour draws the reader in while the underlying point — octopuses solve problems creatively — advances the passage\'s argument.'},
      {q:'What does the passage imply about why the question \'what does it feel like to be an octopus?\' is particularly difficult to answer?',skill:'Theme',opts:['Because octopus cognition is so fundamentally different from human cognition — with distributed neurons and semi-independent arms — that human frameworks for understanding consciousness may simply not apply, making empathy across species nearly impossible.','Because octopuses refuse to cooperate with scientists during experiments — the passage\'s examples of dismantling filtration systems and short-circuiting lights show that octopuses actively resist laboratory testing.','Because octopuses do not have any feelings or experiences at all — their distributed nervous system means each arm acts independently without any central awareness, making consciousness biologically impossible.','Because the question is not actually interesting and no scientist has tried to answer it — the passage mentions the debate only briefly before moving on to more concrete examples of octopus behaviour.'],c:0,e:'The passage explains that octopus intelligence is structured completely differently from ours — two-thirds of neurons in the arms, not the brain. This means our human experience of centralised consciousness may be irrelevant to understanding octopus experience. The difficulty is not lack of data but a fundamental mismatch between our cognitive architecture and theirs, making the philosophical question genuinely hard.'},
      {q:'How does the final paragraph\'s description of Inky\'s escape differ from the opening paragraph\'s description, and why?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['The two descriptions are identical and there is no difference between them — both paragraphs describe Inky pushing the lid off the tank, sliding across the floor, and squeezing through the drain pipe in the same sequence.','The final paragraph describes a completely different escape by a different octopus — the reference to \'recognising an opportunity\' concerns a second, unnamed octopus from the laboratory experiments in paragraph two.','The final paragraph reveals that Inky\'s escape was actually an accident — the phrase \'without any teaching or prior experience\' suggests the escape was a lucky coincidence rather than a planned action.','The opening describes the escape as a dramatic narrative event; the closing reframes it as evidence of cognitive abilities (recognising, formulating, executing) — this shift shows how the intervening paragraphs have changed the reader\'s understanding of what the escape means.'],c:3,e:'In the opening, Inky\'s escape reads as an entertaining anecdote. By the final paragraph, after learning about distributed neurons, independent arms, and the philosophical questions about consciousness, the same event is presented in cognitive terms. The reader now understands the escape as evidence of genuine intelligence rather than a quirky news story. The passage has transformed how we interpret the same event.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about why aquarium staff found Inky\'s escape unsurprising, based on the evidence in paragraph two?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['Inky had escaped many times before and was always recaptured — the trail of water from the tank to the drain was a familiar sight for staff, who had previously retrieved Inky from the aquarium floor.','The staff did not care about the aquarium animals and were negligent — their failure to secure the tank lid properly shows a lack of professionalism that the author criticises by describing the easy escape route.','The staff had deliberately helped Inky escape as part of an experiment — they left the tank lid loose and the drain pipe accessible to test whether Inky could navigate the route to the ocean.','Marine biologists have extensive experience with octopus escapes and problem-solving behaviour — the examples of unscrewing jars, navigating mazes, and short-circuiting lights suggest this kind of behaviour is well-documented and expected by professionals who work with octopuses.'],c:3,e:'Paragraph two states that octopus escape ability is \'well documented\' and provides multiple examples of problem-solving in labs. From this, we can infer that marine biologists already knew octopuses were capable of such feats. The public was surprised because they lacked this knowledge; the scientists were not because Inky\'s behaviour was consistent with decades of observed octopus intelligence.'},
      {q:'The passage says octopus behaviours would, \'in any other context\', be called \'curious, playful, and even mischievous\'. Why does the author add the qualifier \'in any other context\'?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['To highlight the scientific reluctance to attribute human emotional qualities to animals — the qualifier acknowledges that these words carry assumptions about consciousness that may not apply to a creature with such a different neurological structure.','To imply that the behaviours are not real and have been fabricated by researchers — the qualifier \'in any other context\' suggests the Lego and filtration system anecdotes are exaggerated or invented to attract media attention.','To suggest that octopuses are never actually playful or curious — the qualifier indicates that what looks like play is merely a survival reflex, and the distributed nervous system makes genuine curiosity neurologically impossible.','To argue that scientists should never use emotional language under any circumstances — the author believes terms like \'mischievous\' and \'playful\' have no place in marine biology and should be replaced with neutral terminology.'],c:0,e:'The phrase \'in any other context\' flags a scientific tension. If a dog dismantled a toy, we would call it playful without hesitation. With an octopus, whose mind is radically different, scientists hesitate because the same word might imply a conscious experience the octopus does not have. The qualifier shows the author is aware of this philosophical problem and respects it, even while describing behaviours that certainly look playful.'}
  ]},
  {id:'NF04',title:'Why Do We Dream?',type:'nonfiction',source:'Original passage — neuroscience / psychology / sleep',
   text:'Every night, something extraordinary happens inside your skull. As you sleep, your brain — which has spent the day processing conversations, lessons, meals, arguments, and thousands of other experiences — begins to replay, reorganise, and sometimes wildly reimagine the events of your waking life. You dream. And despite centuries of curiosity, scientists still cannot fully agree on why.\n\nThe ancient Egyptians believed dreams were messages from the gods. The Greeks thought they were visits to a shadow world that existed alongside the real one. Sigmund Freud, the father of psychoanalysis, argued in 1899 that dreams were disguised expressions of our deepest, most forbidden desires — a theory that fascinated the public but has largely fallen out of favour with modern neuroscientists, who consider it untestable and overly focused on hidden meaning.\n\nToday, the leading scientific theories are more practical. The most widely accepted is the memory consolidation hypothesis: while you sleep, your brain sorts through the day\'s experiences, decides what to keep and what to discard, and transfers important information from short-term to long-term memory. Dreams, according to this theory, are a by-product of that sorting process — the flickering images you see are your brain filing its paperwork.\n\nA second theory, proposed by neuroscientist Antti Revonsuo, suggests that dreams serve an evolutionary purpose: they allow us to rehearse threatening situations in a safe environment. If your ancestors dreamed about being chased by a predator, they were better prepared to respond if it actually happened. This would explain why so many dreams involve anxiety, danger, or being late for something important — your brain is running safety drills.\n\nA third theory takes a different approach entirely. The activation-synthesis hypothesis, developed by Allan Hobson and Robert McCarley, argues that dreams have no purpose at all. During sleep, random electrical signals fire across the brain, and the conscious mind — which cannot tolerate randomness — weaves these signals into a story. Dreams, in this view, are the brain\'s attempt to make sense of meaningless noise. It is a creative act, but not a meaningful one.\n\nSo which theory is correct? The frustrating answer is that we don\'t know — and it\'s possible that all three are partly right. Dreams may consolidate memories and rehearse threats and create narratives from random signals, depending on the stage of sleep and the individual dreamer. What is certain is that dreaming is universal: every human being does it, every night, whether they remember it or not. Even babies in the womb show brain activity consistent with dreaming.\n\nWhatever their purpose, dreams remain one of the last great mysteries of the human mind — a nightly reminder that the organ we understand least in the entire body is the one sitting right between our ears.',
   questions:[
      {q:'How is this passage primarily structured?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['Problem and solution — the passage identifies a problem with dreaming and proposes how to fix it.','Compare and contrast — three competing scientific theories are presented and evaluated, with a balanced conclusion acknowledging uncertainty.','Chronological order — the passage describes the history of dreaming from ancient times to today.','Persuasive argument — the author argues that one specific theory is correct.'],c:1,e:'The passage presents three theories (memory consolidation, threat rehearsal, activation-synthesis), explains each one, then offers a balanced conclusion that all three might be partly correct. This compare-and-contrast structure allows the reader to weigh the evidence themselves.'},
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['Dreams have no purpose at all and are completely random — the activation-synthesis hypothesis proposed by Hobson and McCarley is the only valid theory discussed in the passage.','The memory consolidation hypothesis has been proven correct and the other theories are wrong — the passage dismisses both Revonsuo\'s threat rehearsal theory and the activation-synthesis hypothesis as outdated.','Scientists have proven that dreams are messages from the gods — the passage states that modern neuroscientists have confirmed the ancient Egyptian belief about divine communication during sleep.','Despite centuries of study, scientists cannot fully explain why we dream — several competing theories exist, each with strengths, and the truth may involve a combination of all of them.'],c:3,e:'The passage presents multiple theories without declaring a winner. The main idea is captured in the conclusion: \'it\'s possible that all three are partly right\'. The passage is about the complexity and uncertainty of dream science, not about one correct answer.'},
      {q:'The passage mentions Freud\'s theory but says it has \'largely fallen out of favour\'. Why does the author include a discredited theory?',skill:'Analyse informational texts',opts:['Because the author agrees with Freud and wants to promote his ideas — the passage presents Freud\'s theory of disguised desires as the most scientifically rigorous of all the dream theories discussed.','To establish Freud\'s psychoanalytic approach as the foundation that all three modern theories directly build upon, since memory consolidation and threat rehearsal both derive from his concept of hidden desires.','To show how scientific understanding evolves — including a historically influential but now rejected theory demonstrates that ideas are tested and revised over time.','Because Freud\'s theory is the most popular one among modern neuroscientists, who still rely on his concept of forbidden desires to explain why dreams involve anxiety, danger, and being late.'],c:2,e:'Including Freud\'s theory serves a structural purpose: it shows how dream science has progressed from mystical and psychological interpretations to neuroscience-based ones. By noting it has \'fallen out of favour\', the author demonstrates that scientific understanding changes — the current theories may also be revised.'},
      {q:'What is the author\'s primary purpose in this passage?',skill:'Author\'s purpose',opts:['To argue that neuroscience is more important than all other sciences.','To inform the reader about different scientific theories of dreaming and honestly present the current state of uncertainty.','To persuade the reader that dreaming is dangerous and should be prevented.','To entertain the reader with descriptions of funny dreams.'],c:1,e:'The passage is informational: it explains three theories, provides evidence for each, and presents a balanced conclusion. The author does not advocate for one theory. The honest acknowledgement of uncertainty (\'the frustrating answer is that we don\'t know\') reinforces the informational rather than persuasive purpose.'},
      {q:'Dreams are described as \'your brain filing its paperwork\' in the memory consolidation theory. What does this metaphor achieve?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['It means that only people who work in offices have dreams — the metaphor limits the memory consolidation theory to people who do administrative work, excluding children and the unemployed.','It suggests that dreaming is boring and not worth studying — by comparing it to mundane paperwork, the author implies that Hobson and McCarley\'s activation-synthesis theory is more exciting and worthy of attention.','It proves that the brain literally contains paper files and filing cabinets — the passage uses this as scientific evidence that short-term and long-term memory are stored in physical folders inside the skull.','It makes an abstract neuroscience concept accessible and relatable — by comparing memory sorting to a mundane office task, the author helps the reader understand a complex process through a familiar image.'],c:3,e:'\'Filing paperwork\' is deliberately ordinary — that\'s the point. By comparing a mysterious process (memory consolidation during sleep) to something mundane and familiar, the author makes the science accessible. The metaphor also subtly supports the theory\'s claim: dreams aren\'t mystical, they\'re the brain doing routine administrative work.'},
      {q:'What tone does the author establish in the opening paragraph, and how does the word \'extraordinary\' contribute to it?',skill:'Tone',opts:['A tone of fear and alarm about the dangers of sleeping — the phrase \'something extraordinary happens inside your skull\' warns the reader that the brain\'s nightly activity could be harmful or uncontrollable.','A clinical, detached tone that avoids any emotional engagement with the subject — the opening relies on technical terminology like \'processing\' and \'reorganise\' to maintain scientific distance from the reader.','A tone of accessible wonder — \'extraordinary\' signals that what happens during sleep is remarkable, inviting the reader to see a familiar nightly experience as something surprising and worthy of investigation.','A humorous tone that treats dreaming as a joke — the list of \'conversations, lessons, meals, arguments\' is meant to be comedic, mocking the triviality of the experiences the brain processes each day.'],c:2,e:'The opening paragraph transforms something everyone does (sleeping) into something worth marvelling at. The word \'extraordinary\' is the key signal: it tells the reader that the passage will reveal the remarkable hidden in the routine. This creates an inviting, curious tone that draws the reader in before the more complex scientific theories are introduced.'},
      {q:'Why does the author present the three modern theories in a specific order — memory consolidation, threat rehearsal, then activation-synthesis?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['They move from the most purposeful theory (dreams serve memory) to the least purposeful (dreams are meaningless noise) — this ordering creates a deliberate progression that challenges the reader\'s assumptions about whether dreams have meaning.','They are ordered chronologically by when each theory was first proposed — memory consolidation was the earliest scientific theory, followed by Revonsuo\'s threat rehearsal, and finally the most recent activation-synthesis model.','The theories are presented in random order with no deliberate structure — the author could have placed the activation-synthesis hypothesis first and the memory consolidation theory last without affecting the passage\'s argument.','The author presents their favourite theory first and the worst theory last — the passage clearly endorses memory consolidation over activation-synthesis by placing it in the most prominent opening position.'],c:0,e:'The three theories form a spectrum of purpose: dreams consolidate memories (highly purposeful), dreams rehearse threats (purposeful but less targeted), dreams are random noise given false meaning (no purpose). By ordering them this way, the author takes the reader on a journey from \'dreams matter\' to \'dreams are meaningless,\' creating intellectual tension that the balanced conclusion must resolve.'},
      {q:'What does the passage\'s mention that \'even babies in the womb show brain activity consistent with dreaming\' add to the overall argument?',skill:'Inference',opts:['It strengthens the claim that dreaming is biologically fundamental rather than culturally learned — if organisms dream before birth, before having experiences to consolidate or threats to rehearse, it suggests dreaming is hardwired into human development.','It suggests that babies dream about being born — since the womb is the only environment they know, their brain activity must involve rehearsing the threat of delivery, confirming Revonsuo\'s evolutionary theory.','It proves that the memory consolidation theory is correct because babies have memories — their brains must be sorting prenatal experiences like sounds and movement into long-term storage while still in the womb.','It is an irrelevant detail that does not connect to the rest of the passage — the mention of babies contradicts all three theories equally and serves only as a curiosity unrelated to the main argument.'],c:0,e:'This detail is strategically placed in the conclusion. If babies dream in the womb — before having memories to consolidate or threats to rehearse — it complicates the first two theories and lends some support to the idea that dreaming might be a basic neurological process (closer to the activation-synthesis view). It also reinforces the passage\'s message that dreaming is truly universal.'},
      {q:'How does the author use Freud\'s theory to develop a theme about the nature of scientific progress?',skill:'Theme',opts:['By suggesting that Freud\'s theory is still the most accurate explanation of dreams — the passage implies that his concept of disguised forbidden desires remains the foundation of modern neuroscience research.','By proving that psychoanalysis and neuroscience are identical disciplines — the passage equates Freud\'s methods with those of Hobson and McCarley, showing they reach the same conclusions about random brain signals.','By arguing that Freud was completely wrong about everything and should be forgotten — the passage dismisses his entire career as worthless because modern neuroscientists consider his dream theory untestable.','By showing how an influential theory can \'fall out of favour\' when it proves untestable, the author illustrates that scientific progress involves discarding ideas that cannot be rigorously tested — even popular ones from respected figures.'],c:3,e:'Freud\'s theory is included not for its content but for what its rejection teaches about science. It was hugely popular and culturally influential, yet modern scientists consider it \'untestable.\' This demonstrates a key theme: in science, testability matters more than popularity or elegance. The passage uses Freud as a stepping stone to show how dream science has matured from speculation to evidence-based inquiry.'},
      {q:'The author calls the activation-synthesis hypothesis \'a creative act, but not a meaningful one\'. What makes this phrasing effective?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['It is a direct quote from Hobson and McCarley\'s original research paper — the author reproduces their exact academic phrasing to give scientific authority to the activation-synthesis hypothesis.','It is a contradiction that makes no logical sense — calling something both creative and not meaningful is grammatically incoherent, revealing the weakness of the activation-synthesis hypothesis itself.','The juxtaposition of \'creative\' and \'not meaningful\' is surprising and thought-provoking — it challenges the assumption that creativity implies purpose, forcing the reader to reconsider what it means for the brain to construct narratives.','It proves the author believes dreams are never creative — the phrase dismisses the narrative-building function of the brain entirely, siding with the memory consolidation theory over activation-synthesis.'],c:2,e:'The phrase is an oxymoron-like pairing that captures the theory\'s core claim perfectly. We usually associate creativity with intention and meaning, but the activation-synthesis hypothesis says the brain creates dream narratives without any purpose — pure pattern-making from noise. The phrasing is memorable because it makes the reader pause and reconsider the relationship between creativity and meaning.'},
      {q:'From what point of view is the passage written, and how does the use of \'you\' and \'your\' affect the reader\'s engagement?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['Stream of consciousness from inside a dreaming brain — the passage replicates the random, disconnected quality of dreams by jumping between theories without logical transitions, mimicking the activation-synthesis process.','Strict first person from a neuroscientist\'s perspective — the narrator uses \'I\' and \'my\' to describe their own research into memory consolidation and personal disagreements with Freud\'s methods.','Third person with no direct address to the reader at all — the passage maintains objective distance by referring only to \'scientists\' and \'researchers\' without ever using the words \'you\' or \'your\'.','Second person address mixed with third-person exposition — the \'you\' and \'your\' make the reader a participant in the subject matter, since everyone dreams, creating personal investment in the scientific theories being discussed.'],c:3,e:'The passage opens with \'every night, something extraordinary happens inside your skull\' and continues using \'you\' and \'your\' throughout. This is effective because dreaming is universal — every reader does it. The second-person address transforms the passage from an abstract science article into something personally relevant: these theories are about what happens inside your own head tonight.'},
      {q:'The final sentence describes the brain as \'the organ we understand least in the entire body\' sitting \'right between our ears\'. What is the effect of this closing image?',skill:'Author\'s purpose & tone',opts:['It is a factual statement about brain location with no rhetorical effect — the author is simply reminding the reader of basic anatomy after a passage that might have caused confusion about where the brain is situated.','It argues that neuroscience funding should be increased immediately — by calling the brain the least understood organ, the author implies that more research money is needed to resolve the debate between the three dream theories.','It creates an ironic contrast between physical proximity and intellectual distance — the brain is the closest organ to us yet the most mysterious, ending the passage on a note of humility that reinforces the theme of scientific uncertainty.','It suggests that ears are more important than brains for understanding dreams — the phrase \'between our ears\' shifts attention to hearing, implying that auditory processing during sleep is the key to understanding why we dream.'],c:2,e:'The closing image is carefully crafted. \'Right between our ears\' emphasises intimacy — the brain is literally inside us. Yet it remains the least understood organ. This ironic juxtaposition leaves the reader with a sense of wonder and humility: the greatest mystery in science is not in outer space but inside our own heads. It perfectly encapsulates the passage\'s tone of informed curiosity tempered by honest uncertainty.'}
  ]},
  {id:'F18',title:'Grandmother\'s Kitchen',type:'fiction',source:'Original passage — family / heritage / food / culture',
   text:'The kitchen smelled of cinnamon and cardamom and something else — something Leila could never quite name but which she associated entirely with her grandmother. It was the smell of slow cooking, of patience, of a woman who believed that every important conversation in life should happen over food.\n\nNani was making biryani. She had been making it since six o\'clock that morning, and it was now half past two, and she showed no sign of being anywhere close to finished. The lamb had been marinating overnight in yoghurt and spices. The rice had been soaked, parboiled, and drained. The onions — and there were many onions — had been sliced into translucent half-moons and fried slowly until they turned the deep amber colour that Nani called \'the colour of doing things properly\'.\n\n\'You cannot rush biryani,\' Nani said, for perhaps the fortieth time that day. \'Biryani is not a microwave meal. Biryani is a relationship. You must give it time, or it gives you nothing back.\'\n\nLeila was thirteen and had heard this speech before, but today she was actually listening. She was perched on the kitchen stool with a notebook open on her lap, writing down every step. Not because her teacher had asked her to — this was not homework — but because something had shifted recently. She had noticed, with the quiet alarm that comes when you see something for the first time that has always been there, that Nani was getting older. Her hands, which could still julienne a carrot faster than anyone Leila knew, trembled slightly when she lifted the heavy pot. She forgot words sometimes — not important words, but words nonetheless, gaps in sentences that hadn\'t been there a year ago.\n\nThe recipes were nowhere. They existed only in Nani\'s hands and in her memory, passed down from her own mother in Lahore and her mother before that, each generation adjusting a spice here, a technique there, but never writing any of it down. Cooking, in Nani\'s family, was taught by standing beside someone and watching. But Leila was the only grandchild who stood beside Nani in the kitchen. Her cousins were busy, or uninterested, or lived too far away. If Leila did not write this down, it would disappear.\n\n\'How much turmeric?\' Leila asked, pen ready.\n\nNani held up her hand, fingers pinched together. \'This much.\'\n\n\'Nani, that\'s not a measurement.\'\n\n\'It is the only measurement that matters.\' Nani smiled, and for a moment the tremor in her hands was invisible. \'Your great-grandmother used exactly this much. I watched her do it a thousand times. Now you are watching me.\'\n\nLeila looked at the pinch of turmeric — a tiny heap of bright gold in her grandmother\'s palm. She couldn\'t write down a pinch. But she could remember it. She could remember the colour, the smell, the warmth of the kitchen, the sound of Nani\'s voice. And maybe that was the real recipe — not the ingredients but the memory of learning them.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['Leila is trying to preserve her grandmother\'s recipes — and the cultural heritage they represent — before they are lost, realising that some knowledge can only be passed on through presence and memory.','Leila wants to become a professional chef when she grows up — her decision to write down the biryani recipe in a notebook shows she is building a portfolio of dishes to use in a future restaurant career.','The passage is mainly about how to make biryani correctly — the detailed steps of marinating lamb, parboiling rice, and frying onions to amber form a complete instructional recipe for the reader to follow.','Nani is a bad cook who refuses to follow proper recipes — her reliance on imprecise measurements like \'this much\' shows she lacks the discipline needed for consistent results in the kitchen.'],c:0,e:'The passage builds from a cooking scene to something much deeper: Leila\'s awareness that Nani is ageing, that the recipes exist nowhere but in her memory, and that preserving them requires more than writing — it requires being there. The biryani is the vehicle; the real subject is intergenerational knowledge and its fragility.'},
      {q:'What theme is developed through Nani\'s repeated statement that \'you cannot rush biryani\' and her comparison of it to \'a relationship\'?',skill:'Theme',opts:['The most valuable things in life — food, relationships, cultural knowledge — require patience, time, and presence, and cannot be reduced to quick instructions or shortcuts.','Nani is old-fashioned and does not understand modern cooking — her dismissal of microwave meals and refusal to use precise measurements reveals she has not adapted to contemporary kitchen practices.','Fast food is always unhealthy and should be avoided — Nani\'s comparison of biryani to a microwave meal is a direct criticism of the fast food industry and its effect on family health.','Biryani takes too long to cook and is not worth the effort — the eight-hour cooking time from six o\'clock to half past two demonstrates an impractical process that modern families cannot realistically sustain.'],c:0,e:'Nani\'s comparison of biryani to a relationship extends beyond cooking. The whole passage mirrors this idea: Leila cannot rush learning from Nani, just as Nani cannot rush the biryani. Presence, patience, and time are required for both. The theme connects food preparation to the deeper process of cultural transmission.'},
      {q:'Why does the author include the detail about Nani\'s hands trembling and her forgetting words?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['To create urgency — Nani\'s physical decline makes Leila\'s attempt to record the recipes feel time-sensitive, raising the emotional stakes of the passage.','To prove that Leila is a better cook than her grandmother — Nani\'s trembling hands and forgotten words show her cooking skills are declining, while Leila\'s careful note-taking demonstrates superior precision.','To show that Nani is too old to cook and should stop immediately — the heavy pot she struggles to lift and the gaps in her sentences suggest she is no longer capable of safely preparing meals.','To suggest that Nani has a specific illness that the passage will diagnose — the forgotten words and trembling hands are clinical symptoms that foreshadow a medical revelation later in the story.'],c:0,e:'The trembling hands and forgotten words are subtle but powerful. They signal that Nani\'s knowledge has a time limit — she won\'t always be able to teach. This transforms Leila\'s notebook from a casual project into something urgent and poignant, and explains why she is \'actually listening\' today when she hasn\'t before.'},
      {q:'Nani describes the colour of properly fried onions as \'the colour of doing things properly\'. What does this phrase reveal about her character and philosophy?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['She sees cooking as a moral act — doing things \'properly\' means giving them the time and care they deserve, and the onion colour is physical proof of patience and attention.','She has invented her own colour chart for cooking that she refuses to share — by keeping the exact amber shade secret from Leila, Nani ensures the recipe can never be fully replicated without her presence.','She is obsessed with the colour of food and judges everything by appearance — the passage suggests Nani prioritises how the biryani looks over how it tastes, valuing presentation above flavour.','She thinks golden onions are the only important ingredient in biryani — Nani devotes more attention to frying onions than to the lamb, rice, or spices, suggesting the rest of the dish is secondary to her.'],c:0,e:'Nani links a visual result (amber onions) to a value (doing things properly). This reveals a worldview where craft, patience, and care are inseparable. The phrase also carries gentle humour — it\'s a very Nani way of expressing a deep philosophy through something as ordinary as fried onions.'},
      {q:'How would you describe the tone of the final paragraph?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Angry — Leila is frustrated that Nani won\'t give precise measurements, and her final thought that she \'couldn\'t write down a pinch\' expresses defeat and resentment towards her grandmother\'s stubbornness.','Sad and hopeless — Leila gives up trying to record the recipes because Nani\'s refusal to use standard measurements means the biryani will inevitably be lost when the oral tradition breaks down.','Tender and bittersweet — Leila accepts that some knowledge can\'t be written down, but finds comfort in the idea that memory itself is a form of preservation.','Indifferent — Leila doesn\'t really care about the recipes and only came to the kitchen because she had nothing else to do on a Saturday afternoon, treating the whole experience casually.'],c:2,e:'The final paragraph is gentle and warm. Leila can\'t capture \'a pinch\' on paper, but she realises the recipe is bigger than ingredients — it includes \'the colour, the smell, the warmth of the kitchen, the sound of Nani\'s voice\'. This is bittersweet because it acknowledges loss (the measurements can\'t be written) while finding beauty in what can be kept (the experience of learning).'},
      {q:'From whose point of view is this passage told, and how does that affect the reader\'s experience?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['Second person, addressing the reader directly and instructing them how to cook biryani — the passage uses \'you\' to guide the reader through each step of marinating lamb and frying onions to amber.','Omniscient third person that gives equal access to every character\'s thoughts, including Leila\'s absent cousins — the passage reveals why each cousin is busy or uninterested by describing their individual perspectives.','First person from Nani\'s perspective, which lets us understand why she refuses to write recipes down — Nani narrates her own memories of learning from her mother in Lahore and explains her philosophy directly.','Third-person limited, focused on Leila — this lets the reader share her growing awareness of Nani\'s ageing and the urgency of recording the recipes, while also observing Nani from the outside.'],c:3,e:'The passage is told in third-person limited through Leila\'s eyes. We see Nani\'s trembling hands and forgotten words because Leila notices them. This perspective is crucial: it lets the reader discover the urgency alongside Leila, making her decision to write things down feel personal and earned rather than simply told to us.'},
      {q:'What does the detail that Leila\'s cousins are \'busy, or uninterested, or lived too far away\' add to the passage?',skill:'Inference',opts:['It suggests that the family has had a serious argument and no longer speaks to each other — the cousins\' absence from Nani\'s kitchen signals a rift in the family that has cut off contact between the generations.','It proves that Nani only wants to teach Leila and has rejected the other grandchildren — Nani has deliberately chosen her favourite grandchild and excluded the cousins from learning the family recipes.','It shows that Leila\'s cousins are lazy and ungrateful people who have deliberately turned their backs on their cultural heritage because they find traditional South Asian cooking beneath them.','It implies that Leila is the last link in a chain of oral tradition — without her, generations of culinary knowledge will be lost, which heightens the emotional stakes of her note-taking.'],c:3,e:'The brief mention of the cousins is not a throwaway detail. It tells us that Leila is the sole bridge between Nani\'s knowledge and the future. Each reason listed — busy, uninterested, far away — is ordinary and blameless, which makes the potential loss feel accidental rather than dramatic, and therefore more realistic and poignant.'},
      {q:'Nani compares biryani to a relationship: \'You must give it time, or it gives you nothing back.\' What literary device is this, and why is it effective?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['It is alliteration because several words begin with the same letter — the repeated \'b\' sounds in \'biryani,\' \'back,\' and \'but\' create a rhythmic pattern that makes Nani\'s speech memorable and poetic.','It is onomatopoeia because it imitates the sound of cooking — the phrase \'gives you nothing back\' echoes the bubbling and sputtering sounds of biryani being prepared in a heavy pot.','It is personification — giving the biryani human qualities of reciprocity — which works because it mirrors the passage\'s deeper message that meaningful connections (between people, between generations) require patience and investment.','It is hyperbole because biryani cannot literally give anything back — Nani is wildly exaggerating for comic effect, and the comparison to a relationship is not meant to be taken seriously at all.'],c:2,e:'By saying biryani \'gives you nothing back\' if you rush it, Nani personifies the dish as a partner in a relationship. This is effective because the passage itself is about a relationship — between Leila and Nani — that also requires time and presence to yield its rewards. The cooking metaphor and the family bond reinforce each other.'},
      {q:'Why does the author specify that Leila\'s notebook is \'not homework\' but her own decision?',skill:'Author\'s purpose & tone',opts:['To indicate that cooking is never taught in British schools — the author is criticising the national curriculum for failing to include South Asian recipes and oral traditions in food technology lessons.','To show that Leila\'s motivation is personal and emotional rather than external — she is preserving heritage because she understands its fragility, not because she has been told to, which makes her actions more meaningful.','To suggest that Leila\'s school does not value cultural traditions — the distinction between homework and personal choice implies her teachers would not consider Nani\'s biryani recipe academically worthwhile.','To prove that Leila is a rebellious student who refuses to do actual homework — she is in the kitchen writing about biryani instead of completing school assignments, showing her defiant attitude.'],c:1,e:'The clarification that this is not homework establishes Leila\'s agency. She has chosen to record the recipes out of love and a growing awareness of mortality. This makes the scene more powerful — a thirteen-year-old independently recognising the importance of cultural preservation carries more emotional weight than a school assignment would.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about the family\'s cultural background from details in the passage?',skill:'Inference',opts:['The family recently moved to the UK and has no established cultural identity — Nani\'s reliance on oral tradition and imprecise measurements suggests the family has not yet adapted to British cooking culture.','The family is French, as biryani is a traditional French dish — Nani\'s use of cardamom and yoghurt marinades reflects classic French culinary techniques passed down through generations in Lahore.','The family has South Asian heritage, likely Pakistani — evidenced by the name \'Nani\' (Urdu for maternal grandmother), biryani, za\'atar-adjacent spice use, the mention of Lahore, and the oral cooking tradition.','Nothing about the family\'s background can be determined from the passage — the terms \'Nani,\' \'biryani,\' and \'Lahore\' are too ambiguous to connect to any specific cultural or national identity.'],c:2,e:'Multiple details point to South Asian, specifically Pakistani, heritage: \'Nani\' is the Urdu word for maternal grandmother, Lahore is a major city in Pakistan, and the oral tradition of recipe transmission is common in South Asian families. These details are woven in naturally, building a rich cultural context without exposition.'},
      {q:'How does the structure of the passage mirror its theme about the transmission of knowledge?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['The passage is structured as a debate between Leila and Nani about modern versus traditional cooking — Leila argues for precise measurements while Nani defends intuition, and neither character concedes ground.','The passage moves from the sensory (smells, colours, sounds) to the emotional (Leila noticing Nani ageing) to the philosophical (realising memory itself is the recipe) — mirroring how cooking knowledge deepens from technique to meaning across generations.','The passage alternates between past and present tense to show the difference between Nani\'s memories of Lahore and the current moment in the kitchen, creating two distinct timelines that run in parallel.','The passage is structured as a recipe with numbered steps for making biryani — the marinating, parboiling, and frying stages are presented in sequential order so the reader could replicate the dish at home.'],c:1,e:'The passage begins with concrete sensory details (cinnamon, cardamom, amber onions), then introduces emotional tension (trembling hands, forgotten words), and ends with a philosophical realisation (the recipe is the memory, not the measurements). This deepening structure mirrors how knowledge is passed between generations — starting with the practical and becoming something richer.'},
      {q:'Leila notices Nani\'s ageing \'with the quiet alarm that comes when you see something for the first time that has always been there\'. What does this phrase reveal about Leila\'s character development?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['It suggests Leila is a very anxious person who worries about everything — her \'quiet alarm\' at Nani\'s ageing is part of a broader pattern of anxiety that also explains why she obsessively writes in her notebook.','It shows that Leila has never paid attention to Nani before and does not care about her — the fact that she only now notices the trembling hands proves she has been ignoring her grandmother for years.','It reveals that Nani has been hiding a serious illness from the family — the trembling hands and forgotten words are symptoms Nani has deliberately concealed, and Leila is the first to uncover the truth.','It shows Leila transitioning from childhood obliviousness to a more mature awareness — she is beginning to see her grandmother not just as a permanent fixture but as a mortal person, which drives her urgency to preserve the recipes.'],c:3,e:'This moment is a turning point in Leila\'s characterisation. The phrase \'quiet alarm\' captures the specific feeling of realising something gradually obvious — Nani has always been ageing, but Leila is only now seeing it. This shift from taking Nani for granted to actively valuing her knowledge marks Leila\'s growth from passive grandchild to active preserver of heritage.'}
  ]},
  {id:'F19',title:'The Mountain Path',type:'fiction',source:'Original passage — hiking / fear of heights / trust',
   text:'The path was no wider than a dinner plate, and it clung to the side of the mountain like a scar. To the left, the rock face rose vertically, grey and damp and streaked with moss. To the right — and this was the part that made Ava\'s legs feel like they were made of water — there was nothing. Just air. A sheer drop of two hundred metres to the valley floor, where a river wound through the trees like a thin silver thread.\n\n\'Don\'t look down,\' said her father, who was three metres ahead and moving with the easy confidence of someone who had done this walk a dozen times. \'Look at your feet. One step at a time.\'\n\nAva did not find this advice helpful. She was already looking at her feet, because looking anywhere else made the world tilt and her stomach rise. The problem was that her feet were on a narrow strip of loose gravel on the edge of a cliff, and looking at them only reminded her of this fact.\n\nShe had agreed to the hike because her father had described it as \'a gentle walk with a couple of interesting sections\'. He had not mentioned that one of these \'interesting sections\' would be a ledge barely wide enough for both of her shoes placed side by side. When she pointed this out, he had laughed and said, \'The exposure looks worse than it is.\' Ava had Googled \'exposure\' later and discovered it was a climbing term meaning \'the feeling of being very high up with nothing between you and a long fall\'. She was not reassured.\n\nBut she kept walking. Not because she was brave — she felt about as brave as a mouse on a motorway — but because stopping was worse. Stopping meant standing still on the ledge, which meant thinking about the ledge, which meant imagining all the ways a person could fall off a ledge. Forward was the only direction that led to wider ground.\n\nHer father reached a broader section and turned to wait. He did not hold out his hand — he knew she would have refused it, because accepting help on a mountain felt like admitting something she wasn\'t ready to admit. Instead he just stood there, solid and patient, the way a lighthouse stands on a cliff: not doing anything dramatic, just being visible.\n\nAva reached him. Her hands were shaking. Her jaw ached from clenching.\n\n\'You\'re doing brilliantly,\' he said.\n\n\'I hate you,\' she said.\n\nHe smiled. \'I know. But look.\' He turned her gently by the shoulders, and for the first time, Ava saw the view. The valley spread below them like an enormous green quilt, patched with fields and stitched with hedgerows, and beyond it, range after range of mountains dissolving into blue haze.\n\nAva stared. The fear was still there. But now there was something else beside it, something larger.\n\n\'Oh,\' she said quietly. And that was enough.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What theme does this passage develop?',skill:'Theme',opts:['Fear does not have to be conquered to be overcome — you can move forward while still being afraid, and the reward can exist alongside the fear rather than replacing it.','Fathers should not take their children hiking without proper safety equipment — the narrow ledge, loose gravel, and two-hundred-metre drop show that Ava\'s father has recklessly endangered his daughter\'s life.','Mountains are too dangerous for children and families should avoid them — Ava\'s shaking hands, clenched jaw, and water-like legs demonstrate that the hike has caused her genuine physical and psychological harm.','Ava is a naturally brave person who enjoys extreme sports — she agreed to the hike eagerly and her comparison of herself to a mouse on a motorway is playful self-deprecation rather than genuine fear.'],c:0,e:'Ava never stops being afraid — her hands shake, her jaw aches, and \'the fear was still there\' even at the end. But she moves forward anyway, and discovers that beauty can coexist with fear rather than requiring its absence. The theme redefines courage as action despite fear, not the absence of it.'},
      {q:'Ava\'s father is compared to \'a lighthouse on a cliff: not doing anything dramatic, just being visible\'. What does this simile reveal about his parenting style?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['He supports Ava not by rescuing her or giving instructions but by being a calm, steady, visible presence — like a lighthouse that guides without intervening, he lets her find her own way while showing her she is not alone.','The simile means he is not paying attention to Ava at all — like an unmanned lighthouse, he is physically present but mentally absent, indifferent to whether she reaches him safely or not.','He is standing on a cliff because he wants to frighten Ava — by positioning himself on the wider section and watching her struggle across the narrow ledge, he is deliberately prolonging her terror.','He is tall and thin, shaped like a lighthouse — the simile is a physical description of the father\'s body, comparing his narrow build to the tower-like structure of a coastal beacon.'],c:0,e:'Lighthouses don\'t grab ships and steer them — they simply exist as a fixed, reliable point of reference. By comparing the father to one, the author shows he understands that Ava needs autonomy, not rescue. He doesn\'t hold out his hand because he knows she needs to do this herself, but his presence provides safety.'},
      {q:'Why does Ava say \'I hate you\' to her father after reaching the wider section, and why does he smile in response?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['Ava genuinely hates her father and their relationship is hostile — the terrifying experience on the narrow ledge has permanently damaged the trust between them, as shown by her aggressive tone.','Ava is delirious from exhaustion and doesn\'t know what she is saying — the physical stress of the narrow path with its loose gravel and sheer drop has left her unable to speak rationally.','The \'I hate you\' is affectionate exasperation — she is angry about being scared but knows the experience was valuable, and his smile shows he understands the real meaning behind the words.','The father smiles because he thinks fear is funny — his amusement at Ava\'s shaking hands and clenched jaw reveals he finds her distress on the narrow ledge entertaining rather than concerning.'],c:2,e:'This exchange reveals a close, trusting relationship. \'I hate you\' here means \'you put me through that and I\'m furious but also grateful\'. The father\'s smile shows he reads the subtext correctly — he knows the complaint is really a sign that Ava trusts him enough to be honest about her feelings.'},
      {q:'The valley is described as \'an enormous green quilt, patched with fields and stitched with hedgerows\'. What effect does this extended metaphor create?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['It suggests the valley was literally made from fabric and thread — the words \'patched\' and \'stitched\' describe an artificial landscape that was physically sewn together rather than formed by nature.','It transforms the landscape into something warm, handcrafted, and comforting — after the terror of the exposed path, the quilt metaphor makes the view feel safe and beautiful, contrasting sharply with the fear that preceded it.','It shows that Ava\'s grandmother is a quilter — the quilt comparison reveals a family connection to needlework that explains why Ava instinctively describes landscapes in textile terms.','It means the fields are rectangular and uniform like patches on a quilt — the metaphor is purely geometric, describing the neat, orderly pattern of farmland visible from the mountain without any emotional significance.'],c:1,e:'After paragraphs of fear (water-legs, mouse-on-a-motorway, clenched jaw), the quilt metaphor introduces warmth and softness. A quilt is handmade, domestic, and comforting — the opposite of the exposed cliff. This contrast makes the view more powerful: the same height that terrified Ava also produces something beautiful.'},
      {q:'The passage ends with Ava saying \'Oh\' and the narrator adding \'And that was enough.\' What tone does this ending create?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Disappointing — Ava is unimpressed by the view, and her single syllable \'Oh\' expresses anticlimax after the mountains dissolving into blue haze fail to live up to her father\'s promise.','Quietly powerful — the simplicity of \'Oh\' captures a moment too big for words, and \'that was enough\' suggests the experience has justified the fear without needing dramatic celebration.','Comedic — the understatement is meant as a joke, matching the earlier humour of the mouse-on-a-motorway simile and the father\'s description of the cliff as an \'interesting section\'.','Confusing — the reader cannot tell what Ava is feeling because the passage mentions \'something else beside it, something larger\' without ever naming the emotion or explaining what \'enough\' means.'],c:1,e:'\'Oh\' is the smallest possible response to an overwhelming experience — one syllable carrying wonder, relief, and awe. \'And that was enough\' tells us that Ava doesn\'t need to shout or celebrate. The view speaks for itself. This understated ending mirrors the passage\'s theme: sometimes the most powerful moments are the quietest.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about the relationship between Ava and her father from his decision not to hold out his hand?',skill:'Inference',opts:['He is indifferent to Ava\'s fear and does not care if she falls — his refusal to extend his hand on the narrow ledge above a two-hundred-metre drop shows a callous disregard for her safety.','He understands Ava well enough to know she needs to accomplish this independently — offering help would undermine her sense of achievement, so his restraint is actually a deeper form of support.','He wants Ava to fall so she learns a lesson about overconfidence — having done the walk a dozen times, he believes the only way to teach respect for mountains is through a frightening near-accident.','He is too tired from the hike to reach out and help her — despite moving with \'easy confidence,\' the father has exhausted himself by walking three metres ahead and cannot physically lift his arms.'],c:1,e:'The passage explicitly states he \'knew she would have refused it, because accepting help on a mountain felt like admitting something she wasn\'t ready to admit.\' His decision not to offer his hand shows emotional intelligence — he reads his daughter accurately and respects her need for autonomy, even in a frightening situation.'},
      {q:'Ava describes herself as feeling \'about as brave as a mouse on a motorway\'. What does this simile achieve?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['It conveys extreme vulnerability through a vivid, slightly humorous image — a mouse on a motorway is tiny, exposed, and in mortal danger, which captures Ava\'s feelings while the humour prevents the tone from becoming too heavy.','It means Ava is as fast as a mouse and can run quickly across dangerous terrain — the simile emphasises her speed and agility on the narrow path, explaining how she crosses the ledge so efficiently.','It suggests Ava is literally the size of a mouse compared to the mountain — the simile is a factual observation about scale, showing how the two-hundred-metre cliff dwarfs a human figure to insect proportions.','It shows that Ava frequently sees mice on roads near her home — the specificity of the motorway image draws on her personal experience of watching small animals navigate traffic in her neighbourhood.'],c:0,e:'The simile works on multiple levels. A mouse on a motorway is comically small, utterly out of its element, and in genuine danger — all of which describe how Ava feels on the ledge. The slight humour of the image also reflects Ava\'s self-aware, sardonic voice, keeping the passage from becoming melodramatic.'},
      {q:'How does the author use the father\'s description of the hike as \'a gentle walk with a couple of interesting sections\' to develop character and humour?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['It proves the father is a liar who deliberately deceived Ava — by calling the cliff ledge \'gentle,\' he manipulated her into a life-threatening situation she would never have agreed to otherwise.','It demonstrates that the father has a poor vocabulary and cannot describe things accurately — he genuinely does not know the right words for \'exposed ledge\' or \'sheer drop\' and calls them \'interesting\' by default.','It shows that the father has never been on this hike before and misjudged the difficulty — his surprise at the narrow ledge matches Ava\'s, suggesting he relied on an inaccurate guidebook description.','It reveals the father as someone who downplays danger with understatement — his casual language contrasts sharply with the terrifying reality, creating dry humour while also showing he is experienced enough not to be worried.'],c:3,e:'The father\'s euphemism — calling an exposed cliff ledge an \'interesting section\' — is a form of understatement that characterises him as calm, experienced, and wryly humorous. Ava\'s reaction (Googling \'exposure\' and being \'not reassured\') creates comic contrast. The gap between his casual description and the terrifying reality drives much of the passage\'s humour.'},
      {q:'What is the author\'s purpose in describing the path as clinging to the mountain \'like a scar\'?',skill:'Author\'s purpose & tone',opts:['To establish danger and unease from the opening line — a scar suggests damage, fragility, and something barely holding together, which immediately puts the reader into Ava\'s anxious mindset.','To indicate that the path is very wide and safe for walking — scars heal completely over time, so the simile reassures the reader that the path is a stable, permanent feature of the mountainside.','To show that the path was created by a natural disaster such as an earthquake — the word \'scar\' implies the mountain was physically damaged, and the moss and damp streaks are evidence of geological trauma.','To suggest the mountain has been injured and is in pain — the simile personifies the mountain as a wounded creature, and the moss growing on the rock face represents its slow, ongoing attempt to heal.'],c:0,e:'The simile \'like a scar\' does important work in the opening sentence. Scars are thin, fragile marks left by damage — associating the path with one immediately signals danger and vulnerability. It also personifies the mountain, making it feel alive and precarious, which mirrors Ava\'s emotional state throughout the passage.'},
      {q:'Why does Ava keep walking forward rather than stopping or turning back?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['Because the path is too narrow to turn around on — the dinner-plate width and loose gravel make it physically impossible to reverse direction, leaving forward as her only option for survival.','Because stopping forces her to think about the danger, which is psychologically worse than moving — forward motion gives her a goal and prevents paralysing fear, revealing that action is her coping mechanism.','Because she is not actually afraid and is just pretending for attention — her exaggerated descriptions of water-legs and clenched jaw are performative complaints designed to make her father feel guilty.','Because her father is pulling her along with a rope — he walks three metres ahead specifically to maintain tension on a safety line that keeps Ava tethered and moving forward along the ledge.'],c:1,e:'The passage explains Ava\'s logic clearly: \'stopping meant standing still on the ledge, which meant thinking about the ledge.\' Movement provides focus and direction. This reveals something about her character — she processes fear through action rather than stillness — and develops the theme that courage is not the absence of fear but continuing despite it.'},
      {q:'From whose point of view is the passage told, and how does this affect the reader\'s understanding of the father?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['Omniscient narrator who reveals both Ava\'s and her father\'s inner thoughts equally — the passage explains Ava\'s fear of the ledge and simultaneously describes her father\'s private reasoning for choosing this hike.','Third-person limited through Ava\'s perspective — we see the father only through her eyes, which means his calm appears almost irritating at first but gradually reveals itself as quiet, perceptive parenting.','Second person, placing the reader directly on the mountain path — the passage uses \'you\' throughout to make the reader feel the loose gravel beneath their feet and the two-hundred-metre drop to their right.','First person from the father\'s perspective, explaining why he chose this hike — the father narrates his own thoughts about parenting as he watches Ava cross the narrow ledge towards him.'],c:1,e:'Because we are locked into Ava\'s perspective, we experience her frustration with her father\'s understatement and his refusal to offer his hand. Only gradually do we understand that his behaviour is deliberate and caring. This limited viewpoint makes the reader work to interpret the father, just as Ava does, creating a more engaging reading experience.'},
      {q:'The passage moves from fear to beauty in its final paragraphs. How does this structural shift develop the passage\'s main idea?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['The shift exists only to describe the scenery and has no connection to Ava\'s emotions — the green quilt of fields and blue mountain haze is a geographical description inserted for setting, separate from the plot.','The shift mirrors Ava\'s emotional journey — the same height that caused terror also produces wonder, showing that fear and beauty can come from the same source and that enduring difficulty can lead to reward.','The beautiful ending cancels out the fear, proving the hike was never actually dangerous — once Ava sees the valley view, her shaking hands and clenched jaw disappear entirely, showing the fear was imaginary.','The shift is accidental and the author forgot they were writing about fear — the abrupt introduction of the quilt metaphor and dissolving mountains is tonally inconsistent with the preceding paragraphs about the ledge.'],c:1,e:'The structural shift from fear to beauty is the passage\'s key move. For most of the text, height equals danger. But in the final paragraphs, the same height reveals a stunning view. This parallel structure — same stimulus, different response — embodies the theme: the things that scare us can also be the source of the most powerful experiences.'}
  ]},
  {id:'F20',title:'The Letter',type:'fiction',source:'Original passage — friendship / misunderstanding / forgiveness',
   text:'The letter had been sitting in Mia\'s coat pocket for three days. She could feel it every time she put her hands in — a folded square of lined paper, its edges softened from being handled too many times. She had written it on Monday night, rewritten it on Tuesday, and nearly thrown it away on Wednesday. Now it was Thursday, and she was standing outside Jess\'s house at half past four, trying to decide whether to push it through the letterbox or walk away.\n\nThey had been best friends for four years. Four years of shared lunches and inside jokes and walking home together every day, taking the long route through the park because Jess liked feeding the ducks and Mia liked the extra time. Four years of knowing each other so well that they could communicate across a classroom with a single raised eyebrow.\n\nAnd then, three weeks ago, it had fallen apart. The argument had started over something small — a comment Mia had made about Jess\'s drawing in art class. She had meant it as a joke, but it hadn\'t landed as one. Jess\'s face had changed — not anger exactly, but something worse: hurt — and by the time Mia realised what she\'d done, Jess had already turned away. The silence that followed was not the comfortable silence of two people who don\'t need to talk. It was the loud, brittle silence of two people who have too much to say and no way to start.\n\nMia had tried to fix it. She had sent texts that went unread. She had waited by Jess\'s locker, but Jess had started using a different route. She had asked their mutual friend, Aisha, to pass on a message, but Aisha — wisely — had refused. \'This is between you two,\' she said. \'You need to say it yourself.\'\n\nSo Mia had written a letter. Not because she was old-fashioned, but because a letter couldn\'t be interrupted. It couldn\'t be misread in the way a text could, stripped of tone and expression. A letter sat in your hands and asked you to listen.\n\nThe letter said: I\'m sorry. Not the quick, defensive sorry that means \'can we stop talking about this\', but the real kind. The kind that says: I was wrong. I hurt you. I understand why you\'re upset. I should have thought before I spoke, and I didn\'t, and that\'s on me.\n\nIt also said: I miss you. I miss the ducks. I miss the long way home.\n\nMia stared at the letterbox. The metal flap was cold and slightly rusted. She could hear a television on inside the house. She thought about walking away — about letting the silence harden into something permanent, a wall that would eventually feel normal.\n\nThen she pushed the letter through. The flap clanged shut. She stood there for a moment, heart hammering, and then she turned and walked home, taking the long way through the park. The ducks were still there.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['Jess is a difficult person who overreacts to everything Mia says, and the three-week silence proves she is deliberately punishing Mia rather than processing genuine hurt.','Mia is angry with Jess and writes the letter to end their friendship permanently, since the apology is really a way of having the last word before moving on.','After a painful misunderstanding damages a close friendship, Mia struggles with vulnerability before choosing to apologise — knowing that the act of reaching out matters even without a guaranteed outcome.','The passage is primarily an argument that handwritten letters are a more effective communication method than digital messages, using Mia\'s situation as supporting evidence.'],c:2,e:'The passage is about the difficulty of genuine apology. Mia rewrites the letter, nearly throws it away, and stands at the letterbox for a long time. The main idea is that repairing a relationship requires vulnerability — putting yourself out there without knowing if it will work.'},
      {q:'The silence after the argument is described as \'not the comfortable silence of two people who don\'t need to talk\' but \'the loud, brittle silence of two people who have too much to say and no way to start\'. What makes this contrast effective?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['It proves that silence is always harmful in friendships and that Mia and Jess should have argued openly instead of going quiet after the art class incident.','It shows that Mia and Jess are both naturally introverted people whose friendship was always based on not needing to speak rather than on genuine emotional closeness.','By placing two types of silence side by side — the good kind they used to share and the painful kind they have now — the author makes the reader feel the loss of their friendship, and the word \'brittle\' suggests it could shatter at any moment.','The contrast reveals that Mia is a stronger communicator than Jess, since Mia eventually finds words through the letter while Jess remains trapped in unbroken silence throughout.'],c:2,e:'The passage establishes that Mia and Jess had comfortable silences (the park walk, the eyebrow communication). Contrasting this with the new silence — \'loud, brittle\' — makes the reader feel what has been lost. \'Brittle\' is particularly effective: it means fragile and easily broken, suggesting the friendship could either shatter completely or crack open into conversation.'},
      {q:'Mia distinguishes between \'the quick, defensive sorry that means can we stop talking about this\' and \'the real kind\'. What theme does this develop?',skill:'Theme',opts:['Saying sorry is always easy and should be done quickly to move on, which is why Mia rewrites the letter several times — she is perfecting the wording rather than struggling with genuine emotion.','The passage argues that apologies are unnecessary between true friends because real friendship means never having to say sorry at all.','Genuine apology requires honesty and vulnerability — it means acknowledging specific harm rather than just wanting the discomfort to end.','Mia has learned from past experience how to craft the perfect apology, and her multiple drafts show her expertise in persuasive writing rather than emotional struggle.'],c:2,e:'The distinction between defensive and genuine apology is central to the passage\'s theme. A defensive sorry protects the apologiser (\'can we stop talking about this\'). A real sorry exposes them (\'I was wrong. I hurt you. That\'s on me.\'). The passage argues that repair requires the harder kind — the one that costs something.'},
      {q:'The passage ends with Mia walking home through the park and noting \'The ducks were still there.\' Why does the author end with this detail?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['To show that Mia is interested in birdwatching as a new independent hobby, signalling she has moved on from needing Jess\'s company on her walks.','To prove that Jess has already forgiven Mia and has been feeding the ducks at the park while waiting for Mia to arrive.','The ducks represent continuity — the park, the route, and the potential for friendship are all still there, suggesting that even after damage, some things endure and the possibility of reconnection remains.','The ducks symbolise Mia\'s guilt — because she never helped Jess feed them, the ducks remind her of how one-sided the friendship always was, which is why she feels obligated to apologise.'],c:2,e:'The ducks were established earlier as part of Mia and Jess\'s friendship ritual (the long way home, feeding the ducks). By ending with them \'still there\', the author creates quiet hope — the elements of the friendship haven\'t disappeared, they\'re just waiting. It also shows Mia choosing the long route alone, which is both sad (Jess isn\'t there) and hopeful (the path is still available).'},
      {q:'How would you describe the overall tone of this passage?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Confident — Mia is certain that delivering the letter will immediately restore the friendship, which is why she rewrites it only to perfect the wording rather than out of any real doubt.','Cold and detached — Mia describes the letterbox and the ducks with clinical precision, suggesting she has already moved on emotionally and is delivering the letter out of duty rather than genuine feeling.','Angry and resentful — Mia blames Jess for overreacting to a harmless joke about her art class drawing, and the letter is really a way of proving that Jess was wrong to be upset.','Vulnerable and hopeful — the passage conveys the difficulty of reaching out after a mistake, with a quiet ending that suggests repair is possible without guaranteeing it.'],c:3,e:'The tone is defined by vulnerability. Mia rewrites the letter, nearly throws it away, and stands at the letterbox with her heart hammering. She doesn\'t know if it will work. The ending is hopeful but restrained — the ducks are there, the park is there, but Jess hasn\'t responded yet. The passage refuses to provide false certainty.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about Jess\'s character from her response to Mia\'s comment in art class?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['Jess is an aggressive person who deliberately picks fights, since her immediate reaction to Mia\'s art class comment was open anger rather than the quieter hurt the passage actually describes.','Jess does not care about art and was already planning to end the friendship, which is why she had already prepared an alternative route to her locker before the argument even happened.','Jess is sensitive about her creative work and values Mia\'s opinion highly — the fact that a joke from Mia caused hurt rather than anger suggests the comment struck a vulnerable spot from someone whose approval matters to her.','Jess is jealous of Mia\'s artistic ability and reacted out of envy, since the passage implies Mia is the more talented artist and Jess\'s drawing was objectively poor.'],c:2,e:'The passage notes Jess\'s face showed \'not anger exactly, but something worse: hurt.\' Hurt is a more vulnerable emotion than anger — it means the comment reached something personal. Since the comment was about her drawing, and it came from her best friend, we can infer that Jess\'s creative work is important to her and that she is particularly affected by criticism from people she trusts.'},
      {q:'Why does Mia choose to write a letter rather than send another text message?',skill:'Inference',opts:['Because a letter forces the recipient to engage with the full message without the misunderstandings that texts create — it cannot be half-read, misinterpreted without tone, or easily dismissed, making it a more deliberate and vulnerable form of communication.','Because Mia does not own a mobile phone and cannot send texts, since the passage mentions she had to ask Aisha to deliver messages in person rather than contacting Jess digitally.','Because Jess has blocked Mia\'s number and cannot receive any digital messages, which is confirmed by the passage stating that Mia\'s texts went unread over the three-week silence.','Because their school has banned mobile phones entirely, which is why Mia had to rely on waiting by Jess\'s locker and asking Aisha to carry a message face to face.'],c:0,e:'The passage explicitly states Mia\'s reasoning: \'a letter couldn\'t be interrupted. It couldn\'t be misread in the way a text could, stripped of tone and expression. A letter sat in your hands and asked you to listen.\' The choice of medium reflects the seriousness of the apology — a letter demands attention and carries physical weight that a text does not.'},
      {q:'What is the author\'s purpose in detailing the specific memories Mia has of the friendship — shared lunches, inside jokes, the long route through the park?',skill:'Author\'s purpose & tone',opts:['To make the reader feel the weight of what has been lost — by showing the friendship as rich, specific, and deeply woven into daily life, the author raises the stakes of the potential permanent break.','To show that Mia is nostalgic and lives in the past rather than dealing with the present, since she dwells on ducks and inside jokes instead of directly confronting Jess at school.','To prove that Mia and Jess spent too much time together and their friendship was unhealthily codependent, making the three-week separation a positive development rather than a loss.','To show that Mia has an unusually precise memory, which explains why she remembers the exact comment she made about Jess\'s drawing and can reconstruct conversations word for word.'],c:0,e:'These specific details — the ducks, the eyebrow communication, the long way home — make the friendship feel real and lived-in. Without them, the reader would only know the girls were friends. With them, the reader can feel the texture of the friendship and understand exactly what Mia stands to lose, which makes her hesitation at the letterbox more tense and her decision more courageous.'},
      {q:'Mia describes the letterbox flap as \'cold and slightly rusted\'. What is the effect of this sensory detail?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['It suggests Jess\'s family is neglectful of their home, and the rusted letterbox symbolises the way Jess has also neglected the friendship by refusing to read Mia\'s text messages.','It slows the pace and heightens tension at the climactic moment — the physical detail grounds the reader in Mia\'s immediate experience, showing how hyperaware she is of her surroundings as she delays making her decision.','It foreshadows that the letter will be physically damaged by the rusty flap and will arrive torn or smudged, preventing Jess from reading Mia\'s full apology.','It proves that Mia has been standing outside Jess\'s house for several hours, because she has had time to study the letterbox in minute physical detail.'],c:1,e:'At the moment of greatest tension, the author zooms into a tiny sensory detail. This mirrors how people in stressful situations often fixate on small, irrelevant things — the cold metal, the rust. It also slows the narrative pace, making the reader wait alongside Mia before the decisive action, which builds suspense effectively.'},
      {q:'What does Aisha\'s refusal to pass on Mia\'s message reveal about the nature of genuine reconciliation?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['That Aisha is taking Jess\'s side in the argument and wants to punish Mia by forcing her to experience the discomfort of a face-to-face confrontation she is clearly dreading.','That passing messages through mutual friends is the most mature way to resolve conflicts, and Aisha\'s refusal shows poor judgement because Mia\'s request was perfectly reasonable.','That real apologies must come directly from the person who caused the hurt — using an intermediary would be another way of avoiding vulnerability, and Aisha understands that Mia needs to face Jess herself for the apology to be meaningful.','That Aisha secretly caused the original argument by encouraging Mia to make the comment about Jess\'s drawing, and her refusal to help now reveals her guilt.'],c:2,e:'Aisha\'s response — \'This is between you two. You need to say it yourself\' — is wise because it forces Mia towards direct communication. An apology delivered through a third party lacks the personal vulnerability that makes it genuine. Aisha\'s refusal, though it frustrates Mia, ultimately pushes her towards the letter, which is a much more meaningful act.'},
      {q:'The passage is told in past tense but covers events across several days (Monday to Thursday). How does this structure create tension?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['The timeline is confusing and undermines the narrative, because jumping between Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday makes it unclear whether Mia wrote one letter or several different ones.','The multiple days show that Mia is procrastinating and does not genuinely care about repairing the friendship, since someone who truly cared would have delivered the letter on Monday night.','The passage should have been written in present tense for greater immediacy, because the past tense reveals from the start that the friendship was never repaired and the letter did not work.','By compressing the timeline — showing the letter being written, rewritten, nearly discarded, and finally delivered — the structure mirrors Mia\'s internal struggle, with each day representing another layer of doubt she must overcome.'],c:3,e:'The day-by-day structure (written Monday, rewritten Tuesday, nearly thrown away Wednesday, delivered Thursday) externalises Mia\'s inner conflict. Each day represents a new stage of doubt and courage. By the time she stands at the letterbox on Thursday, the reader understands this is not an impulsive decision but one that has been agonised over, making the final moment more powerful.'},
      {q:'How does the passage explore the difference between comfortable and uncomfortable vulnerability?',skill:'Theme',opts:['Only Mia is vulnerable in this passage; Jess shows no vulnerability because her reaction of hurt rather than anger in art class was a deliberate power move to control the friendship.','The passage does not explore vulnerability — it is primarily about the practical advantages of handwritten letters over digital messages, using the Mia and Jess situation as a case study.','The friendship was built on comfortable vulnerability (inside jokes, eyebrow communication, shared routines), but repairing it requires uncomfortable vulnerability (admitting fault, risking rejection) — the passage argues both are necessary for genuine connection.','The passage suggests vulnerability is always negative and should be avoided, since Mia\'s openness in the letter leaves her exposed to rejection and the ending gives no confirmation that it was worthwhile.'],c:2,e:'The passage contrasts two kinds of openness. The friendship\'s comfortable vulnerability is shown through shared routines and wordless communication. But after the argument, repair demands a harder kind — Mia must say \'I was wrong\' without knowing if it will be accepted. The passage suggests that deep relationships require both: the easy closeness of daily life and the difficult honesty of admitting fault.'}
  ]},
  {id:'NF05',title:'How Volcanoes Build Islands',type:'nonfiction',source:'Original passage — geology / Hawaii / earth science',
   text:'The Hawaiian Islands are among the most remote places on Earth — a chain of volcanic peaks rising from the middle of the Pacific Ocean, more than 3,700 kilometres from the nearest continent. There are no land bridges, no continental shelves connecting them to anything. They exist because of fire.\n\nDeep beneath the Pacific, a column of superheated rock — known as a mantle plume or \'hotspot\' — rises from near the Earth\'s core towards the surface. When this plume reaches the ocean floor, it melts through the thin crust above it and erupts, sending lava pouring into the sea. Over thousands of years, the lava builds up layer upon layer, growing taller and wider until it finally breaks the surface of the ocean. A new island is born.\n\nBut the Pacific Plate — the vast slab of crust on which the ocean floor sits — is not stationary. It moves northwest at roughly seven centimetres per year, about the speed at which your fingernails grow. As the plate drifts over the hotspot, the active volcano is gradually carried away from its heat source. Its eruptions slow, then stop. Meanwhile, the hotspot burns through the crust in a new location, and a new island begins to form. The result, over millions of years, is a chain: a line of islands stretching across the ocean like footprints, with the oldest and most eroded at one end and the youngest and most active at the other.\n\nThis is exactly what we see in Hawaii. The Big Island, at the southeastern end of the chain, sits directly over the hotspot today. It is home to Kilauea, one of the most active volcanoes on Earth, which has been erupting almost continuously since 1983. Moving northwest along the chain, the islands grow progressively older, smaller, and more weathered. Kauai, the oldest of the main islands, is roughly five million years old and has been sculpted by erosion into dramatic cliffs and canyons. Beyond Kauai, the chain continues as a series of tiny, low-lying atolls and submerged seamounts — the worn-down remains of islands that were once as tall and fiery as the Big Island is today.\n\nAnd the process hasn\'t stopped. Thirty kilometres southeast of the Big Island, a new seamount called Loihi is already growing on the ocean floor, fed by the same hotspot that built its neighbours. It is currently about a thousand metres below the surface. Scientists estimate that it will break through the waves in somewhere between ten thousand and one hundred thousand years, becoming the newest Hawaiian island.\n\nHawaii, in other words, is not finished. The chain is still being written, one eruption at a time — a geological conveyor belt that has been operating for at least seventy million years and shows no sign of slowing down.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['Kilauea is the most dangerous volcano in the world and could erupt catastrophically at any time, which is why the passage focuses on warning readers about the risks of living on the Big Island.','The Hawaiian Islands were created by volcanic eruptions from a stationary hotspot beneath a moving tectonic plate — a process that has been operating for millions of years and is still continuing today.','Hawaii is a popular tourist destination because of its dramatic volcanic landscape, which is why the passage primarily focuses on describing the islands\' scenic beauty rather than explaining geological processes.','Scientists have proven that all the Hawaiian Islands will eventually sink beneath the ocean and disappear entirely, since the older islands like Kauai are already eroding into low-lying atolls.'],c:1,e:'The passage explains the hotspot mechanism (paragraphs 2–3), shows how it created the Hawaiian chain (paragraph 4), and reveals that the process is ongoing (paragraphs 5–6). The main idea is the dynamic, continuing nature of island formation — Hawaii isn\'t a finished product but an ongoing process.'},
      {q:'How is this passage primarily structured?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['Problem and solution — the passage identifies the threat that Hawaiian volcanoes pose to local residents and proposes scientific monitoring of Kilauea and Loihi as the solution.','Compare and contrast — the passage systematically compares the Big Island, Kauai, and the atolls to argue that older islands are geologically superior to younger, more volatile ones.','Sequential explanation — the passage explains a geological process step by step, then shows the evidence in Hawaii, then extends the pattern into the future.','Persuasive argument — the author uses the example of Loihi growing on the ocean floor to convince readers that geology is the most important branch of science.'],c:2,e:'The passage follows a clear sequence: it explains the hotspot mechanism (cause), shows how it creates an island chain (effect), maps this onto the real Hawaiian chain (evidence), and then extends forward to Loihi (future prediction). Each paragraph builds logically on the one before.'},
      {q:'The Pacific Plate moves \'at roughly seven centimetres per year, about the speed at which your fingernails grow\'. Why does the author include this comparison?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['To prove that fingernails grow at exactly the same speed as tectonic plates, establishing a direct biological link between human growth rates and the geological forces that shape the Hawaiian island chain.','To show that the Pacific Plate moves dangerously fast and could cause sudden destruction, since seven centimetres per year is rapid enough to shift entire islands in a short time.','To make an abstract, difficult-to-imagine speed feel concrete and relatable — the reader can look at their own fingernails and grasp a scale that would otherwise be meaningless.','To suggest that human biological growth and geological movement are driven by the same underlying physical forces, connecting the reader\'s body to the Earth\'s internal processes.'],c:2,e:'Seven centimetres per year is almost impossible to visualise. By comparing it to fingernail growth — something the reader can literally see on their own body — the author transforms an abstract number into a tangible experience. This is a common technique in science writing: anchoring unfamiliar scales to familiar ones.'},
      {q:'The passage describes the island chain as \'footprints\' stretching across the ocean. What does this metaphor help the reader understand?',skill:'Analyse informational texts',opts:['That the islands are shaped exactly like human feet when viewed from above, which is why early Polynesian navigators named them after parts of the body.','That ancient Polynesian travellers walked between the islands when sea levels were lower, leaving a trail that later became the volcanic chain we see today.','That the hotspot itself physically moves across the ocean floor, dragging magma behind it and depositing islands at regular intervals along its northwest path.','That the islands form a sequential trail left behind as the plate moves over the hotspot — just as footprints record a person\'s path, the islands record the plate\'s movement through geological time.'],c:3,e:'Footprints record movement — they show where someone has been. Similarly, the Hawaiian chain records the Pacific Plate\'s journey over the hotspot. The oldest islands are the earliest \'footprints\', and the Big Island is where the \'walker\' stands now. This metaphor makes the abstract concept of plate movement feel intuitive.'},
      {q:'Why does the author include the information about Loihi, the underwater seamount growing southeast of the Big Island?',skill:'Author\'s purpose',opts:['To frighten readers about an imminent volcanic eruption that will endanger communities on the Big Island when Loihi\'s thousand-metre seamount breaks through the surface.','To suggest that scientists should intervene to prevent Loihi from becoming a full island, since its growth could destabilise the Big Island\'s existing volcanic systems.','To provide an unrelated fun fact about underwater mountains, since Loihi is a separate geological phenomenon unconnected to the hotspot mechanism described earlier in the passage.','To demonstrate that the geological process is ongoing and real, not just historical — it reinforces the passage\'s central point that Hawaii is \'not finished\' and the chain is still being written.'],c:3,e:'Loihi transforms the passage from a historical explanation into a living story. Without it, the reader might think the hotspot process is something that happened in the past. By showing a new island actively forming right now, the author proves the process is ongoing and reinforces the final sentence: \'the chain is still being written\'.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about the age of Loihi compared to the Big Island of Hawaii?',skill:'Inference',opts:['Loihi is older than the Big Island because it is deeper underwater — depth indicates age in the hotspot system, with the deepest formations being the most ancient.','Loihi is older because smaller islands always form first in a volcanic chain, and the Big Island grew larger only because it received more lava over a longer period.','Loihi is much younger than the Big Island because it is still forming underwater, whereas the Big Island is already a large, active landmass above the surface.','Loihi and the Big Island are the same age because they were both created by the same hotspot and are located only thirty kilometres apart on the same section of the Pacific Plate.'],c:2,e:'The passage explains that the hotspot creates new islands sequentially as the plate moves northwest. Since Loihi is southeast of the Big Island and still underwater, it must be the newest addition to the chain. The Big Island, already above sea level and volcanically active, has had thousands more years of eruptions building it up.'},
      {q:'What theme does the passage develop about the relationship between time and landscape?',skill:'Theme',opts:['That geological processes have stopped in modern times, since the passage implies Kilauea\'s eruptions are winding down and Loihi will be the last island the hotspot ever produces.','That time has no effect on the physical shape of the Earth, since the Hawaiian chain has remained unchanged despite millions of years of erosion, waves, and tectonic plate movement.','That landscapes are not permanent but are shaped by slow, continuous geological processes operating over millions of years.','That the Hawaiian Islands will remain exactly as they are forever, since the passage describes Kauai\'s cliffs and the Big Island\'s volcanoes as permanent, fixed features of the Pacific.'],c:2,e:'The passage repeatedly emphasises timescales: thousands of years for an island to form, millions of years for the chain, seven centimetres of movement per year. The theme is that what appears permanent and solid is actually in constant, slow motion. Even the Big Island is just one frame in an ongoing geological film.'},
      {q:'From whose point of view is this passage written, and how does that affect the information presented?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['It is written from the point of view of a Hawaiian resident who witnessed the eruptions, which shapes the reader\'s experience by controlling what information is revealed and when throughout the narrative.','It is written from the perspective of Kilauea volcano itself, personifying the mountain as a living narrator that describes its own eruptions and its relationship with the moving Pacific Plate.','It is a first-person account by a geologist who discovered the hotspot, which shapes the reader\'s experience by controlling what information is revealed and when throughout the narrative.','It is written from an objective, scientific third-person perspective, which allows the author to present geological evidence and timescales without personal bias, lending credibility to the explanation.'],c:3,e:'The passage maintains a detached, explanatory tone throughout. The third-person scientific perspective allows the author to discuss events spanning millions of years — far beyond any individual experience. This objectivity makes the geological claims feel authoritative and trustworthy rather than anecdotal.'},
      {q:'What is the overall tone of this passage?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Humorous and light-hearted throughout — the fingernail comparison and the phrase \'a new island is born\' are jokes designed to entertain rather than inform the reader about geology.','Dry and uninterested, as though the author finds Hawaiian geology tedious — the flat recitation of facts about plate speed and Kauai\'s age suggests a reluctant textbook writer.','Anxious and fearful about future volcanic eruptions — the mention of Loihi growing beneath the surface and Kilauea erupting since 1983 creates a tone of mounting geological dread.','Wonder combined with scientific clarity — the author conveys awe at the scale of the process while explaining the mechanics precisely and accessibly.'],c:3,e:'Phrases like \'a new island is born\' and \'the chain is still being written\' convey genuine wonder, while the precise scientific detail (mantle plume, seven centimetres per year) keeps the tone grounded. The combination makes the passage both emotionally engaging and intellectually rigorous.'},
      {q:'The passage calls the process a \'geological conveyor belt\'. What literary device is this, and what does it help the reader understand?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['It is alliteration because \'geological\' and \'conveyor\' share similar consonant sounds, drawing the reader\'s ear to the rhythm of the phrase.','It is a simile because the author writes the islands stretch \'like footprints\', using the word \'like\' to compare the hotspot system to a belt in a factory.','It is personification because it gives the Earth\'s crust human qualities by suggesting the hotspot deliberately chooses where to build each new island in the chain.','It is a metaphor comparing the hotspot-and-plate system to a factory conveyor belt — it helps the reader visualise how islands are produced in a line, one after another, in a continuous mechanical process.'],c:3,e:'A conveyor belt moves objects along a fixed path in sequence, which is exactly what the plate-over-hotspot system does with islands. The metaphor simplifies a complex geological process into a familiar industrial image. It also implies regularity and continuity, reinforcing the idea that this process is ongoing and predictable.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about why the passage mentions that Hawaii is \'more than 3,700 kilometres from the nearest continent\'?',skill:'Inference',opts:['To warn tourists that Hawaii is too far away to visit easily, since the 3,700-kilometre distance from any continent makes emergency evacuation during eruptions nearly impossible.','To prove that Hawaii is the most remote place on the entire planet, which is why no animal or plant species could ever reach the islands without human assistance.','To suggest that the distance measurement is only an estimate and that the islands may actually be much closer to Asia than scientists currently believe.','To emphasise that the islands\' extreme isolation makes their volcanic origin all the more remarkable — they cannot be explained by ordinary continental geology, which heightens the significance of the hotspot explanation.'],c:3,e:'By stressing the remoteness first, the author creates a puzzle: how can islands exist so far from any continent? This primes the reader to appreciate the hotspot explanation as the answer. The isolation detail also rules out simpler geological explanations like continental shelf activity, making the volcanic mechanism feel more extraordinary.'},
      {q:'The passage describes Kauai as \'sculpted by erosion into dramatic cliffs and canyons\'. What does the word \'sculpted\' suggest about the erosion process?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['It personifies erosion as an artist deliberately shaping the landscape, suggesting that the natural forces have created something beautiful rather than merely destructive.','It implies that Kauai looks identical to the Big Island, since the same volcanic forces built both and erosion would produce the same cliff and canyon formations everywhere.','It suggests that erosion happened rapidly and recently, carving Kauai\'s cliffs and canyons within a few hundred years rather than over the five million years the passage describes.','It means that early Hawaiian settlers physically carved the cliffs and canyons into the rock, shaping Kauai\'s landscape through deliberate construction rather than natural forces.'],c:0,e:'The word \'sculpted\' carries connotations of artistry and intention. A sculptor creates something beautiful through careful removal of material — just as erosion has shaped Kauai\'s raw volcanic rock into striking geographical features. This word choice frames natural erosion as a creative rather than purely destructive force.'}
  ]},
  {id:'NF06',title:'The Science of Fear',type:'nonfiction',source:'Original passage — psychology / neuroscience / fight-or-flight',
   text:'Imagine you are walking through a forest and you see a shape on the path ahead. It is long, thin, and coiled. Your heart rate spikes. Your muscles tense. Your breathing quickens. You freeze mid-step, your eyes locked on the shape — and then, a second later, you realise it is a stick. You laugh at yourself, your shoulders drop, and you walk on. But for that one second, your body was preparing to fight for its life.\n\nThis is the fight-or-flight response, and it is one of the oldest survival mechanisms in the human body. When your brain detects a potential threat — a snake, a loud noise, a car swerving towards you — it triggers a cascade of chemical reactions faster than conscious thought. The amygdala, a small almond-shaped structure deep in the brain, acts as the alarm system. It receives sensory information and, if it detects danger, sends an emergency signal to the hypothalamus, which activates the sympathetic nervous system. Within milliseconds, adrenaline floods your bloodstream.\n\nThe effects are dramatic. Your heart pumps faster, sending oxygen-rich blood to your muscles. Your pupils dilate to let in more light. Non-essential functions — digestion, immune response, even your ability to feel pain — are temporarily shut down. Your body is redirecting every available resource towards one goal: survival. You are faster, stronger, and more alert than you were five seconds ago.\n\nThis system evolved millions of years ago, when the threats humans faced were physical and immediate — predators, falling rocks, rival groups. It was superbly effective in that environment. The problem is that the modern world has changed far faster than our biology. Today, the amygdala cannot distinguish between a charging lion and an upcoming exam, between a physical attack and a critical comment from a classmate. It fires the same alarm for all of them.\n\nThis mismatch explains why anxiety is so common in modern life. Your body prepares you to run from a predator, but there is no predator — just a maths test or a social situation you\'re dreading. The adrenaline has nowhere to go. Your heart pounds, your palms sweat, your stomach churns, and your brain screams danger — all in response to a threat that does not require you to fight or flee. The system that once saved your ancestors\' lives is now, in many cases, making yours harder.\n\nUnderstanding this can actually help. When you feel anxious before a test or a presentation, your body is not malfunctioning — it is doing exactly what it was designed to do. The alarm is real; the danger is not. Recognising the difference won\'t stop the adrenaline, but it can stop you from believing that your fear means something is genuinely wrong. Sometimes, the snake is just a stick.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['Humans should avoid all stressful situations to prevent the fight-or-flight response, since the passage argues that triggering the amygdala repeatedly causes permanent damage to the nervous system.','The fight-or-flight response is a dangerous malfunction that should be treated with medication, since the passage describes the system shutting down digestion and immune function as harmful side effects.','The amygdala is the most important part of the brain and controls all human emotions, which is why the passage devotes most of its attention to describing this single brain structure.','The fight-or-flight response is an ancient survival system that helped our ancestors but now causes anxiety because it cannot distinguish between physical dangers and modern stresses.'],c:3,e:'The passage explains what the fight-or-flight response is (paragraphs 1–3), why it evolved (paragraph 4), and why it causes problems in modern life (paragraph 5). The main idea is the mismatch between an ancient system and a modern environment — and the final paragraph suggests understanding this mismatch can help.'},
      {q:'How is this passage structured?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['Hook, explanation, historical context, modern application, practical conclusion — the passage moves from a vivid opening scenario through science to a useful takeaway.','Compare and contrast only — the passage exclusively alternates between ancient scenarios like predators and falling rocks and modern ones like exams and social situations, with no other structural element.','Strict chronological order — the passage traces fear from prehistoric cave-dwellers through ancient civilisations to the present day, covering each historical period in sequence.','Persuasive argument — the author is promoting a specific therapeutic technique for anxiety, using the forest scenario and the amygdala explanation as evidence that their method works.'],c:0,e:'The passage follows a clear arc: it hooks the reader with the stick/snake scenario, explains the biology, contextualises it historically, applies it to modern anxiety, and ends with practical advice. Each section builds on the previous one, making the science feel relevant to the reader\'s own life.'},
      {q:'The opening and closing both reference the snake/stick scenario. Why does the author use this circular structure?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['To prove that sticks are more common than snakes in forests, providing a factual claim about wildlife frequency that supports the scientific argument about false alarms in the amygdala.','Because the passage is primarily about forest safety and the author wants to remind readers to watch their step on woodland paths, using the neuroscience as background context for a practical warning.','Returning to the opening image creates a satisfying frame — but the second time, \'the snake is just a stick\' carries deeper meaning because the reader now understands the science, transforming a simple metaphor into a practical tool for managing anxiety.','Because the author forgot they had already used the snake example in the opening paragraph and accidentally repeated it, creating an unintentional echo rather than a deliberate structural choice.'],c:2,e:'The circular structure gives the passage narrative satisfaction. When we first read the stick/snake scenario, it\'s just an anecdote. By the end, after learning about the amygdala and the ancient-modern mismatch, \'the snake is just a stick\' becomes a mantra for managing anxiety. The same words mean more the second time.'},
      {q:'The passage states that the amygdala \'cannot distinguish between a charging lion and an upcoming exam\'. What is the purpose of this comparison?',skill:'Analyse informational texts',opts:['To suggest that schools should eliminate exams because the biological stress they cause is equivalent to facing a predator, making tests a form of physical harm to students.','To prove that exams are genuinely as dangerous as lions, since the identical adrenaline response means the body experiences the same level of real physical threat in both situations.','To show that ancient humans encountered charging lions so frequently that the amygdala evolved specifically to detect large predators, rather than responding to threats in general.','To make the concept of evolutionary mismatch concrete and relatable — by placing an absurd pairing side by side, the author highlights how poorly calibrated the system is for modern life.'],c:3,e:'The lion/exam pairing is deliberately absurd — placing a life-threatening predator next to a school test highlights how irrational the fear response can feel. The reader immediately understands the mismatch: the same alarm system that makes sense for a lion makes no sense for homework. This comparison makes the scientific concept memorable.'},
      {q:'Why does the author end with practical advice (\'recognising the difference won\'t stop the adrenaline, but it can stop you from believing your fear means something is genuinely wrong\')?',skill:'Author\'s purpose',opts:['To give the reader a useful takeaway — the passage isn\'t just informational but empowering, showing that understanding the science of fear can help you respond to anxiety more rationally even if you can\'t eliminate it.','To suggest that all anxiety is imaginary and people should simply ignore the physical symptoms, since the passage proves that racing hearts and sweaty palms have no real biological cause.','To prove that adrenaline is a harmful chemical that damages the body, since the passage describes it shutting down digestion, immune response, and the ability to feel pain.','Because the author is a therapist advertising their services, using the scientific explanation of the amygdala and adrenaline as a sales pitch for professional anxiety treatment.'],c:0,e:'The final paragraph transforms the passage from pure information into something personally useful. The author is honest — understanding won\'t stop the physical symptoms — but argues that knowledge changes your interpretation. \'The alarm is real; the danger is not\' is a distinction that could genuinely help a Year 7 student before a test.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about why the author chose to open with a second-person scenario (\'Imagine you are walking through a forest...\')?',skill:'Inference',opts:['Because the author was writing a fictional short story rather than a science text, and the forest scenario is meant to be read as the opening chapter of a novel about a character\'s fear of snakes.','To prove that forests are dangerous places full of snakes, establishing early in the passage that readers should avoid woodland areas where they might trigger their fight-or-flight response.','To test whether the reader has ever actually walked in a forest, since only someone with direct experience would understand the specific physical sensations of freezing mid-step on a path.','To make the reader experience the fight-or-flight response personally, rather than reading about it abstractly — by placing you in the scenario, the author ensures you understand the feeling before learning the science.'],c:3,e:'The second-person address is a deliberate rhetorical strategy. By saying \'you\' rather than \'a person\', the author triggers the reader\'s own memory of fear. This means when the scientific explanation follows, it connects to something the reader has felt, not just read about. It bridges the gap between personal experience and neuroscience.'},
      {q:'What theme does the passage develop about the relationship between biology and modern life?',skill:'Theme',opts:['That biology is always perfectly adapted to whatever environment we live in, since the amygdala\'s ability to trigger adrenaline during exams shows it has successfully updated for modern threats.','That modern life is easier than ancient life in every way, which is why the fight-or-flight response has become completely unnecessary and serves no useful function in the present day.','That our biological systems evolved for a world very different from the one we now live in, creating a mismatch that can cause real suffering even though the systems are working exactly as designed.','That our bodies will quickly evolve to match the modern world within a few generations, since the passage states that the sympathetic nervous system is already adapting to distinguish exams from predators.'],c:2,e:'The passage builds its central theme around evolutionary mismatch. The fight-or-flight system is not broken — it is performing its intended function. The problem is that its intended function was designed for sabre-toothed tigers, not maths tests. This theme resonates with GCSE-level students who experience exam anxiety regularly.'},
      {q:'What is the tone of the final paragraph, and how does it differ from the rest of the passage?',skill:'Tone',opts:['The tone becomes more frightening and urgent, warning readers that unchecked anxiety will worsen unless they seek immediate professional help for their overactive amygdala.','The tone remains purely scientific with no emotional shift, since phrases like \'your body is not malfunctioning\' and \'the alarm is real\' maintain the same clinical detachment as the adrenaline explanation.','The tone is sarcastic and mocks people who feel anxious, dismissing their exam stress as trivial compared to the real dangers faced by ancient humans confronting predators and falling rocks.','The tone shifts from explanatory and scientific to reassuring and empowering — the author moves from describing a problem to offering the reader a way to think about it differently.'],c:3,e:'Throughout most of the passage, the tone is informative and analytical. In the final paragraph, it becomes warm and directly supportive: \'your body is not malfunctioning\' and \'the alarm is real; the danger is not\'. This tonal shift transforms the passage from a biology lesson into something genuinely helpful for the reader.'},
      {q:'The amygdala is described as the brain\'s \'alarm system\'. What literary device is this, and why is it effective?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['It is a simile because the passage uses the word \'as\' to compare the amygdala\'s function to an alarm, placing the two side by side with an explicit connecting word.','It is a metaphor that compares a complex brain structure to something simple and familiar — an alarm — making its function instantly understandable without requiring detailed neurological knowledge.','It is onomatopoeia because the word \'alarm\' imitates the loud ringing sound that the amygdala supposedly produces when it detects a threat like a snake on a forest path.','It is hyperbole because the amygdala is far more complex than any alarm — calling it a simple alarm system dramatically understates the structure\'s role in processing fear and memory.'],c:1,e:'Calling the amygdala an \'alarm system\' is a metaphor that does heavy explanatory lifting. Alarms detect threats and trigger responses — which is exactly what the amygdala does. The reader immediately grasps the function without needing to understand the neuroscience. It also sets up the later point that sometimes alarms go off when there is no real danger.'},
      {q:'From the passage, what can you infer about why the author lists specific physical effects of adrenaline (heart pumping, pupils dilating, digestion shutting down)?',skill:'Inference',opts:['To frighten readers into avoiding all stressful situations, since learning that adrenaline shuts down digestion and immune response should convince them that stress is physically destructive.','To help readers recognise these symptoms in their own bodies — by listing the physical effects, the author enables the reader to connect the science to their own experience of fear or anxiety.','To prove that adrenaline is a harmful chemical that should be eliminated from the body, since shutting down digestion and immune response clearly damages long-term health.','Because the author needed to fill space in the paragraph and chose to list random biological facts about pupil dilation and digestion that are unconnected to the fight-or-flight argument.'],c:1,e:'The detailed list serves a practical purpose. A student who feels their heart racing before a presentation can now understand why. The passage is not just explaining biology in the abstract — it is giving readers a framework for interpreting their own bodily sensations. This connects directly to the final paragraph\'s empowering message.'},
      {q:'How does the author\'s use of short, punchy sentences contribute to the passage\'s effect?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['Short sentences prove the author has a limited vocabulary and cannot construct longer, more sophisticated sentences like those found in advanced scientific writing about neuroscience.','Short sentences are required in all science writing by convention, and the author is simply following standard formatting rules for articles about neuroscience and the amygdala.','They are used only for decorative purposes and add nothing to the meaning, since the same information about heart rate and pupil dilation would be equally effective in longer sentences.','Short sentences like \'You freeze mid-step\' and \'The alarm is real; the danger is not\' mirror the sudden, sharp nature of the fight-or-flight response itself, making the reader feel the urgency the passage describes.'],c:3,e:'The sentence structure reinforces the content. When describing the fight-or-flight response, short sentences create a rapid, tense rhythm that mimics the body\'s sudden reaction. This is a deliberate stylistic choice — the form matches the function, making the reader experience urgency rather than just reading about it.'},
      {q:'The passage mentions that the fight-or-flight system \'evolved millions of years ago\'. What does this detail help explain?',skill:'Theme',opts:['It suggests that ancient humans never felt fear because the fight-or-flight system had only just evolved and had not yet been tested against real predators or falling rocks.','It means the fight-or-flight system will disappear within the next million years as human evolution catches up with the modern environment and the amygdala becomes redundant.','It proves that the fight-or-flight response is completely outdated and no longer works at all, since the passage states the system cannot distinguish between a lion and a maths test.','It explains why the system is poorly suited to modern threats — millions of years of evolution cannot be overwritten in a few thousand years of civilisation, which is the root cause of the mismatch the passage describes.'],c:3,e:'The timescale is crucial to the passage\'s argument. Evolution operates over millions of years; human civilisation has existed for only a few thousand. This vast difference in speed explains why our bodies still react to exams as if they were predators. The detail grounds the mismatch theme in concrete evolutionary logic.'}
  ]},
  {id:'NF07',title:'Why Leaves Change Colour',type:'nonfiction',source:'Original passage — biology / seasons / chemistry',
   text:'Every autumn, something remarkable happens to the trees. Leaves that have been green all summer — producing food, exchanging gases, converting sunlight into energy — begin to turn. First yellow, then orange, then red, and finally brown. It happens so gradually that you barely notice it day by day, and then one morning you look up and the whole canopy has caught fire. But what exactly is happening inside those leaves, and why?\n\nThe answer begins with chlorophyll, the pigment that makes leaves green. Chlorophyll is essential to photosynthesis — the process by which plants convert sunlight, water, and carbon dioxide into glucose and oxygen. During spring and summer, leaves produce chlorophyll continuously, and its green colour is so dominant that it masks all the other pigments present in the leaf.\n\nBut chlorophyll is expensive to produce. It requires significant energy and nutrients, particularly nitrogen and magnesium. As the days shorten and temperatures drop in autumn, the tree faces a calculation: is it worth continuing to invest in leaves that will soon be damaged by frost? The answer, for deciduous trees, is no. The tree begins to withdraw valuable nutrients from its leaves, pulling nitrogen and magnesium back into the branches and trunk where they can be stored safely over winter. As the chlorophyll breaks down and is not replaced, the green colour fades — and the other pigments, which were there all along, are finally revealed.\n\nThe yellows and oranges come from carotenoids — the same family of pigments that makes carrots orange and bananas yellow. These pigments were present in the leaf throughout the summer but invisible beneath the chlorophyll. They are not new; they were simply hidden.\n\nThe reds, however, are different. Red pigments — called anthocyanins — are actively produced by some trees in autumn, not revealed. Scientists believe anthocyanins act as a kind of sunscreen, protecting the leaf\'s cells from bright light during the vulnerable period when chlorophyll is being withdrawn. Without this protection, the leaf could be damaged before the tree has finished reclaiming its nutrients.\n\nSo autumn colour is not, as many people assume, a sign of death. It is the opposite: it is the tree carefully, efficiently preparing for survival. The yellows show the tree withdrawing resources. The reds show it protecting those resources during transit. Even the final browning — caused by tannins left behind after everything useful has been removed — is evidence of a job completed.\n\nWhen you see a hillside blazing with autumn colour, you are not watching a forest die. You are watching thousands of trees making the same quiet, intelligent decision: to let go of what they cannot keep, in order to protect what they can.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['Autumn colour change is not a sign of death but an active, efficient survival strategy — trees withdraw nutrients and protect their cells through a carefully managed chemical process.','Chlorophyll is the only pigment in leaves and disappears completely in autumn, leaving the leaf with no colour until new pigments are generated from the remaining glucose reserves.','Red leaves are caused by cold temperatures freezing the chlorophyll inside them, which crystallises into red-tinted ice structures visible through the leaf surface.','Autumn leaves change colour because they are dying and rotting — the browning process spreads from the leaf tip inward as cells decompose in sequence.'],c:0,e:'The passage systematically dismantles the assumption that autumn colour means death. Each colour is explained as part of a survival strategy: yellows reveal nutrient withdrawal, reds show active protection, and browns signal completion. The main idea reframes autumn as preparation, not decline.'},
      {q:'How is the passage primarily structured?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['Sequential explanation with a reframing conclusion — the passage explains each stage of colour change in order, then reframes the whole process as survival rather than death.','Chronological narrative — the passage follows a single oak tree from spring bud-break through summer growth to its final brown leaf-fall in late November.','Persuasive argument — the author wants to convince readers that autumn is the best season by ranking it against spring, summer, and winter using scientific evidence.','Problem and solution — the passage identifies chlorophyll loss as a disease threatening trees and proposes that nitrogen supplements could prevent autumn colour change entirely.'],c:0,e:'The passage moves through the science in a logical sequence (chlorophyll → carotenoids → anthocyanins → tannins), explaining each colour change in turn. The final two paragraphs then reframe everything: what looked like death is actually intelligent survival. This structure guides the reader from observation to understanding to reinterpretation.'},
      {q:'The passage distinguishes between yellow/orange pigments and red pigments. What is the key difference?',skill:'Analyse informational texts',opts:['There is no difference — all autumn colours are caused by the same process of chlorophyll breaking down at different rates, producing yellows first and reds later as the decay progresses.','Yellow and orange carotenoids were present all summer but hidden by chlorophyll — they are revealed. Red anthocyanins are actively produced in autumn — they are new. This means autumn reds require energy, suggesting they serve a specific purpose.','Yellow pigments are produced first because carotenoids require less energy to manufacture than anthocyanins, and trees prioritise the cheaper pigment during nutrient withdrawal.','Red pigments are always present in leaves but yellow ones are not — anthocyanins are permanent while carotenoids must be freshly synthesised each autumn from stored magnesium.'],c:1,e:'This distinction is scientifically important and the passage highlights it clearly. Carotenoids are \'not new; they were simply hidden\'. Anthocyanins are \'actively produced\'. If the tree is spending precious energy making red pigment during a shutdown phase, there must be a good reason — which the author explains as cellular sun protection.'},
      {q:'Why does the author begin with the description of a canopy that has \'caught fire\'?',skill:'Author\'s purpose',opts:['To engage the reader with a vivid, poetic image before introducing the science — making the topic feel visually exciting and personally familiar before the technical explanation begins.','To suggest that climate change is causing forest fires, linking the visual similarity between autumn canopies and actual wildfires to warn readers about rising global temperatures.','To warn readers that the chemical reactions inside autumn leaves generate dangerous levels of heat, which is why fallen leaves sometimes feel warm to the touch.','To establish that the passage will focus on the destructive power of fire in forests, foreshadowing a later discussion of how tannins make dead leaves flammable.'],c:0,e:'Opening with \'the whole canopy has caught fire\' creates a vivid, almost cinematic image that draws the reader in emotionally before the science begins. This technique — hooking with beauty, then explaining with science — makes the technical content more engaging because the reader already cares about what they\'re learning about.'},
      {q:'The final sentence says trees are \'letting go of what they cannot keep, in order to protect what they can\'. What does this metaphor suggest beyond the literal science?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['It means trees make conscious decisions and have human-like emotions, proving that deciduous species experience grief when shedding their leaves each autumn.','Trees are sad about losing their leaves and wish they could keep them, which is why anthocyanins are produced — as a final act of beautification before the leaf falls.','The phrase works as both a scientific summary and a life lesson — just as trees shed leaves to survive winter, letting go of what you cannot control can be a form of strength rather than weakness.','The metaphor suggests that all trees will eventually die, with each autumn representing one step closer to the tree exhausting its finite supply of stored nitrogen.'],c:2,e:'The final sentence operates on two levels. Scientifically, it summarises nutrient withdrawal. But the phrasing — \'letting go of what they cannot keep, in order to protect what they can\' — resonates as a broader truth about resilience and prioritisation. This elevates the passage from pure science to something the reader might think about beyond biology.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about why deciduous trees shed their leaves but evergreen trees do not?',skill:'Inference',opts:['Evergreen trees live in places where autumn never happens, thriving only in tropical climates where temperatures remain constant and chlorophyll production is never interrupted.','Evergreen trees do not have chlorophyll and therefore never change colour — their needles are green because of a completely different pigment that does not break down in cold weather.','The passage implies that shedding leaves is a cost-benefit decision — deciduous trees judge it not worth maintaining leaves through frost, suggesting that evergreens have adapted differently, perhaps with leaves that are cheaper to maintain or more frost-resistant.','Deciduous trees are weaker than evergreen trees and cannot survive winter, which is why deciduous species have shorter lifespans and are gradually being replaced by conifers across Europe.'],c:2,e:'The passage frames leaf-shedding as a calculated decision: \'is it worth continuing to invest in leaves that will soon be damaged by frost?\' For deciduous trees, the answer is no. This implies that evergreen trees have a different answer — their needle-like leaves are typically cheaper to maintain and more resistant to frost damage, so the cost-benefit calculation works differently.'},
      {q:'What is the overall tone of this passage?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Mournful and sad about the death of leaves each autumn — phrases like \'caught fire\' and \'no longer replaced\' convey a sense of loss and irreversible decline.','Admiring and reverential — the author treats the trees\' survival strategy with respect and wonder, portraying a chemical process as something almost intelligent and beautiful.','Coldly scientific with no emotional engagement whatsoever — the passage reads like a chemistry textbook, listing pigment names and nutrient cycles without any figurative language.','Humorous and joking about the changing seasons — the comparison of carotenoids to carrots and bananas is meant as comedy, and the personification of trees is played for laughs.'],c:1,e:'Words like \'remarkable\', \'caught fire\', \'carefully, efficiently preparing for survival\', and \'quiet, intelligent decision\' reveal an author who is genuinely impressed by what trees do. The tone elevates a biology topic into something almost philosophical, which makes the science feel meaningful rather than merely factual.'},
      {q:'The passage says the tree \'faces a calculation\'. What literary device is this, and what effect does it create?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['It is alliteration because \'faces\' and \'calculation\' start with similar sounds, creating a rhythmic echo that draws the reader\'s ear to the financial language in the paragraph.','It is hyperbole because trees cannot actually do mathematics — the author deliberately exaggerates the tree\'s ability to overstate how much energy chlorophyll production requires.','It is a simile comparing the tree to a calculator, using the word \'like\' implicitly to suggest that biological processes resemble human arithmetic.','It is personification — attributing rational decision-making to a tree — which helps the reader understand the biological process as purposeful and strategic rather than random.'],c:3,e:'Personification gives the tree agency and intelligence. While trees do not literally calculate, the biological process functions as if they do — weighing the cost of maintaining leaves against the benefit of reclaiming nutrients. This literary device makes the science more intuitive and the tree more sympathetic as a character in its own survival story.'},
      {q:'What theme does the passage develop about appearances versus reality?',skill:'Theme',opts:['That reality always matches what we see at first glance — autumn colours are exactly what they appear to be, simple visual signals that winter is approaching.','That death and decay are the only possible interpretations of change — the browning of tannins proves that autumn is fundamentally a process of decomposition with no survival value.','That what appears to be decay and death (autumn colour) is actually evidence of active, intelligent survival — things are not always what they seem on the surface.','That autumn colours are purely decorative and have no biological function — carotenoids and anthocyanins exist solely to attract animals that will spread the tree\'s seeds before winter.'],c:2,e:'The passage explicitly challenges the assumption that autumn colour means death: \'autumn colour is not, as many people assume, a sign of death. It is the opposite.\' This theme — that surface appearances can mislead us about underlying reality — runs throughout the passage and is reinforced by the reveal that carotenoids were \'hidden\' all summer.'},
      {q:'From whose perspective is the final paragraph written, and what effect does this have?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['It switches to first person as the author describes their own garden, sharing a personal anecdote about watching a specific maple tree change colour outside their kitchen window.','It is written from the perspective of a tree describing its own experience of withdrawing chlorophyll, giving the passage an intimate first-person voice in its closing lines.','It is narrated by a scientist conducting an experiment in a laboratory, measuring the exact nitrogen content of individual leaves as they change from green to brown.','It shifts to address the reader directly (\'When you see a hillside blazing...\'), which transforms the passage from an abstract science explanation into a personal invitation to see the world differently.'],c:3,e:'The shift to \'you\' in the final paragraph is significant. After five paragraphs of objective explanation, the author suddenly speaks to the reader, asking them to reinterpret something they see every year. This makes the science personal — the next time the reader sees autumn leaves, they will think differently about what is happening.'},
      {q:'Why does the author compare carotenoids to the pigments in carrots and bananas?',skill:'Inference',opts:['To argue that carrots and bananas change colour in autumn too, since all organisms containing carotenoids undergo the same seasonal pigment breakdown.','To suggest that carotenoids are only found in food, not in leaves — the author implies that trees absorb these pigments through their roots from decomposing fruit in the soil.','To prove that leaves are edible like carrots and bananas, since the shared carotenoid pigments mean autumn leaves contain the same nutrients as these common foods.','To connect an unfamiliar scientific term to everyday objects the reader already knows — making the chemistry feel accessible and helping the reader visualise the colour more concretely.'],c:3,e:'The comparison anchors abstract chemistry in everyday experience. A student might not know what \'carotenoids\' are, but they know what colour a carrot is. By linking the two, the author builds a bridge from the familiar to the unfamiliar, which is a core technique in effective science communication.'},
      {q:'The passage describes browning as \'evidence of a job completed\'. How does this phrase contribute to the passage\'s argument?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['It implies that brown leaves are the most beautiful stage of autumn, suggesting that tannins produce a richer, more complex visual display than the earlier reds and yellows.','It reframes the least attractive stage of autumn — brown, dead-looking leaves — as a positive outcome, completing the passage\'s argument that every stage of colour change is purposeful survival, not decay.','It means the browning process is incomplete and will reverse in spring, when the tree pushes new chlorophyll back into the same leaves to restore their green colour.','It suggests that trees have jobs and earn wages like humans, extending the personification to imply that nutrient withdrawal is a form of labour the tree performs for payment.'],c:1,e:'Brown leaves are typically seen as ugly and dead. By calling them \'evidence of a job completed\', the author applies the same reframing used throughout the passage. Even this final, least appealing stage is presented as purposeful. The phrase completes the argument: from green to brown, every change is part of the survival strategy.'}
  ]},
  {id:'NF08',title:'The Lost City of Pompeii',type:'nonfiction',source:'Original passage — history / archaeology / Vesuvius',
   text:'On the morning of 24 August, AD 79, the people of Pompeii went about their ordinary lives. Bakers lit their ovens. Merchants opened their shops. Children ran through the narrow streets, dodging donkeys loaded with goods. It was a prosperous Roman city of roughly eleven thousand people, built on the fertile slopes of a mountain they called Vesuvius. They knew it was a volcano — but it had been quiet for so long that most regarded it as harmless. The soil it produced was extraordinary for growing grapes, and the wine made from those grapes was famous across the empire.\n\nBy the following morning, the city no longer existed.\n\nThe eruption began around midday with a sound that witnesses described as louder than anything they had ever heard. A column of superheated ash, pumice, and gas shot twenty-five kilometres into the sky, blocking out the sun and plunging the region into darkness. For the next eighteen hours, volcanic debris rained down on Pompeii, burying the streets under nearly three metres of pumice stone. Many residents fled during this phase, but those who stayed — whether by choice, inability, or a belief that the worst was over — were killed in the final stages of the eruption, when a series of pyroclastic surges swept down the mountain.\n\nA pyroclastic surge is among the most terrifying phenomena in nature. It is a fast-moving cloud of superheated gas and rock fragments, travelling at speeds of up to seven hundred kilometres per hour and reaching temperatures above five hundred degrees Celsius. When the surges reached Pompeii, they killed every remaining living thing in the city within seconds. The heat was so intense that it vapourised soft tissue instantly.\n\nAnd then Pompeii vanished. Over the following centuries, additional eruptions buried the city deeper. Its location was forgotten. It was not until 1748 that systematic excavation began, revealing a city frozen in the middle of ordinary life. Archaeologists found loaves of bread still in ovens, election slogans painted on walls, pet dogs still chained to doorposts, and the plaster casts of human bodies preserved in the positions in which they died — a mother shielding her child, a man covering his mouth, a group huddled together in a cellar.\n\nPompeii is extraordinary not because of the disaster itself — volcanic eruptions are a geological fact — but because of what the burial preserved. Most ancient cities are known only through fragments: a broken pot here, a coin there. Pompeii offers something far rarer: a complete snapshot of daily life, frozen at a specific moment in time. We know what Pompeiians ate, how they decorated their homes, what jokes they scratched on walls, and how they voted in elections.\n\nIn destroying Pompeii, Vesuvius also preserved it — creating one of the most complete and haunting records of any civilisation in human history.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['The passage argues that Vesuvius remains an active threat today and that modern Naples should prepare for a similar eruption based on the geological evidence presented.','Pompeii was a minor, insignificant settlement whose destruction had little impact on the Roman Empire — the passage focuses on the eruption itself rather than the city\'s archaeological value.','The eruption of Vesuvius destroyed Pompeii but also preserved it — creating an unparalleled archaeological record of ancient Roman daily life.','The passage\'s main point is that systematic excavation beginning in 1748 has now recovered every possible artefact from Pompeii, leaving nothing further for archaeologists to discover.'],c:2,e:'The passage\'s central argument is the paradox stated in the final sentence: destruction and preservation happened simultaneously. The eruption killed everyone and buried the city, but in doing so it created a time capsule. This dual nature — tragedy and treasure — is the main idea.'},
      {q:'Why does the author begin with a description of ordinary morning life in Pompeii before the eruption?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['To establish that Pompeii\'s economy depended heavily on agriculture and trade, providing context for why the city\'s destruction had significant economic consequences across the wider Roman Empire.','To humanise the Pompeiians by showing their sophistication and cultural achievements, arguing that they were more advanced than most other Roman cities of the same period.','To create dramatic irony — the reader knows the disaster is coming but the people don\'t, making the contrast between their ordinary morning and their fate more powerful and emotionally engaging.','To demonstrate that the city\'s residents had no scientific understanding of volcanoes, which the author uses to argue that Roman society lacked the knowledge to prepare for natural disasters.'],c:2,e:'Opening with bakers, merchants, and children creates dramatic irony: the reader knows what these people don\'t. This makes the short sentence \'By the following morning, the city no longer existed\' devastatingly effective. The technique also connects to the passage\'s larger point — Pompeii is remarkable because it preserves exactly this kind of daily life.'},
      {q:'The passage includes specific numbers: twenty-five kilometres high, seven hundred kph, five hundred degrees Celsius. What purpose do these serve?',skill:'Analyse informational texts',opts:['They establish the author\'s credentials as a volcanologist rather than a historian, signalling that the passage is a scientific paper rather than a historical narrative about Pompeii\'s people.','They are included primarily to compare Vesuvius unfavourably with other volcanic eruptions around the world, suggesting that Pompeii\'s destruction was relatively minor by geological standards.','They are rough approximations that the passage presents as unreliable, warning the reader that ancient volcanic data should be treated with scepticism rather than accepted as precise fact.','They make the eruption\'s power concrete and measurable — without numbers, \'very hot and very fast\' is vague, but specific figures help the reader grasp the sheer scale and lethality of a pyroclastic surge.'],c:3,e:'Specific numbers transform abstract descriptions into measurable realities. \'Fast-moving cloud\' is vague; \'seven hundred kilometres per hour\' is visceral — the reader can compare it to things they know (a car, a plane). These figures serve the passage\'s informational purpose by making the science precise and the danger tangible.'},
      {q:'Pompeii is described as \'a complete snapshot of daily life, frozen at a specific moment in time\'. What does the word \'snapshot\' suggest?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['It suggests that the Romans themselves documented their city through paintings and mosaics that functioned like photographs, providing the archaeological evidence we rely on today.','Like a photograph that captures a single instant, the volcanic burial preserved Pompeii at one precise moment — making it a uniquely detailed and vivid record compared to the fragments that survive from most ancient cities.','The word emphasises the speed and violence of the eruption, suggesting the city was snapped apart like a physical object rather than gradually buried under layers of ash and pumice.','It implies that what archaeologists have uncovered is only a brief, incomplete glimpse of Pompeii — a superficial image rather than a deep understanding of how the city actually functioned.'],c:1,e:'A snapshot is a photograph taken in an instant, preserving everything exactly as it was. Applying this to Pompeii captures the uniqueness of the site: it doesn\'t show Roman life in general but Roman life at one specific moment on one specific day. This metaphor helps the reader understand why Pompeii is so valuable to archaeologists.'},
      {q:'The final sentence says \'In destroying Pompeii, Vesuvius also preserved it.\' Why does the author choose to end with this paradox?',skill:'Author\'s purpose',opts:['To suggest that all volcanic eruptions ultimately benefit humanity by preserving archaeological evidence, implying the deaths of the Pompeiians were a worthwhile sacrifice for historical knowledge.','To argue that modern archaeologists should rebury Pompeii under volcanic material to protect the site from weathering and tourist damage, just as Vesuvius originally preserved it.','The paradox captures the passage\'s central argument in a single memorable sentence — destruction and preservation are inseparable, making the reader rethink disaster as something that can simultaneously destroy and create.','Because the author wants to end on a note of scientific uncertainty, suggesting that researchers still cannot explain how volcanic ash preserved organic material like bread and wooden furniture.'],c:2,e:'Ending with a paradox gives the reader something to think about beyond the facts. The sentence is deliberately contradictory — destroying and preserving are opposites — which makes it memorable and thought-provoking. It encapsulates the entire passage\'s argument: Pompeii\'s tragedy is inseparable from its archaeological value.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about why many Pompeii residents did not flee during the initial eruption?',skill:'Inference',opts:['All residents deliberately chose to stay because Pompeiians worshipped Vesuvius as a god and believed the eruption was a sacred event that would bring blessings to those who remained.','The Roman military sealed the city gates and prevented evacuation, trapping the population inside as part of an imperial policy to protect valuable property from looters during natural disasters.','The eruption happened entirely at night while everyone was sleeping, so residents had no warning — however, the passage explicitly states it began around midday, which contradicts this reading.','The passage suggests multiple reasons: some may have been physically unable to leave, some chose to stay, and some believed the worst was over after the initial pumice fall — underestimating the deadly pyroclastic surges that followed.'],c:3,e:'The passage specifically notes people stayed \'whether by choice, inability, or a belief that the worst was over\'. This suggests a range of human responses to disaster — some couldn\'t leave (elderly, enslaved people), some chose to protect property, and some misjudged the danger. The passage avoids blaming the victims while explaining why they remained.'},
      {q:'What is the tone of the second paragraph — \'By the following morning, the city no longer existed\'?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Sarcastic and mocking — the blunt phrasing implies the author considers the Pompeiians foolish for living near a volcano and is dismissing their fate as predictable and avoidable.','Scientifically detached and clinical — the sentence reads like a geological report cataloguing eruption statistics, deliberately avoiding any human dimension or emotional weight.','Hopeful and forward-looking — the sentence implies that although the city was destroyed, its people survived and rebuilt elsewhere, giving the paragraph an uplifting conclusion.','Stark and devastating — the single short sentence after the vivid description of daily life creates a shocking tonal contrast that conveys the totality of the destruction with brutal simplicity.'],c:3,e:'This one-sentence paragraph is deliberately jarring. After the warm, human detail of the opening paragraph, the reader is hit with a flat, devastating statement. The contrast between the two paragraphs mirrors the contrast the Pompeiians experienced — between ordinary life and total annihilation. The tone conveys more through understatement than a dramatic description could.'},
      {q:'What theme does the passage develop about the relationship between destruction and preservation?',skill:'Theme',opts:['That human memory is ultimately more powerful than physical evidence — the passage suggests that oral histories and written accounts of Pompeii matter more than the archaeological remains themselves.','That natural disasters serve a necessary ecological purpose by clearing away old civilisations and making room for new cultural developments to emerge in their place.','That destruction and preservation can be inseparable — the same volcanic eruption that killed thousands also created an unparalleled historical record, suggesting that loss and legacy are sometimes two sides of the same event.','That preservation requires active intervention from modern scientists — without deliberate archaeological excavation, the buried city would have had no historical significance whatsoever.'],c:2,e:'The passage builds towards its central paradox: \'In destroying Pompeii, Vesuvius also preserved it.\' This theme challenges simple narratives about disaster being purely negative. The eruption was catastrophic for those who lived through it, but it gave future generations an irreplaceable window into the past. The theme asks us to hold both truths simultaneously.'},
      {q:'The passage lists specific archaeological finds: \'loaves of bread still in ovens, election slogans painted on walls, pet dogs still chained to doorposts\'. What literary technique is this, and what effect does it achieve?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['It is alliteration — the repeated sounds in \'loaves\', \'election\', and \'pet\' create a rhythmic pattern that makes the list of archaeological finds more poetic and musical than informative.','It is an extended metaphor comparing Pompeii to a museum exhibit, suggesting the city was deliberately arranged for display rather than discovered in its natural buried state.','It is an accumulation of concrete, everyday details that makes the ancient city feel real and human — each item represents a frozen moment of ordinary life, which is more emotionally powerful than abstract descriptions of Roman culture.','It is hyperbole — the author deliberately exaggerates the preservation of everyday items to make Pompeii seem more dramatic than other archaeological sites that have yielded similar finds.'],c:2,e:'The accumulation of specific, mundane details is highly effective. Bread in ovens, slogans on walls, and chained dogs are not grand historical artefacts — they are traces of everyday life interrupted mid-action. This specificity makes the ancient Romans feel like real people rather than distant historical figures, which deepens the emotional impact of the disaster.'},
      {q:'From what point of view does the author present the Pompeiians, and how does this affect the reader\'s response?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['The author writes from the perspective of Vesuvius itself, personifying the volcano as a conscious force that deliberately chose to destroy the city it had nurtured with fertile soil.','The author presents the Pompeiians as reckless people who ignored obvious warning signs from the volcano, creating a tone of blame that suggests their destruction was largely self-inflicted.','The author presents the Pompeiians as ordinary, relatable people going about their daily lives — bakers, merchants, children — which makes the reader empathise with them and feel the tragedy more keenly than if they were presented as distant historical figures.','The author presents the Pompeiians as wealthy aristocrats focused on luxury and wine production, emphasising their privilege to create emotional distance between them and the modern reader.'],c:2,e:'By choosing to show bakers, merchants, and children rather than emperors or senators, the author makes the Pompeiians universally relatable. The reader can imagine themselves in that morning scene. This humanising perspective makes the destruction feel personal and tragic rather than merely historical, which is essential to the passage\'s emotional impact.'},
      {q:'Why does the passage contrast Pompeii with \'most ancient cities\' that are \'known only through fragments\'?',skill:'Inference',opts:['To suggest that archaeologists have been wasting resources on less productive sites and should redirect all funding and attention exclusively to Pompeii and similar volcanic burial sites.','To help the reader understand what makes Pompeii uniquely valuable — without this comparison, the reader might not appreciate how rare it is to have such a complete picture of an ancient civilisation\'s daily life.','To argue that broken pots and scattered coins from other ancient cities are fabricated or unreliable evidence, making Pompeii the only trustworthy source of information about the ancient world.','To prove that no other ancient Roman city has ever been excavated, positioning Pompeii as the sole source of all knowledge about how Romans lived, worked, and governed.'],c:1,e:'The comparison provides essential context. A student might not automatically understand why Pompeii matters more than other ruins. By explaining that most ancient cities yield only \'a broken pot here, a coin there\', the author frames Pompeii as extraordinary — a complete snapshot versus scattered fragments. The contrast makes the site\'s significance immediately clear.'},
      {q:'The passage describes plaster casts of bodies \'preserved in the positions in which they died — a mother shielding her child\'. What effect does this specific detail create?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['It proves that Roman family structures placed mothers in charge of child safety during emergencies, reflecting a formal social policy about parental roles during volcanic eruptions.','It creates a deeply human and emotional image that transcends the historical distance — the universal instinct of a parent protecting their child makes the ancient tragedy feel immediate and personal to the modern reader.','It is included as clinical forensic evidence to demonstrate the temperature of the pyroclastic surge, showing that bodies were preserved because the heat killed them before they could change position.','It suggests that the plaster casting technique invented in the 1800s distorted the original body positions, meaning the poses we see today may not reflect what actually happened during the eruption.'],c:1,e:'Of all the details the author could have chosen, a mother shielding her child is the most universally resonant. Every reader, regardless of age or background, can understand this instinct. The detail collapses the 2,000-year gap between the reader and the Pompeiians, making the ancient tragedy feel present and real. It is the passage\'s most emotionally powerful moment.'}
  ]},
  {id:'NF09',title:'The Lost Land of Doggerland',type:'nonfiction',source:'Original passage — prehistory / geography / archaeology',
   text:'Between roughly 12,000 and 8,000 years ago, you could have walked from England to the Netherlands without getting your feet wet. Where the North Sea now lies, there was land — a vast, low-lying territory of marshes, rivers, forests, and open grassland that archaeologists have named Doggerland, after the Dogger Bank, a shallow area of the North Sea where fishing trawlers have been hauling up ancient bones and stone tools for over a century.\n\nDoggerland was not empty. It was home to communities of Mesolithic hunter-gatherers who lived along its rivers, fished in its lakes, and hunted the red deer and wild boar that roamed its forests. Archaeological evidence — including harpoon points, flint blades, and the remains of campsites found on the seabed — suggests that it was one of the most densely populated regions in Europe at the time. Far from being a marginal swamp, Doggerland was the heartland.\n\nSo what happened to it? The answer is climate change — not the kind caused by humans, but the natural warming that ended the last Ice Age. As global temperatures rose, the enormous ice sheets that had covered much of northern Europe began to melt. Sea levels rose — not suddenly, but steadily, generation by generation. The coastline crept inward. Rivers swelled. Low-lying land that had been dry for thousands of years was gradually swallowed by the advancing North Sea.\n\nFor the people living there, the change would have been slow enough to adapt to within a single lifetime but fast enough to notice. A fishing camp that your grandfather used might be underwater by the time you were old enough to fish. Forests where your family had hunted for generations would become marshes, then mudflats, then open sea. It was not a catastrophe but a long, slow erasure.\n\nThe final blow may have come around 6,200 BC. Geologists have found evidence of a massive underwater landslide — called the Storegga Slide — off the coast of Norway, which triggered a tsunami that swept across the remaining low-lying areas of Doggerland. Any land that had survived the rising seas was likely devastated by this single event. Within a few centuries, Doggerland was gone. Britain became an island.\n\nToday, the evidence of this lost world lies beneath the waves. Fishing boats still occasionally dredge up Mesolithic tools and animal bones from the seabed. In 2019, a team of researchers used seismic survey data to map the ancient landscape in extraordinary detail, revealing river valleys, coastlines, and what appear to be the locations of settlements — a ghost map of a country that no longer exists.\n\nDoggerland is a reminder that the world we know is not the world that has always been — and that the ground beneath our feet is less permanent than we like to believe.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['Doggerland was primarily a temporary land bridge used by migrating animals, with little evidence of permanent human settlement — its disappearance was caused by a single catastrophic tsunami event.','The passage focuses on the geological formation of the North Sea basin, tracing how tectonic plate movements over millions of years gradually created the body of water that now separates Britain from mainland Europe.','A vast inhabited land once connected Britain to Europe but was gradually submerged by rising seas after the last Ice Age — its rediscovery challenges our assumptions about the permanence of geography.','Modern archaeological technology has allowed researchers to fully excavate Doggerland\'s seabed settlements, providing a complete picture of Mesolithic life that confirms earlier historical assumptions about prehistoric Europe.'],c:2,e:'The passage explains what Doggerland was (inhabited, important), how it was lost (climate change, sea level rise, tsunami), and what its rediscovery means (geography is impermanent). The main idea combines historical fact with a broader lesson about how landscapes change over time.'},
      {q:'How is this passage structured?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['Chronological narrative followed by evaluation — the passage traces Doggerland\'s history from its formation through its flooding, then evaluates the competing scientific theories about what caused its final disappearance.','Description, explanation, evidence — the passage describes Doggerland, explains how it was lost, and presents modern archaeological evidence of its existence.','Problem and solution — the passage identifies the mystery of Doggerland\'s disappearance as a problem and then presents the archaeological methods researchers have developed to solve it.','Compare and contrast — the passage systematically compares Doggerland\'s ancient landscape with the modern North Sea environment, examining what has changed and what geographical features remain.'],c:1,e:'The passage follows a clear three-part structure: what Doggerland was (paragraphs 1–2), how it disappeared (paragraphs 3–5), and what evidence survives today (paragraph 6). Each section serves a different purpose — imagination, explanation, and proof — building a complete picture.'},
      {q:'The disappearance of Doggerland is described as \'not a catastrophe but a long, slow erasure\'. Why does the author choose the word \'erasure\'?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['\'Erasure\' emphasises the role of human activity in Doggerland\'s destruction — it implies that people living there contributed to the flooding through deforestation and land mismanagement over many generations.','\'Erasure\' suggests something being gradually removed until it no longer exists — like rubbing out pencil marks, the sea slowly deleted the land, making the process feel deliberate and irreversible rather than dramatic.','\'Erasure\' creates a sense of violent, sudden destruction that mirrors the Storegga tsunami — it conveys the forceful, dramatic nature of how the sea overwhelmed the land in a single catastrophic event.','\'Erasure\' highlights the scientific precision of the geological process — it is a measured, clinical term that reflects the author\'s intention to keep the description factual and emotionally neutral throughout the passage.'],c:1,e:'\'Erasure\' is more evocative than \'flooding\' or \'submersion\'. It suggests careful, gradual removal — like wiping a whiteboard clean. The word implies completeness (nothing left) and irreversibility (you can\'t un-erase). It also contrasts effectively with the tsunami paragraph that follows, where the final blow is sudden rather than slow.'},
      {q:'The passage says Doggerland\'s change was \'slow enough to adapt to within a single lifetime but fast enough to notice\'. What does this paradox help the reader understand?',skill:'Analyse informational texts',opts:['It explains why Doggerland\'s communities developed advanced boat-building technology — they needed watercraft to keep pace with the rapidly shifting coastline and maintain connections between settlements.','It illustrates the scientific debate about whether Doggerland\'s inhabitants migrated willingly to higher ground or were forced out by sudden flooding events that gave them no time to prepare.','It demonstrates that the flooding was so gradual it had no real impact on daily life — the inhabitants simply moved their camps a few metres each year without any sense of disruption or loss.','It captures the human experience of gradual environmental change — the people weren\'t overwhelmed by a single disaster but watched their world slowly shrink, which is a different and perhaps more unsettling kind of loss.'],c:3,e:'The paradox puts the reader in the shoes of Doggerland\'s inhabitants. A sudden flood is terrifying but brief. Watching your grandfather\'s fishing camp slowly disappear over decades is a different kind of loss — a slow grief. This human-scale description makes an abstract geological process emotionally real.'},
      {q:'The researchers\' map of Doggerland is described as \'a ghost map of a country that no longer exists\'. Why does the author use this phrase?',skill:'Author\'s purpose',opts:['The phrase is evocative and haunting — \'ghost map\' suggests something that exists only as a trace or shadow of what once was, making the reader feel the weight of what has been lost and the strangeness of mapping a vanished world.','The phrase emphasises the technical achievement of the researchers — \'ghost map\' highlights the sophisticated seismic technology required to produce accurate underwater surveys of ancient geological formations.','The phrase critiques the limitations of modern archaeology — \'ghost\' implies that the map is speculative and unreliable, warning the reader not to accept the findings as confirmed historical fact.','The phrase draws attention to the political implications of the discovery — by calling it a \'country\', the author suggests Doggerland should be recognised as a lost nation with significant cultural heritage.'],c:0,e:'\'Ghost map\' is a powerful two-word image. Ghosts are traces of things that no longer exist physically but haven\'t fully disappeared. A ghost map suggests something caught between presence and absence — the river valleys and settlements are real, but the land that contained them is gone. This captures both the achievement of the research and the poignancy of what it reveals.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about why the passage opens with the striking image of walking from England to the Netherlands?',skill:'Inference',opts:['To suggest that a physical land bridge still exists just below the surface of the North Sea and could be uncovered again if sea levels were to drop by even a small amount.','To immediately challenge the reader\'s assumptions about geography — the idea of walking between two countries now separated by sea grabs attention and establishes that the world was once fundamentally different from how it appears today.','To prove that the distance between England and the Netherlands is negligible, implying that the North Sea is so shallow it barely qualifies as a real body of water.','Because the author is arguing that ancient Mesolithic people regularly commuted between England and the Netherlands for trade, making the walk a routine daily journey rather than a striking concept.'],c:1,e:'The opening is designed to create cognitive dissonance. The reader knows you cannot walk from England to the Netherlands — so the claim that you once could immediately challenges their view of the world. This hooks the reader and sets up the passage\'s larger theme: geography is not permanent.'},
      {q:'What is the tone of the phrase \'not a catastrophe but a long, slow erasure\'?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Humorous and light-hearted — the phrase treats the flooding of Doggerland as an amusing geographical curiosity, using playful language to entertain the reader rather than evoke any sense of loss.','Melancholic and reflective — the phrase conveys a quiet sadness about gradual loss that is more unsettling than a dramatic disaster because it was slow enough to witness but impossible to prevent.','Angry and accusatory — the phrase blames the Mesolithic inhabitants for failing to build sea defences that could have prevented the flooding and preserved their homeland for future generations.','Urgent and alarming — the phrase is a warning about modern climate change, using Doggerland as evidence that current coastal cities will soon suffer the same rapid submersion.'],c:1,e:'The tone here is contemplative rather than dramatic. A catastrophe is sudden and violent; an erasure is gradual and quiet. The melancholic quality comes from the helplessness implied — the people of Doggerland could watch their world shrinking but could do nothing to stop it. This understated tone is more emotionally effective than dramatic language would be.'},
      {q:'What theme does the passage develop about the permanence of the world around us?',skill:'Theme',opts:['That the physical world we take for granted — continents, coastlines, islands — is far less permanent than we assume, and that landscapes can change dramatically over timescales that are long for humans but short in geological terms.','That only human activity such as deforestation and farming can alter coastlines — the passage implies that natural climate change alone would not have been powerful enough to submerge Doggerland.','That the North Sea is a permanent and unchanging feature of European geography — the passage treats it as a fixed boundary that has always separated Britain from the continent.','That geographical change only occurs through sudden catastrophic events like tsunamis — the passage argues that gradual sea-level rise alone could never have submerged an entire landmass.'],c:0,e:'The final sentence makes this theme explicit: \'the ground beneath our feet is less permanent than we like to believe.\' The entire passage builds towards this realisation — a populated, thriving landmass was completely erased by rising seas. The theme challenges the reader\'s instinctive belief that the map they know is the map that has always been.'},
      {q:'The passage uses the example of \'a fishing camp that your grandfather used\' being underwater. What literary device is this?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['It is an example of alliteration — the repeated \'f\' sounds in \'fishing\' and \'family\' create a soothing rhythm that makes the experience of losing land to the sea sound pleasant and musical.','It is a hypothetical personal scenario that puts the reader in the shoes of a Doggerland inhabitant — by using \'your grandfather\', it makes the abstract process of sea-level rise feel intimate and generational.','It is a factual account of one specific Mesolithic family whose fishing camp was excavated from the seabed, providing direct archaeological evidence of the generational impact of rising seas.','It is a metaphor comparing the submerged fishing camp to a deceased grandparent, suggesting that landscapes die and are mourned in the same way that family members are.'],c:1,e:'The author shifts from geological abstraction to human-scale storytelling. By saying \'your grandfather\', the reader is placed inside a Doggerland family, watching the landscape change across generations. This technique transforms a process that took thousands of years into something emotionally comprehensible within a few sentences.'},
      {q:'From the evidence presented, what can you infer about the sophistication of Doggerland\'s inhabitants?',skill:'Inference',opts:['They were primitive nomads who wandered randomly across the landscape without any technology, surviving purely on foraged plants and lacking the intelligence to craft tools or establish settlements.','They had developed metal-working, agriculture, and written language thousands of years before other European societies, making Doggerland the most advanced civilisation of the prehistoric world.','The archaeological evidence of harpoon points, flint blades, and campsites suggests they were skilled toolmakers and organised communities — not primitive wanderers but people adapted to their environment with specialised technology.','They were settled farmers who grew wheat and barley and raised domesticated cattle — the passage\'s mention of \'open grassland\' implies they had already cleared forests to create agricultural fields.'],c:2,e:'The passage mentions specific artefacts — harpoon points (for fishing), flint blades (for cutting), and campsites (indicating organised settlement). Each of these implies skill, planning, and community organisation. The passage also calls Doggerland \'the heartland\' and \'one of the most densely populated regions in Europe\', reinforcing that these were thriving, capable communities.'},
      {q:'Why does the author mention the Storegga Slide tsunami as \'the final blow\'?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['Because tsunamis are always the last stage of any sea-level rise event, following a fixed geological sequence that the author is accurately documenting as scientific fact.','To prove that the Storegga tsunami was the sole cause of Doggerland\'s disappearance, dismissing the centuries of gradual sea-level rise as irrelevant to the land\'s eventual submersion.','The phrase personifies the geological process as a deliberate attack, and the word \'final\' suggests a narrative of cumulative damage — rising seas weakened Doggerland over millennia, and the tsunami delivered the finishing strike.','Because \'final blow\' is a standard geological term used in academic papers about tsunamis, and the author is quoting directly from the scientific research on the Storegga Slide.'],c:2,e:'The phrase \'final blow\' comes from fighting or boxing — it is the strike that ends the contest. By using this metaphor, the author frames the gradual flooding as a long battle that Doggerland was losing, with the Storegga tsunami as the knockout punch. This narrative structure makes the geological history feel dramatic and story-like.'},
      {q:'How does the passage\'s point of view shift between the historical and the modern sections?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['The passage shifts from an imaginative reconstruction of the past (walking to the Netherlands, your grandfather\'s fishing camp) to a modern scientific perspective (seismic surveys, 2019 research teams), grounding speculation in hard evidence.','There is no shift in perspective — the passage maintains a strictly scientific tone from beginning to end, never asking the reader to imagine or emotionally engage with the lost landscape.','The passage is written entirely as a first-person account by a Mesolithic hunter-gatherer who personally witnessed Doggerland\'s flooding, giving it the immediacy of an eyewitness memoir.','The modern section is written from the perspective of the North Sea itself, personifying the water as a conscious entity that chose to claim the land and now guards its secrets on the seabed.'],c:0,e:'The passage uses two distinct modes. The historical sections ask the reader to imagine Doggerland as a living place, using sensory and personal details. The modern sections present concrete scientific evidence — seismic data, mapped river valleys, dredged artefacts. This shift from imagination to evidence strengthens the argument by supporting the speculative reconstruction with hard facts.'}
  ]},
  {id:'NF10',title:'The Great Stink of London',type:'nonfiction',source:'Original passage — Victorian engineering / public health / Thames',
   text:'In the summer of 1858, the smell coming from the River Thames was so overpowering that Parliament could not function. Members of the House of Commons, whose chamber overlooked the river, hung sheets soaked in chloride of lime across the windows in a desperate attempt to block the stench. It didn\'t work. The curtains turned brown. Committees were abandoned. One MP described the odour as \'a pestilence that would make strong men weep.\' The press called it the Great Stink, and it would change London forever.\n\nThe cause was grimly simple. London\'s population had exploded during the Industrial Revolution, growing from one million in 1800 to nearly three million by the 1850s. But the city\'s waste disposal system had not kept pace. Raw sewage from homes, factories, and slaughterhouses poured directly into the Thames — the same river from which many Londoners drew their drinking water. In the searing heat of that summer, the river essentially became an open sewer, and the smell that rose from it was the smell of an entire city\'s waste baking in the sun.\n\nThe consequences went far beyond discomfort. Cholera — a devastating waterborne disease that causes severe dehydration and can kill within hours — had already swept through London four times, most recently in 1854. A doctor named John Snow had demonstrated, through careful mapping of cases, that cholera spread through contaminated water rather than through the air, as most people believed. But his findings were largely ignored by the authorities, who continued to blame the disease on \'miasma\' — bad-smelling air.\n\nThe Great Stink changed this, though not quite for the right reasons. Parliament didn\'t act because it accepted Snow\'s science. It acted because MPs couldn\'t breathe. The smell — which was, ironically, not the actual cause of cholera — was so unbearable that it finally forced the government to fund a solution. Within eighteen days of the stink reaching its worst, Parliament approved funding for a vast new sewer system designed by the engineer Joseph Bazalgette.\n\nBazalgette\'s design was revolutionary. He constructed over 1,300 miles of underground sewers beneath London\'s streets, intercepting waste before it reached the Thames and carrying it eastward to treatment works far downstream. The system was built using 318 million bricks and took seven years to complete. When it was finished, cholera deaths in London dropped dramatically — not because the smell was gone, but because the water was clean.\n\nThe Great Stink is one of history\'s stranger turning points. Parliament solved a genuine public health crisis — but for the wrong reason. They acted to escape a smell, not to save lives. The smell was not dangerous; the invisible bacteria in the water were. Sometimes, it seems, progress happens not because people understand the problem, but because the problem becomes too unpleasant to ignore.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['London\'s catastrophic sewage problem was only addressed when the smell became unbearable to Parliament — the right solution was implemented, but for the wrong reasons, creating an ironic turning point in public health history.','The passage primarily celebrates John Snow as a scientific hero whose cholera research was quickly adopted by Parliament and led directly to the construction of the sewer system.','The passage argues that the Great Stink was caused by industrial pollution from factories rather than human sewage, and that Parliament acted to protect the economy rather than for personal comfort.','The passage focuses on Joseph Bazalgette\'s engineering genius as its central theme, presenting the political and scientific context only as background to his architectural achievement.'],c:0,e:'The passage\'s central irony drives its main idea: Parliament funded Bazalgette\'s sewers not because they understood cholera science (Snow\'s work was ignored) but because the smell was intolerable. The solution worked — cholera deaths dropped — but the motivation was comfort, not understanding. This makes it a turning point built on misunderstanding.'},
      {q:'How is this passage structured?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['Cause, complication, ironic resolution — the passage explains the cause of the crisis, the scientific misunderstanding that delayed action, and the ironic reason action was finally taken.','Compare and contrast — the passage alternates between John Snow\'s scientific approach and Bazalgette\'s engineering approach, weighing which contribution mattered more to London\'s survival.','Strict chronological order — the passage narrates events year by year from 1800 to 1865, with each paragraph covering a specific date in the timeline of the cholera epidemic.','Persuasive argument — the author builds a case that Parliament was morally responsible for cholera deaths and should have acted sooner, using evidence and rhetorical appeals to convince the reader.'],c:0,e:'The passage builds in layers: the crisis (paragraphs 1–2), the ignored science (paragraph 3), the ironic trigger for action (paragraph 4), and the solution (paragraph 5). The final paragraph ties everything together with the central irony. This structure creates a narrative arc that is more engaging than a simple timeline.'},
      {q:'The passage explains that Parliament \'didn\'t act because it accepted Snow\'s science\' but \'because MPs couldn\'t breathe\'. What does this distinction reveal?',skill:'Analyse informational texts',opts:['That Parliament had already accepted Snow\'s waterborne theory but needed the smell as a convenient excuse to justify the enormous cost of Bazalgette\'s sewer project to the public.','That political action is often driven by immediate discomfort rather than evidence — the government ignored scientific proof for years but responded within days when personally affected by the smell.','That MPs understood the science perfectly well but were too distracted by other political matters to prioritise public health until the stench interrupted their parliamentary sessions.','That Snow\'s miasma theory was eventually proven correct — the smell itself was spreading cholera through the air, which is why removing the smell from Parliament\'s vicinity stopped the epidemic.'],c:1,e:'This is the passage\'s sharpest insight. Snow had the evidence for years, but abstract data about waterborne disease didn\'t move Parliament. The smell — which was ironically not the actual danger — motivated immediate action because it affected the decision-makers personally. The passage asks whether this pattern (ignoring evidence until discomfort forces action) is a wider human tendency.'},
      {q:'The final sentence says \'progress happens not because people understand the problem, but because the problem becomes too unpleasant to ignore\'. What makes this an effective conclusion?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['It is a restatement of John Snow\'s cholera hypothesis in modern language, reminding the reader that waterborne disease was the true cause of the crisis rather than the smell that motivated Parliament.','It generalises from the specific story to a broader truth about human nature and how change happens — transforming a Victorian history lesson into a relevant observation about politics, science, and motivation.','It is a direct criticism of modern politicians, arguing that today\'s governments are repeating Parliament\'s 1858 mistake by ignoring scientific evidence about current public health threats.','It celebrates Parliament\'s wisdom in finally acting, suggesting that responding to unpleasant conditions is actually the most rational and effective form of decision-making.'],c:1,e:'The final sentence lifts the passage from a historical anecdote to a universal observation. It invites the reader to consider whether this pattern — ignoring evidence until the problem becomes personally uncomfortable — applies beyond Victorian London. This gives the passage relevance beyond its historical subject.'},
      {q:'Why does the author include the detail that Parliament approved funding \'within eighteen days\' of the stink reaching its worst?',skill:'Author\'s purpose',opts:['To suggest that Bazalgette\'s entire sewer network was designed and constructed in just eighteen days, emphasising the urgency and speed of Victorian engineering.','To prove that Parliament was efficient and well-organised, since eighteen days shows how quickly the government could respond when it chose to prioritise infrastructure investment.','To show that eighteen days was far too long to wait when thousands of Londoners were already dying from cholera in their homes and neighbourhoods.','To emphasise the contrast between years of inaction on cholera and the speed of response to personal discomfort — highlighting the irony that smell succeeded where science had failed.'],c:3,e:'The speed is the point. John Snow\'s cholera evidence was ignored for years. The Great Stink produced action in eighteen days. This timeframe makes the irony concrete and measurable: personal discomfort motivated the government faster than thousands of preventable deaths had. The detail is a quiet, devastating critique of political priorities.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about why Parliament acted so quickly once the smell became unbearable, despite ignoring cholera for years?',skill:'Inference',opts:['Because the MPs themselves were directly affected by the smell — cholera killed poor Londoners in distant neighbourhoods, but the stench invaded Parliament itself, making the problem impossible to ignore or delegate.','Because Queen Victoria personally ordered Parliament to address the smell after it reached Buckingham Palace, forcing MPs to respond to royal pressure rather than public need.','Because John Snow presented his cholera map directly to Parliament in 1858 and MPs finally accepted that contaminated water, not miasma, was the true cause of the epidemic.','Because Parliament had been gradually developing a public health strategy since the first cholera outbreak and the Great Stink simply provided the final piece of evidence they needed.'],c:0,e:'The key inference is about proximity and self-interest. Cholera affected the poor, whose suffering was geographically and socially distant from MPs. The smell, however, penetrated Parliament\'s own chambers. The passage implies that people in power often act only when a problem affects them personally — a sharp political observation embedded in the historical narrative.'},
      {q:'What theme does the passage develop about the relationship between understanding and action?',skill:'Theme',opts:['That incorrect motivations always lead to incorrect solutions — since Parliament acted to escape a smell rather than to fight cholera, the sewer system must have been fundamentally flawed in its design.','That scientific understanding always leads directly to political action — once Snow mapped the cholera outbreaks, Parliament immediately recognised the need for clean water infrastructure.','That correct action does not always require correct understanding — Parliament built the right solution (sewers) for the wrong reason (smell, not bacteria), suggesting that progress can occur even when the underlying science is misunderstood.','That Victorian politicians were more responsive to scientific evidence than modern leaders, since Parliament eventually did build the sewer system that Snow\'s research demanded.'],c:2,e:'The passage\'s central irony reveals a theme about how progress actually works. John Snow understood cholera correctly but couldn\'t motivate action. The smell, which was not the actual danger, succeeded where science failed. The theme suggests that the path to progress is messier and more accidental than we might like to believe.'},
      {q:'What is the tone of the passage when describing Parliament\'s response to the smell?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Neutral and purely factual — the author presents details like MPs hanging chloride-soaked curtains and abandoning committees as straightforward historical reporting without any implied commentary.','Sympathetic and understanding of the terrible smell, emphasising how unbearable conditions in the chamber forced reasonable people to act under extreme duress.','Wryly ironic — the author describes MPs fleeing from a smell with understated mockery, highlighting the absurdity that discomfort motivated them faster than thousands of deaths.','Angry and accusatory, the author openly condemns Parliament for ignoring Snow\'s evidence and directly states that MPs were responsible for thousands of preventable cholera deaths.'],c:2,e:'The tone is not overtly critical but quietly devastating. Details like \'curtains turned brown\', \'committees were abandoned\', and the eighteen-day turnaround are presented factually but carry an ironic edge. The author lets the facts speak for themselves — the contrast between years of inaction on cholera and days of action on smell conveys judgement without stating it directly.'},
      {q:'The passage describes the Thames as \'an open sewer\'. What literary device is this?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['It is understatement because the Thames was far worse than any ordinary sewer — with waste from three million people baking in summer heat, the word \'sewer\' understates the horrifying reality.','It is a simile because the phrase uses the comparison word \'as\' in \'became an open sewer\' to liken the river to a sewage channel, creating a vivid image through indirect comparison.','It is a metaphor that vividly conveys the river\'s condition — a river should carry fresh water, but calling it an open sewer immediately communicates the horrifying reversal of its natural function.','It is personification because describing the Thames as \'open\' suggests the river deliberately chose to reveal London\'s waste, giving it the human quality of intentional exposure.'],c:2,e:'Calling the Thames \'an open sewer\' is a metaphor that works through shocking contrast. Rivers represent life, freshness, and nature; sewers represent waste and disease. Combining the two creates a vivid image of how badly London had failed to manage its own growth. The metaphor is more powerful than simply saying \'the river was very dirty\'.'},
      {q:'From the passage, what can you infer about John Snow\'s social standing or influence at the time?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['Snow was celebrated as a national hero during his lifetime, with Parliament publicly crediting his cholera map as the reason for commissioning Bazalgette\'s sewers.','Snow was a senior government health adviser whose cholera research was officially commissioned by Parliament and carried the authority of the Prime Minister\'s office.','Snow was a Member of Parliament who used his voting power to push for sewer funding, but was outnumbered by colleagues who believed miasma theory explained cholera outbreaks.','Despite being scientifically correct, Snow lacked sufficient political influence to change government policy — his findings were \'largely ignored by the authorities\', suggesting that being right is not always enough to create change.'],c:3,e:'The passage tells us Snow \'demonstrated, through careful mapping\' that cholera was waterborne, yet his findings were \'largely ignored\'. This implies a gap between scientific truth and political power. Snow could prove his case but could not force action — a position that many scientists throughout history have found themselves in when challenging established beliefs.'},
      {q:'Why does the author include the specific detail that Bazalgette used \'318 million bricks\'?',skill:'Inference',opts:['To suggest that the project was wasteful and used too many resources — Bazalgette over-engineered the system, spending far more than Parliament had authorised in its original eighteen-day funding approval.','Because the exact brick count proves that Bazalgette personally inspected every brick before it was laid, demonstrating his obsessive attention to quality control throughout the seven-year build.','To prove that bricks are the best building material for sewers, since the system\'s longevity compared to wooden or stone alternatives demonstrates their superior resistance to sewage corrosion.','To convey the enormous scale of the engineering project — the specific number makes the achievement feel concrete and impressive, helping the reader appreciate the ambition and effort required to solve the crisis.'],c:3,e:'The number 318 million is staggering and almost unimaginable, which is exactly the point. It transforms \'Bazalgette built sewers\' into something the reader can marvel at. The specific figure also contrasts with the vagueness of the political response, suggesting that while politicians dithered, the engineer delivered something precise and monumental.'},
      {q:'The passage says cholera deaths dropped \'not because the smell was gone, but because the water was clean\'. What is the significance of this distinction?',skill:'Theme',opts:['It suggests the sewer system was a failure because it was built for the wrong reason — since Parliament targeted smell rather than bacteria, the sewers could not have effectively reduced cholera.','It means Parliament deserves full credit for understanding the science of cholera, since approving Bazalgette\'s sewers within eighteen days shows that MPs had privately accepted Snow\'s waterborne theory.','It proves that smell has no connection to hygiene whatsoever — the Thames could have remained foul-smelling and Londoners would still have been safe, since odour and disease are entirely unrelated.','It reinforces the passage\'s central irony — the solution worked for scientific reasons (clean water) that Parliament never intended, proving that the right outcome can emerge from the wrong reasoning.'],c:3,e:'This distinction is the passage\'s sharpest point. The sewers solved cholera not because Parliament understood the disease but because Bazalgette\'s engineering happened to address the real cause. The sentence crystallises the entire passage\'s argument: sometimes progress happens accidentally, when the right solution is implemented for the wrong reason.'}
  ]},
  {id:'NF11',title:'How the Printing Press Changed Everything',type:'nonfiction',source:'Original passage — history / technology / Gutenberg',
   text:'Before 1440, if you wanted a copy of a book, someone had to write it out by hand. Every word, every page, every letter — copied with a quill pen by a scribe who might spend months or even years on a single volume. Books were extraordinarily expensive. A Bible could cost as much as a house. Most people would never touch one, let alone own one. Knowledge was locked inside monasteries, universities, and the libraries of the very wealthy.\n\nThen Johannes Gutenberg, a German goldsmith from Mainz, invented something that would reshape the world: the movable-type printing press. The idea itself was not entirely new — the Chinese had been using carved woodblock printing for centuries — but Gutenberg\'s innovation was to create individual metal letters that could be rearranged and reused. A printer could set a page of text using these movable letters, ink the surface, press paper onto it, and produce dozens of identical copies in the time it would have taken a scribe to write a single page.\n\nThe effect was explosive. Within fifty years of Gutenberg\'s first printed Bible in 1455, there were printing presses in every major European city, and an estimated twenty million books had been produced. By 1500, that number had risen to an almost inconceivable two hundred million. For the first time in human history, ideas could spread faster than a person could walk.\n\nThe consequences rippled outward in every direction. Martin Luther\'s ninety-five theses — his challenge to the Catholic Church — were printed and distributed across Germany within weeks, helping to trigger the Protestant Reformation. Scientific discoveries could now be shared accurately between researchers in different countries, accelerating the pace of innovation. Pamphlets and newspapers appeared, giving ordinary people access to information that had previously been controlled by elites. Literacy rates, which had been low for centuries, began to climb.\n\nNot everyone welcomed the change. Some religious leaders feared that giving ordinary people access to the Bible would lead to dangerous misinterpretation. Governments worried that pamphlets could spread sedition. Scribes, whose livelihoods depended on hand-copying, saw their profession begin to disappear. The printing press, like many transformative technologies, created winners and losers.\n\nBut the genie could not be put back in the bottle. Once information could be reproduced cheaply and quickly, the structures that depended on controlling it — the Church, the monarchy, the old universities — were forced to adapt or lose influence. The printing press did not cause the Renaissance, the Reformation, or the Scientific Revolution single-handedly. But it is almost impossible to imagine any of them happening without it.\n\nGutenberg died in 1468, largely forgotten and financially ruined. He never saw the full impact of what he had created. The machine that would transform civilisation earned its inventor almost nothing — a pattern that, five centuries later, still feels remarkably familiar.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['The printing press was invented in China and Gutenberg simply copied the idea, importing carved woodblock technology directly from Chinese traders and rebranding it as his own European creation.','The printing press revolutionised the spread of knowledge by making books affordable and widely available, triggering religious, scientific, and political transformations that reshaped Western civilisation.','Printing books by hand was faster and more efficient than using a press, which is why scribes remained the dominant producers of books well into the sixteenth century.','Gutenberg was the richest man in Europe because of the printing press, amassing a fortune from Bible sales that funded printing operations across every major European city.'],c:1,e:'The passage traces a chain of consequences from Gutenberg\'s invention: cheap books led to faster information sharing, which fuelled the Reformation, scientific progress, rising literacy, and the erosion of elite control over knowledge. The main idea is about the cascading impact of democratising information.'},
      {q:'How is this passage structured?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['Strict chronological order — every event is listed by exact date from 1440 to 1500, with each paragraph covering a specific decade in the history of European printing.','Compare and contrast — hand-copying and printing are compared throughout, with alternating paragraphs dedicated to the advantages and disadvantages of each method.','Persuasive argument — the author argues that we should return to hand-copying books, using the scribes\' lost livelihoods and the spread of seditious pamphlets as evidence against printing.','Before, innovation, consequences, resistance, legacy — the passage moves from the pre-press world through the invention to its effects, opposition, and lasting significance.'],c:3,e:'The passage follows a clear arc: the pre-press world (paragraph 1), the invention (paragraph 2), the explosive spread (paragraph 3), the consequences (paragraph 4), the resistance (paragraph 5), and the broader legacy (paragraphs 6–7). Each section builds on the previous one.'},
      {q:'Paragraph five describes opposition to the printing press from religious leaders, governments, and scribes. Why does the author include this?',skill:'Analyse informational texts',opts:['To suggest that governments should have banned the printing press, since the spread of seditious pamphlets and religious misinterpretation outweighed any benefits of wider literacy.','To provide a balanced view — showing that transformative technologies create resistance and disruption alongside progress, and that not everyone benefited equally.','To prove that scribes were right and printing was inferior to hand-copying, since hand-copied manuscripts contained fewer errors and were more beautifully crafted than early printed books.','To argue that the printing press was a mistake that should never have been invented, since the destruction of the scribal profession and the spread of misinformation caused more harm than good.'],c:1,e:'Including opposition makes the passage more balanced and nuanced. It prevents a simplistic \'technology = progress\' narrative by acknowledging genuine costs: scribes lost their livelihoods, authorities lost control. This complexity makes the argument more credible and encourages the reader to think critically about technological change.'},
      {q:'The passage says \'the genie could not be put back in the bottle\'. What does this idiom mean in context?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['The printing press was shaped like a bottle, and Gutenberg used this visual resemblance deliberately when marketing his invention to wealthy patrons in Mainz.','Once information could be reproduced cheaply, the change was irreversible — no authority could undo the spread of knowledge or return to the old system of controlled information, just as a released genie cannot be recaptured.','It means the printing press was magical and worked by supernatural forces, which is why religious leaders feared it — they believed Gutenberg had made a pact with dark powers to create the machine.','Gutenberg kept a genie in a bottle in his workshop, and the Arabian folklore reference is the author\'s way of connecting European printing history to Middle Eastern storytelling traditions.'],c:1,e:'The genie-in-a-bottle idiom means something released that cannot be contained again. Applied to the printing press, it captures the irreversibility of the information revolution: once books were cheap and widespread, the Church, monarchy, and universities could not restore their monopoly on knowledge. The idiom makes this abstract point vivid and memorable.'},
      {q:'The final paragraph notes that Gutenberg \'died largely forgotten and financially ruined\' and calls this \'a pattern that still feels remarkably familiar\'. What is the author suggesting?',skill:'Author\'s purpose',opts:['That the printing press was not actually a successful invention, since Gutenberg\'s personal financial ruin proves the technology was commercially unviable during the fifteenth century.','That inventors and innovators often fail to benefit from their own creations — a pattern repeated throughout history, including in the modern technology industry, where creators are not always the ones who profit.','That Gutenberg was a bad businessman who deserved to fail, since he refused to patent his movable-type system and foolishly shared his methods with competing printers across Germany.','That all inventors die poor and there is no point inventing anything, since the passage presents Gutenberg\'s ruin as the inevitable fate of anyone who creates something new.'],c:1,e:'The final line extends the passage beyond history into the present. By calling Gutenberg\'s fate \'remarkably familiar\', the author invites the reader to think about modern parallels — inventors and creators whose work transforms the world but whose personal rewards don\'t match. It adds a bittersweet, thought-provoking coda to the passage.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about why Gutenberg\'s invention spread so quickly across Europe?',skill:'Inference',opts:['Because Gutenberg personally travelled to every European city to sell his presses, establishing a network of franchised print shops that he controlled from his base in Mainz.','The demand for books already existed — knowledge had been locked away for centuries, so when printing made books affordable, the pent-up demand from scholars, clergy, and an emerging literate class drove rapid adoption across every major city.','Because there was no demand for books and printers had to give them away free until Martin Luther\'s theses created the first mass market for printed material in the 1510s.','Because the Church ordered every city to buy a printing press immediately, hoping to use the technology to distribute approved religious texts and counter the spread of heretical pamphlets.'],c:1,e:'The passage establishes that books were desperately expensive and knowledge was \'locked inside monasteries\'. This implies enormous latent demand. When Gutenberg\'s press dramatically reduced costs, it unleashed demand that had been suppressed by scarcity for centuries. The fifty-year spread across all major European cities reflects how ready the market was for this technology.'},
      {q:'What theme does the passage develop about the relationship between technology and power?',skill:'Theme',opts:['That the printing press had no political consequences whatsoever — it was a purely commercial tool that affected book prices but left the power structures of Church and monarchy untouched.','That controlling information is a form of power, and technologies that democratise information inevitably threaten existing power structures — the Church, monarchy, and universities lost influence because they could no longer control what people read and knew.','That power and information have no connection to each other — the Church and monarchy maintained full control over society even after two hundred million books were in circulation by 1500.','That technology always strengthens existing power structures — the printing press ultimately gave the Church and monarchy more influence by letting them distribute official proclamations more efficiently.'],c:1,e:'The passage traces a clear link between information access and power. Before printing, knowledge was controlled by elites. After printing, \'ordinary people\' could access information. The consequence — that \'structures that depended on controlling it were forced to adapt or lose influence\' — reveals the theme that democratising information redistributes power.'},
      {q:'What is the tone of the final paragraph about Gutenberg\'s death?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Indifferent and unemotional about Gutenberg as a person — the final paragraph treats his death as a minor footnote, showing no sympathy for his poverty or any interest in his personal story.','Angry and bitter about the injustice of Gutenberg\'s poverty — the author openly condemns fifteenth-century society for exploiting Gutenberg\'s genius and deliberately driving him into financial ruin.','Celebratory and joyful about Gutenberg\'s achievements — the final paragraph is a triumphant tribute to the inventor, presenting his death as the peaceful end of a life well lived.','Bittersweet and reflective — the author presents a poignant irony that the man who changed civilisation died forgotten and poor, with a knowing nod to modern parallels that adds a layer of melancholy to the triumph.'],c:3,e:'The final paragraph\'s tone is carefully balanced. \'Largely forgotten and financially ruined\' is sad, but not melodramatic. The phrase \'a pattern that still feels remarkably familiar\' adds knowing irony rather than anger. The tone is bittersweet — acknowledging both the triumph of the invention and the personal tragedy of the inventor without tipping into sentimentality.'},
      {q:'The passage says ideas could now \'spread faster than a person could walk\'. What does this phrase highlight about the pre-press world?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['It emphasises how desperately slow information travelled before printing — when every book was hand-copied, ideas could only move as fast as the person carrying the single manuscript, making the printing press a revolutionary leap in communication speed.','It suggests that printing presses could physically move faster than humans, since Gutenberg\'s machines were transported by horse-drawn cart across Europe at speeds no person could match on foot.','It means that people in the Middle Ages could not walk very quickly because poor road conditions and lack of footwear limited travel to only a few kilometres per day.','It is a scientific measurement of how fast ideas travel through the air, referencing the speed at which news of Luther\'s theses physically moved across Germany by messenger and print.'],c:0,e:'The phrase works by establishing a baseline. Before printing, an idea could only travel as fast as a person carrying a hand-copied manuscript — essentially walking speed. The printing press shattered this limit by creating multiple copies that could be distributed simultaneously. The comparison makes the revolution in communication speed viscerally clear.'},
      {q:'How does the author present the character of Gutenberg across the passage?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['As a wealthy businessman who profited enormously from his invention — the passage implies that Gutenberg\'s Bible sales made him the richest craftsman in Mainz before his retirement.','As a villain who destroyed the livelihood of scribes — the passage presents Gutenberg as someone who knowingly eliminated an entire profession to advance his own commercial interests.','As a brilliant but ultimately tragic figure — his innovation changed the world, but he personally gained almost nothing from it, creating a portrait of genius unrewarded that resonates across centuries.','As an unimportant figure whose contribution was minor — the passage credits Chinese woodblock printing as the real innovation and treats Gutenberg\'s movable type as a small technical refinement.'],c:2,e:'Gutenberg appears at the beginning as an innovative goldsmith and at the end as a forgotten, ruined man. The passage does not dwell on his personal story but frames it powerfully: seven paragraphs describe the civilisation-changing impact of his invention, and then one sentence reveals he died with almost nothing. The contrast between impact and reward defines his character in the passage.'},
      {q:'The passage states that \'the genie could not be put back in the bottle\'. What can you infer about why the author chose this particular idiom?',skill:'Inference',opts:['Because Gutenberg found an actual genie that helped him build the press, and the author uses this detail to connect the invention of printing to the magical thinking common in medieval Europe.','Because the author could not think of a more original phrase and fell back on a cliche, weakening what should have been the passage\'s most powerful metaphor about irreversible change.','Because, like a genie, the printing press granted enormous power that could not be controlled once released — the idiom captures both the transformative potential and the irreversibility of the technology in a single familiar image.','Because the printing press was shaped like a bottle, and Gutenberg\'s original design drawings show a vessel-like frame that inspired the author\'s choice of this particular idiom.'],c:2,e:'The genie idiom works on multiple levels. A genie grants wishes — the press granted access to knowledge. A released genie cannot be recaptured — printed books cannot be unprinted. The idiom also carries a note of ambiguity: genies can be dangerous, just as the passage acknowledges the press created \'winners and losers\'. The familiar image makes the complex historical point immediately graspable.'},
      {q:'Why does the author mention that \'the Chinese had been using carved woodblock printing for centuries\' before Gutenberg?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['To provide historical accuracy and a balanced perspective — acknowledging that printing existed before Gutenberg prevents a Eurocentric view while still explaining what made his specific innovation (movable metal type) revolutionary.','To suggest that the printing press was actually unimportant because it already existed — since Chinese woodblock printing predated Gutenberg by centuries, his contribution was merely derivative.','To prove that Chinese printing was superior to European printing, since woodblock technology produced more beautiful and durable pages than Gutenberg\'s movable metal type ever achieved.','To argue that Gutenberg stole his idea entirely from China, deliberately concealing his debt to Chinese printers in order to claim full credit for an invention that was not originally his.'],c:0,e:'This detail shows intellectual honesty. The author could have presented Gutenberg as inventing printing from nothing, but instead acknowledges the Chinese precedent. This gives the reader a more accurate and globally aware perspective while clarifying that Gutenberg\'s contribution was specifically movable metal type — an important distinction that makes the passage more precise and fair.'}
  ]},
  {id:'NF12',title:'Amelia Earhart\'s Last Flight',type:'nonfiction',source:'Original passage — aviation / history / mystery',
   text:'On 1 June 1937, Amelia Earhart took off from Miami, Florida, in a twin-engine Lockheed Electra, attempting to become the first woman to fly around the world. She was thirty-nine years old, already the most famous female pilot on the planet, and she had spent two years planning this flight — the longest and most dangerous of her career. Her navigator, Fred Noonan, sat behind her with a stack of charts and a chronometer. They carried enough fuel for twenty hours of flying.\n\nFor the first five weeks, everything went to plan. Earhart and Noonan flew east across the Atlantic, through Africa, across the Indian subcontinent, through Southeast Asia, and down to Australia. By the end of June, they had covered thirty-five thousand kilometres — roughly eighty per cent of the route. Only the Pacific remained.\n\nOn 2 July, they took off from Lae, New Guinea, heading for Howland Island — a tiny, flat coral atoll in the middle of the Pacific Ocean, barely three kilometres long and less than a kilometre wide. It was, by any measure, one of the most difficult navigation targets in the world. Finding it required pinpoint accuracy across 4,100 kilometres of open ocean, with no landmarks, no GPS, and only basic radio equipment.\n\nThey never arrived. The last radio transmission received from Earhart was at 8:43 am local time. She reported that they were running low on fuel and could not see the island. \'We are on the line 157-337,\' she said — a reference to a navigational line of position. After that, silence.\n\nThe search that followed was the largest and most expensive in American history at that time. The US Navy deployed sixty-six aircraft and nine ships, covering over 400,000 square kilometres of ocean. They found nothing — no wreckage, no oil slick, no debris. Earhart, Noonan, and their aircraft had vanished as completely as if they had never existed.\n\nAlmost ninety years later, the mystery remains unsolved. The most widely accepted theory is that the plane ran out of fuel and crashed into the Pacific, sinking in deep water. A competing theory suggests that Earhart and Noonan may have landed on a nearby uninhabited island called Nikumaroro, where expeditions have found artefacts that could — but have not been conclusively proven to — belong to the missing aviators. Other theories range from the plausible to the absurd.\n\nWhat is not in dispute is Earhart\'s legacy. Before her disappearance, she had set multiple aviation records, campaigned for women\'s rights, and inspired a generation of female pilots. She once wrote: \'The most difficult thing is the decision to act. The rest is merely tenacity.\' It is a sentence that could serve as the motto for her entire, extraordinary life.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['The passage argues that advances in modern technology have finally revealed what happened to Earhart and Noonan near Howland Island, resolving the decades-old mystery once and for all.','The passage presents Earhart as a reckless amateur whose lack of navigation experience and poor planning made the failed Pacific crossing entirely predictable and avoidable.','Amelia Earhart\'s attempt to fly around the world ended in an unsolved disappearance, but her legacy as a pioneering aviator and advocate for women endures.','The passage criticises the US Navy\'s search operation as half-hearted and argues that a more committed effort with better equipment would have recovered the Lockheed Electra.'],c:2,e:'The passage tells two stories: the mystery of the disappearance (paragraphs 1–6) and the enduring significance of Earhart\'s life (paragraph 7). The main idea combines both — the mystery matters because the person behind it matters.'},
      {q:'Why does the author structure the flight chronologically before switching to the mystery and legacy?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['Because all non-fiction passages must follow strict date order from her childhood aviation dreams through to her final flight from Lae.','To allow the author to compare each leg of the journey with Noonan\'s previous solo navigation flights across the same routes, highlighting his declining accuracy.','Because the author wants to argue that the Pacific crossing was no more dangerous than the earlier Atlantic leg, and that the disappearance was caused solely by radio failure.','The chronological build-up creates tension — the reader follows the successful journey and then experiences the sudden shift to silence and disappearance, making the loss more impactful before the passage pivots to legacy.'],c:3,e:'By tracking the flight\'s progress (80% complete, only the Pacific remaining), the author creates hope and momentum. The abrupt shift to \'They never arrived\' is devastating precisely because the reader has been following along. This structure makes the disappearance feel personal rather than just historical.'},
      {q:'The passage describes Howland Island as \'barely three kilometres long and less than a kilometre wide\'. Why does the author include these measurements?',skill:'Analyse informational texts',opts:['To make the navigational challenge concrete and comprehensible — when the reader understands how tiny the target was in the vastness of the Pacific, the difficulty of the task becomes viscerally clear.','To show that Earhart chose Howland Island as a refuelling stop specifically because its small size made it invisible to enemy aircraft during the politically tense 1930s.','To demonstrate that Howland Island\'s coral atoll geography made it an ideal emergency landing strip, large enough for the Lockheed Electra to touch down safely.','To explain why the US Navy later built a larger airstrip on Howland Island so that future pilots would not face the same navigational difficulties Earhart encountered.'],c:0,e:'The measurements do essential work. \'Small island in the Pacific\' is vague. \'Three kilometres long\' — especially set against 4,100 kilometres of open ocean — makes the reader feel the impossibility of the navigation challenge. It also builds sympathy: this wasn\'t poor flying, it was an extraordinarily difficult target.'},
      {q:'The passage says Earhart, Noonan, and their plane \'had vanished as completely as if they had never existed\'. What effect does this phrase create?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['It implies the search teams focused on the wrong coordinates because Earhart\'s final radio message gave an incorrect line of position.','It suggests Earhart and Noonan secretly survived and lived under assumed identities on Nikumaroro, which is why no physical remains were ever recovered.','It conveys the totality of the disappearance — no wreckage, no trace, nothing — making the mystery feel eerie and absolute, and highlighting why it has remained unsolved for nearly ninety years.','It indicates the Lockheed Electra was deliberately designed to sink without a trace, implying the aircraft manufacturer concealed a known mechanical defect.'],c:2,e:'The phrase goes beyond \'they were not found\' to suggest complete erasure — as if reality itself had absorbed them. This captures the unique quality of the Earhart mystery: it\'s not that evidence is ambiguous, it\'s that evidence barely exists. The totality of the disappearance is what makes it so haunting.'},
      {q:'Why does the author end with Earhart\'s own words — \'The most difficult thing is the decision to act. The rest is merely tenacity\'?',skill:'Author\'s purpose',opts:['To suggest that Earhart\'s quote about tenacity actually refers to the difficulty of navigating to Howland Island rather than to her broader philosophy of life.','Because the quote proves Earhart predicted her own disappearance and accepted the risk of death before she departed from Lae, New Guinea.','To demonstrate that Earhart\'s literary skills were more impressive than her aviation achievements and that she should be remembered primarily as an author.','Ending with Earhart\'s voice shifts the focus from the mystery of her death to the meaning of her life — the quote captures her philosophy of courage and determination, ensuring the reader remembers her as a person, not just a disappearance.'],c:3,e:'The quote recentres the passage. After paragraphs about vanishing and unsolved mystery, the reader might remember Earhart mainly as someone who was lost. Her own words — about acting and persevering — remind us that she was defined by what she did, not by how she died. It\'s a deliberate choice to end on agency rather than absence.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about Fred Noonan\'s role and importance on the flight?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['Noonan was merely a passenger who came along for the adventure and had no technical responsibilities during the thirty-five thousand kilometre journey.','Noonan was included only because aviation regulations in 1937 required a second crew member on international flights, regardless of whether they had any useful skills.','As the navigator carrying charts and a chronometer, Noonan was essential to finding Howland Island — without GPS, the entire flight depended on his ability to calculate their position using manual navigation methods.','Noonan was actually the pilot of the Lockheed Electra while Earhart served as navigator, reading the charts and chronometer from the rear seat.'],c:2,e:'The passage mentions Noonan specifically with \'a stack of charts and a chronometer\' — tools of celestial navigation. Given that Howland Island was \'one of the most difficult navigation targets in the world\' and they had \'no GPS and only basic radio equipment\', Noonan\'s skill was literally a matter of life and death. His role was indispensable to the mission\'s success.'},
      {q:'What is the tone of the sentence \'After that, silence\'?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Angry and accusatory, blaming the US Coast Guard cutter Itasca for failing to maintain radio contact with Earhart during the final approach to Howland Island.','Cheerful and optimistic, implying that radio silence was a routine occurrence on long Pacific flights and that Earhart likely landed safely on Howland without incident.','Stark, final, and haunting — the two-word sentence creates an abrupt halt that mirrors the sudden loss of contact, making the reader feel the shock and emptiness that followed Earhart\'s last transmission.','Scientific and neutral, presenting the radio log data in the same detached technical register used throughout the passage to describe aviation equipment and navigation methods.'],c:2,e:'The brevity is the point. After the detailed, specific last transmission (\'We are on the line 157-337\'), the two-word sentence creates a jarring void. The reader experiences a miniature version of what the radio operators felt — one moment there is a voice, the next there is nothing. The abruptness makes the disappearance feel real and immediate.'},
      {q:'What theme does the passage develop about the nature of legacy?',skill:'Theme',opts:['That Earhart has no lasting legacy because her around-the-world flight failed at the eighty per cent mark, overshadowing all her previous aviation records and activism.','That a person\'s legacy is defined by how they lived, not how they died — despite the mystery of her disappearance, Earhart is remembered for her achievements, courage, and advocacy for women\'s rights.','That Earhart\'s true legacy depends entirely on recovering the Lockheed Electra from the Pacific, and until the wreckage is found her achievements remain historically unverified.','That the unsolved nature of the disappearance has harmed the reputation of female pilots, undoing Earhart\'s earlier work to inspire women in aviation.'],c:1,e:'The passage devotes six paragraphs to the disappearance but concludes by pivoting to Earhart\'s life. The final paragraph insists that \'what is not in dispute is Earhart\'s legacy\' — her records, her activism, her philosophy. The theme is that legacy is built through action and courage, not determined by how one\'s story ends.'},
      {q:'The passage calls the search \'the largest and most expensive in American history at that time\'. What does this detail help the reader infer?',skill:'Inference',opts:['It proves the US Navy already knew Earhart had crashed and organised the massive search purely as a public relations exercise to avoid political criticism.','It suggests that the sixty-six aircraft and nine ships would have been sufficient to find the wreckage if the Pacific Ocean were shallower in that region.','It means the US government classified the search results because Earhart had been conducting secret surveillance of Japanese military bases in the Marshall Islands.','It reveals how famous and important Earhart was — the scale of the search reflects her celebrity status and the nation\'s emotional investment in finding her, not just the military\'s standard procedure.'],c:3,e:'The scale of the search — sixty-six aircraft, nine ships, 400,000 square kilometres — is extraordinary. This tells the reader how important Earhart was to the American public. An ordinary missing plane would not have received this level of response. The detail indirectly characterises Earhart as a national figure whose loss mattered enormously to the country.'},
      {q:'How does the author use sentence length to create effect in the paragraph about the search?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['The author uses uniformly short sentences throughout the search paragraph to mirror the rapid, efficient pace of the US Navy\'s military-style rescue operation.','The long sentences listing search resources are intended to exhaust the reader and create a sense of fatigue that mirrors the weeks of fruitless searching across the Pacific.','Every sentence in the search paragraph is deliberately the same length to represent the monotonous, repetitive nature of flying grid patterns over open ocean.','The long, detailed sentence listing the search resources (sixty-six aircraft, nine ships, 400,000 square kilometres) is followed by the short, devastating sentence \'They found nothing\' — the contrast between effort and result creates a powerful sense of futility.'],c:3,e:'The technique is contrast. The reader absorbs the enormous scale of the search through accumulated detail, building expectation of a result. Then \'They found nothing\' punctures that expectation with brutal brevity. The structural contrast between the two sentences mirrors the emotional reality: massive effort, zero result. This is a sophisticated writing technique that GCSE students should learn to recognise.'},
      {q:'Why does the author describe the competing theories as ranging \'from the plausible to the absurd\'?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['To signal the author\'s objective, evidence-based perspective — by dismissing some theories as absurd, the author guides the reader to take the evidence-based theories seriously while acknowledging that the mystery has attracted speculation.','Because the author believes the Nikumaroro island theory and the deep-water crash theory are equally supported by artefact evidence and should be given identical weight.','To reveal that the author has personally investigated the Nikumaroro site and discovered conclusive proof of what happened to Earhart and Noonan after they left Lae.','To dismiss the work of the sixty-six aircraft crews and nine ship crews who participated in the original 1937 search operation as incompetent and poorly coordinated.'],c:0,e:'The phrase reveals the author\'s analytical point of view. Rather than treating all theories equally (false balance) or endorsing one theory definitively (premature conclusion), the author creates a spectrum from plausible to absurd. This models good critical thinking — not all claims deserve equal weight — while remaining honest about the fact that the mystery is genuinely unsolved.'},
      {q:'The passage says Earhart \'had spent two years planning this flight\'. What does this detail suggest about her character?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['It reveals her as methodical, determined, and serious — this was not an impulsive adventure but a carefully prepared undertaking, which deepens the tragedy of its failure and reinforces her quote about tenacity.','It proves that two years of planning was insufficient because Earhart failed to account for the difficulty of locating a three-kilometre island across 4,100 kilometres of open ocean.','It suggests she was indecisive and overly cautious, spending far longer on preparation than other pilots of the era who completed similar circumnavigation routes more quickly.','It means the flight was someone else\'s idea and she reluctantly agreed only after two years of persuasion from her navigator.'],c:0,e:'Two years of planning characterises Earhart as disciplined and professional, not reckless. This detail is important because it counters any assumption that the flight failed due to poor preparation. It also connects to her own quote about tenacity — she applied sustained effort and commitment to everything she did, from planning to execution.'}
  ]},
  {id:'NF13',title:'The Plastic Problem',type:'nonfiction',source:'Original passage — environment / ocean pollution / sustainability',
   text:'Every year, approximately eight million tonnes of plastic enter the world\'s oceans. To put that number into perspective, it is roughly equivalent to emptying one rubbish truck of plastic into the sea every single minute of every single day. And once it\'s there, it doesn\'t go away. A plastic bottle dropped into the ocean today will still be there in four hundred and fifty years.\n\nPlastic is, in many ways, a miracle material. It is cheap, lightweight, durable, waterproof, and endlessly versatile. Since it was first mass-produced in the 1950s, it has transformed medicine, construction, transport, and food packaging. The problem is not that plastic exists — it is that we treat a material designed to last forever as though it were disposable. Roughly half of all plastic produced is used once and then thrown away.\n\nIn the ocean, plastic breaks down — but it never fully disappears. Sunlight and wave action fragment larger items into smaller and smaller pieces, eventually creating what scientists call microplastics: particles less than five millimetres across, often invisible to the naked eye. These microplastics are now found everywhere: in Arctic sea ice, in the deepest ocean trenches, in the stomachs of fish and seabirds, and — as recent studies have confirmed — in human blood.\n\nThe effects on marine life are devastating. Seabirds mistake floating plastic for food and feed it to their chicks, whose stomachs fill with bottle caps and lighters instead of fish. Turtles eat plastic bags, confusing them with jellyfish. Whales have been found dead with dozens of kilograms of plastic in their stomachs. Coral reefs, already stressed by warming oceans, become smothered by plastic debris that blocks the sunlight they need to survive.\n\nSolutions exist, but none is simple. Recycling, which is often presented as the answer, currently handles less than ten per cent of the plastic ever produced. Much of what we believe we are recycling is actually shipped to other countries, where it may end up in landfill or in the ocean anyway. Biodegradable plastics sound promising but require specific industrial conditions to break down and often don\'t decompose in the sea at all.\n\nThe most effective approaches, according to environmental scientists, target the problem at source: reducing the amount of single-use plastic produced in the first place. Banning plastic bags, charging for disposable cups, redesigning packaging to use less material — these upstream interventions prevent waste from being created rather than trying to clean it up afterwards. Several countries have already implemented such policies with measurable results.\n\nBut ultimately, the plastic crisis is not a technical problem — it is a human one. The technology to reduce plastic pollution already exists. What is needed is the collective will to use it. The ocean does not have a plastic problem. We do.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['The passage primarily examines how microplastics enter the food chain through marine organisms and argues that the health effects on humans are the most urgent aspect of the crisis requiring immediate medical research.','Ocean plastic pollution is a severe crisis caused by treating a permanent material as disposable — solutions exist but require systemic change rather than individual recycling alone.','The passage argues that plastic has no beneficial uses whatsoever and that the medical, construction, and transport industries would function better without it.','The passage concludes that current recycling programmes already handle the vast majority of plastic waste and that no additional upstream interventions are necessary.'],c:1,e:'The passage balances appreciation for plastic\'s usefulness with a clear-eyed account of the damage caused by treating it as disposable. It critiques recycling as insufficient and argues for upstream solutions. The final paragraph reframes the crisis as human rather than technical — the knowledge exists, the will doesn\'t.'},
      {q:'How is this passage structured?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['Problem, context, evidence, inadequate solutions, better solutions, call to action — the passage layers the issue systematically before ending with a challenge to the reader.','Persuasive argument relying entirely on emotional descriptions of dead seabirds and whales, with no statistical evidence or scientific data to support its claims.','Compare and contrast — the passage systematically compares plastic packaging with biodegradable paper alternatives to argue that paper should replace plastic entirely.','Strict chronological history tracing the development of plastic from its 1950s mass production through each decade of increasing ocean pollution to the present day.'],c:0,e:'The passage builds in layers: the scale of the problem (paragraph 1), why plastic is both useful and problematic (2), the science of microplastics (3), the impact on wildlife (4), why current solutions fall short (5), what actually works (6), and a final reframing (7). Each layer adds depth.'},
      {q:'The passage states that recycling \'currently handles less than ten per cent of the plastic ever produced\' and that some recycled plastic is \'shipped to other countries where it may end up in landfill or the ocean\'. Why does the author include this?',skill:'Analyse informational texts',opts:['To prove that recycling companies deliberately ship plastic overseas knowing it will end up in the ocean, making the entire industry complicit in marine pollution.','To suggest that sending plastic to landfill is environmentally preferable to recycling because landfill at least keeps the waste contained on land rather than in the ocean.','To challenge the common assumption that recycling solves the problem — by showing its limitations, the author builds the case for upstream solutions that prevent waste being created in the first place.','To argue that individual households should stop recycling entirely and instead focus on purchasing only biodegradable products that decompose naturally in seawater.'],c:2,e:'The recycling statistics are strategically placed. Many readers assume recycling is the solution. By showing it handles only 10% and that some \'recycled\' plastic ends up in the ocean anyway, the author disrupts that assumption and prepares the reader to consider more fundamental changes — reducing production rather than managing waste.'},
      {q:'The opening compares eight million tonnes of ocean plastic to \'emptying one rubbish truck into the sea every single minute\'. Why does the author use this comparison?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['To suggest that coastal rubbish truck disposal is the primary route by which plastic enters the ocean, and that regulating truck access to beaches would solve the crisis.','To show that the eight million tonnes figure is evenly distributed across all oceans, affecting coastal and deep-water environments in exactly equal measure.','To prove that municipal waste collection vehicles are responsible for most ocean plastic because they routinely dump excess loads into rivers flowing to the sea.','To transform an abstract, incomprehensible number into a vivid, repeating image — one truck per minute is something the reader can visualise and feel shocked by in a way that \'eight million tonnes\' alone cannot achieve.'],c:3,e:'Eight million tonnes is a number too large to feel. One rubbish truck per minute is an image — you can see it, time it, and feel its relentlessness. The repetition (\'every single minute of every single day\') compounds the impact. This is a classic science communication technique: anchor vast numbers to human-scale images.'},
      {q:'The final sentence states: \'The ocean does not have a plastic problem. We do.\' Why does the author end this way?',skill:'Author\'s purpose',opts:['To prove that the ocean\'s natural currents and wave action break down all plastic within four hundred and fifty years, meaning the problem is ultimately self-correcting.','To shift responsibility from the environment to human beings — the problem is not a natural disaster but a consequence of human choices, and framing it this way makes the reader feel personally implicated and empowered to act.','To suggest that marine organisms have already adapted to digest microplastics, so the ocean\'s ecosystem will eventually absorb the pollution without human intervention.','To blame individual consumers rather than manufacturers, arguing that people who buy single-use plastic bear sole moral responsibility for every piece of ocean debris.'],c:1,e:'The final sentence is a deliberate reframing. By saying the ocean doesn\'t have the problem — we do — the author transfers ownership from the environment to humanity. This is empowering, not just guilt-inducing: if we created the problem through choices, we can solve it through different choices. It\'s a call to action disguised as a correction.'},
      {q:'The passage describes plastic as \'a miracle material\' before detailing its destructive effects. What literary device is this an example of?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['Alliteration — the repeated M sound in \'miracle material\' creates a soothing rhythm that makes the reader associate plastic with comfort and safety.','Simile — plastic is compared to a miracle using the word \'like\', suggesting it has supernatural properties similar to those found in medicine and construction.','Onomatopoeia — the word \'miracle\' imitates the crackling sound that plastic makes when it fragments into microplastics under sunlight and wave action.','Irony — calling plastic a \'miracle\' before showing the devastation it causes creates a deliberate contrast between its intended purpose and its actual impact.'],c:3,e:'This is situational irony: a \'miracle material\' has become an environmental catastrophe. The author uses the word \'miracle\' sincerely (plastic is genuinely useful) but the rest of the passage undercuts the celebration, creating a tension between admiration and horror that drives the argument forward.'},
      {q:'What can be inferred about the author\'s view of individual recycling efforts?',skill:'Inference',opts:['The author considers individual recycling helpful but insufficient — the passage implies that systemic changes to production matter far more than consumer-level waste management.','The author thinks individuals should stop recycling entirely because the ten per cent processing rate proves the entire system is fundamentally broken beyond repair.','The author believes recycling is the single most important action anyone can take, and that raising the ten per cent rate is more effective than any upstream intervention.','The author believes the countries that have already implemented bag bans and cup charges have completely eliminated their contribution to ocean plastic pollution.'],c:0,e:'The passage states recycling handles less than 10% of plastic ever produced and that some recycled material ends up in landfill or the ocean. While the author does not say recycling is worthless, the emphasis on \'upstream interventions\' — reducing production at source — implies individual recycling alone is far from sufficient.'},
      {q:'From whose point of view is this passage primarily written?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['A marine biologist reporting first-hand observations of dead seabirds and whales found during personal research expeditions to the Arctic and the deepest ocean trenches.','A government official defending existing recycling programmes and announcing new policies that will raise the current ten per cent processing rate to full capacity.','A plastic manufacturer arguing that the material\'s durability, low cost, and versatility in medicine and construction far outweigh the temporary inconvenience of ocean pollution.','An informed, concerned commentator who presents scientific evidence objectively while making a clear moral argument that humanity must take responsibility for the crisis.'],c:3,e:'The author writes as an informed outsider — not a scientist, manufacturer, or politician, but someone synthesising evidence from multiple sources. The tone is authoritative but accessible, and the final paragraph\'s shift to \'we\' signals a concerned citizen urging collective responsibility rather than a specialist lecturing from above.'},
      {q:'What is the overall tone of the passage?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Indifferent and detached, presenting the eight million tonnes statistic and the wildlife deaths as neutral data points without any indication that the author finds them concerning.','Angry and accusatory, singling out plastic manufacturers and recycling companies by name as the parties solely responsible for the eight million tonnes entering the ocean annually.','Urgent but measured — the author conveys the seriousness of the crisis with evidence and restrained language rather than emotional outbursts, creating a tone that is alarming without being hysterical.','Lighthearted and humorous, using the rubbish truck comparison and the four-hundred-and-fifty-year bottle statistic as playful exaggerations designed to entertain rather than alarm.'],c:2,e:'The passage avoids sensationalism despite covering a devastating topic. Words like \'devastating\' appear, but they are supported by evidence (dead whales, smothered coral) rather than emotional rhetoric. The measured delivery makes the urgency feel earned and credible, which is more persuasive than alarm alone.'},
      {q:'What theme does the passage explore through the contrast between plastic\'s durability and its disposal?',skill:'Theme',opts:['The theme of short-term convenience versus long-term consequences — humanity uses a permanent material for temporary purposes, and the mismatch creates lasting environmental damage.','The theme of nature\'s ability to break down any material eventually, as demonstrated by sunlight and wave action fragmenting plastic into harmless microplastic particles.','The theme that individual consumers bear sole responsibility for the crisis because roughly half of all plastic produced is used once and discarded by households.','The theme that scientific innovation will inevitably produce a replacement material as cheap and versatile as plastic but fully biodegradable in seawater.'],c:0,e:'The passage explicitly states: \'we treat a material designed to last forever as though it were disposable.\' This mismatch — permanent material, temporary use — is the central tension. The theme warns that failing to consider long-term consequences of short-term convenience creates problems that outlast us by centuries.'},
      {q:'The passage describes microplastics found \'in Arctic sea ice, in the deepest ocean trenches, in the stomachs of fish and seabirds, and in human blood\'. What effect does this list create?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['It proves that microplastics are a natural part of all ecosystems because they appear in such diverse environments, from Arctic ice to deep ocean trenches.','It shows that microplastics are confined to remote environments like the Arctic and deep ocean trenches, suggesting they pose no direct threat to human populations.','The escalating list moves from remote environments to the human body, creating a growing sense of alarm as the reader realises microplastics are not just an ocean problem but a personal health concern.','It is included to prove that scientists have already mapped every location containing microplastics, meaning the contamination is fully understood and can be easily cleaned up.'],c:2,e:'The list follows a deliberate geographical and emotional progression: from the distant Arctic, to the deep ocean, to animals, and finally to human blood. Each item brings the problem closer to the reader. By the time the list reaches \'human blood\', the issue is no longer abstract — it is literally inside us.'},
      {q:'What can you infer about why the author mentions that biodegradable plastics \'require specific industrial conditions to break down\'?',skill:'Inference',opts:['The author wants readers to support the biodegradable plastics industry by purchasing its products, since these materials represent the most effective upstream solution to ocean pollution.','The author implies that biodegradable plastics are misleading because consumers assume they decompose naturally, when in reality they often need facilities most waste never reaches — making them a false solution.','The author is arguing that building more industrial composting facilities is the single most effective upstream intervention, more impactful than banning plastic bags or charging for cups.','The author believes biodegradable plastics decompose rapidly in seawater and will eventually replace conventional plastic as the standard material for packaging and single-use items.'],c:1,e:'By noting that biodegradable plastics need industrial conditions and \'often don\'t decompose in the sea at all\', the author implies that the \'biodegradable\' label gives consumers false reassurance. This fits the passage\'s broader argument: apparent solutions often fall short of their promise, and only upstream reduction truly works.'}
  ]},
  {id:'NF14',title:'The Invention of the Internet',type:'nonfiction',source:'Original passage — technology / communication / history',
   text:'The internet was not invented by a single person on a single day. It was not even invented for the purpose most people use it for today. It began as a military project, evolved into an academic tool, and only became the global communication network we now depend on through decades of incremental development by hundreds of researchers, many of whom never became famous.\n\nThe story usually begins with ARPANET, a network created by the United States Department of Defense in 1969. The original goal was practical: to connect computers at different universities and research centres so that scientists could share data without physically transporting it. The first ever message sent across ARPANET was supposed to be the word \'LOGIN\', sent from a computer at UCLA to one at Stanford. The system crashed after the first two letters. The first message transmitted on what would become the internet was, rather fittingly, \'LO\'.\n\nThrough the 1970s and 1980s, the network grew slowly, connecting universities and government agencies. The breakthrough that transformed it from a specialist tool into something ordinary people could use came in 1989, when a British scientist named Tim Berners-Lee, working at CERN in Switzerland, proposed a system for organising and linking information using hypertext. He called it the World Wide Web. It was not the internet itself — the internet is the physical network of connected computers, while the Web is the system of linked pages that runs on top of it — but it was the interface that made the internet usable.\n\nBerners-Lee made a decision that would prove more consequential than almost any in the history of technology: he gave it away for free. He did not patent the Web. He did not charge for its use. He believed that a system for sharing human knowledge should be open to everyone, and he acted on that belief at enormous personal financial cost. The Web spread across the world precisely because nobody owned it.\n\nThe growth that followed was staggering. In 1993, there were roughly six hundred websites in the world. By 2000, there were seventeen million. Today, there are nearly two billion. The internet has reshaped commerce, communication, politics, education, entertainment, and the way human beings form relationships. It is difficult to think of a single aspect of modern life it has not touched.\n\nBut this transformation has not been without cost. The same openness that allows knowledge to spread freely also allows misinformation, surveillance, and harassment. The same network that connects a student in rural Kenya to the world\'s greatest libraries also connects extremists to each other. The internet, like the printing press before it, is a tool — and like all tools, its value depends entirely on how it is used.\n\nThe question is no longer whether the internet will shape the future. It already has. The question is who gets to decide how.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['The internet evolved gradually through decades of collaboration, was made accessible by the World Wide Web, and has transformed modern life — but its openness creates risks alongside benefits.','Tim Berners-Lee regrets giving the Web away for free and the passage argues he should have patented the hypertext system to fund further research at CERN.','The internet is mainly used for entertainment and has no serious purpose, as shown by the passage\'s focus on websites growing from six hundred to two billion rather than on academic research.','The internet was invented by one person in a single moment of genius, with the passage crediting the entire creation to the UCLA researcher who typed the first ARPANET message in 1969.'],c:0,e:'The passage emphasises the internet\'s gradual, collaborative development (not a single invention), Berners-Lee\'s decision to keep it open, the explosive growth that followed, and the dual-edged nature of that openness. The main idea is about the internet as a tool whose impact depends on how it\'s used.'},
      {q:'The passage compares the internet to the printing press. Why is this comparison made?',skill:'Analyse informational texts',opts:['Because the internet runs on paper, just like the printing press — the passage draws a physical connection between the two technologies through their shared reliance on written text.','Because both were invented in Germany by goldsmiths, and the passage links ARPANET\'s military origins to Gutenberg\'s commercial workshop to show how innovation always begins in unexpected places.','To prove that the printing press was more important than the internet, since the passage suggests that physical books remain more reliable than digital information that can be edited or deleted.','Both are information technologies that democratised access to knowledge but also enabled harmful uses — the comparison places the internet in a historical pattern and warns against viewing any technology as purely positive.'],c:3,e:'The printing press parallel is strategic. The earlier passage about Gutenberg showed that revolutionary information technology creates both progress and disruption. By connecting the internet to this pattern, the author argues that the challenges of the digital age are not unprecedented — and that history offers lessons about managing transformative tools.'},
      {q:'How is this passage structured?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['Persuasive argument — the author argues that the internet should be shut down, using the examples of misinformation and surveillance to build a case for returning to pre-digital communication methods.','Problem and solution — the passage identifies internet problems like misinformation and surveillance, then proposes that Berners-Lee\'s open-access model is the solution to each one.','Chronological development with a balanced evaluation — the passage traces the internet\'s history, then assesses both its benefits and its risks before posing a forward-looking question.','Compare and contrast only — the passage systematically compares ARPANET with the World Wide Web, weighing the military network against Berners-Lee\'s academic system to determine which was more important.'],c:2,e:'The passage moves chronologically from ARPANET (1969) through the Web (1989) to today, then pivots to evaluation: the benefits (connection, knowledge) and risks (misinformation, surveillance). The final question (\'who gets to decide how\') opens the discussion rather than closing it, inviting the reader to think further.'},
      {q:'The first ARPANET message was supposed to be \'LOGIN\' but the system crashed after \'LO\'. The author calls this \'rather fitting\'. Why?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['Because the author thinks system crashes are funny — the humour of the UCLA-to-Stanford failure is the passage\'s way of lightening the tone before the more serious discussion of misinformation.','Because the crash proved the internet would never work properly, foreshadowing the later problems of misinformation and surveillance that the passage describes as consequences of the network\'s unreliable design.','Because \'LO\' is a greeting meaning \'behold\' — the author is making a wry observation that the internet\'s first word was accidentally profound, as if announcing something momentous.','Because \'LO\' is the inventor\'s name — the passage implies that the UCLA researcher deliberately typed their own initials as a signature before the system crashed at Stanford.'],c:2,e:'\'LO\' — an archaic exclamation meaning \'look!\' or \'behold!\' — is an accidentally perfect first word for a technology that would transform how humanity sees and accesses information. The author\'s \'rather fittingly\' is a dry, witty observation that the internet announced itself with unintended grandeur.'},
      {q:'The passage says Berners-Lee \'gave it away for free\' and \'acted on that belief at enormous personal financial cost\'. What do these phrases reveal about how the author views Berners-Lee\'s decision?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['The author presents the decision as both principled and sacrificial — Berners-Lee chose public benefit over personal wealth, and the passage frames this as the reason the Web succeeded globally.','The phrases suggest the Web was worthless because it was free, implying that Berners-Lee\'s hypertext system had no commercial value and that CERN would have rejected a patent application.','The author believes Berners-Lee should sue everyone who uses the internet, since the passage frames his decision not to patent the Web as a mistake that left him unable to control how his invention was used.','The author thinks Berners-Lee was foolish to give away something valuable, since the passage\'s reference to \'enormous personal financial cost\' is presented as evidence that he made a poor strategic decision.'],c:0,e:'The language is carefully admiring without being sentimental. \'Gave it away\' emphasises generosity. \'Enormous personal financial cost\' acknowledges the sacrifice. \'The Web spread across the world precisely because nobody owned it\' frames the decision as both morally right and strategically effective — openness was the key to its success.'},
      {q:'What can be inferred about why ARPANET was originally designed to connect universities rather than the general public?',skill:'Inference',opts:['The government wanted to prevent ordinary people from ever accessing the network — the passage\'s reference to the Department of Defense suggests ARPANET was classified and deliberately restricted to keep it secret.','ARPANET was a social media platform designed for university students, which explains why the first message was sent between UCLA and Stanford rather than between military installations.','The technology was created to serve a specific military and academic need — sharing research data between institutions — and the idea of ordinary people using it for communication or entertainment was not part of the original vision.','Universities paid the most taxes and therefore deserved internet access first, which is why the Department of Defense directed funding specifically to UCLA and Stanford as the initial network nodes.'],c:2,e:'The passage states ARPANET\'s goal was to let scientists \'share data without physically transporting it\'. This was a practical research tool, not a communication network for the public. The inference is that the internet\'s current social and commercial uses were entirely unintended — it evolved far beyond its original purpose.'},
      {q:'What is the overall tone of the passage?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Neutral and detached — the author presents facts with no personal perspective, avoiding any judgement of Berners-Lee\'s decision and treating both misinformation and knowledge-sharing as equally unimportant outcomes.','Nostalgic — the author wishes the internet could return to its early academic purpose, lamenting the shift from ARPANET\'s small network of university researchers to today\'s two billion websites.','Admiring but cautionary — the author celebrates the internet\'s collaborative development and transformative power while warning that its openness creates serious risks.','Entirely negative — the author believes the internet has done more harm than good, emphasising surveillance, extremism, and harassment while dismissing the benefits of global communication and education.'],c:2,e:'The passage admires the collaborative development of the internet and Berners-Lee\'s generosity, but the tone shifts in the penultimate paragraph to acknowledge misinformation, surveillance, and extremism. This balance — celebration tempered by warning — creates a tone that is appreciative but clear-eyed, refusing to be purely optimistic or pessimistic.'},
      {q:'What theme does the passage explore through the story of the internet\'s development?',skill:'Theme',opts:['The theme that powerful tools are morally neutral — their impact depends entirely on how humans choose to use them, meaning progress always carries both promise and risk.','The theme that individuals are more important than collaborative effort in creating change, with the passage crediting Berners-Lee alone for the internet\'s success and dismissing the hundreds of researchers who built ARPANET.','The theme that military projects always produce beneficial civilian technology, since ARPANET\'s origins in the Department of Defense prove that military investment inevitably leads to tools that improve everyday life.','The theme that all technology is inherently dangerous and should be avoided, as demonstrated by the passage\'s argument that the internet\'s connection of extremists outweighs its connection of students to libraries.'],c:0,e:'The passage explicitly states the internet is \'a tool\' whose \'value depends entirely on how it is used.\' This theme — that technology is neutral and human choices determine its impact — runs through the entire piece, from ARPANET\'s original purpose to the modern challenges of misinformation and surveillance.'},
      {q:'The passage distinguishes between \'the internet\' and \'the World Wide Web\'. Why does the author make this distinction?',skill:'Inference',opts:['Because the author wants to show off technical knowledge to impress the reader — the distinction between physical network and linked pages serves no purpose other than demonstrating the author\'s expertise in computer science.','To argue that the internet should be used without the Web, suggesting that Berners-Lee\'s hypertext system is an unnecessary layer that complicates the simple network ARPANET\'s creators intended.','To correct a common misconception — most people use the terms interchangeably, but understanding that the Web is a layer running on top of the internet helps the reader appreciate Berners-Lee\'s specific contribution.','To prove that the Web is not important because it is not the internet itself, diminishing Berners-Lee\'s contribution by showing that the physical network built by the Department of Defense was the real achievement.'],c:2,e:'Many people confuse the internet (the physical network) with the Web (the system of linked pages). By clarifying that Berners-Lee created the interface, not the infrastructure, the author helps the reader understand exactly what made the internet accessible to ordinary people — and why Berners-Lee\'s contribution was so specifically important.'},
      {q:'What does the rapid growth from six hundred websites in 1993 to nearly two billion today reveal about the passage\'s argument?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['It suggests that only six hundred websites are actually worth visiting — the jump to two billion implies most sites are low quality, and the passage uses the statistics to criticise the uncontrolled expansion of online content.','It shows that the internet stopped growing after 2000 and is now declining, since the passage\'s jump from seventeen million websites to two billion disguises the fact that many sites have since been abandoned.','It demonstrates the explosive, exponential nature of the internet\'s impact — the sheer scale of growth supports the author\'s claim that the internet has reshaped virtually every aspect of modern life.','It proves that most websites are useless and there are too many of them — the passage presents the growth from six hundred to two billion as evidence that Berners-Lee\'s free model led to uncontrollable sprawl.'],c:2,e:'The statistics serve as concrete evidence for the passage\'s claims about transformation. Going from 600 to 2 billion websites in roughly 30 years illustrates exponential growth that is hard to comprehend. This numerical evidence makes the abstract claim that the internet \'reshaped commerce, communication, politics\' feel tangible and undeniable.'},
      {q:'From whose perspective is this passage written, and how does that affect the reader\'s understanding?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['Tim Berners-Lee himself, reflecting on his own invention with personal regret, which explains the passage\'s detailed knowledge of the \'enormous personal financial cost\' and the decision not to patent the Web.','A government official defending the decision to fund ARPANET with public money, which explains why the passage opens with the Department of Defense and presents the military origins of the internet positively.','A knowledgeable narrator who maintains historical distance, allowing them to evaluate both the achievements and failures of the internet\'s development without bias towards any single figure or organisation.','A technology company executive arguing for stricter internet regulation, which explains why the passage emphasises the dangers of misinformation and surveillance in the penultimate paragraph.'],c:2,e:'The passage is written from a third-person, historically informed perspective. This distance allows the author to celebrate Berners-Lee\'s generosity while also acknowledging the internet\'s dark side (misinformation, extremism) without seeming contradictory. A more personal perspective would risk bias; the removed viewpoint lends credibility to the balanced evaluation.'},
      {q:'The passage says the internet \'connects a student in rural Kenya to the world\'s greatest libraries\' but \'also connects extremists to each other\'. What literary device is used here?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['Juxtaposition — placing a deeply positive example directly next to a deeply negative one forces the reader to confront the internet\'s dual nature in a single, striking contrast.','Metaphor — the internet is compared to a library, with the Kenyan student example suggesting that the network functions as a single vast repository of books rather than a communication tool.','Hyperbole — the examples are exaggerated for dramatic effect, since a student in rural Kenya is unlikely to access the world\'s greatest libraries and the extremist connection is overstated.','Personification — the internet is given the ability to connect people as if it were human, with the word \'connects\' attributing intentional agency to a network that the passage earlier described as merely a tool.'],c:0,e:'By placing the Kenyan student and the extremists side by side in the same sentence structure, the author creates a powerful juxtaposition. The reader cannot celebrate one without acknowledging the other. This device encapsulates the passage\'s central argument: the same openness enables both the best and worst uses of the technology.'}
  ]},
  {id:'NF15',title:'How Do Satellites Stay Up?',type:'nonfiction',source:'Original passage — physics / space / orbits',
   text:'There are currently more than seven thousand active satellites orbiting the Earth, doing everything from broadcasting television signals to monitoring the weather, from guiding your phone\'s GPS to photographing distant galaxies. But how do they stay up there? If gravity pulls everything towards the ground, why don\'t satellites simply fall?\n\nThe answer is that they do fall — constantly. A satellite in orbit is falling towards the Earth every single second. The trick is that it is also moving sideways fast enough that, as it falls, the curve of the Earth drops away beneath it at the same rate. The satellite falls, but the ground curves away, so it never actually hits anything. It is, in effect, falling around the planet in a continuous loop. This is what an orbit is: not floating, not hovering, but perpetual falling with style.\n\nThe concept was first described by Isaac Newton in the 1680s, long before any satellite existed. Newton imagined a cannon on top of a very tall mountain. If you fired the cannon horizontally, the ball would fly forward and then curve down to the ground. If you fired it faster, it would travel further before landing. And if you fired it fast enough — at roughly 28,000 kilometres per hour — it would travel so far that the Earth\'s surface would curve away beneath it at the same rate it fell. The ball would never land. It would orbit.\n\nDifferent satellites orbit at different heights depending on their purpose. Low Earth orbit, between 200 and 2,000 kilometres up, is used by the International Space Station and most Earth-observation satellites. At this altitude, satellites travel at around 27,500 kilometres per hour and circle the planet every ninety minutes. Higher up, at about 36,000 kilometres, geostationary satellites orbit at exactly the same speed the Earth rotates, meaning they appear to hover over the same spot on the surface — perfect for telecommunications and weather monitoring.\n\nGetting a satellite into orbit requires enormous energy. A rocket must accelerate the satellite to orbital speed while also lifting it above the thickest part of the atmosphere, where air resistance would slow it down. Once in orbit, however, the satellite needs almost no fuel. In the vacuum of space, there is virtually no friction to slow it down, so it continues moving at the same speed indefinitely — unless something disturbs it.\n\nThis lack of friction is also a problem. When a satellite reaches the end of its useful life, it doesn\'t slow down and fall. It stays in orbit, becoming space debris — a growing cloud of defunct satellites, rocket stages, and fragments that now numbers over thirty thousand trackable objects. At orbital speeds, even a fleck of paint can damage a working spacecraft.\n\nThe sky above us is more crowded than it has ever been — and getting more so every year.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['Satellites remain in orbit primarily because the vacuum of space eliminates air resistance, allowing them to glide indefinitely once launched — though Newton\'s gravitational theories help explain why they eventually fall back to Earth as debris.','Satellites stay in orbit by falling continuously while moving sideways fast enough to match the Earth\'s curvature — a principle first described by Newton — but this same physics creates a growing space debris problem.','The passage focuses on how different types of satellites serve different purposes at various altitudes — from low Earth orbit for space stations to geostationary orbit for telecommunications — and explains why each altitude requires specific rocket designs.','Newton\'s cannon thought experiment demonstrates that satellites need constant thrust from onboard engines to maintain their altitude, which is why they carry large fuel reserves and eventually run out of power, becoming space debris.'],c:1,e:'The passage explains the counter-intuitive physics of orbits (falling, not floating), traces the idea to Newton, describes different orbit types, and then reveals the downside: what keeps satellites up also keeps space debris up. The main idea connects elegant physics to a modern practical problem.'},
      {q:'Orbit is described as \'perpetual falling with style\'. What effect does this phrase create?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['It creates a sense of danger and urgency — the word \'falling\' reminds the reader that satellites could crash to Earth at any moment, and \'with style\' softens the warning so it does not frighten younger readers.','It gives the passage a formal, academic tone — the phrase sounds like something from a university textbook, which signals to the reader that the information is scientifically rigorous and peer-reviewed.','It makes a counter-intuitive physics concept memorable and slightly humorous — the reader expects orbiting to mean floating, so \'falling with style\' is surprising and reframes their understanding in a way that sticks.','It emphasises the elegance of the engineering behind satellites — \'style\' refers to the careful design work by engineers who ensure that satellites fall in precisely controlled trajectories rather than random paths.'],c:2,e:'The phrase works because it\'s unexpected and witty. \'Perpetual falling\' captures the physics accurately (satellites are always falling). \'With style\' adds personality and humour, making the concept memorable. It\'s the kind of phrase a reader might repeat to someone else — which is exactly what good science communication aims for.'},
      {q:'Why does the author include Newton\'s cannon thought experiment?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['To provide historical context showing that the idea of orbit was already well understood centuries ago, which helps the reader appreciate how long humans waited before technology caught up with theory.','To give the reader a concrete visual analogy — imagining a ball fired from a mountaintop is easier to picture than abstract descriptions of curved motion, making the physics of orbiting accessible without mathematical formulas.','To build understanding step by step — by starting with a slow cannonball that falls quickly and gradually increasing speed until it orbits, the author makes the concept of orbital mechanics intuitive rather than requiring equations.','To establish Newton\'s authority as a scientist so that the reader trusts the subsequent explanation of orbital speeds and altitudes, grounding the technical details in a recognisable historical figure.'],c:2,e:'Newton\'s cannon is a teaching device. It starts with something obvious (a ball falls to the ground) and incrementally builds to something counter-intuitive (a ball that falls forever). By the time the reader reaches orbital speed, the concept feels logical rather than magical. This step-by-step structure is the passage\'s most effective pedagogical choice.'},
      {q:'The passage explains that in space, \'there is virtually no friction\' and a satellite \'continues moving at the same speed indefinitely\'. The author then says \'This lack of friction is also a problem.\' Why is this an effective transition?',skill:'Analyse informational texts',opts:['It reframes a positive feature (no friction means satellites stay in orbit without fuel) as a negative one (no friction also means dead satellites stay in orbit as debris) — showing the reader that the same physics creates both the solution and the problem.','It introduces a new scientific concept — the author shifts from discussing orbital mechanics to discussing environmental damage, signalling that the passage is moving from physics into a separate topic about pollution and waste management.','It serves as a counterargument to Newton\'s original theory — the author is suggesting that Newton did not foresee the problem of debris, and that modern science has revealed a flaw in his understanding of orbital mechanics.','It surprises the reader by reversing their expectations about space travel — having just learned that no friction is beneficial, the reader is now asked to reconsider whether frictionless environments create their own engineering challenges for rocket designers.'],c:1,e:'This is a pivoting technique: the same fact (no friction in space) is first presented as an advantage (free perpetual motion) and then as a disadvantage (space debris never comes down). By using the word \'also\', the author signals that the reader\'s understanding is about to be complicated, not overturned.'},
      {q:'The passage states that \'even a fleck of paint can damage a working spacecraft\' at orbital speeds. Why does the author include this detail?',skill:'Author\'s purpose',opts:['To illustrate a specific engineering vulnerability — the detail draws attention to the fact that spacecraft coatings degrade over time in the harsh conditions of space, creating a cycle where existing satellites generate the very debris that threatens them.','To emphasise the cumulative nature of the debris problem — the paint fleck represents the smallest possible piece of debris, and the author uses it to suggest that even the most minor objects contribute to an increasingly dangerous orbital environment.','To make the abstract concept of orbital speed feel tangible and dangerous — if something as tiny as a paint fleck can cause damage at 27,500 kph, the reader grasps just how fast these objects are moving and why debris is a serious threat.','To shift the passage\'s focus from the physics of orbits to the economics of space operations — the paint fleck detail implies that even minor collisions create costly repair needs, helping the reader understand why debris is a financial as well as scientific concern.'],c:2,e:'The paint fleck detail anchors an abstract speed (27,500 kph) to a visceral image. It\'s one thing to know satellites move fast; it\'s another to realise that at that speed, a fleck of paint hits like a bullet. This detail makes the debris problem feel real and urgent in a way that statistics alone cannot.'},
      {q:'What can be inferred about why the passage opens with a list of satellite functions (television, weather, GPS, galaxies)?',skill:'Inference',opts:['To demonstrate the range of scientific disciplines involved in satellite technology — from meteorology to astronomy — showing the reader that satellites represent a cross-disciplinary achievement rather than a single field of engineering.','To create a sense of wonder at the sheer number of satellites above us — by listing their many functions, the author prepares the reader for the later revelation about space debris and the crowded nature of Earth\'s orbit.','To provide a logical framework for the passage\'s structure — each function mentioned in the opening corresponds to a different orbit type discussed later, helping the reader connect practical uses to specific altitudes.','To establish how dependent modern life already is on satellites — the reader recognises services they use daily, making the question of how satellites stay up feel personally relevant rather than abstractly scientific.'],c:3,e:'The opening list is strategic: it connects the reader to satellites through everyday experiences (TV, GPS, weather). This makes the subsequent physics explanation feel relevant rather than academic. If the passage opened with orbital mechanics, many readers might disengage; starting with familiar services keeps them curious.'},
      {q:'What is the overall tone of this passage?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Serious and cautionary — the author presents the science of orbits primarily as a warning about the dangers of space debris, using technical detail to build a sense of urgency about an environmental crisis above our heads.','Nostalgic and reflective — the author looks back admiringly at Newton\'s era and suggests that modern satellite technology, while impressive, has introduced complications that the elegance of early scientific thinking did not anticipate.','Objective and detached — the author maintains strict neutrality throughout, presenting facts about satellites and orbits without expressing any personal interest, excitement, or concern about the subject matter.','Enthusiastic and explanatory — the author is genuinely excited by the science and wants the reader to share that excitement, using vivid language and humour alongside technical accuracy.'],c:3,e:'The tone is warm and engaging. Phrases like \'falling with style\' and the Newton cannon thought experiment show an author who enjoys the subject and wants to make it accessible. Even the space debris section, which is serious, is presented with clarity rather than anxiety. The overall effect is of a passionate science communicator, not a worried alarmist.'},
      {q:'What theme does the passage explore through the connection between orbits and space debris?',skill:'Theme',opts:['The theme that human ingenuity consistently outpaces our ability to manage its consequences — the passage traces how the brilliance of orbital mechanics has led to an environmental crisis that engineers are now struggling to solve.','The theme that the same physical laws which enable human achievement also create unintended consequences — the very property that keeps satellites useful (no friction) also makes debris permanent.','The theme that scientific understanding progresses through paradox — Newton\'s elegant theory of orbits seemed complete until the modern era revealed that the very elegance of frictionless motion creates problems Newton could never have anticipated.','The theme that technological dependence makes societies vulnerable — the passage suggests that our reliance on satellites for everyday services like GPS and television means the debris problem threatens not just space exploration but modern civilisation itself.'],c:1,e:'The passage shows that frictionless space is both a gift (satellites orbit indefinitely without fuel) and a curse (debris also orbits indefinitely). This duality — the same physics enabling both the solution and the problem — is a theme about unintended consequences that applies far beyond space science.'},
      {q:'The passage describes Newton\'s cannon thought experiment from the 1680s. What can be inferred about why scientists didn\'t build satellites until centuries later?',skill:'Inference',opts:['Newton\'s mathematical framework was only approximate, and subsequent physicists — particularly Einstein — had to refine the equations of orbital mechanics before engineers could calculate the precise speeds and trajectories needed to achieve stable orbit.','Political and cultural factors delayed satellite development — the scientific establishment saw Newton\'s thought experiment as purely theoretical and actively discouraged practical attempts to test it until the space race changed public attitudes.','The materials science required for satellite construction did not exist in Newton\'s era — while the physics of orbit was understood, no metals or alloys of that period could withstand the extreme temperatures and radiation found beyond the Earth\'s atmosphere.','The theoretical understanding existed long before the technology to achieve it — Newton could describe orbital mechanics, but humanity lacked the rocket technology and materials needed to actually reach orbital speed until the mid-twentieth century.'],c:3,e:'The passage notes Newton described orbits in the 1680s, \'long before any satellite existed.\' This implies the gap between theory and practice was technological, not intellectual. Reaching 28,000 kph requires rocket technology that didn\'t exist until the twentieth century. The inference is that understanding how something works and being able to do it are very different things.'},
      {q:'From what point of view is this passage written, and how does this affect the explanation?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['A knowledgeable science communicator writing for a general audience — the author understands the physics deeply but deliberately avoids jargon and uses analogies to make the concepts accessible to non-specialists.','A worried environmentalist focused entirely on the dangers of space debris, which explains why the passage ends with the warning that the sky is \'more crowded than it has ever been\' rather than celebrating satellite technology.','An astronaut describing their personal experience of being in orbit, which explains the passage\'s vivid description of satellites \'falling around the planet\' and the first-hand knowledge of orbital speeds.','A satellite engineer writing a technical manual for colleagues — the passage\'s precise figures of 27,500 kilometres per hour and 36,000 kilometres altitude suggest specialist knowledge aimed at a professional audience.'],c:0,e:'The author\'s perspective is that of an educator bridging specialist knowledge and public understanding. This is evident in choices like the Newton cannon analogy, the \'falling with style\' phrase, and the careful avoidance of equations. The point of view shapes the passage into something engaging rather than intimidating.'},
      {q:'What literary device does the author use when describing a satellite as \'falling around the planet in a continuous loop\'?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['Personification — the satellite is given human emotions about falling, suggesting it experiences fear or excitement as it travels at 27,500 kilometres per hour around the curved surface of the Earth.','Simile — the satellite is compared to something falling using the word \'like\', drawing a direct comparison between orbital motion and Newton\'s cannonball dropping from a mountaintop.','Alliteration — the repeated \'f\' sound in \'falling\' and \'around\' creates a rhythmic pattern that mimics the continuous circular motion of a satellite in low Earth orbit.','Paradox — the idea of \'falling around\' something contradicts everyday understanding of falling (which implies going down), forcing the reader to reconceptualise what falling means in the context of orbital physics.'],c:3,e:'\'Falling around\' is paradoxical because in everyday experience, falling means going down. The phrase forces the reader to expand their understanding: in orbit, falling is not a straight line but a curve that matches the Earth\'s surface. This paradox is the key insight of the entire passage, and the language makes it impossible to miss.'},
      {q:'Why does the author mention that geostationary satellites \'appear to hover over the same spot on the surface\'?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['To suggest that satellites can be seen hovering with the naked eye — the passage implies that geostationary satellites at 36,000 kilometres are visible from the ground as stationary points of light.','To connect the technical concept of orbital speed matching Earth\'s rotation to a practical, visible result — the reader understands why satellite dishes point at a fixed spot in the sky, linking abstract physics to everyday experience.','To argue that geostationary orbit is the only useful type of orbit — the passage contrasts it favourably with low Earth orbit by noting that the International Space Station must circle the planet every ninety minutes.','To prove that some satellites are not actually moving at all — the passage uses \'appear to hover\' to suggest that geostationary satellites are genuinely stationary rather than orbiting at the same speed as Earth\'s rotation.'],c:1,e:'The \'appear to hover\' detail bridges theory and daily life. Geostationary satellites are why TV dishes point at a fixed direction — they track a satellite that stays in one apparent position. By mentioning this, the author connects the orbital mechanics explanation to something the reader may have noticed without understanding, making the physics feel relevant and satisfying.'}
  ]},
  {id:'NF16',title:'The Rise of Electric Cars',type:'nonfiction',source:'Original passage — transport / environment / technology',
   text:'Electric cars are often presented as a brand-new technology — a twenty-first-century solution to twenty-first-century problems. In fact, they are older than most people realise. The first electric vehicle was built in the 1830s, decades before the petrol engine was invented. By 1900, electric cars outsold both petrol and steam-powered vehicles in the United States. They were quiet, clean, and easy to operate, and they were particularly popular with women, who found them more practical than the noisy, difficult-to-start petrol alternatives.\n\nSo what happened? The answer is Henry Ford. In 1908, Ford introduced the Model T — a petrol car that was mass-produced on an assembly line, making it far cheaper than any electric alternative. At the same time, the discovery of vast oil reserves in Texas made petrol extraordinarily cheap. Electric cars, which were expensive and limited in range, could not compete. By the 1920s, they had virtually disappeared from the roads.\n\nFor nearly a century, petrol dominated. Then, as evidence mounted that burning fossil fuels was driving climate change, interest in electric vehicles returned. The turning point came in 2008, when Tesla released the Roadster — a fully electric sports car that could travel over 300 kilometres on a single charge and accelerate from zero to sixty miles per hour in under four seconds. It shattered the perception that electric cars were slow, boring, or impractical.\n\nToday, electric vehicles are the fastest-growing segment of the global car market. In 2023, roughly one in five new cars sold worldwide was electric. Norway leads the way, with electric vehicles accounting for over eighty per cent of new car sales. Governments around the world are setting deadlines to phase out new petrol cars entirely, with the UK targeting 2035.\n\nBut the transition is not without complications. The batteries that power electric cars require lithium, cobalt, and other rare minerals, the extraction of which causes significant environmental damage in countries like the Democratic Republic of Congo and Chile. Charging infrastructure remains patchy, particularly in rural areas. And the electricity used to charge an electric car is only as clean as the power grid it comes from — in countries that rely heavily on coal, an electric car may produce more carbon emissions over its lifetime than a modern petrol engine.\n\nElectric vehicles are almost certainly part of the solution to climate change. But they are not the whole solution, and pretending they are risks distracting from harder questions about public transport, urban planning, and whether a society built around private cars — electric or otherwise — is sustainable in the long term.\n\nThe car of the future may well be electric. The question is whether the future still needs quite so many cars.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['Electric vehicles represent the single most important technological solution to climate change, and government deadlines like the UK\'s 2035 target will ensure a smooth and complete transition away from fossil-fuel-powered transport.','The passage primarily traces how Henry Ford\'s mass-production methods and the discovery of cheap oil in Texas destroyed the early electric car industry, arguing that economic forces rather than technology have always determined which vehicles dominate the market.','Electric cars have a longer history than most people realise and are growing rapidly, but they are part of a larger solution to climate change rather than a complete answer — harder questions about transport and sustainability remain.','The environmental costs of electric car batteries — particularly lithium and cobalt mining in developing countries — mean that electric vehicles may actually cause more ecological damage than the petrol cars they are designed to replace.'],c:2,e:'The passage avoids both uncritical enthusiasm and dismissal. It acknowledges electric cars\' potential while highlighting complications (mining, charging, grid emissions) and argues the bigger question is about transport systems, not just engine types. The main idea is nuanced: electric cars help, but are not sufficient alone.'},
      {q:'Why does the author begin with the surprising fact that electric cars existed in the 1830s?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['To establish the passage\'s credibility by demonstrating thorough historical research — starting with the earliest origins shows the author has investigated the full timeline rather than focusing only on recent trends.','To challenge the common assumption that electric cars are new — by showing they are over a century old, the author reframes the current transition as a return rather than an invention, which makes the reader question why they disappeared in the first place.','To bore the reader with irrelevant historical details, since the 1830s electric vehicle and the 1900s sales figures have no bearing on the modern Tesla Roadster or the UK\'s 2035 phase-out target.','To prove that 1830s technology was superior to modern technology, since the passage notes that early electric cars outsold petrol vehicles before Ford\'s assembly line made them obsolete.'],c:1,e:'The opening is designed to surprise. Most readers assume electric cars are cutting-edge. Learning they outsold petrol cars in 1900 forces a question: what happened? This question drives the reader through the Ford/oil explanation and reframes today\'s transition as a return to a suppressed technology, not a new invention.'},
      {q:'The passage states that in countries relying on coal power, an electric car \'may produce more carbon emissions over its lifetime than a modern petrol engine\'. Why does the author include this counterintuitive detail?',skill:'Analyse informational texts',opts:['To demonstrate that the environmental benefit of electric cars depends on context — the car itself produces no emissions, but the electricity powering it might, showing that the solution is more complex than simply switching vehicle types.','To prove that coal power stations should be closed immediately — the passage uses the comparison between electric and petrol car emissions to argue that energy policy must change before vehicle technology can make any difference.','To argue that electric cars are worse than petrol cars and should be banned — the passage presents the lifetime emissions comparison as evidence that the entire transition away from petrol engines is misguided.','Because the author is sponsored by the petrol industry, which explains why the passage highlights complications like lithium mining in Congo and Chile rather than focusing on the benefits of zero tailpipe emissions.'],c:0,e:'This detail is the passage\'s most important complication. It shows that electric cars are not automatically green — their benefit depends on the energy grid. This prevents simplistic thinking and supports the passage\'s broader argument that solving climate change requires systemic change (clean energy, better transport) not just technological substitution.'},
      {q:'The final sentence asks: \'The question is whether the future still needs quite so many cars.\' What is the effect of ending with a question?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['It suggests the author is against all forms of transport — the phrase \'quite so many cars\' implies that public transport, cycling, and walking should replace all private vehicle ownership entirely.','It means the passage has no conclusion and is unfinished — the question about whether the future needs cars is left unanswered because the author ran out of evidence after discussing battery mining and grid emissions.','It shows the author doesn\'t know the answer and should have done more research, since the passage admits that Norway has eighty per cent electric sales without examining whether this has reduced that country\'s carbon emissions.','It challenges the reader to think beyond the passage\'s immediate topic — shifting from \'what kind of car?\' to the deeper question of whether car-dependent societies are sustainable, leaving the reader with something to consider.'],c:3,e:'Ending with a question is a deliberate rhetorical choice. Rather than closing the topic, it opens a bigger one: the passage has discussed what powers cars, but the final question asks whether the car itself is the right unit of transport. This elevates the passage from a technology article to a piece about societal choices.'},
      {q:'What is the author\'s primary purpose in this passage?',skill:'Author\'s purpose',opts:['To inform the reader about the history, growth, and limitations of electric vehicles while encouraging critical thinking about whether technology alone can solve climate change.','To argue that everyone should stop driving immediately, with the final question about whether society needs \'quite so many cars\' serving as a direct call for readers to give up private vehicle ownership.','To sell electric cars to the reader — the passage\'s description of the Tesla Roadster\'s acceleration and range is designed to persuade consumers that electric vehicles are exciting and desirable.','To prove that Henry Ford was responsible for climate change, since the passage blames the Model T\'s mass production and cheap Texas oil for creating a century of fossil fuel dependency.'],c:0,e:'The passage is informational but with a critical edge. It presents facts about electric car history and growth (informing), raises complications about mining and grid emissions (complicating), and ends by questioning car dependency itself (provoking). The author doesn\'t tell the reader what to think but gives them the tools to think carefully.'},
      {q:'What can be inferred about why electric cars were \'particularly popular with women\' in the early 1900s?',skill:'Inference',opts:['Petrol cars required physical cranking to start and were noisy and mechanically temperamental, while electric cars were simpler to operate — the inference is that social norms and practical design made electric cars more accessible to women at that time.','Electric cars were painted in colours that appealed specifically to women — the passage\'s description of them as \'quiet\' and \'clean\' suggests manufacturers deliberately marketed them with feminine aesthetics.','Women received discounts on electric car purchases from manufacturers — the passage notes that electric cars were more expensive than petrol alternatives, so price reductions would explain their popularity with women.','Women were legally required to drive electric cars in the early 1900s, since the passage states they were \'particularly popular with women\' in a way that suggests obligation rather than personal choice.'],c:0,e:'The passage says women found electric cars \'more practical than the noisy, difficult-to-start petrol alternatives.\' Early petrol cars required hand-cranking (physically demanding and sometimes dangerous) and were mechanically complex. The inference is that electric cars\' ease of use made them accessible in an era when women were often excluded from mechanical knowledge.'},
      {q:'What is the overall tone of the passage?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Balanced and thought-provoking — the author presents electric cars positively while raising genuine complications, creating a tone that respects the reader\'s intelligence rather than pushing a simple narrative.','Hostile and dismissive — the author clearly opposes the transition to electric vehicles, using the complications of lithium mining in Congo and patchy charging infrastructure to discredit the entire electric car movement.','Entirely optimistic — the author believes electric cars will solve all environmental problems, presenting the growth to one in five new cars sold and Norway\'s eighty per cent share as proof that the climate crisis is being resolved.','Sarcastic — the author mocks people who buy electric cars, using the phrase \'pretending they are\' to ridicule consumers who believe switching to electric vehicles is sufficient to address climate change.'],c:0,e:'The tone is neither promotional nor dismissive. The passage celebrates electric cars\' history and growth but honestly addresses battery mining, charging infrastructure, and grid emissions. The final question about whether we need so many cars at all shows a tone that trusts the reader to handle complexity rather than needing a simple hero-or-villain narrative.'},
      {q:'What theme does the passage explore through the rise, fall, and return of electric vehicles?',skill:'Theme',opts:['The theme that technological progress is not always linear — good ideas can be suppressed by economic forces and later revived when circumstances change, suggesting that the \'best\' technology does not always win.','The theme that all technological change is inevitable and cannot be influenced by human decisions, since the passage shows electric cars returning after a century without any deliberate effort by governments or manufacturers.','The theme that Henry Ford was personally responsible for climate change, since the Model T\'s assembly-line production and cheap Texas oil are presented as the direct cause of a century of carbon emissions.','The theme that petrol engines are inherently superior to electric motors in every way, as demonstrated by Ford\'s Model T outselling electric alternatives and dominating the market for nearly a century.'],c:0,e:'Electric cars dominated in 1900, were killed by cheap petrol and mass production, and returned a century later due to climate concerns. This arc demonstrates that technological adoption is shaped by economics, politics, and circumstance — not just technical merit. The theme warns against assuming the current dominant technology is necessarily the best one.'},
      {q:'The passage mentions that Tesla\'s Roadster \'shattered the perception that electric cars were slow, boring, or impractical\'. What literary device is used here?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['Personification — the car is given the human ability to feel excitement — the Roadster\'s acceleration from zero to sixty in under four seconds is described as if the vehicle itself experiences a thrill.','Onomatopoeia — \'shattered\' imitates the sound of breaking glass, echoing the physical noise of the Roadster\'s powerful electric motor as it accelerated past traditional sports cars on the test track.','Simile — the Roadster is compared to shattered glass using \'like\' — the passage likens the car\'s sleek design to broken crystal fragments to emphasise its radical departure from traditional vehicle shapes.','Metaphor — \'shattered\' compares a change in public perception to breaking something physically, conveying the sudden and dramatic nature of the shift in how people viewed electric vehicles.'],c:3,e:'\'Shattered\' is a forceful metaphor that implies the old perception was rigid and brittle — like glass — and was broken dramatically rather than gradually eroded. The word choice conveys that the Roadster did not merely change opinions; it destroyed the old narrative completely, which fits the car\'s role as a turning point in the passage.'},
      {q:'From whose perspective is the passage written, and how does this shape the argument?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['An electric car owner sharing their personal driving experience, which explains the passage\'s enthusiastic description of the Tesla Roadster\'s speed and range as first-hand testimony rather than researched facts.','A climate change denier who wants to discredit the electric car industry, which explains why the passage raises complications about lithium mining and coal-powered charging rather than celebrating electric vehicles.','A critically informed commentator who supports the electric transition but refuses to oversimplify it — this perspective allows the author to celebrate progress while honestly addressing the mining, infrastructure, and grid problems that enthusiasts often overlook.','A car manufacturer trying to sell electric vehicles to the reader, which explains why the passage highlights the Tesla Roadster\'s impressive acceleration and Norway\'s eighty per cent market share.'],c:2,e:'The author writes as an informed analyst rather than an advocate or opponent. This perspective is crucial: it allows the passage to acknowledge electric cars\' benefits without becoming an advertisement, and to raise complications without seeming hostile. The balanced viewpoint makes the final question about car dependency feel like genuine inquiry rather than rhetoric.'},
      {q:'Why does the author specifically mention the Democratic Republic of Congo and Chile in relation to battery minerals?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['To make the environmental and ethical costs of electric cars geographically concrete — naming specific countries forces the reader to recognise that the clean technology they benefit from creates real damage in identifiable places.','To recommend these countries as holiday destinations for the reader — the passage mentions Congo and Chile because their natural landscapes, affected by lithium and cobalt mining, attract eco-tourists.','Because these are the only two countries where lithium and cobalt are extracted, and the passage implies that solving the mining problem in just these two nations would make electric car batteries entirely sustainable.','To argue that mining should be banned in all countries worldwide, since the passage presents the environmental damage in Congo and Chile as evidence that mineral extraction is inherently destructive everywhere.'],c:0,e:'Naming specific countries transforms an abstract concern (\'mining causes damage\') into something the reader can locate on a map. The Democratic Republic of Congo is associated with exploitative cobalt mining, and Chile with lithium extraction in fragile ecosystems. These references prevent the reader from treating electric cars\' environmental costs as vague or theoretical.'},
      {q:'What can be inferred about why the author includes the UK\'s 2035 petrol car phase-out target?',skill:'Inference',opts:['To argue that the 2035 deadline is too soon and should be delayed — the passage\'s mention of patchy charging infrastructure and coal-dependent grids suggests the UK is not ready for a complete transition by that date.','To prove that the UK is the only country banning petrol cars — the passage singles out Britain\'s 2035 target without mentioning that Norway already has eighty per cent electric sales, implying the UK leads alone.','To show that the transition to electric vehicles is not just a market trend but a government-mandated shift — the specific date makes the change feel imminent and personally relevant to UK readers.','To suggest that petrol cars will become illegal to own after 2035, since the passage says the UK is targeting that year to \'phase out new petrol cars entirely\', implying existing petrol vehicles must also be surrendered.'],c:2,e:'Including the UK target serves multiple purposes: it grounds the global trend in the reader\'s own country, makes the timeline concrete (2035 is close enough to affect current car-buying decisions), and shows that governments — not just markets — are driving the transition. For UK students reading this passage, the detail makes the issue personally relevant.'}
  ]},
  {id:'NF17',title:'Food Miles: How Far Did Your Dinner Travel?',type:'nonfiction',source:'Original passage — geography / sustainability / food systems',
   text:'A typical supermarket meal in the United Kingdom might include chicken from Thailand, green beans from Kenya, rice from India, and strawberries from Spain. Before it reaches your plate, your dinner may have travelled a combined distance of over twenty thousand kilometres — roughly half the circumference of the Earth. The term for this distance is \'food miles\', and it has become one of the most discussed concepts in the debate about sustainable eating.\n\nThe logic behind the food miles argument is straightforward: transporting food long distances requires fuel, which produces carbon emissions, which contribute to climate change. Therefore, buying local food should be better for the environment because it travels shorter distances. This reasoning feels intuitive, and it has driven a growing \'buy local\' movement, with farmers\' markets, seasonal eating campaigns, and supermarket labels highlighting British-grown produce.\n\nBut the science is more complicated than the slogan. Research has consistently shown that transport accounts for only a small fraction of a food\'s total carbon footprint — typically less than ten per cent. The much larger factors are how the food was produced: what farming methods were used, how much water and fertiliser were required, whether the land was heated or irrigated, and how much waste occurred along the supply chain.\n\nThis leads to some surprising results. A study by Lincoln University in New Zealand found that lamb shipped from New Zealand to the UK actually had a lower total carbon footprint than lamb raised in Britain, because New Zealand\'s grass-fed farming system required far less energy than the UK\'s more intensive methods. Similarly, tomatoes grown outdoors in Spain and trucked to London produce fewer emissions than tomatoes grown in heated greenhouses in England, even though the Spanish ones travel much further.\n\nNone of this means food miles are irrelevant. Air-freighted food — particularly fresh produce like berries and asparagus flown in from distant countries — does carry a significantly higher carbon cost than food transported by ship or road. And there are valid reasons beyond carbon to support local food systems: they strengthen rural economies, reduce packaging, increase freshness, and reconnect consumers with the seasons.\n\nThe key lesson is that environmental impact cannot be reduced to a single number. \'How far did it travel?\' is an important question, but it is not the only question — and sometimes it is not even the most important one. \'How was it grown?\' often matters more.\n\nFood choices are complex, and anyone who tells you there is a simple rule — \'always buy local\', \'never eat imported\' — is oversimplifying a system that resists easy answers. The most sustainable diet is not necessarily the most local one. It is the most informed one.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['While food miles matter, they are only one part of a food\'s environmental impact — how food is produced often matters more than how far it travels, and sustainable eating requires informed choices rather than simple rules.','Local food is always better for the environment because shorter transport distances guarantee a lower carbon footprint, as shown by the farmers\' market and seasonal eating examples cited in the passage.','All imported food is harmful because the twenty-thousand-kilometre journey described in the opening produces more emissions than any production method could offset.','The passage argues that food miles are completely irrelevant because the New Zealand lamb and Spanish tomato studies prove transport emissions never matter in any circumstance.'],c:0,e:'The passage doesn\'t dismiss food miles but places them in context. Transport is typically less than 10% of a food\'s carbon footprint; production methods dominate. The main idea is that sustainability is complex and requires looking at the whole picture, not just distance.'},
      {q:'How is this passage structured?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['Persuasive argument — the author uses the New Zealand lamb and Spanish tomato examples solely to convince readers to stop buying British-grown produce.','Claim, complication, evidence, balanced conclusion — the passage presents the food miles argument, challenges it with evidence, then offers a nuanced conclusion.','Strict chronological order — the passage traces food miles from their earliest use in the 1990s through to present-day supermarket labelling campaigns.','Compare and contrast only — each paragraph pairs one British food product against one imported alternative to measure their relative carbon footprints.'],c:1,e:'The passage follows a classic complicating structure: it presents the intuitive food miles argument (paragraphs 1–2), challenges it with evidence (paragraphs 3–4), acknowledges where food miles do matter (paragraph 5), and concludes with a balanced message (paragraphs 6–7). This structure teaches the reader to think critically rather than accept simple narratives.'},
      {q:'The passage cites a study showing New Zealand lamb shipped to the UK has lower emissions than British lamb. Why is this example included?',skill:'Analyse informational texts',opts:['To provide a concrete, counterintuitive example that challenges the reader\'s assumption that local always means greener — demonstrating that production methods can outweigh transport emissions.','To encourage readers to buy New Zealand lamb specifically, since the Lincoln University study proves it is the most environmentally sustainable meat available in British supermarkets.','To show that transport accounts for over ninety per cent of a food\'s carbon footprint, which is why lamb shipped from New Zealand has such dramatically lower emissions.','To prove that New Zealand\'s climate is better than Britain\'s in every respect, making all New Zealand agricultural exports greener regardless of farming method.'],c:0,e:'The New Zealand lamb example is the passage\'s most powerful piece of evidence because it directly contradicts intuition. If food that travels 19,000 km can have lower emissions than food from the next county, the reader must reconsider their assumptions. The specific, credible source (Lincoln University) adds authority.'},
      {q:'The final sentence says \'The most sustainable diet is not necessarily the most local one. It is the most informed one.\' What makes this an effective conclusion?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['It tells the reader exactly what to eat for every meal by listing which imported products are acceptable and which local ones should be avoided.','It means the passage dismisses the buy-local movement entirely, since calling for an \'informed\' diet implies that farmers\' market shoppers are uninformed.','It reframes the entire discussion — shifting the standard from \'local\' (a simple geographic rule) to \'informed\' (a complex, personal judgement), empowering the reader to think rather than follow slogans.','It proves that environmental labelling on supermarket packaging is always misleading and should be removed from British-grown produce.'],c:2,e:'The final sentence replaces a simple rule (\'buy local\') with a harder but more accurate principle (\'be informed\'). This is empowering rather than prescriptive — it trusts the reader to evaluate evidence rather than follow a slogan. It also encapsulates the passage\'s entire argument in two sentences.'},
      {q:'What is the author\'s primary purpose in this passage?',skill:'Author\'s purpose',opts:['To sell imported food products to British consumers by demonstrating that chicken from Thailand and beans from Kenya are always greener than their British equivalents.','To argue that farmers\' markets are a waste of time because the passage\'s evidence about rural economies and seasonal freshness shows these benefits are negligible.','To prove that the ten-per-cent transport figure means carbon emissions from food are too small to warrant any change in consumer behaviour.','To challenge a popular assumption about food miles by presenting evidence that environmental impact is more complex than distance alone — encouraging critical thinking about sustainability claims.'],c:3,e:'The author\'s purpose is to complicate, not dismiss. The passage respects the food miles concept but shows it\'s incomplete. By presenting evidence that production methods often matter more than transport, the author encourages readers to look beyond simple labels and think critically about environmental claims — a skill that extends beyond food.'},
      {q:'What can be inferred about why the author describes a typical UK supermarket meal at the start of the passage?',skill:'Inference',opts:['Because the author works for a supermarket chain that imports chicken from Thailand and green beans from Kenya and wants to justify those supply routes.','To prove that British supermarkets sell only imported food, since the meal described contains no British-grown ingredients whatsoever.','To advertise specific supermarket products such as Thai chicken and Kenyan beans by making them sound exotic and appealing to the reader.','To make the abstract concept of food miles tangible and personal — by listing specific items the reader probably eats, the author shows that the issue directly affects the reader\'s own daily life.'],c:3,e:'The opening meal — chicken from Thailand, beans from Kenya, rice from India, strawberries from Spain — is designed to surprise the reader with the global journey of their ordinary dinner. By making it personal (\'your plate\', \'your dinner\'), the author ensures the reader sees food miles as their own issue, not an abstract environmental debate.'},
      {q:'What is the overall tone of the passage?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Measured and intellectually honest — the author complicates a popular environmental argument without dismissing it, creating a tone that respects both the reader\'s concern for the environment and their intelligence.','Preachy and moralistic — the author lectures the reader about what to eat, using phrases like \'oversimplifying\' and \'resists easy answers\' to shame anyone who follows the buy-local movement.','Aggressive and dismissive — the author attacks people who buy local food by describing farmers\' markets and seasonal eating campaigns as naive and scientifically ignorant.','Entirely neutral with no opinion expressed at any point, as the passage avoids all evaluative language and never suggests which approach to food sustainability is better.'],c:0,e:'The tone is carefully balanced. The author takes the food miles concern seriously (\'none of this means food miles are irrelevant\') while presenting evidence that complicates it. This intellectual honesty — acknowledging a good argument while showing it is incomplete — creates a tone that feels trustworthy and respectful rather than condescending.'},
      {q:'What theme does the passage explore through the food miles debate?',skill:'Theme',opts:['The theme that consumers have no power to influence environmental outcomes because the passage shows that carbon footprints are determined entirely by production methods beyond an individual shopper\'s control.','The theme that local food is always the most ethical choice, as demonstrated by the passage\'s list of benefits including rural economies, reduced packaging, and seasonal reconnection.','The theme that simple rules often fail to capture complex realities — well-intentioned environmental slogans can be misleading, and genuine sustainability requires deeper understanding rather than easy answers.','The theme that scientific studies are unreliable, since the Lincoln University research and the Spanish tomato comparison reach conclusions that contradict common sense.'],c:2,e:'The passage repeatedly shows that intuitive rules (\'local is better\') break down under scrutiny. New Zealand lamb, Spanish tomatoes, and air-freighted berries all complicate the simple food miles narrative. The theme is that environmental issues resist simplification, and that slogans — however well-intentioned — can mislead if not supported by deeper understanding.'},
      {q:'The passage lists several non-carbon benefits of local food: \'strengthening rural economies, reducing packaging, increasing freshness, reconnecting consumers with the seasons\'. Why does the author include these?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['To concede that the \'buy local\' argument has genuine merits beyond carbon emissions — this concession strengthens the author\'s credibility by showing fairness and prevents the passage from appearing one-sided.','To contradict the earlier scientific evidence about carbon footprints by showing that non-carbon benefits outweigh the New Zealand lamb and Spanish tomato findings.','To prove that local food is better than imported food in every way, since strengthening rural economies and increasing freshness are more important than carbon emissions.','Because the author is a local farmer who benefits from the buy-local movement and wants to highlight its advantages over the imported food industry.'],c:0,e:'This is a rhetorical concession — acknowledging the opposition\'s strongest points. By admitting local food has real benefits (economy, freshness, seasonality), the author appears fair-minded rather than dismissive. This strengthens the overall argument: even after granting these benefits, the central point remains that food miles alone are an incomplete measure of sustainability.'},
      {q:'From whose perspective is this passage written?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['A British farmer arguing against food imports, since the passage\'s detailed list of local food benefits — rural economies, freshness, seasonality — reveals the author\'s personal stake in the buy-local movement.','An informed analyst who has studied the evidence on both sides of the food miles debate and presents a nuanced view that challenges popular assumptions while respecting genuine environmental concerns.','A supermarket executive justifying the sale of imported produce, since the New Zealand lamb and Spanish tomato examples specifically defend the long-distance supply chains that supermarkets rely on.','A Kenyan green bean farmer defending the export industry, since the opening paragraph\'s mention of beans from Kenya suggests the author has first-hand knowledge of that particular supply chain.'],c:1,e:'The author writes without a personal economic stake in the debate, which allows for genuine balance. They present the food miles argument fairly, challenge it with evidence, acknowledge where it holds, and conclude with a call for informed rather than rule-based thinking. This removed, analytical perspective gives the passage credibility with readers on both sides.'},
      {q:'Why does the author specifically use the Spanish tomato versus English greenhouse tomato comparison?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['To argue that Spain has better weather than England in every season, which means all Spanish agricultural products are greener than their English equivalents regardless of farming method.','Because the author wants to discourage greenhouse farming entirely, using the heated English greenhouse as evidence that artificial growing environments should be banned in the UK.','To prove that transport distance is always the best measure of environmental impact, since the Spanish tomatoes travel further yet still produce fewer emissions than locally grown ones.','Because it provides a vivid, everyday example where \'local\' is actually worse for the environment — heated English greenhouses use more energy than Spanish sunshine, making the counterintuitive result easy for the reader to understand and remember.'],c:3,e:'The tomato example works because it is simple, relatable, and counterintuitive. Most readers would assume a tomato grown in England is greener than one trucked from Spain. Learning that the heated greenhouse makes the English tomato worse for the climate is surprising and memorable — it demonstrates the passage\'s core argument in a single, concrete case.'},
      {q:'The passage says \'anyone who tells you there is a simple rule is oversimplifying a system that resists easy answers\'. What does this reveal about the author\'s attitude towards environmental campaigners?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['The author thinks simple rules like \'always buy local\' are correct and should be followed, since the passage\'s list of local food benefits confirms they lead to the most sustainable outcomes.','The author believes all environmental campaigners are liars because the food miles concept is based on the false premise that transport accounts for most of a food\'s carbon footprint.','The author has no opinion on environmental campaigners because the passage focuses exclusively on scientific data about carbon footprints without mentioning any advocacy groups or movements.','The author respects the intention behind environmental campaigns but criticises their tendency to reduce complex issues to slogans — suggesting that oversimplification, even with good intentions, can be misleading and counterproductive.'],c:3,e:'The author does not attack campaigners personally but critiques the oversimplification of their messaging. The phrasing \'anyone who tells you there is a simple rule\' is aimed at slogans, not people. This nuanced criticism respects the movement\'s goals while arguing that its methods sometimes undermine those goals by encouraging shallow rather than informed engagement.'}
  ]},
  {id:'NF18',title:'The Athletes Who Changed the Rules',type:'nonfiction',source:'Original passage — sport / fairness / prosthetics / ethics',
   text:'In 2012, Oscar Pistorius became the first double-amputee sprinter to compete at the Olympic Games. Running on carbon-fibre blades known as \'Cheetahs\', he reached the semi-finals of the 400 metres in London — racing against able-bodied athletes on the biggest stage in world sport. The moment was celebrated by many as a triumph of human determination. But it also opened a question that sport has been wrestling with ever since: when does assistive technology stop being a leveller and start being an advantage?\n\nThe debate centres on whether prosthetic running blades give their users any biomechanical benefit over biological legs. Pistorius\'s blades were lighter than human legs and returned energy differently during a stride. Some scientists argued this gave him an unfair advantage, particularly in the later stages of a race when biological muscles fatigue but carbon fibre does not. Others countered that Pistorius faced enormous disadvantages — slower starts, reduced balance, and no ability to feel the track surface — that more than offset any benefit from the blades.\n\nThe International Association of Athletics Federations initially banned Pistorius from able-bodied competition in 2008, citing research that suggested his blades provided a measurable energy return advantage. Pistorius appealed to the Court of Arbitration for Sport, which overturned the ban, ruling that the evidence was inconclusive. The court did not say the blades provided no advantage — only that the science was not clear enough to justify exclusion.\n\nThis unresolved question has grown more urgent as prosthetic technology advances. Modern running blades are more efficient, more customisable, and more responsive than the ones Pistorius used. In long jump, athlete Markus Rehm — a single leg amputee — has jumped distances that would have won gold at several Olympic Games, yet he has been prevented from competing because officials cannot determine whether his blade gives him an unfair advantage in the take-off phase.\n\nThe implications stretch beyond individual athletes. If prosthetic limbs eventually become demonstrably superior to biological ones — which some engineers believe is only a matter of time — the fundamental category that separates the Olympics from the Paralympics begins to dissolve. Would an able-bodied sprinter consider using a prosthetic to gain an edge? Would regulations even be able to keep pace with the technology?\n\nThese are not hypothetical questions for the distant future. They are being asked now, in courtrooms and committee meetings, by athletes, engineers, ethicists, and governing bodies who are trying to define fairness in an era when the human body is no longer the only equipment in the race.\n\nSport has always been about pushing limits. The question these athletes force us to ask is simple but profound: where does the athlete end and the equipment begin?',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['Oscar Pistorius proved that prosthetic limbs give no advantage at all, since the Court of Arbitration for Sport ruled definitively that his Cheetah blades imposed only disadvantages.','The passage argues that the Olympics and Paralympics should merge into one competition because Markus Rehm\'s long jump distances prove the distinction between the two events is already meaningless.','Advances in prosthetic technology are challenging sport\'s definition of fairness — the line between assistive device and performance advantage is blurring, forcing fundamental questions about competition and the human body.','Prosthetic limbs should be banned from all sports because the IAAF\'s original 2008 ban on Pistorius was scientifically justified and should never have been overturned on appeal.'],c:2,e:'The passage doesn\'t take a firm side on whether blades are advantageous. Instead, it traces a growing dilemma: as prosthetics improve, the boundary between assistance and advantage becomes harder to define. The main idea is about the question itself — what is fairness when technology meets the human body?'},
      {q:'The Court of Arbitration \'did not say the blades provided no advantage — only that the science was not clear enough to justify exclusion\'. Why does the author highlight this distinction?',skill:'Analyse informational texts',opts:['To show that the ruling was carefully limited — it didn\'t declare the blades fair, it declared the evidence insufficient, meaning the question remains genuinely open rather than settled.','To prove that the Court made a mistake in its ruling because later evidence about Rehm\'s long jump performances confirmed that prosthetic blades do provide a measurable energy return advantage.','To argue that courts should not be involved in sports decisions because the Court of Arbitration lacked the scientific expertise to evaluate biomechanical evidence about blade energy return.','To suggest that Pistorius privately knew his Cheetah blades gave him an advantage in the later stages of races when biological muscles fatigue but carbon fibre does not.'],c:0,e:'This distinction is crucial to the passage\'s argument. If the court had said \'no advantage\', the debate would be over. Instead, \'inconclusive\' means the question persists. The author highlights this to show the reader that the fairness debate is unresolved and likely to intensify as technology improves.'},
      {q:'How is this passage structured?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['Compare and contrast — each paragraph pairs one advantage of prosthetic blades against one disadvantage, alternating systematically to create a balanced scientific evaluation.','Strict chronological order — the passage moves year by year from Pistorius\'s 2008 ban through his 2012 Olympic appearance to Rehm\'s subsequent competitions, following an exact timeline.','Persuasive argument — the author uses Pistorius\'s slower starts and reduced balance as evidence that prosthetic athletes are unfairly disadvantaged and should have separate competitions.','Case study → broader debate → future implications — the passage uses Pistorius\'s story to introduce a wider ethical question that escalates with technological progress.'],c:3,e:'The passage builds from specific to general: Pistorius\'s individual case (paragraphs 1–3), then Rehm\'s case showing the problem is growing (paragraph 4), then the broader hypothetical about technology surpassing biology (paragraph 5), and finally the philosophical question at the core (paragraphs 6–7). Each step widens the scope.'},
      {q:'The final question asks: \'Where does the athlete end and the equipment begin?\' What makes this an effective ending?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['It proves the author believes prosthetic blades should be classified as equipment rather than as part of the athlete\'s body for competition purposes.','It distils the entire passage\'s complex ethical debate into a single, memorable question that the reader cannot easily answer — forcing them to engage with the ambiguity rather than expecting a neat conclusion.','It is a practical question about where to physically draw the boundary between Pistorius\'s Cheetah blades and his biological limbs for biomechanical measurement.','It suggests that prosthetic athletes like Pistorius and Rehm have already crossed the line and should be reclassified as technology-assisted competitors.'],c:1,e:'The question is powerful because it is genuinely hard to answer. Every athlete uses equipment (shoes, swimsuits, bikes), but we draw a line somewhere. Prosthetics blur that line. The question doesn\'t have a right answer, which is the point — it leaves the reader thinking rather than satisfied, matching the passage\'s theme of unresolved complexity.'},
      {q:'What is the author\'s primary purpose in this passage?',skill:'Author\'s purpose',opts:['To argue that all prosthetic athletes should be excluded from mainstream competition because the IAAF\'s original ban was correct and the Court of Arbitration\'s reversal was a scientific error.','To explore a complex ethical question about fairness, technology, and the human body in sport — presenting multiple perspectives without declaring a winner, and encouraging the reader to form their own view.','To promote the development of more advanced prosthetic blades by showing that athletes like Rehm can already match Olympic-level long jump distances.','To celebrate Oscar Pistorius as proof that prosthetic technology has already surpassed biological limbs, since he reached the Olympic 400-metre semi-finals against able-bodied sprinters.'],c:1,e:'The passage is deliberately balanced. It presents arguments on both sides (blades offer advantages / blades impose disadvantages), acknowledges the court\'s inconclusive ruling, and raises future questions without answering them. The author\'s purpose is exploratory: laying out the landscape so the reader can think critically about fairness.'},
      {q:'What can be inferred about why the International Association of Athletics Federations initially banned Pistorius rather than allowing him to compete while the science was studied?',skill:'Inference',opts:['Pistorius had violated anti-doping regulations alongside using prosthetic blades, which gave the IAAF additional grounds for exclusion beyond the biomechanical evidence.','The IAAF wanted to prevent Pistorius from reaching the Olympic semi-finals because his success would embarrass able-bodied sprinters and undermine the prestige of the 400 metres.','The ban was designed to force prosthetic technology companies to share their research data with the IAAF before athletes could use new blade designs in competition.','The governing body likely prioritised protecting the perceived fairness of competition over individual inclusion — banning first and investigating later suggests they viewed potential unfair advantage as a greater risk than wrongful exclusion.'],c:3,e:'The IAAF\'s approach — ban first, let the athlete appeal — reveals a conservative institutional mindset: when in doubt, protect the status quo. This inference is important because it shows how governing bodies default to exclusion rather than inclusion, which the passage uses to raise broader questions about who bears the burden of proof in fairness debates.'},
      {q:'What is the overall tone of the passage?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Thoughtful and deliberately unresolved — the author explores a genuine ethical dilemma without pretending to have the answer, creating a tone of intellectual curiosity rather than moral certainty.','Celebratory — the author is entirely positive about prosthetic athletes competing in mainstream sport, describing Pistorius\'s Olympic semi-final as a triumph that settled the fairness debate permanently.','Hostile — the author clearly believes prosthetic athletes should be banned, since the passage emphasises the Cheetah blades\' lighter weight and energy return while downplaying the athletes\' disadvantages.','Dismissive — the author treats the debate as already resolved by the Court of Arbitration\'s ruling and sees no reason for further investigation into blade biomechanics.'],c:0,e:'The tone is exploratory rather than declarative. The author presents arguments on both sides (advantages vs. disadvantages of blades), notes the court\'s inconclusive ruling, and poses questions without answering them. This deliberately unresolved tone mirrors the subject matter — the ethical dilemma is genuinely unresolved, and the tone reflects that honestly.'},
      {q:'What theme does the passage explore through the examples of Pistorius and Rehm?',skill:'Theme',opts:['The theme that technology always makes sport more fair, as demonstrated by Pistorius reaching the Olympic semi-finals and Rehm achieving distances that would have won Olympic gold.','The theme that sports governing bodies always make the correct decisions, since both the IAAF\'s original ban and the Court of Arbitration\'s reversal were based on sound scientific evidence.','The theme that disabled athletes will always be disadvantaged because Pistorius\'s slower starts and reduced balance prove that prosthetics can never fully compensate for a missing limb.','The theme that definitions of fairness are not fixed but evolve as technology challenges existing categories — what seems fair in one era may become inadequate as new possibilities emerge.'],c:3,e:'Both Pistorius and Rehm demonstrate that traditional definitions of fairness assumed a biological baseline. Prosthetics disrupt this baseline, forcing sport to reconsider what \'fair\' means. The theme is that fairness is not a fixed standard but a negotiated concept that must evolve with technology — a lesson applicable far beyond sport.'},
      {q:'The passage mentions that Pistorius\'s blades were \'lighter than human legs and returned energy differently\'. What literary technique does the author use by presenting both sides of the scientific debate?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['The author uses repetition of the same argument, restating the energy return advantage multiple times to convince the reader that Pistorius\'s Cheetah blades were unfair.','The author uses only emotional appeals, relying on the inspirational story of Pistorius\'s Olympic appearance rather than engaging with the biomechanical data about blade energy return.','Balanced argument — the author presents evidence for advantage (lighter, different energy return) and disadvantage (slower starts, reduced balance, no track sensation) side by side, allowing the reader to weigh both perspectives without being told what to conclude.','The author uses hyperbole to exaggerate Pistorius\'s disadvantages — claims about slower starts and inability to feel the track surface are overstated to generate sympathy for the athlete.'],c:2,e:'Presenting both scientific perspectives equally is a deliberate rhetorical strategy. By giving roughly equal space to \'advantage\' and \'disadvantage\' arguments, the author models fair-minded analysis. The reader is not manipulated toward either conclusion but is shown how to evaluate competing evidence — a skill the passage implicitly teaches.'},
      {q:'From whose point of view is this passage written, and why is that perspective effective?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['An engineer who designed the Cheetah blades, which explains why the passage emphasises the technical sophistication of carbon-fibre prosthetics and their improving efficiency over time.','An impartial observer who understands both the sporting and ethical dimensions of the debate — this perspective is effective because it allows the reader to trust the author is not advocating for a particular outcome.','An athlete with prosthetic legs who wants to defend their right to compete, which explains why the passage gives more space to the disadvantages of blades than to their potential advantages.','A sports official who has already decided that prosthetics should be banned, which explains why the passage opens by describing the IAAF\'s initial decision to exclude Pistorius from competition.'],c:1,e:'The author\'s impartiality is key to the passage\'s effectiveness. By not taking a side, the author creates space for the reader to think independently. An advocate\'s perspective would feel one-sided; an official\'s would feel bureaucratic. The observer\'s position allows for genuine exploration of a complex issue without the baggage of a predetermined conclusion.'},
      {q:'The passage asks whether \'an able-bodied sprinter would consider using a prosthetic to gain an edge\'. What is the purpose of this hypothetical?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['To suggest that able-bodied athletes are already secretly considering prosthetic enhancements because modern blades are more efficient and customisable than the ones Pistorius used.','To push the debate to its logical extreme — if prosthetics eventually surpass biological limbs, the current distinction between Olympics and Paralympics collapses, forcing the reader to confront how fundamentally technology could reshape sport.','To argue that all athletes should be required to use standardised prosthetic limbs so that competition is based purely on training and technique rather than biological variation.','To prove that prosthetic technology will never be better than biological limbs because Pistorius\'s slower starts and reduced balance show that blades cannot replicate natural leg function.'],c:1,e:'The hypothetical is deliberately provocative. By imagining an able-bodied athlete choosing a prosthetic, the author takes a current controversy and projects it forward to its most unsettling implication. This forces the reader to engage with the philosophical core of the debate: what does it mean to compete as a human being when technology can enhance or replace the body?'},
      {q:'What can be inferred about why the passage mentions that these debates are happening \'in courtrooms and committee meetings\'?',skill:'Inference',opts:['To show that the question of prosthetics in sport is not theoretical but is actively being decided by real institutions right now — the mention of legal and administrative settings conveys urgency and real-world consequences.','To prove that all sports disputes should be settled in court because the IAAF\'s original scientific research was not rigorous enough to withstand legal scrutiny at the Court of Arbitration.','Because the author is a lawyer who specialises in sports law and wants to advertise the role of legal professionals in resolving disputes about prosthetic technology in athletics.','To argue that lawyers and committee members should have the final say over athletes because the IAAF and the Court of Arbitration produced better-informed decisions than the athletes themselves could.'],c:0,e:'Mentioning courtrooms and committee meetings grounds the philosophical debate in institutional reality. These are not abstract thought experiments — real athletes\' careers depend on these decisions. The detail adds urgency and shows that the ethical questions the passage raises are already demanding practical answers from real decision-makers.'}
  ]},
  {id:'NF19',title:'Why Video Games Are Harder to Make Than You Think',type:'nonfiction',source:'Original passage — technology / design / teamwork / creativity',
   text:'Most people who play video games have no idea how many people it takes to make one. A major modern title — the kind that sells millions of copies and takes up half your hard drive — might require a team of three hundred to a thousand people working for three to five years. The budget can easily exceed one hundred million pounds, rivalling the cost of a Hollywood blockbuster. And unlike a film, which plays the same way every time, a video game must account for millions of possible player decisions, any one of which could break the experience.\n\nThe process begins with design. A game designer is not someone who draws characters — that\'s an artist\'s job. A designer creates the rules: how the world works, what the player can do, what happens when they succeed or fail. This requires a combination of creativity, logic, and psychology. A good designer understands not just what is fun, but why it is fun — and more importantly, what will still be fun after the player has done it for the fiftieth time.\n\nThen come the artists, who build everything the player sees: characters, landscapes, buildings, weather, lighting, menus, and the thousand tiny visual details that make a world feel real. A single character model in a modern game might contain tens of thousands of individual polygons, each one placed and textured by hand. The environments are even more complex — a realistic forest scene might require individually modelled trees, grass that responds to wind, water that reflects light accurately, and animals that behave convincingly.\n\nProgrammers turn all of this into something that actually works. They write the code that makes the physics engine simulate gravity, that tracks the player\'s health and inventory, that controls how enemies react to being spotted, and that ensures the whole thing runs smoothly at sixty frames per second on hardware that varies wildly from player to player. When something goes wrong — and something always goes wrong — it is the programmers who hunt down the bug, which might be buried in millions of lines of code.\n\nSound designers, writers, composers, voice actors, quality testers, project managers, marketing teams, and community managers round out a development team that, in its scale and complexity, resembles less a creative studio and more a small city.\n\nAnd yet, despite all this, roughly seventy per cent of video games fail to make back their development costs. The industry is brutally competitive, player expectations are constantly rising, and a single bad review at launch can doom a project that hundreds of people spent years building.\n\nThe next time you pick up a controller, it might be worth pausing — just for a moment — to consider the small city of people who built the world you\'re about to enter.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['Video games are only made by programmers who write millions of lines of code, while designers, artists, and sound engineers play minor supporting roles in the process.','The passage argues that video games are too expensive because budgets exceeding one hundred million pounds are unsustainable when seventy per cent of titles fail commercially.','Making video games is easy because modern game engines automatically generate realistic forests, character models, and physics simulations without requiring large teams.','Video game development is an enormously complex, expensive, collaborative process involving hundreds of specialists — yet most games still fail commercially, making it one of the riskiest creative industries in the world.'],c:3,e:'The passage systematically reveals the scale and complexity of game development (design, art, code, sound, testing), then delivers the sobering fact that 70% of games fail commercially. The main idea combines admiration for the craft with an honest assessment of the industry\'s difficulty.'},
      {q:'Why does the author dedicate separate paragraphs to designers, artists, programmers, and other roles?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['To argue that designers are more important than programmers because the design paragraph comes first and describes creativity, logic, and psychology while the programming paragraph only describes technical debugging.','To make the passage longer by repeating the same basic point — that game development is complex — using different examples in each paragraph without adding new information.','Because the author wanted to rank the roles from most creative to least creative, placing designers and artists before programmers to suggest a clear hierarchy of importance.','To show the breadth and specialisation of game development — each paragraph reveals a different discipline, building the reader\'s understanding layer by layer until they grasp the full scale of the operation.'],c:3,e:'The role-by-role structure is deliberate. Each paragraph adds another layer of complexity: design (rules), art (visuals), code (functionality). By the time the reader reaches the list of additional roles (sound, writers, testers, managers), the accumulation of specialisms makes the \'small city\' metaphor feel earned rather than exaggerated.'},
      {q:'The passage states that \'roughly seventy per cent of video games fail to make back their development costs\'. Why is this statistic included near the end rather than at the beginning?',skill:'Analyse informational texts',opts:['Placing it after the detailed description of development effort makes the statistic more impactful — the reader has just learned how much work goes into a game, so learning that most still fail creates a powerful contrast between effort and outcome.','To discourage the reader from ever wanting to make video games by showing that even teams of a thousand people working for five years cannot guarantee a commercially successful product.','Because the seventy per cent figure is the passage\'s least important point and is included as an afterthought to round out the discussion of team sizes and budgets.','Because the author wanted to end on a negative note, using the failure rate to argue that the video game industry is a poor career choice for young people.'],c:0,e:'If the 70% failure rate appeared in paragraph one, it would be just a number. By placing it after paragraphs describing the massive effort — years of work, hundreds of people, millions of pounds — the statistic lands with emotional weight. The reader thinks: all that work, and it still usually fails? That\'s the moment the passage achieves its purpose.'},
      {q:'The development team is compared to \'less a creative studio and more a small city\'. What does this metaphor achieve?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['It proves that game studios are literally the size of cities because teams of three hundred to a thousand people require buildings as large as a small urban centre.','It suggests that game development has grown too large and should return to smaller teams, since a \'small city\' implies the process has become inefficiently bloated.','It means game development is primarily an administrative challenge, since running a small city is more about management and logistics than creativity or technical skill.','It conveys the scale, diversity, and complexity of game development — a city has many specialised roles (builders, artists, administrators, services) working together to function, just as a game team does.'],c:3,e:'The \'small city\' metaphor works because cities contain diverse, interdependent specialists — architects, engineers, artists, administrators, service workers — all contributing to a functioning whole. Applying this to a game studio captures not just the size but the complexity and interdependence of the team. It\'s the passage\'s most memorable image.'},
      {q:'The final paragraph asks the reader to \'pause, just for a moment\' before picking up a controller. What is the author\'s purpose?',skill:'Author\'s purpose',opts:['To tell the reader to stop playing video games until they have studied how each role — designer, artist, programmer, sound engineer — contributes to the finished product.','To advertise the video game industry as an exciting career, since the passage\'s descriptions of design, art, and programming are intended to recruit young people into development roles.','To encourage appreciation — by asking the reader to think about the human effort behind the game, the author transforms a casual act (picking up a controller) into a moment of recognition for the hundreds of people whose work made it possible.','To suggest that players should feel guilty for paying too little, since budgets of one hundred million pounds and a seventy per cent failure rate mean most developers lose money.'],c:2,e:'The final paragraph is a gentle call for awareness, not a lecture. By asking for \'just a moment\' of reflection, the author keeps the tone light while making a real point: every game world was built by real people. This transforms the reader\'s relationship with the product — they might see it differently next time they play.'},
      {q:'What can be inferred about why the author distinguishes between a game designer and an artist in the second paragraph?',skill:'Inference',opts:['To argue that artists are less important than designers because artists only build visual elements while designers create the rules, logic, and psychological systems that make games fun.','Because game designers and artists have completely different skill sets, so the author separates them to show that creative and visual work never overlap in the development process.','The author is a game designer who wants to emphasise that design requires creativity, logic, and psychology — skills that are more intellectually demanding than the visual work artists perform.','Most readers assume a game designer draws characters, so the author corrects this misconception to show that design is about systems, rules, and psychology — not visuals — revealing an intellectual depth that readers might not expect.'],c:3,e:'The correction (\'a game designer is not someone who draws characters\') anticipates a common misunderstanding. By clarifying that design involves rules, logic, and psychology, the author elevates the reader\'s understanding of the field. This supports the passage\'s overall goal: showing that game development is far more intellectually demanding than outsiders assume.'},
      {q:'What is the overall tone of the passage?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Bitter — the author is frustrated that game developers are not appreciated, using the seventy per cent failure rate and the phrase \'brutally competitive\' to express resentment toward players who take their work for granted.','Admiring and revelatory — the author genuinely respects the complexity of game development and wants to open the reader\'s eyes to a creative process they likely underestimate.','Dry and academic — the passage reads like a technical manual, listing polygon counts, frame rates, and team sizes without conveying any enthusiasm for the creative process behind them.','Condescending — the author looks down on players who pick up a controller without understanding the thousands of polygons and millions of lines of code that built the world they are entering.'],c:1,e:'The tone is warm and appreciative throughout. Words like \'small city\' and the closing \'pause, just for a moment\' show genuine respect rather than resentment. The author is not angry that players don\'t appreciate developers — they are enthusiastic about revealing a world the reader hasn\'t seen, which creates an inviting rather than lecturing tone.'},
      {q:'What theme does the passage explore through the contrast between the effort of development and the 70% failure rate?',skill:'Theme',opts:['The theme that only programmers matter because they are the ones who hunt down bugs in millions of lines of code and ensure the game runs at sixty frames per second.','The theme that all creative industries have identical success rates, since the Hollywood blockbuster comparison implies that films and games fail at the same seventy per cent rate.','The theme that video games are a waste of money because budgets exceeding one hundred million pounds and a seventy per cent failure rate prove the industry is financially irresponsible.','The theme that creative work carries enormous risk — years of collaborative effort and millions of pounds can result in failure, showing that success in creative industries is never guaranteed regardless of talent or investment.'],c:3,e:'The passage builds appreciation for the scale of game development before revealing that most games fail commercially. This juxtaposition creates a theme about creative risk: even extraordinary effort and talent cannot guarantee success. The theme applies beyond gaming to any creative industry where massive investment meets uncertain outcomes.'},
      {q:'The author describes a realistic forest scene requiring \'individually modelled trees, grass that responds to wind, water that reflects light accurately, and animals that behave convincingly\'. What effect does this list create?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['The list is included to teach the reader how to create their own video game forest by specifying the exact components — trees, wind-responsive grass, reflective water, and convincing animals — needed for realism.','Accumulation — the growing list of specific, labour-intensive details builds a sense of overwhelming complexity, helping the reader understand why game art requires such large teams and long development times.','The list proves that forests are the most common setting in video games because artists spend more time modelling trees, grass, and wildlife than any other environmental features.','The list shows that game graphics are less detailed than real life because individually modelled trees and wind-responsive grass still cannot fully replicate the complexity of a natural forest.'],c:1,e:'The list uses accumulation — each new item adds another layer of work. By the time the reader reaches \'animals that behave convincingly\', they have mentally constructed the enormous effort required for just one scene. This technique makes the passage\'s claims about team size and budget feel justified rather than exaggerated.'},
      {q:'From whose point of view is this passage written, and how does it affect the reader\'s experience?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['A parent who disapproves of children playing video games, using the seventy per cent failure rate and enormous budgets to argue that the industry is an irresponsible waste of talent and money.','A professional game reviewer who evaluates games for a living and uses insider knowledge of polygon counts, frame rates, and team sizes to judge whether a title justifies its development cost.','A game developer complaining about their working conditions, using the details about bugs buried in millions of lines of code and brutally competitive industry pressures to express personal frustration.','An informed outsider who appreciates game development without being a developer themselves — this perspective mirrors the reader\'s own position, making the revelations feel like shared discoveries rather than insider lectures.'],c:3,e:'The author writes as someone who has learned about game development and wants to share that knowledge, not as a developer speaking from inside the industry. This perspective is effective because it mirrors the reader\'s own outsider position. The discoveries feel mutual — as if the author is saying \'I was amazed by this, and you will be too.\''},
      {q:'Why does the author compare a game development budget to \'a Hollywood blockbuster\'?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['To argue that films are always more expensive than video games, since the passage says game budgets can \'rival\' Hollywood but never explicitly states they exceed them.','To suggest that game developers should work in Hollywood instead, since films have a higher commercial success rate than the video game industry\'s seventy per cent failure figure.','To give the reader a familiar reference point for understanding the scale of investment — most readers know films cost millions, so the comparison immediately conveys that game development operates at a similar financial level.','Because the author believes films and games are identical products, since both involve artists, writers, and sound designers working for years on a single creative project.'],c:2,e:'The Hollywood comparison is a deliberate anchoring technique. Most readers have some sense of how expensive blockbuster films are, so saying game budgets rival them instantly communicates scale. Without this reference point, \'one hundred million pounds\' might not register as extraordinary. The comparison makes the number meaningful.'},
      {q:'What can be inferred about why the author mentions that \'a single bad review at launch can doom a project\'?',skill:'Inference',opts:['To highlight the precariousness of game development — despite years of work by hundreds of people, commercial success depends partly on critical reception at a single moment, revealing how little control developers have over their product\'s fate.','To argue that game reviewers are unfair because they judge a product in a single review without appreciating the years of work by hundreds of specialists that went into building it.','Because the author is a game reviewer who wants readers to understand that a single critical assessment can determine whether a hundred-million-pound project succeeds or fails commercially.','To prove that reviews are the only factor that determines whether a game succeeds, since the passage does not mention marketing, pricing, or competition as contributing to the seventy per cent failure rate.'],c:0,e:'This detail underscores the passage\'s theme of risk. After building the reader\'s appreciation for the scale of effort involved, the author reveals that a single bad review can undo it all. The inference is that game development is not just complex but precarious — success is fragile, and factors beyond the developers\' control can determine the outcome.'}
  ]},
  {id:'NF20',title:'The Children Who Mapped the Stars',type:'nonfiction',source:'Original passage — history of science / citizen science / astronomy',
   text:'In 1885, the director of Harvard College Observatory had a problem. His team of male astronomers was falling behind on the enormous task of cataloguing and classifying the thousands of stars visible through the observatory\'s powerful new telescope. The work was painstaking: each star had to be located, its brightness measured, its spectrum analysed, and its position recorded. It required intelligence, patience, and extraordinary attention to detail. The director, Edward Charles Pickering, made a decision that scandalised the scientific establishment: he hired women.\n\nThe women — initially recruited at a salary of twenty-five cents per hour, less than a factory worker — became known as the Harvard Computers. They were not allowed to operate the telescope themselves. Instead, they worked with photographic glass plates: images of the night sky that they examined, measured, and classified by hand, using magnifying glasses and meticulous handwritten logs. The work was repetitive, demanding, and considered by many male scientists to be beneath serious intellectual effort.\n\nThey proved everyone wrong. Over the following decades, the Harvard Computers made discoveries that fundamentally changed our understanding of the universe. Williamina Fleming developed a system for classifying stars by their spectra that is still used today. Annie Jump Cannon refined this system and personally classified over 350,000 stars — more than any other human being in history. And Henrietta Swan Leavitt discovered a mathematical relationship between a certain type of star\'s brightness and its pulsation period, which gave astronomers a way to measure distances across the universe for the first time.\n\nLeavitt\'s discovery was particularly transformative. Before her work, astronomers had no reliable method for determining how far away stars and galaxies were. Her finding — known as the period-luminosity relationship — became the foundation for Edwin Hubble\'s later proof that the universe extends far beyond our own galaxy. It was, in effect, the ruler that allowed humanity to measure the cosmos. Leavitt received no prize for this work during her lifetime, and when the Swedish Academy considered nominating her for a Nobel Prize in 1924, they discovered she had died three years earlier.\n\nThe story of the Harvard Computers raises uncomfortable questions about who gets credit for scientific discovery and whose contributions are remembered. These women did not lack ability — they lacked opportunity, recognition, and fair pay. When given the chance to work, even under restrictive conditions, they produced science of the highest order.\n\nToday, citizen science projects — programmes that invite ordinary people to contribute to real research — carry echoes of the Harvard Computers. Volunteers classify galaxies, track wildlife, and analyse climate data, proving that scientific discovery has never been the exclusive property of professionals.\n\nThe stars that Cannon classified are still in the sky. The ruler that Leavitt built is still in use. Their work outlasted every barrier placed in front of it.',
   questions:[
      {q:'What is the main idea of this passage?',skill:'Main idea',opts:['Citizen science projects are more important than professional research because the Harvard Computers\' discoveries surpassed those of the male astronomers who operated the telescope.','Edward Pickering was the most important astronomer in history because his decision to hire women led directly to the discoveries of Fleming, Cannon, and Leavitt.','Women were only suited to the repetitive classification work because the passage notes they were not allowed to operate the telescope and instead examined photographic glass plates by hand.','The Harvard Computers — women hired for routine astronomical work — made groundbreaking scientific discoveries despite systemic barriers, raising questions about who gets credit for knowledge and whose contributions history remembers.'],c:3,e:'The passage tells the story of women who achieved extraordinary science under restrictive conditions, then broadens to ask why their contributions were undervalued. The main idea combines the historical narrative with a contemporary question about recognition, credit, and opportunity in science.'},
      {q:'Why does the author move from the historical story to modern citizen science in the final paragraphs?',skill:'Text structure',opts:['To connect the Harvard Computers\' legacy to the present — showing that the principle they embodied (non-professionals making real scientific contributions) continues today, giving their story ongoing relevance.','To suggest that modern volunteers are exactly the same as the Harvard Computers because both groups classify data, track natural phenomena, and contribute to research without professional training.','To argue that citizen science is replacing professional astronomy because programmes that invite ordinary people to classify galaxies make trained astronomers unnecessary.','Because the author wanted to end by criticising modern science for still excluding women, using citizen science as evidence that professional institutions remain as restrictive as they were in 1885.'],c:0,e:'The citizen science connection prevents the passage from being just a historical curiosity. By linking the Harvard Computers to modern volunteer researchers, the author argues that the underlying principle — scientific ability exists far beyond the usual professional boundaries — is timeless and still being proven today.'},
      {q:'The passage notes that when the Swedish Academy considered Leavitt for a Nobel Prize, \'they discovered she had died three years earlier\'. Why does the author include this detail?',skill:'Analyse informational texts',opts:['To sharpen the passage\'s argument about recognition — Leavitt\'s work was Nobel-worthy, but the system was so slow to acknowledge women\'s contributions that she died before it could honour her, making the injustice feel concrete and personal.','To prove that the Nobel Prize has unfair rules about deceased nominees, since Leavitt\'s period-luminosity relationship was clearly the most important astronomical discovery of her era.','To argue that the Nobel Prize should be abolished because its failure to honour Leavitt proves it has always been biased against women working in observational astronomy.','To suggest that Leavitt\'s discovery was not truly her own because Edwin Hubble later used the period-luminosity relationship to prove the universe extends beyond our galaxy.'],c:0,e:'This detail is devastating in its simplicity. Leavitt\'s science was good enough for a Nobel Prize — but the recognition came too late. The gap between her contribution (transformative) and her recognition (posthumous, still insufficient) encapsulates the passage\'s argument about systemic undervaluation more powerfully than any general statement could.'},
      {q:'Leavitt\'s discovery is described as \'the ruler that allowed humanity to measure the cosmos\'. What does this metaphor achieve?',skill:'Vocabulary in context',opts:['It means Leavitt invented a physical measuring instrument that astronomers still use in observatories to calculate the distance between stars and galaxies.','It suggests that the cosmos is fundamentally simple because Leavitt\'s period-luminosity relationship reduced the vast complexity of the universe to a single mathematical formula.','It proves that Leavitt was more interested in mathematics than astronomy because the period-luminosity relationship is a mathematical formula rather than a direct observation of the stars.','It makes an abstract mathematical relationship feel concrete and essential — a ruler is a basic, fundamental tool that makes measurement possible, and calling Leavitt\'s discovery a \'ruler for the cosmos\' conveys both its simplicity and its enormous significance.'],c:3,e:'The ruler metaphor is effective because everyone knows what a ruler does: it measures things you couldn\'t measure before. Calling Leavitt\'s discovery a cosmic ruler makes the reader instantly understand its importance — before this, astronomers couldn\'t measure the universe. After it, they could. The metaphor bridges complex science and everyday understanding.'},
      {q:'The final sentence says: \'Their work outlasted every barrier placed in front of it.\' What is the effect of this ending?',skill:'Author\'s purpose',opts:['It suggests that the barriers were not actually very difficult to overcome because the women were still able to make major discoveries despite being paid only twenty-five cents per hour.','It transforms the passage\'s ending from historical into inspirational — framing the women\'s legacy as proof that genuine scientific contribution cannot be permanently suppressed by prejudice, leaving the reader with a sense of justice and admiration.','It summarises the technical details of star classification by reminding the reader that Cannon\'s spectral system and Leavitt\'s period-luminosity relationship are still used in modern astronomy.','It means the stars the women studied have not moved since 1885, so their catalogues remain accurate simply because the objects they recorded have stayed in the same positions.'],c:1,e:'The final sentence reframes the entire passage. Rather than ending on injustice (low pay, no Nobel Prize), the author ends on endurance: the work survived. Stars Cannon classified are still classified her way. Leavitt\'s ruler is still used. This shifts the emotional register from anger to admiration — the barriers were real, but the work was stronger.'},
      {q:'What can be inferred about why Pickering\'s decision to hire women \'scandalised the scientific establishment\'?',skill:'Inference',opts:['The scandal was about women working at night near telescopes, which violated social conventions about where women could be present after dark in the 1880s.','Pickering hired women because they were cheaper at twenty-five cents per hour, and male scientists objected because the lower wages undercut their own salary negotiations.','Scientists were worried that women would damage the photographic glass plates, which were expensive to produce and irreplaceable records of the night sky.','The scientific community in the 1880s considered serious intellectual work to be exclusively male — hiring women for observatory work challenged deeply held beliefs about gender and capability that went beyond any individual decision.'],c:3,e:'The word \'scandalised\' reveals how entrenched gender barriers were in 1880s science. The establishment did not merely disagree with Pickering — they were shocked. This implies that the exclusion of women was so deeply normalised that even considering them for scientific work was seen as outrageous, which makes the women\'s subsequent achievements even more remarkable.'},
      {q:'What is the overall tone of the passage?',skill:'Tone',opts:['Detached and academic — the passage reads like an encyclopaedia entry, listing Pickering\'s hiring decision, the women\'s salary, and Cannon\'s 350,000 star classifications without expressing any personal feeling.','Admiring but indignant — the author celebrates the women\'s extraordinary achievements while expressing restrained anger at the systemic barriers and lack of recognition they faced.','Sarcastic — the author mocks the scientific establishment with bitter humour, using phrases like \'beneath serious intellectual effort\' and \'they proved everyone wrong\' to ridicule the male astronomers\' prejudice.','Entirely neutral — the author presents facts like the twenty-five-cent wage and the missed Nobel nomination without suggesting whether these outcomes were fair or unfair.'],c:1,e:'The tone balances celebration and critique. Phrases like \'they proved everyone wrong\' convey admiration, while details like the 25-cent hourly wage and Leavitt\'s posthumous near-Nobel convey indignation. The author does not rage — the restraint makes the injustice feel more powerful because the facts speak for themselves.'},
      {q:'What theme does the passage explore through the story of the Harvard Computers?',skill:'Theme',opts:['The theme that scientific progress requires expensive equipment above all else, since Pickering\'s powerful new telescope was the essential tool that enabled the Harvard Computers\' discoveries.','The theme that women are naturally better at repetitive work than men, since the Harvard Computers excelled at the painstaking task of examining and classifying photographic glass plates by hand.','The theme that talent exists everywhere but opportunity does not — the women had exceptional ability all along, and the passage argues that systemic barriers, not lack of capability, determined whose contributions were recognised.','The theme that historical injustices have been fully corrected in modern times, since citizen science projects now invite ordinary people to classify galaxies and contribute to real research.'],c:2,e:'The passage states explicitly: \'These women did not lack ability — they lacked opportunity, recognition, and fair pay.\' This sentence encapsulates the theme. The Harvard Computers\' story demonstrates that when barriers are even partially lowered, the talent that emerges can change our understanding of the universe. The theme warns against assuming that those who succeed are the only ones with ability.'},
      {q:'The passage notes that the Harvard Computers\' work was \'considered by many male scientists to be beneath serious intellectual effort\'. What literary device does this detail serve?',skill:'Literary devices',opts:['Dramatic irony — the reader knows these women made universe-changing discoveries, so the male scientists\' dismissal of their work as intellectually trivial becomes deeply ironic and highlights the absurdity of gender prejudice.','Metaphor — the phrase \'beneath serious intellectual effort\' compares the women\'s classification work to manual labour, suggesting the male scientists viewed it as a physical rather than mental task.','Hyperbole — the author exaggerates how dismissive the male scientists were because in reality most 1880s astronomers supported Pickering\'s decision to hire women for observatory work.','Foreshadowing — it hints that the women will eventually be recognised during their lifetimes, since the passage later reveals that the Swedish Academy considered Leavitt for a Nobel Prize.'],c:0,e:'This is dramatic irony because the reader already knows (or is about to learn) that the Harvard Computers made fundamental scientific breakthroughs. The male scientists\' condescension looks foolish in hindsight, and the irony sharpens the passage\'s argument: the very people dismissing the work were wrong about both the work and the workers.'},
      {q:'From whose perspective is this passage written, and how does that perspective shape the narrative?',skill:'Point of view',opts:['Edward Pickering defending his hiring decision by explaining that the women were cheaper than male astronomers and could perform the repetitive classification work just as accurately.','A modern astronomer who uses Cannon\'s classification system daily and wants to argue that contemporary science has fully corrected the gender biases of the 1880s.','A modern historian who has the benefit of hindsight — this allows the author to highlight the gap between how the women were treated and what they actually achieved, creating a narrative of vindication that a contemporary account could not have provided.','One of the Harvard Computers writing about her own experience, describing the daily routine of examining photographic glass plates and the frustration of earning only twenty-five cents per hour.'],c:2,e:'The historical distance is essential. A contemporary account would not know the women\'s work would endure for over a century. The modern perspective allows the author to frame the story as vindication — \'their work outlasted every barrier\' — which gives the narrative its emotional arc: from dismissal to triumph across time.'},
      {q:'Why does the author describe Annie Jump Cannon as having \'personally classified over 350,000 stars — more than any other human being in history\'?',skill:'Character analysis',opts:['To suggest that classifying stars is easy work that anyone could do in large quantities, since the sheer number of 350,000 implies the task was repetitive and required patience rather than intelligence.','To prove that Cannon was the only Harvard Computer who did meaningful work, since Fleming\'s classification system and Leavitt\'s period-luminosity relationship are mentioned only briefly by comparison.','To convey the extraordinary scale of Cannon\'s individual contribution — the specific number and the historical superlative (\'more than any other human being\') transform her from a member of a group into a record-holder whose personal dedication was unmatched.','Because the author wanted to show that Cannon worked faster than the male astronomers, implying that women are naturally more efficient at repetitive astronomical classification.'],c:2,e:'The detail individualises Cannon within the group narrative. \'350,000 stars\' conveys tireless dedication, and \'more than any other human being in history\' places her achievement beyond gender categories entirely. She did not just do well for a woman in a restrictive era — she did more than anyone, ever. This reframing is powerful and deliberate.'},
      {q:'The passage ends with \'Their work outlasted every barrier placed in front of it.\' Why does the author choose the word \'outlasted\' rather than \'overcame\'?',skill:'Analyse literature',opts:['The author chose \'outlasted\' because it sounds more poetic than \'overcame\', creating a lyrical ending that prioritises style over the passage\'s substantive argument about recognition and credit.','The author used \'outlasted\' to suggest the barriers still exist today, implying that modern women scientists face the same twenty-five-cent wages and exclusion from operating telescopes.','\'Outlasted\' implies endurance over time rather than a single moment of triumph — the women did not dramatically defeat prejudice but quietly produced work so fundamental that it survived long after the barriers and the people who erected them were gone.','\'Outlasted\' means the same thing as \'overcame\' and was chosen randomly, since either word could describe how Fleming, Cannon, and Leavitt\'s discoveries survived beyond the 1880s.'],c:2,e:'\'Overcame\' would imply a dramatic victory — the women fighting and winning. \'Outlasted\' is subtler and more accurate: the women did not dismantle the barriers during their lifetimes (Leavitt died unrecognised). Instead, their work endured beyond the barriers\' relevance. The word choice honours persistence and quality over confrontation, and reflects the actual historical reality more truthfully.'}
  ]}
];
